<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-DOLE-1STLD-W     04-10 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DOLE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE IS SHUNNING `DEAD END' ABORTIO FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 4th an 5th grafs to clarify Mrs. Dole's approach to
discussion of abortion.)  (ART ADV: New York Times photos of Dole are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (ac) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Stepping carefully into the debate on
abortion that has roiled her party for years, Elizabeth Dole said
Friday that as a possible Republican Presidential candidate, she
would not be drawn into ``dead-end debates'' over a constitutional
amendment to ban abortion, because ``it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to a supporter and a brief exchange with reporters
after a speech here, Mrs. Dole made her most extensive comments on
the subject since she undertook her exploratory campaign last
month. In doing so, she echoed the modulated posture of her party's
other leading contender, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who opposes
abortion but refuses to say whether he would insist that a running
mate share his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a divisive and irrelevant debate, in terms of an
amendment,'' Mrs. Dole told reporters after a speech to a
University of Southern California group, made up almost entirely of
women, that raises money for scholarship funds. During the speech
Mrs. Dole made no mention of the abortion issue, long a staple of
the Republican Party platform.
</P>
<P>
   The very way in which Mrs. Dole chose to address the issue
showed her trepidation about addressing it.
</P>
<P>
   She made her remarks first only in writing, in a letter to Sandy
Cowen-Miller of Phoenix, a supporter who was at a meeting in
Arizona last week in which another woman asked Mrs. Dole how
Republicans ``can preserve our ideals and our party, too.'' In the
letter, Mrs. Dole said she opposed abortion, except in cases of
rape or incest, or to save the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   But she also noted in the letter that Congress had not voted on
a constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion in 15 years, and
added: ``Republican women can set the example. We can refuse to be
drawn into dead-end debates. We can concentrate instead on what we
agree upon most: we can stop partial-birth abortions, enact
parental notification requirements, continue the ban on government
funding and do everything possible to place unwanted babies with
adoptive parents who will love and care for them.''
</P>
<P>
   She blamed the press for placing ``such an inordinate focus on
an amendment that urgent issues such as domestic violence, child
care, sexual harassment, women's health and the financial security
of women are nearly ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the speech Mrs. Dole's aides called reporters, saying she
would release the letter and hold a rare question-and-answer
session about it. But after the speech, Mrs. Dole declined to
elaborate much, saying only that the party's platform should be
modified to ``add the fact that good and honorable people disagree
on the subject of abortion,'' and that ``we should agree to
respectfully disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has drawn fire from both supporters and opponents of
abortion for his attempt to bridge such divisions, and Mrs. Dole
drew similarly sharp responses Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's called presidential courage,'' said Kate Michelman,
head of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, which has run television commercials here and in New
Hampshire and Iowa branding Mrs. Dole as ``anti-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What she clearly is trying to do is have it both ways,'' Ms.
Michelman added. ``She clearly has reiterated her opposition to a
woman's right to choose, and at the same time, she's saying to the
American public, `But don't worry, because I won't support a
constitutional amendment.' Well, the American people don't want
that in their leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Goeglein, a spokesman for another prospective Republican
candidate, Gary Bauer, welcomed Mrs. Dole's emphasis on the ``need
to change hearts and minds in the country,'' but said that was not
enough. ``We should also be actively pursuing a legislative agenda,
and obviously the Republican Party platform reflects that, and Gary
would be categorically opposed to changing the platform.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole said, ``What I'm doing is really reflecting what
I'm seeing all around the country,'' in terms of uneasiness and
worry about internal divisions in the party. She added: ``For me,
there's no question in my mind that people want to see us move
forward and accomplish some good things, not just kind of endlessly
debate something that really is not going anywhere. It's not going
to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
