<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTH-LONG DELAY IN DEPLOYMENT OF APACHE HELICOPTERS POSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 3rd graf to correct title for Gen. Wesley Clark to `SENIOR
MILITARY COMMANDER'; 11th graf for clarification of types of
additional aircraft; 20th graf to ID quoted official as `Defense
Department' official.) 
 (ART ADV: A map and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four days after NATO approved the deployment of two
dozen American Apache helicopter gunships to attack Yugoslav tanks,
frustrated NATO and Pentagon officials now estimate that it could
take a month before the helicopters are available to fly into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. C-17 cargo planes carrying the first loads of equipment and
supplies to support the Apaches began arriving in Albania's
capital, Tirana, over the last two days. But officials said the
full deployment had moved sluggishly, and they cited bad weather,
slow-moving bureaucracy and an air-traffic bottleneck over Albania
because of the airlift of food and relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's senior military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, has
expressed aggravation at the delays of the Apaches, which are
suited to seek out and destroy tanks and other armored vehicles
involved in the attacks on Kosovo's ethnic Albanians. A NATO
official said Clark on Friday scolded officials organizing the
airlift into Albania, ordering them to do more to speed the
deployment.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO authorized the use of the Apaches on Monday, officials
said it would take only seven to 10 days to have them ready for
their combat missions.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has also come under criticism for not moving fast
enough to protect the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians
that it says are now living in the open in Kosovo under threat of
attack from Yugoslav forces and with little food and water.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO has reported making progress against Yugoslavia's
military and police forces, bad weather has once again enveloped
the Balkans, limiting the alliance's attacks to cruise missiles and
high-flying warplanes, like the B-2 bombers. The skies over
Belgrade were overcast all day, with the clouds dipping as low as
1,500 feet at times.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches can fly effectively in any weather and, officials
said, could be put to good use against Yugoslav forces in what are
now lulls in NATO's raids.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's attacks resumed for a 17th day Friday, relying
heavily on cruise missiles, officials said. Five explosions were
reported Friday evening in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital. The
official Yugoslav news agency reported that a television
transmitter had been hit on Mount Goles near Kosovo's provincial
capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The latest attacks came hours after President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia rejected an effort by a Cypriote official, Spyros
Kyprianou, to secure the release of three U.S. soldiers who were
captured along the Yugoslav-Macedonian border on March 31.
Kyprianou said Milosevic had ruled out ``any peaceful gestures''
because of the intensification of NATO's bombing in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered still more U.S.
forces to join in a NATO force that has already grown significantly
since the strikes began on March 24. Cohen sent six more F-15C
fighter jets now based in Alaska to the region and ordered a Navy
minesweeper, the Inchon, to stay in the Adriatic rather than leave
as scheduled for the Persian Gulf. The Inchon has helicopters
aboard that could be used in the relief operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said Cohen now had an
official request from Clark for dozens of additional fighter and
support aircraft, including more fighters like the F-16, the F-15
and the A-10, which is designed to fly low and attack ground troops
and armor, and refueling aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional pressure on the Clinton administration also
continued to grow. A bipartisan group of senators and
representatives who traveled to NATO's headquarters with Cohen this
week sent President Clinton a letter, urging him to do more to at
least plan for the use of ground forces and to prepare the American
public for a long campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even assuming the success of the air campaign to significantly
degrade Milosevic's military capability, there is less certainty
that NATO's broader objectives in Kosovo (removal of Milosevic's
troops and return of refugees with international protection) will
be achieved,'' the group of nine Republicans and Democrats wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rain and clouds set in again, U.S. and other NATO
warplanes had for the first time begun to strike armored forces
operating in Kosovo. And on Thursday the Pentagon said the strikes
had effectively cut the fuel and ammunition lines to the
40,000-strong Yugoslav army and to police units in the province.
</P>
<P>
   But officials concede that they have so far done little to
destroy the front-line armored forces accused of carrying out the
worst of the attacks in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clark had requested the deployment of the Apache helicopters _
along with long-range rocket batteries used to back them up _ more
than two weeks ago to accelerate that effort. But carrying out his
request initially stalled because of concerns about putting ground
forces so close to the fighting in Yugoslavia, and now because of
the sluggish deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials now concede officially that the schedule of putting
Apaches in place in seven to 10 days has slipped. Maj. Gen. Charles
Wald, the deputy director of strategic plans and policy for the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said Friday that it was unlikely that even
an ``initial operational capability'' would be in place before
seven days.
</P>
<P>
   A major factor in the delay has been the small and underequipped
airport outside Tirana, which has been overwhelmed by the enormous
effort to ship food and other supplies to more than 200,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees who fled Yugoslav forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already shipped 230,000 daily rations,
100,000 gallons of water and 700 tents to Albania and has plans for
still more shipments in the days and weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Defense Department official in Washington said NATO's
focus on the relief effort in Albania had slowed the effort to move
the Apache unit there. ``If we wanted them in quickly, it wouldn't
take long to get them in,'' the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. `It's a question of priorities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other officials have said that even if the Apaches arrived soon,
Yugoslavia's air defense system was still formidable enough to make
flying the helicopters risky. Clark has indicated that the Apaches
would join the fight right away, but other Pentagon officials would
prefer to use the Apaches only after the air defenses are further
weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said the Air Force had sent a team of experts to Tirana's
airport to install a lighting system and air-traffic control
equipment that could allow landings and takeoffs at night; they are
now limited to daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time it will be easier to bring more equipment in,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather over the Balkans has been so bad that it has
delayed the installation and testing of that equipment, which is
not expected to be in place before the end of the weekend. The
weather has also delayed some of the cargo flights from Germany,
where the Apaches and related forces are based.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of five C-17 flights scheduled to fly to Albania on
Thursday made it through the clouds and rain, while the other had
to cancel its flight. Friday, only five of seven were able to land,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior defense official said that if the airport
operated 24 hours a day and was not hampered by the weather, the
full force could arrive within 16 days. At the current pace,
however, the estimate is that 25 more days will be needed, meaning
it will be May 2 when the full force is there.
</P>
<P>
   This official and others said another problem was the ``weight''
of the Army's force. Although the Apaches themselves are expected
to fly to Albania, the rocket batteries, armored vehicles and other
equipment to set up a secure base for 2,800 soldiers will require
some 150 cargo flights from Germany to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Army is sending the force into remote, rugged
terrain in Europe's poorest country means that the force must bring
with it everything the soldiers need to live and work. ``It's not
like taking an airplane and landing at Aviano,'' the senior defense
official said, referring to the air base in Italy that is the nexus
of NATO's attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches, along with the long-range rocket batteries, will
ultimately set up a base at an airfield now being carved out of a
pasture in an undisclosed location between Tirana and Albania's
northern border with Kosovo. The helicopters are likely to operate
in smaller groups from hidden bases in the mountains and forests
close to Kosovo's border.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, in a television interview from NATO's headquarters in
Brussels, Belgium, said Friday that the Apaches would allow NATO to
``work beneath the weather'' when rain and clouds scuttle other
flights.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance confirmed Friday that one of three bombs aimed
earlier this week at the main telephone exchange in Pristina had
missed its target and slammed into a residential area, although it
was unclear if anyone had died as a result. The Yugoslav
authorities say 10 people were killed when an errant bomb hit the
city on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bomb appeared to be seduced off the target at the final
stages,'' said NATO's military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby
of Britain. ``Close inspection of imagery indicates that it landed
some 200 to 300 meters away in what seems to be a small residential
area.'' He said the telephone exchange was a ``critical target''
since it was used for communications between Belgrade and Serbian
forces in Kosovo. He said NATO regretted any possible loss of
civilian life as a result of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes Friday night hit a sprawling industrial complex in
Kragujevac that included the country's only auto plant. Pentagon
and NATO officials said the factory also made military vehicles and
was thus a legitimate military target.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
