<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGER-ADS-LADN     04-10 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGER-ADS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS ON THE RISE AT DODGER STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not long ago, pitching at Dodger Stadium occurred
only between the mound and home plate, except for orange Unocal
balls atop the outfield pavilions. Now commercialism has spread
through the ballpark, one of the final holdouts of a baseball
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   What in the name of Sandy Koufax is going on? older fans may be
asking, particularly since the Dodgers are one of the most
influential names in sports. As in most enterprises, the answer
comes down to the bottom line, and the Dodgers, with the second
biggest payroll in baseball, are obviously trying to recover some
of that cash. Like the cool $105million they are spending on
pitcher Kevin Brown over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Though not overwhelming, the roster of advertising at the
37-year-old park more than doubled this season with a trio of ads
(Dodge, Bud Lite and Pacific Bell) adorning the outfield fence,
logos in both dugouts (New Era athletic uniforms), one in the
visitor's bullpen (MasterCard) and several along the foul lines,
including one for the Department of Water and Power.
</P>
<P>
   The incursion began in earnest last year with rotating
advertisements behind home plate. Industry observers believe the
ads _ nearly all at field level _ are aimed as much at the millions
watching at home on television as fans at the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 1 to 10 compared to other teams, the Dodgers are
probably a 3 right now,'' said Dean Bonham, head of a Denver-based
sports consulting firm. ``But I would imagine they'll be a 7 or 8
in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the ads, particularly those in the outfield, have
been designed to blend with the overall decor, they are surely
something of a jolt to fans who recall the four decades of the
O'Malley family's ownership prior to Rupert Murdoch's takeover last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers have done a pretty good job of phasing in
advertising tastefully because the ads are much less invasive than
they could be,'' said sports consultant and USC marketing professor
David Carter. ``And I think they are first and foremost for the TV
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Stockhamer, the team's vice president of marketing, said
response to the new ads has been minimal. ``There's really been
very little reaction,'' he noted. ``We think Dodger Stadium has
less ad signage than almost any other sports facility. We've also
tried to make the signage blend in with the aesthetic of the
park.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teams have been far more aggressive in recent years. For
example, The Gap chain now has ads on the left-center and
right-center ``gaps'' on outfield fences at eight Major League
parks.
</P>
<P>
   Stockhamer said Dodger management recognizes the increased ads
represent a significant break with tradition. ``We're trying to be
thoughtful about this,'' he added. ``It's very important to us that
the sponsors be involved in our community activities. So you can't
just go out and buy a sign at Dodger Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he noted, Pacific Bell has teamed with the Dodgers
on a program to encourage reading among children, while the Los
Angeles Department of Water and Power has backed the new Dodger
Experience museum area, which is free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he was especially impressed with the Dodger
Experience. ``It's a great way for them to link the past with the
present and shows the appreciation for what the Dodgers mean to
baseball,'' he added. ``They are not forgetting that connection,
although I'd be remiss if I didn't mention that they are selling
merchandise there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stockhamer also admitted that the realities of supporting a
roster with a $79 million payroll, trailing only the New York
Yankees, also played a role in the new ads appearing. ``There are
only so many revenue streams that a club has,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham said the Dodgers appear to have recognized that they need
to take a go-slow approach. ``The Dodgers fans are fairly
conservative when it comes to commercialization, and I think the
management is sensitive to that,'' he said. ``But to survive, the
team has to squeeze every last dollar. So over the long term, the
Dodgers are not going to be any different from other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter believes the Dodgers were already moving toward ads in
the outfield last year when they posted murals of past Dodger
greats on the walls. ``I think they were trying to prepare people
to focus on the wall because there was going to be advertising at
some point,'' he said. ``And if they win the pennant this year, the
fans' tolerance for advertising will increase.''
</P>
<P>
   More advertising is clearly the direction for the entire game. A
few weeks ago, reports emerged that Major League Baseball was
considering the idea of allowing advertising on players' uniforms,
much like professional soccer teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think uniform ads are inevitable as one more strategy to
generate revenues and solve the disparity between large-market and
small-market teams,'' Bonham said. ``I would suggest we're going to
see corporate names on uniforms. It's something we need to get used
to.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
