<HEADLINE>
HARPER GETS A BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ His minutes are declining, but don't mistake
that for a decline in Derek Harper's stamina or ability. The
16-year veteran says he's just fine, though his coach admits he's
happy to give the 37-year-old a rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers' starting point guard played a season-low
17 minutes Tuesday against Utah, as rookie Tyronn Lue got hot in
his debut and played most of the game. The next night at
Sacramento, Harper played a new season-low 13 minutes, as backup
Derek Fisher got in a groove.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis said it's no reflection on Harper, who's
averaging 7.5 points and 4.5 assists in 26.3 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never intended to play Derek Harper that many minutes to
begin with,'' Rambis said. ``He was brought in as a veteran backup
point guard, and that was our initial intention for him. He just
played so phenomenally well, that he deserved more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to see what Ty could do and the possibilities he
could bring to a ball club. And in Sacramento, Fisher played very
well, and I've been very consistent in that if an individual or a
unit goes well, they stay in the game and get more time.''
</P>
<P>
   And Harper's not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're called upon to play, you play, and when you're
not, you just sit and support the people that are playing,'' he
said. ``This is my 16th year in the league, so I don't ever
question that kind of stuff.... I'm past that in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing several 25- to 30-minute games, Harper said he
feels ``good physically.... Age is overrated, man.'' Yet his
production is also down _ he's shooting 28.2 percent (11 for 39)
over his past seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Harper welcomes the rest, and Rambis admits his heavy minutes
are a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I look at the stats sheet,'' he said. ``I know what
it's like to play when you're that old. It takes its toll on you.
When you start playing back-to-backs, your body takes a beating....
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a very good scenario for us, to get him as much
rest as possible going into the playoffs. We know what he can do,
we know he can step it up in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Model citizen: Dennis Rodman still picks up technical fouls at a
pace just slightly beneath his rebounding rate, but he has
otherwise been on his best behavior for the past two weeks _ since
the day he ditched practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis had a 30-minute hear-to-heart with Rodman that day and
said afterward that Rodman had agreed to be more a part of the team
for the rest of the season. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been on time for everything. He's done everything that we
wanted him to do,'' Rambis said. ``I have absolutely zero
complaints with him.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rodman has made his presence felt as much as his absences
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talking more, he's communicating more, especially on the
court and in the locker room,'' Harper said. ``I think it's helping
us, especially from a defensive standpoint, because that's where
most of his communication is coming from ... Dennis has been very
positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
