<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE AS BURKETT'S STRETCH WOES CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers right-hander John Burkett suffers
from a baseball version of multiple-personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Suggested title for his biography: ``Dr. Windup, Mr. Stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett once again demonstrated an inability to pitch from the
stretch with runners aboard, and that flaw reared its ugly head
during last night's 8-4 defeat to the Anaheim Angels at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett surrendered three hits to the Angels during six at-bats
with runners aboard, and the final two resulted in four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there feeling like I didn't have any weapons,''
Burkett said, ``and it showed.''
</P>
<P>
   The show didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Angels third baseman Troy Glaus delivered the knockout punch
with a two-out, two-run double during the third inning. Glaus
deposited a 3-2 curveball into the gap in left-center field that
scored Randy Velarde and Darin Erstad and provided the Angels a 5-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, though, viewed the pitch prior to that as the turning
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I've got to make my pitch,'' said Burkett, who
surrendered five runs on seven hits. ``If I make that pitch, I'm
out of the inning and maybe I can grind it out like \RAnaheim
left-hander Chuck\S Finley did. He didn't have his best stuff
either, but he was able to grind it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett's 2-2 fastball, though, eluded the strike zone by the
narrowest of margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was off the plate,'' Burkett said. ``I think Pudge made it
look good, but it was off the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   What made matters worse, Burkett said, was that Glaus appeared
to be looking for a breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was frozen. I think I could have thrown it right down the
middle and he would have taken it,'' Burkett said. ``Now, you've
got to make another pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The inability to pitch effectively from the stretch haunted
Burkett all last season. Opponents hit only .254 against the
right-hander with no one on base, but Burkett surrendered a .347
batting average with runners aboard. That ranked as the fifth-worst
figure among American League pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Todd Greene found Burkett's delivery from the
stretch inviting, as well. Greene followed Glaus' second-inning
single with a two-run homer on a first-pitch slider that gave the
Angels a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett worked extensively this spring on his mechanics from the
stretch and remains convinced that improvement will be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I made progress,'' Burkett said. ``I still believe
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers rallied throughout the evening, and a fifth-inning,
solo home run by catcher Ivan Rodriguez off Finley pulled the
Rangers within one run at 5-4. Right-hander Esteban Loaiza, who
replaced Burkett, gave the Rangers that opportunity by retiring 10
of the first 11 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, though, struck for three runs during the seventh
inning against Loaiza, whose 4 1/3-inning appearance marked the
second-longest relief appearance of his career. Tim Salmon's
two-out, two-run home run proved to be the final straw and gave the
Angels an 8-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't tired,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He was
throwing 95 and getting good hitters out. He made one bad pitch to
Salmon, and that was it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0105EDT &QL; 
