<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     04-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BOWLING NIGHT, RANGERS HAVE FEW STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It was unofficially Bowling Night at The
Ballpark in Arlington last night, which means:
</P>
<P>
   (a) We should have all gone bowling instead.
</P>
<P>
   (b) Hanging sliders from Ranger pitchers looked as big as
bowling balls to the visiting Angels' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   (c) Starter John Burkett rolled at least two too many
gutterballs.
</P>
<P>
   (d) We should have stayed home and rented a tape of Dudley
Moore's ``Arthur'', which featured the greatest bowling line ever
from the late John Gielgud, who told Liza Minnelli in his
wonderfully stuffy English accent: ``Normally one would have to go
to a bowling alley to meet a girl like you.''
</P>
<P>
   (e) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Hint: Take (e).
</P>
<P>
   All of this, sadly, leads us back to that sorest and sorriest of
subjects, Rangers' pitching, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   There are far too many nights when trying to win with this staff
is like trying to make the 7-10 split. This was another of them.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who has been known to roll a perfect 300-game or two on
the hardwood, served up a home run to the game's first batter _
sound familiar? _ and a two-run homer to Todd Greene an inning
later.
</P>
<P>
   It was like throwing gutterballs in the first two frames, and
the Angels opened a four-game series between the two AL West
archrivals with an 8-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing they didn't bring their ``A'' team.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, back in California with an ankle sprain and watching
on TV, probably took a look at the watermelons Burkett was lobbing
up to the plate and grabbed a bat in his living room.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have played four games, won one of them a 6-0
victory behind Aaron Sele, but have given up a whopping 26 runs in
the other three. That's 6.5 per game, even with the shutout, and
that simply won't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played only four games,'' manager Johnny Oates stressed
to us doom sayers who keep harping on this subject. ``What we have
to do is, the night we give up eight, score 10. No, we can't keep
giving up eight runs a game, but we don't have to throw shutouts
either. We need to be somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, at the end of 50 games, it's still at 6 1/2 \Rruns\S,
that's when you send up the flag. But it won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the sample is minuscule at this point, but the evidence
to date certainly looks damning.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro's home run in the first was the first of his
career. Yes, even banjo hitters are now finding the range to the
most distant points of Home Run Porch.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's more damaging two-run shot in the second was a laser
beam to straightaway center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burkie struggled with his command,'' Oates said. ``Almost
every hit he gave up was on a hanging breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When Todd Zeile's bases-empty homer cut it to 3-1 in the bottom
of the inning, Burkett hurried back out to the mound in the top of
the third and gave up singles to Randy Velarde and Darin Erstad
before hanging another lollipop down the middle for Troy Glaus. The
Angels' third baseman banged it off the top of the left-field wall
for a two-run double that mercifully sent Burkett to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   The most encouraging stretch of the night for the Rangers was
the 3 1/3 innings of shutout relief from previously scorched
Esteban Loaiza from the third through the sixth. Unfortunately,
even that was spoiled by Oates' questionable decision to stay with
him when he ran into trouble in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had cut Anaheim's lead to a run while Loaiza held
the Angels in check. But a leadoff single, a sacrifice bunt and a
run-scoring double by Randy Velarde made it 6-4 and left the fans
uneasy with the middle of the Angels' order due at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Oates could have brought in left-hander Mike Munoz to face
lefty-swinging Erstad, but elected to stay with the laboring
Loaiza. Zeile's diving stop robbed Erstad of a hit, but that was
only a temporary reprieve. Loaiza dropped down sidearm in an
attempt to gun a 2-2 fastball past Tim Salmon, left the pitch up
and down the middle, and Salmon was on it like a shark on a wounded
gamefish. The two-run homer broke the Rangers' (come)backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have brought in Munoz, but Loaiza was still throwing
well and he wasn't tired,'' Oates said, defending his decision.
``He's gone longer than that several times this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, however, without getting bombed, which is why it might have
been nice to get him out after a successful outing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well. Maybe next time they'll give away bowling shirts.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
