<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS AS FRAUD POLICE WON'T WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The federal government and AARP are partnering up in
an enterprise that is probably not in the best interests of
Medicare beneficiaries, those who provide for their health-care
needs, or the political health of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the concept sounds good, even noble. The idea is to
enlist the 39 million or so Medicare enrollees as an army to fight
fraud and thereby bolster the program's financial health. To this
end, the lobby formerly known as the American Association of
Retired Persons has joined with government in a campaign to recruit
seniors to serve in what amounts to a health-care gestapo.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala put it more
delicately when she exhorted beneficiaries, ``We're asking you to
be the eyes and ears of the Medicare program.''
</P>
<P>
   Now what could be wrong with asking Medicare beneficiaries to
police their health-care system for fraud and abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty, actually.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, it replaces trust, the basic cornerstone of
doctor-patient relationships, with distrust. The cornerstone of
this program is the assumption that health-care providers aren't to
be trusted because everyone involved is a potential cheat. Can
anyone believe that turning patients into adversaries will improve
the quality of medicine?
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, asking old people to become snitches robs them of
their dignity. More troubling, perhaps, it empowers those with mean
and vindictive streaks to go out of their way to make trouble for
doctors, nurses, clinics and hospitals they feel haven't treated
them with proper deference or respect. In the wrong hands it can
become a tool of petty vengeance. The program's organizers counsel
restraint and use of proper channels, but this admonition will no
doubt be lost on the mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Thirdly, there is the question of whether encouraging a
vigilante approach is unnecessary overkill. Nancy W. Dickey,
president of the American Medical Association, noted recently that
the physician community has in the main worked cooperatively with
government to reduce fraud and abuse. To this end, she said in a
recent essay in /{The Wall Street Journal/}, the level of Medicare
payments deemed ``improper'' declined by nearly 50 percent from
1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As for estimating the magnitude of fraud, the methodology used
is suspect. The sampling of claims reviewed to screen for improper
payments is so minuscule as to make it statistically irrelevant. An
audit of only 600 Medicare claims, Dickey said, resulted in
government watchdogs claiming $12.6 billion worth of rip-offs last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In a broader political context, this is an approach to
governance that brings out the worst in the American character.
Snitches might be useful in fighting street crime, but transforming
America's senior citizens into a secret police against those trying
to help them puts the nation on a dangerous slippery slope to
despotism.
</P>
<P>
   Government overreaching is perhaps understandable, because this
is the nature of governments, even democratic republics. What's
puzzling is AARP's eagerness to play handmaiden to a police-state
initiative. It probably has something to do with Lord Acton's
observation about how power corrupts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-10 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTION, KAN., AND Y2K PROTECTION: A MATCH MADE IN CYBERHEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Small-town folks in Kansas and computer geeks from
California will hold a hometown barbecue today to celebrate a
strange Y2K kinship that brought together a struggling town and a
start-up online data management firm.
</P>
<P>
   It all started seven months ago with a public relations guy
named Ted Ladd. It was Ladd's job to create a big splash ad
campaign for  &LR; Backup, a 4-year-old San Diego company that earns its
money backing up computer files for homes and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd envisioned a Times Square or Sunset Strip blitz featuring a
Y2K countdown clock. ``Protect your data before it's too late,''
was the gist of the proposed campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Too costly, his colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not go the opposite direction? they asked. Put up a
billboard in the middle of nowhere, or better yet adopt a town and
protect every computer file in town from the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   So Ladd punched up his favorite Internet search engine looking
for unique names of Midwestern towns under 1,000 people. After
discarding Backup Corner, Pa., and Millennium, N.C., he hit the
mark with Protection, Kan., population 560.
</P>
<P>
   And the more research he did, the better the idea sounded.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the town, 143 miles south of Wichita along
the Oklahoma border, was established in 1884 at a time when
protectionist policy dominated presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three years later, the national spotlight hit Protection
when it became the first town in America to be protected against
polio with the Salk vaccine. And today, Ladd said, it will be ``the
only town in America protected from Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is simple: Give every computer user in town _ that's
about 250 people _ a $99 online account that will back up their
files at the end of the day on a computer in San Diego. Total
retail value: almost $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Protection residents invited Ladd and his colleagues into their
homes. The Kansans had heard of Y2K but thought it was only a
big-city worry.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until a year ago when the roof blew off Don's Place on
Main Street and destroyed the restaurant's computer and valuable
files that owner Don Dellinger found out how reliant he had become
on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all talked about (the Y2K bug), joking about how computers
are going to go down, but not much attention was paid to it,''
Dellinger said over the clatter of the dinner crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the storm brought it to our attention. I had to build my
files from scratch. You're always supposed to back up your computer
files, but who really does?''
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger had to redesign his menus and format new financial
spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, 25 women have been sprucing up the town for
today's big barbecue. And Dellinger has painted a spare room in his
restaurant to showcase photos of the artwork of Stan Herd, a local
man known the world over for his colorful crop artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Herd, who now lives in Lawrence, Kan., will unveil his latest
creative venture, a 650-foot-long artwork carved out of wheat, the
town's ``stamp of approval'' against Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners Sally Selzer, Orlin Loucks and Danny McLarty
will give tours of their Y2K-ready shops. And computer files at the
town bank, co-op, feed yard and cattle chute manufacturer are safe
from fire, disaster or year 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
   The adopt-a-town campaign has planted a seed in a town
struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shrinking like everyone else,'' said Dellinger, who in
the past quarter-century has seen the railroads stop rolling
through his town. ``You lose your school one month and then the
next month this (computer effort) starts up and you remain enthused
about your little community.''
(BULLET)Briday was another day for the Y2K nonrecord book.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some predictions to the contrary _ ``Some fear today is
Y2K doomsday,'' the San Jose Mercury News reported Friday morning _
the 99th day of the year passed without any serious reported Y2K
glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts were concerned that day 99 in year 99 would trip up
computers that counted the date from the first day of the calendar
year, instead of by the month. In some cases, a string of nines was
used by programmers to signal the end of a program, or to tell a
computer to purge information.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too early to say definitively that there were no
problems Friday, no major outages were reported anywhere in the
U.S. or overseas.
(BULLET)It was more public relations than public preparedness, but
the nation's electric utilities conducted a nationwide Y2K test
Friday to see whether they could communicate if telephone service
goes out.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the test, about 200 utilities across the country
simulated a telecommunications outage that cut off communications
between electric substations, generating plants, other utilities
and the regional power pool.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the utilities used emergency radios to replace
telephone and computer data systems. The test went off with minor
hitches caused by lightning in some areas, employees who hadn't
been trained on mobile equipment in a few cases, and equipment that
still needs to be fine-tuned, according to the North American
Electric Reliability Council, an industry group that coordinated
the test,
(BULLET)The Federal Aviation Administration, which says it's 88
percent Y2K-ready, will put its money where its computers are late
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA will try the first live test of its Year 2000 air
traffic control computer fixes from the Denver International
Airport control center. The agency plans to split the computers
controlling air traffic around the airport and turn the clock ahead
to Jan. 1, 2000, in half of the systems.
</P>
<P>
   The radar systems will track both commercial flights and an FAA
Lear Jet.
</P>
<P>
   During the four-hour test, technicians will check computer
software changes designed to solve the Y2K problem. The FAA plane
and the small amount of commercial traffic expected during the
midnight hours will be tracked by air traffic control systems not
participating in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the computers will be rejoined and tapes from both
sides will be sent to the agency's technical center in Atlantic
City, N.J., for comparison. The results will be released next week.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said all of its systems would be Y2K ready by June
30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
