<SLUG> BC-PLANETHOLLYWOOD-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANET HOLLYWOOD//AMC VENTURE SCALED BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Almost two years after AMC Entertainment Inc.
and Planet Hollywood decided to reach for the stars together, not
one of their Planet Movies By AMC centers has opened.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for the once-high-flying Planet Hollywood and AMC
to open mega-movies and restaurants under one roof. By now, the
joint venture was supposed to have eight to 10 up and running
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that only one is under construction and, if all
goes according to plan, will open late next month in Easton, Ohio,
said AMC spokeswoman Brenda Nolte.
</P>
<P>
   After that, she said, it's wait and see, which raises the
question: What about the joint venture's commitment to Kansas City?
</P>
<P>
   As far as Nick Bashkiroff is concerned, there still is a
commitment to build in downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the chairman of Planet Hollywood standing on stage
and the chairman of AMC standing on stage saying they're going to
come to Kansas City, and that's pretty formal,'' he said, referring
to a news conference in the summer of 1997 announcing the joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
   But Bashkiroff declined to say whether there was a signed lease
for the Planet Hollywood//AMC venture _ or any others for the
downtown Kansas City venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on documents signed or not signed,''
he said. ``That's something that I don't think is necessary for
people outside of the company to know at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of Planet Hollywood have fallen fast. Its original
appeal came from movie prop-laden eateries and movie star names
like Demi Moore, Bruce Willis and Whoopi Goldberg, who as investors
showed up for openings in New York, Paris and London. Movie fans
flocked to the restaurants and, as they departed, were funneled
through stores stocked with glizty, expensive merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   But as more and more of the restaurants have opened, the
investor-stars have been reluctant to make the trek to places like
the Gurnee Mills mall north of Chicago, known for its plethora of
outlet stores, and the mall to end all malls, the Mall of America
outside Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the food, which hasn't won good reviews and
is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Bashkiroff conceded as much: ``What you have to remember is that
repeat business is primarily tied to the quality of your
food....It's nice to have all kinds of environmentals...if you
don't expect people to come back (more than once), and with a good
portion of the ticket being merchandise purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Patty Caruso of Planet Hollywood said she wasn't sure
why plans for the Planet Hollywood-AMC venture had been scaled
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted to make sure we didn't go too big too
fast,'' Caruso said. ``Obviously, we're struggling a little bit
right now, and we're in the doldrums, but I think the decision to
pull back was made before that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Those doldrums are reflected in the financials. On the day it
went public in 1995, Planet Hollywood stock shot up to its all-time
high of 32.
</P>
<P>
   George K. Baum &AMP; Co. analyst Herb Buchbinder said Planet
Hollywood's problems have put a big question mark over the future
of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this whole Planet Hollywood thing looking so bad, why
would AMC want to go forward?'' asked Buchbinder. ``They did make a
big deal out of it initially, but it's really cooled off since
then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
