<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-SENTENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAXIMUM SENTENCE IMPOSED IN ABUSE OF TWO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ The scars on the little girl's face are obvious.
It's the emotional damage that is not so easy to see.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents say the girl, now 7, and her 8-year-old brother will
never fully recover from the summer of torture they endured at the
hands of a Merriam woman.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, a Johnson County judge Friday imposed the
maximum sentence of six years in prison for Sandra S. Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   The children were abused when they stayed with Wheeler last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hollow victory. It can't fix what she did,'' said the
children's mother, Lolita Warnock. ``But she shouldn't get off on
probation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler pleaded no contest in February to two counts of child
abuse, and District Judge Peter Ruddick found her guilty of the
felony charges.
</P>
<P>
   At that hearing, Assistant District Attorney Sheri McCracken
described how the children were beaten, kicked, bound with duct
tape and burned with hot water and bleach and how clumps of hair
were pulled from their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was dehydrated and lost weight. His sister may have
suffered permanent eye damage.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler is a cousin of the children's father. The children
stayed with her and her three children for about a month last July
and August.
</P>
<P>
   Lolita Warnock said she would never forget the ``haunted look''
on the children's faces when she first saw them after Wheeler took
them back home to the Wichita area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not over it now. They're not going to be over it in a
year. They're never going to get over it,'' she told the judge
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She said that even now, whenever the children see the type of
van Wheeler drove, they ask whether it's her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live with this fear that she might show up,'' Warnock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, 35, asked for probation Friday, tearfully pleading with
Ruddick to allow her to remain free so she could receive counseling
and treatment and be with her own three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children need me very much,'' Wheeler said. ``I really
don't know how my children will make it without me.''
</P>
<P>
   She described her battles with drugs, caused by the pain of
surgeries that have left her disabled and using a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Jay Norton, asked that she be sent to the
community corrections residential center, which would provide an
intensive, highly supervised probation environment.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said a mental health evaluator found that Wheeler had a
low risk of violent behavior. He called witnesses to testify Friday
that Wheeler was a loving mother.
</P>
<P>
   He said she entered pleas to the charges to spare the children
from having to testify.
</P>
<P>
   McCracken asked for the maximum sentence, saying Wheeler was
asking for the kind of mercy she didn't show with the children.
</P>
<P>
   She said Wheeler threatened to kill them and told them they
would never see their mother again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant is their nightmare. She will never go away,''
McCracken said. ``They are scarred.''
</P>
<P>
   Before imposing sentence, Ruddick said he had received many
letters from people supporting Wheeler. Most said they could not
believe she was capable of the kind of abuse she was convicted of
committing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is it is unbelievable,'' the judge
said. ``It amounted to nothing less than torture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
