<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KANSAS-LEGISLATURE-KA     04-10 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-LEGISLATURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE FAILS TO ADJOURN, WILL RETURN TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The Kansas Legislature had planned to adjourn
Friday for a two-week break, but _ as often happens in the
statehouse _ the proceedings didn't follow the script.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight Friday morning, negotiations on a $9 billion
state budget broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, as the full Legislature convened,
sign-carrying protesters patrolled the hallways, some walking, some
in wheelchairs, demanding more money for social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, negotiators produced a deal on the state
budget. But doubts arose whether the Legislature would approve it,
and anyway, there wasn't enough time to distribute and analyze it
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   To reach a resolution, leaders said they would keep the House
and Senate in session at least through Saturday. After a break, the
Legislature will return April 28.
</P>
<P>
   In further maneuvering over highway construction, a proposal
bubbled to the surface, then disappeared in favor of still another
plan. But that one, too, failed to attract enough support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty close to chaos, but not nearly as much as the
House,'' said Sen. Audrey Langworthy, a Prairie Village Republican.
``That's normal for this time of year. You've just got to keep
talking and negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Robin Jennison, a Healy Republican, disagreed. ``I
don't think things are in chaos,'' Jennison said. ``But I would
have liked to have had the budget done and gotten out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget wrangling involves how much to spend on the
Department of Social and Rehabilitation Services, and how to
rechannel money from administration to programs.
</P>
<P>
   The 12:30 a.m. Friday walkout occurred when Senate budget
negotiators made an offer to their House counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `That's unacceptable. Let's stay here and talk,' ''
said Rep. Phill Kline, a Shawnee Republican who is the House
appropriations chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dave Kerr, a Hutchinson Republican who is the Senate
appropriations chairman, then declared the meeting over and
departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tired and ready to go home,'' Kerr said. ``We're just
country kids. We're not used to staying up that late.''
</P>
<P>
   When the negotiators reconvened Friday, lobbyists and staff
members filled every available chair in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Activists seeking more funding for social programs milled in the
hallways, some of them carrying signs. ``Fund People Not Things,''
one placard read.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few hours, a deal emerged
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I'm pleased,'' Kline said. ``I wish we would be a
little tighter on spending.''
</P>
<P>
   One key point was money for programs that aid the
developmentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Activists were seeking to preserve current funding for people
already in community programs, eliminate a 350-person waiting list
of persons needing care and increase the pay for workers who
provide the care.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative budget deal gave them some of what they wanted.
Money to eliminate the waiting list was removed. They vowed to
press the Legislature for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice but to come back,'' said Tom Laing, director
of InterHab and an advocate for community programs.
</P>
<P>
   Further budget debate will occur when the Legislature finishes
in late April. The highway construction issue will await action
then.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, leaders struggled to craft a transportation plan
that would attract enough votes.
</P>
<P>
   A negotiated version late in the morning was too modest for
Senate Democrats, and they said a larger plan should be offered to
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, a slightly more ambitious plan emerged,
but a nose count of Republicans failed to show enough votes, and
Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, called it
quits for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's considerable support for a highway plan,'' he
said. ``The question is, what's it going to look like.''
</P>
<P>
   He said further work on a transportation plan should be
postponed until lawmakers return at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better go home, cool off and come back fresh,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The last proposal Republicans and Democrats presented to their
members in informal meetings would have increased the gasoline tax
by 6 cents a gallon, boosted car and truck registration fees and
provided authority to issue up to $950 million of bonds for roads,
bridges, airports and railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained that money for public schools was being
pushed aside as Republicans pressed for a transportation plan.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, Senate Democrats were saying they wanted
support for a $50-a-student increase in school aid this year and
next.
</P>
<P>
   Bond countered: ``Democrats want to leverage education against
highways. I'm not interested in trades. Each issue has to stand on
its own merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the activity, Rep. Mike O'Neal, a Hutchinson
Republican, left the statehouse to get married. A few hours later,
he and his wife, Cindy O'Neal, who is also his secretary, were back
in the Statehouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
