A3037 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-MISSOURI-KAN &LR;      04-10 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MISSOURI-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATES LOOK FOR ANOTHER CHANCE FOR CONCEALED-WEAPONS
LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri gun-rights' advocates, still angry
about the rejection of concealed handguns, are looking toward next
year's race for governor as the best chance of getting a law on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   And many are looking for revenge on organizations and
politicians who helped defeat Proposition B, which on Tuesday
failed 52 percent to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other gun advocates blame the loss on vote fraud, the governor
or newspapers. A few even blame the National Rifle Association for
not spending more, even through it spent nearly $4 million, almost
five times as much as the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Others saw in the election results the foundation of a future
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens in 104 of 114 counties held that the right to carry
was the right thing for them,'' said Whit O'Daniel, field director
for Missourians Against Crime. ``So the right to carry is not dead.
The right governor would make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B went to a public vote because Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
Democrat, has consistently threatened to veto any measure allowing
concealed weapons. Carnahan's term ends next year.
</P>
<P>
   But both parties' leading candidates in next year's race say
they would not sign a bill like Proposition B, which would have
allowed Missourians to carry concealed handguns with relatively few
restrictions. Both, however, left enough wiggle room to support a
more-stringent proposal.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Bob Holden, the Democratic front-runner, opposed
Proposition B and said he did not see the need for people to carry
concealed guns.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was more inclined to favor what is known as a
``may-issue'' law, which requires applicants to have a strong
reason for needing to carry a gun and gives authorities broad
discretion on who gets a permit.
</P>
<P>
   A bill might be palatable if it restricted where concealed guns
could be carried and limited permit holders to off-duty and retired
police officers, court personnel and others with a demonstrated
need, Holden said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Talent, the front-runner for the Republican
nomination, supported Proposition B as a crime deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's vote, in which Talent's home turf of St. Louis
County was the decisive factor, Talent said he would not sign a
similar bill if he were governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people made their decision, and you have to respect
that,'' Talent said. ``But I think the legislature could find a way
to address some of the concerns people had.''
</P>
<P>
   Talent said he could support a ``may-issue'' law. He said he
preferred ``shall-issue'' proposals like Proposition B, which
require authorities to issue permits to anyone who fits the
qualifications. Shall-issue laws have worked well in other states,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-rights advocates would find a ``may-issue'' law hard to
swallow. At a Web site sponsored by Missourians for Personal
Safety, several people posted suggestions on ways to tighten the
proposal to make it more acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   They said to prohibit guns near schools, in bars or at sports
stadiums and to exclude permits from people convicted of
misdemeanor sex crimes. But several others opposed that approach.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of messages suggested boycotting companies such as
Hallmark Cards Inc. that gave money to fight Proposition B. Others
suggested refusing to contribute to fund-raisers run by the Police
Chiefs Association and the Sheriff's Association _ even though the
Sheriff's Association was neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Several messages picked up on the National Rifle Association's
attack on Carnahan last week, vowing to take revenge next year when
he runs for the U.S. Senate. Carnahan did not actively campaign
against Proposition B, but the association still blamed him.
</P>
<P>
   The association said Carnahan orchestrated the campaign against
concealed weapons. He even dispatched his daughter, Robin, to run
Safe Schools and Workplaces, which led the opposition, the
association said. Carnahan spokesman Chris Sifford scoffed at the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 37 years old,'' Sifford said. ``She didn't ask her dad
whether she could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe Schools spokeswoman Lawren Massey said it was all sour
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wrote the bill, they picked the date for the vote, and
they managed the entire process, and now that it's decided, they
can't accept the choice that Missourians made,'' Massey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
