<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIEFING-INFO-KAN &LR;      04-10 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIEFING-INFO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA, OTHERS LAMENT LACK OF DETAILS ABOUT AIR CAMPAIGN OVER
SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MUPRHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In this, the information age, there is an
information gap between the war front in Yugoslavia and the home
front in America.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be just the way the Pentagon wants it.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists and other war-watchers are lamenting the lack of
details about the NATO air campaign over Serbia. They want more
specifics on the numbers of air missions, targets hit, tonnage of
bombs dropped and casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Pentagon often falls back on the term ``degraded''
to describe the effect of air strikes on Serbian capabilities. The
word was used six times, for example, in an 11-line Pentagon
statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make these very vague claims of degrading, but their
claims are extremely limited and there is no sign of a decisive
effect on the ground,'' said John Steinbruner, a senior fellow in
foreign policy studies at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbruner thinks the Pentagon would be happy to reveal more if
it had something positive to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own guess is that if there was a compelling display of
effectiveness directly linked to the operation in Kosovo, we'd be
seeing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said there have been many successful bombing
missions, but describing them all publicly would help Yugoslav
leader Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information you provide to him on what we believe we have
accomplished, how we accomplished it, what munitions we used, what
aircraft we used, when they took off, when they landed, all those
kinds of things, play into an intelligence picture we do not at
this point want to provide,'' Capt. Michael Doubleday, deputy
assistant secretary of defense, told reporters this week.
</P>
<P>
   But some Pentagon reporters said that Milosevic will know most
of what he needs to know about an attack after it's over, and that
to withhold information prevents the public from deciding whether
the war is advisable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's helpful in the long run,'' said Dana Priest
of The Washington Post. ``They don't give us any data, even weeks
later, to help us independently assess the advocacy of the air
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Priest and Richard Parker, defense correspondent for Knight
Ridder Newspapers, said the Pentagon gave out much more information
during other military campaigns, including daily reports on damage
inflicted in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get any of that,'' Parker said. ``We don't know where
the targets are, by and large. The maps they use each day have
markings on them, but only show generally what sort of target it
was and roughly what part of Serbia it was in.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday and Friday, the Pentagon did release its most
detailed photographs and films yet of air-strike damage, but they
still amounted mostly ``to a snapshot of one night's work,'' Parker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know cumulatively what is going on,'' Parker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Richard Bridges, director of defense information at the
Pentagon, said the government was not obligated ``to put a
scorecard out there'' cataloging bomb damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very frankly, I don't think the American people or the people
of Kansas City want the amount of detail the media are asking
for,'' Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   To a degree, the press is a victim of its own technological
advances. The Internet and 24-hour new channels produce
instantaneous information that could help the enemy, Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can report real-time aircraft taking off and show
pictures of the weapons they are carrying,'' Bridges said. ``That
is about as early a warning as you can get. This is a different
world that it was 10 years ago and it requires the application of
different concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference from 10 years ago _ shortly before the
Persian Gulf War _ is that the military leadership has changed.
Priest said Defense Secretary William Cohen was less open than his
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cohen is very insular, he keeps his business tight,'' Priest
said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, retired Lt. Gen. Tom Kelly recalled media briefings
he gave on the Persian Gulf War under the leadership of Gen. Colin
Powell and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two minutes of guidance from Colin Powell before I went
down there,'' Kelly said. ``He said, `Don't go down there and start
any fights and don't address future operations.' I wasn't told I
wasn't allowed to tell them anything else. Our assumption was that
everything comes out in the long run, so don't cover it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was easier for the Pentagon to talk about the Persian
Gulf War than about Serbia because it was an American campaign,
whereas 19-member NATO is in control of the Serbian effort, said
retired Army Col. Ken Allard.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is an altogether more committee-prone structure,'' said
Allard, now a senior associate with the Center for International
and Strategic Studies. ``You tend to get a much more homogenized
version of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker agreed that NATO is a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think NATO knows but isn't saying and I think a lot of
people here don't know until much later what happened,'' Parker
said. ``Cohen doesn't want to upset the allies and they control the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Allard said the Pentagon is justified in keeping from the media
details that could hamper the war effort and risk American lives.
He thinks the real problem is an absence of information on why the
Serbian campaign was started and why it isn't more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (the Persian Gulf War) we used overwhelming force to
achieve some very specific objectives,'' Allard said. ``Here, we
are using an underwhelming force for very vague purposes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
