A3042 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI &LR;      04-10 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT GAME WALTZES OLAZABAL INTO MASTERS LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Getting back on your feet again is a figure of
speech. For Jose Maria Olazabal, it was a goal, a dream, and for
the longest time, an impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 months in the mid-1990s, the leader of the Masters could
not walk, suffering from a lower back hernia that caused severe
pain in his feet. Friday, Olazabal cruised around Augusta National
effortlessly, firing a 6-under-par 66 to take a one-shot advantage
over Scott McCarron after two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly rejuvenated at 44, Greg Norman is in a tie for third
place with U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen at 139, turning Magnolia
Lane into memory lane. They are three shots behind Olazabal, who is
at 8-under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still looking for Tiger Woods and David Duval, the
supposed favorites, you'll find them far down the leaderboard.
Woods lofted one into Rae's Creek Friday and shot his second
consecutive even-par round. Duval had a 74, leaving the world's
top-ranked player at 145, nine shots back.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, a 33-year-old Spaniard, has long been recognized as
one of the world's finest golfers, winning 21 tournaments across
the globe, including a Masters championship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He always plays well at Augusta, finishing 14th or higher in
seven of his past eight appearances. That knowledge is helping him
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very special place for me,'' Olazabal said.
``Experience is a great factor here. The more you know the course,
the more you know what you have to do, where you have to hit the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Olazabal had direction, hitting 13 of 17 greens and
stroking only 25 putts. Three years ago, he didn't know where he
was going. He thought he was headed for a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly walk,'' Olazabal said. ``I watched golf and TV
and listened to music. It was not very nice at all. When you can't
walk, that's the lowest you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal was misdiagnosed by three doctors, including one from
the Mayo Clinic. They all thought he had rheumatoid arthritis in
his feet. He eventually got another opinion from a German doctor
who discovered that his foot problems were being caused by a lower
back hernia.
</P>
<P>
   His treatment consisted of physical therapy along with
injections of iron, zinc, amino acids and shark cartilage, which
could still come in handy if Norman closes in this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days when I woke up in the morning, I knew my first
move would be to the bathroom,'' he told the Manchester Guardian.
``It was only nine feet from by bedroom, but I couldn't get there
on my feet. I had to crawl. I would get very, very depressed. I
wanted to just walk again at that time. I never thought of suicide
because always in the back of my mind, I hoped I might be made well
again that I could play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal could not drive a car or a golf ball. For six months,
he did not touch a club. A cane seemed like a more realistic
possibility until he got the proper diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   He did not play in a golf tournament from September 1995 to
February '97, missing the '96 Masters, two years after winning the
green jacket. He watched the tournament from his home in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to try to be positive in a situation like
that,'' Olazabal said. ``I was just thinking that one day I will be
back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he was. Olazabal has a wonderful quick tempo and
splendid short game that he crafted as an adolescent. At the age of
15, he noticed that his friends were typically hitting the ball 30
to 40 yards farther than him. To compensate, he worked on shots
around the green.
</P>
<P>
   The early practice may have contributed to two par-saving
recoveries Friday. A chip from behind the fifth green led to a par
putt from 7 feet. A blast from a greenside bunker at 7 led to a par
putt from 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Olazabal birdied after coaxing a delicate chip down a
severe slope within one foot of the hole. He capped his round with
a birdie putt from 10 feet at the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, a 33-year-old from Sacramento, seems like a fun guy to
have a beer with at the 19th hole. He and his buddies at UCLA used
to have a few on Friday night before they would settle in to watch
the Masters on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron figured a TV set was as close as he would get to
Augusta. He wanted to turn pro but realized he wasn't good enough.
He worked with his father in the golf apparel business before
rekindling his game.
</P>
<P>
   He used to putt left-handed but has become more successful with
a long putter more commonly seen on the senior tour. The highlight
of McCarron's round came when he used that oversized wand and
drained a 55-footer at No. 4, the only birdie of the day at the
205-yard hole.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, McCarron has used his length off the tee and touch on
the greens to become a legitimate candidate to win the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I get my power from?'' he said in response to a
question. ``I don't know. I've always hit the golf ball far. It's
only recently that I've been able to find it after I hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, if you are looking for McCarron, he's somewhere in the
middle of the pack or in the column under ``Missed Cut.'' But he
feels comfortable in these surroundings, in this kind of company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a lesser-known,'' McCarron said.
``When I'm playing with Norman or (Fred) Couples, I feel I'm as
good as them. You have to believe that or you don't belong out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal is just happy to be out here again. When asked about a
shot that he hit at 13 on Thursday, when his ball miraculously
skipped across the hazard and landed safely on the other side,
Olazabal said: ``It was a good break, but I haven't had too many
breaks in my life, so I'll take that one.''
</P>
<P>
   If Olazabal continues to play like he has, this weekend might be
a grueling test for everyone else, but just a walk in the park for
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
