<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3046 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NORMAN-SPI &LR;      04-10 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NORMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK HOPING NEW OUTLOOK KEEPS IN MASTERS CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Blazing into contention, Greg Norman returned to
Augusta National yesterday, and now everyone is wondering if his
demons will too.
</P>
<P>
   The dashing Australian shot a 4-under-par 68 to move into a tie
for third place and within three shots of leader Jose Maria
Olazabal after the second round of The Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Olazabal will command much of the attention this
afternoon, Norman has the most intriguing storyline. Rejected three
times here, he was defeated by Jack Nicklaus in 1986, demoralized
by Larry Mize in '87 and devastated by Nick Faldo in '96.
</P>
<P>
   The setback three years ago was one of the most memorable
collapses in golf. Norman entered the final round with a six-shot
lead and lost to Nick Faldo by five strokes after shooting a 78.
</P>
<P>
   How will he hold up this weekend? Will he win his first green
jacket? Will he respond under pressure or wilt like he has in the
past?
</P>
<P>
   Reporters fired questions at Norman, who handled every one of
them like the deft veteran he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite enjoying it, to tell you the truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since undergoing shoulder surgery last April that forced him to
give up golf for seven months, Norman has undergone a
transformation. He looks at golf as being a part of life, but not
the largest part. He would rather be at home with his wife, Laura,
and teen-aged kids, Morgan-Leigh and Gregory, than on the driving
range.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has a big-picture perspective that could, in an ironic
development, produce a Masters title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he tried too hard,'' said David Leadbetter, his coach.
``A different attitude can really help in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Laura Norman, ``He realized there are other things in life.
That may translate into playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mark O'Meara decided to quit being a perfectionist, he won
The Masters and British Open last year. Now that Norman has stopped
being so driven, perhaps the dividends will be evident Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling extremely relaxed and in control of what I'm
doing,'' Norman said. ``I don't have a sense of urgency. Urgency is
something where you're trying to force the issue. If you try to
force the issue, you don't relax on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman still has the desire. He believes that, even at 44, he
can win The Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just as big a killer as I've ever been on the golf course
_ as I used to be _ because I want it,'' he said. ``But at the same
time, I've surrounded myself with the right things, and it takes a
lot of pressure off. Golf is not everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman bogeyed the first hole Friday to fall to even-par. The
old Norman might have pressed and ended up losing patience and
ground to the leaders. The new Norman stuck with it and did not
have another bogey. He was solid and spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Once a lamentable figure, Norman could become the conversation
piece that talks back this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the tragedies we have had here, it would be a little
sweeter for us,'' said Laura Norman.
</P>
<P>
   His wife added that Norman was bothered more by Mize's
sudden-death chip-in than Faldo's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg just didn't play well (against Faldo),'' she said. ``When
you don't play well, you can justify losing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Faldo defeat stands out because of the way it happened,
a supposedly gifted golfer proved that even the most skilled can
suffer mental breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Norman said the loss to Faldo had more of a positive than
negative impact. He still hears from people offering encouragement,
stemming from what happened three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My locker is full of letters this week,'' he said. ``It
changed my life and made me appreciate people in a different way
because of the support they gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Norman would feel vindicated if he earns the green
jacket Sunday. Friday, he would not speculate on the possibility.
But his wife did, revealing that part of Norman's competitive
nature will never go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a heartbreaker for him here,'' Laura Norman said.
``I don't think it would make everything else OK. At the end of the
day, he would still say he wanted the other two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
