<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ROCKIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS DOUBLES FUN FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a night when Gary Sheffield was on the bench
with a sore right hip, the Los Angeles Dodgers' offense got a jolt
from first baseman Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Karros tied a Dodgers record with three doubles and led a 17-hit
attack as the Dodgers rebounded from their lone loss of the season
with a 9-6 win Friday night over the Colorado Rockies at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Karros also tied a career high with four hits, scored twice, had
an RBI and even stole his second base of the season. Devon White
also tied a career high with four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort (1-0) won in his season debut, though it was
sometimes laboring. He allowed three hits and three runs (two
earned) and struck out seven, but he also wasn't very pitch
efficient. He threw 98 pitches (54 strikes) in five innings. Jeff
Shaw got the final three outs for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies starter John Thomson (0-1) was knocked out in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' third double, a drive to the left-center-field fence,
scored Todd Hundley to give the Dodgers a 6-4 lead. Karros stole
third, and after Mike DeJean relieved Chuck McElroy and walked
Adrian Beltre, Jacob Brumfield's infield single plated Karros to
make it 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Dave Hansen continued his hot start with a single
to right to score Beltre with the Dodgers' eighth run.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers staked Dreifort the four-run lead, but up reared the
control problems Dreifort tends to suffer from inning to inning.
</P>
<P>
   He had allowed one hit through four innings, though he needed a
baserunning blunder by Dante Bichette to get out of a bases-loaded
situation in the second. Dreifort, who tied a career high with six
walks, walked three Rockies in that inning but was unscathed when
Jeff Reed lined to shortstop Jose Vizcaino, who caught the ball and
also caught Bichette breaking for home instead of back to the base.
Vizcaino fired to Beltre for the double play.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the end of the walks for Dreifort. After looking
masterful and appearing confident in striking out the side in the
fourth, he walked Darryl Hamilton with two outs in the fifth.
Hamilton stole second and Neifi Perez followed with a base hit to
center. But with the memory fresh of White throwing out Mike
Lansing at home Thursday, Hamilton held at third.
</P>
<P>
   Why steal a base with two outs and then hold on a single to
center? It didn't matter because Dreifort uncorked one of his three
wild pitches to allow Hamilton to score and cut the Dodgers lead to
5-2. Dreifort then walked Angel Echevarria, and Perez scored on a
single by Bichette. Vinny Castilla struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The final Dodger to appear this season was Dave Mlicki, who took
over for Dreifort. Mlicki, the sixth starter in a five-man
rotation, gave up a leadoff double to Hamilton in the seventh.
Hamilton went to third on a fly out and scored on Roberto Ramirez's
single to right as the Rockies pulled within 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 1-0 lead in the second when Karros doubled
and scored on Beltre's double to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Perez scored on Eric Young's throwing error in the third to even
the score 1-1, but the Dodgers answered quickly. White, who singled
in his first three at-bats, began the rally in the third with a
one-out hit. His hustle and baserunning savvy gave the Dodgers a
2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi singled to left and White made a wide turn around
second. Rockies left fielder Bichette tried to throw behind White
at second, so White immediately broke toward third. Lansing, the
Rockies' second baseman, threw the ball wildly to third, allowing
White to score and Mondesi wound up on third.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi scored on a wild pitch to give the Dodgers a 3-1 lead.
Todd Hundley singled and Karros doubled to put runners in scoring
position, but all the Dodgers could muster was a Beltre sacrifice
fly to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers padded their lead in the fourth, but they might have
run themselves out of a bigger inning. Young singled with one out
and went to third on Vizcaino's double. White singled to right to
score Young and put the Dodgers ahead 5-1, but the chance for the
big inning was squelched when Vizcaino was thrown out at the plate
by Echevarria. It came with Mondesi on deck.
</P>
</TEXT>
