<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TIMBERWOLVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT TIMBERWOLVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Few who saw Friday night's game will buy the
notion _ in fact, the very words seem absurd _ but the Los Angeles
Lakers wake up today as a resurgent force in the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of a too-difficult 96-89 victory over the Minnesota
Timberwolves at the Forum, the Lakers reclaimed fourth place in the
conference for the first time since March 25.
</P>
<P>
   With two straight wins, a home-court seeding (for now) and
something resembling momentum, the Lakers can now focus on a
stretch run that will give them four shots at conference-leading
Portland, starting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They hardly appear up to the task, based on Friday's near loss
to a depleted Timberwolves team that was down two starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers squandered a 10-point, third-quarter lead and let the
Wolves pull ahead by two points five minutes into the fourth.
Minnesota was missing offensive stalwarts Joe Smith and Terrell
Brandon, and Kevin Garnett had an off-night. But little-known Tom
Hammonds scored 22 points _ 12 in the fourth quarter _ to lead a
surprising charge.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota forged its last tie at 84-84 with about two minutes to
go, but Shaquille O'Neal staved off the upset, scoring four
straight points, then feeding Robert Horry for a layup to regain a
four-point lead with a just over a minute to go.
</P>
<P>
   Former Clippers guard James Robinson threw up a 3-point airball
with about a minute left to end the threat, and Glen Rice's two
free throws secured a 93-87 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Rice finished with 25 points each, and Horry provided
a needed punch with 13 points on 5-for-5 shooting, and seven
rebounds off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 games to go, there's precious little time for
momentum-building toward the postseason. What the Lakers really
need is a long string of wins to ensure a top-four seeding in the
conference and home-court advantage in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're going _ winning one, losing one, winning two,
losing one _ I think we can't afford to focus on anything but our
game,'' Derek Harper said. ``I think right now everyone is
jockeying themselves for the end of the season and trying to be on
a positive note. You want to end the season on a positive to go
into the playoffs and be playing good basketball at the end of the
season. That's where our focus should be. Hopefully, that's where
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers led 50-43 at halftime, but they should have had a
much bigger cushion against a depleted Timberwolves team.
</P>
<P>
   Starting forward Smith was attending his father's funeral, and
starting point guard Brandon was out with a right thigh contusion,
leaving Minnesota with a starting lineup of Garnett and four guys
they picked up at the ``Y'' _ Sam Mitchell, Dean Garrett, Bobby
Jackson and Malik Sealy.
</P>
<P>
   Even Garnett wasn't at full strength, playing with a bruised
abdomen suffered the night before against the Clippers. But he was
healthy enough to post 12 points and seven rebounds in the first
half, and along with Sam Mitchell's 10 points, kept the Wolves
close.
</P>
<P>
   Led by 17 points from Rice and 13 points and 10 rebounds from
O'Neal, the Lakers shot 52.5 percent in the half and outrebounded
Minnesota 24-19. Somehow, even shooting 38.3 percent, the Wolves
pulled within two points around the two-minute mark. But a late
surge, started with a Rice 3-pointer, gave the Lakers the
seven-point edge at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
