<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY BEATS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Chuck Finley has had this love-hate
relationship with the Texas Rangers during his career. He loves
coming to Texas because his parents always make the trip from his
home state of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But he hates losing and that's what the Anaheim Angels pitcher
always seems to do against the Rangers. Not this time, though.
</P>
<P>
   Finley gave the Angels exactly what they needed _ six good
innings _ and the offense snapped its minislump in an 8-4 Angels
victory Friday before 31,633 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (1-0) had not beaten the Rangers since June 29, 1995, and
it took a 20-run outburst by the Angels offense in that one. He
entered Friday's game with a personal nine-game losing streak
against the Rangers and a 7-16 lifetime mark, including 4-9 in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Was Finley worried about the streak?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't, but my parents were, he said. ``My dad (Charles)
mentioned if I didn't do good he was going to charge me for gas.
But I could give up eight runs and he'll hug me and say I did a
good job. Thank God he doesn't know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley was not dominating by any means _ he gave up four runs
and nine hits _ but he was efficient while making 91 pitches,
striking out five and walking one. No Angels starter had gone more
than 41/3 innings in the club's first three games, and the bullpen
needed a break.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who was pushed back in the starting rotation because a
neck strain during spring training, provided such a break, handing
the ball over to Mark Petkovsek to start the seventh. Petkovsek,
acquired from the Cardinals during the offseason, threw two
scoreless innings and was followed by Troy Percival, who pitched a
1-2-3 ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with Finley, even if he didn't get off to a good
start. He gave up three runs and seven hits in the first three
innings before settling into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started going with more slow stuff after the first three
innings,'' Finley said. ``I started throwing curveballs and splits
and spotted the fastball around. (Catcher) Charlie (O'Brien) did a
great job orchestrating the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it helped Finley that the offense escaped the spell
the Indians pitching staff had put on the team. After the three
season-opening games against the Indians, the Angels began the
four-game set with Texas hitting .202 (19 for 94) as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro, getting his third consecutive start in left
field, set the tone early, hitting his first major-league home run
to lead off the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us a real lift in the first inning,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``I sensed a different atmosphere on the bench
tonight. They said we've got to pick it up and get it going. We
can't let these guys trample over us. I was happy to see the guys
picked it especially after a long night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels didn't arrive in Texas until 7 a.m. Friday and didn't
get to their hotel until about 8. But it didn't seem to affect the
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon homered (No.2) and doubled. Troy Glaus had two hits,
including a two-run double and Todd Greene hit his first home run
of the season. Randy Velarde, Darin Erstad and Andy Sheets also had
two hits apiece in the 12-hit attack. Rangers starter John Burkett
(0-1) lasted only 22/3 innings (5 runs, 7 hits).
</P>
<P>
   For one night anyway, no one was worried about a lineup that
didn't have Mo Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and Gary DiSarcina. And when
Palmeiro led off the game with his homer (one homer in 418
major-league at-bats), the Angels had to know it was going to be
their night and a memorable one for Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had about three (homers) since Little League, so I kind
of remember 'em,'' he said. ``I was coming around third base and
Tim Belcher told me to slow down. I said I know what I'm doing.
Let's get this over with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
