r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-10 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NL WEST, IQ A BIG STAT CATEGORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a mental Murderers Row, the greatest
collection of baseball brainpower since John J. McGraw dined alone.
</P>
<P>
   The National League West presents a rare challenge for new
arrival Davey Johnson of the Los Angeles Dodgers. Almost every time
he looks across a baseball diamond this season, attempting to read
the opposing manager, he'll see brilliance staring back.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they'll be seeing the same in him.
</P>
<P>
   There's Colorado's Jim Leyland, Johnson's opposite number Friday
night, his cigarette-burned fingers clutching a $2 million-a-year
contract, richest in the history of baseball managers.
</P>
<P>
   There's San Francisco's Dusty Baker, the only manager to wear
wristbands, because you can work up a sweat squeezing 90 wins out
of the division's poorest franchise.
</P>
<P>
   There's San Diego's Bruce Bochy, hard-looking under those albino
eyelashes but really a nice guy, maligned for the pitching moves
that backfired in Game 1 of the World Series but deserving credit
for the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   There's Arizona's Buck Showalter, a weary-looking 42-year-old,
the only one of the group who hasn't won a division title, though
he was on his way with the '94 Yankees before the strike.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Johnson, owner of the highest career winning
percentage among active major-league managers, a percentage that
edged upward to .576 with a 9-6 victory over Leyland's Rockies on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, maybe never, has there been a division like this, in
which every manager has a Manager of the Year trophy somewhere at
home, every manager has led a team to the playoffs, every manager
has an unblemished record of improving the teams that hire him.
</P>
<P>
   On average, when one of the five NL West managers has taken over
a club, it has moved up by 14 games and two places in the standings
in his first full season.
</P>
<P>
   After Leyland went from Florida to the Rockies last October,
former Marlin Gary Sheffield was quoted saying, ``He makes them
better by 10 games right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen games? Ten games? Can one man be worth that much? Can
five men?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put much emphasis on that,'' Johnson said in the
Dodger Stadium dugout. ``The old thing is: Players win games,
managers lose 'em. I don't often think I won a game or lost a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Raul) Mondesi (for instance) wins it. If I give him a rest
that might have gotten him playing at a high level, maybe....''
</P>
<P>
   How much does a good manager matter?
</P>
<P>
   Leyland's next victory will be his 1,000th in the majors. Only
Tony La Russa, Bobby Cox and Joe Torre, among active managers, have
done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the only guy who's (also) lost 1,000,'' said Leyland
(he isn't), ``So I don't pay too much attention to things like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago the Marlins won the World Series. Last year
(after the salary dump), I lost 108 games. So I'm living proof that
it's not the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a way of expressing the managers' mission
statement: Put the players in position to make the fullest use of
their individual talents.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect of having a division full of proven winners might
be this: They cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the game, you don't feel superior to the other
manager and you don't feel inferior,'' Leyland said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson, who is 11 wins away from 1,000: ``I know what
Jim's going to do. Jim knows what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What they don't always know, less than two months after they
reported to spring training, is what their players are going to do.
So neither Johnson nor Leyland is in midseason form. Johnson thinks
it will take three or four turns through the rotation before his
pitchers' tendencies become recognizable. Namely _ the tipoffs that
his starters are tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Baltimore's Mike) Mussina, he'd start throwing more of the
soft stuff. Scotty (Erickson), he'd start muscling up, trying to
throw harder, and his ball would straighten out,'' Johnson said,
recalling his two seasons with Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn a lot. Like (Thursday) night with Carlos (Perez).''
</P>
<P>
   After that game was delayed 1 hour 25 minutes by rain, the
Dodgers left-hander threw just 56 pitches in the first six innings
while shutting out the Rockies. Then he gave up a three-run homer
to Todd Helton and the Dodgers were on their way to their first
loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I misjudged the effect of the delay,'' Johnson said.
``Because one of the signs of being tired is hanging a slider.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, Johnson had to decide whether to put Sheffield
in the lineup a night after the left fielder came out of a game
with a pulled hip muscle. He kept him on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially in the cool weather, it's better to be on the safe
side,'' Johnson said. ``A guy comes in cold, he pulls something,
and !ital!then!off! I've cost the team 10 games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
