<HEADLINE>
SHARKS BITE DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It wasn't too long ago that the Anaehim Mighty
Ducks were talking about finishing as high as fourth in the Western
Conference. Then fifth became the goal as the Phoenix Coyotes
slowly pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night the San Jose Sharks dropped the Ducks into
sixth place as they defeated Anaheim 4-1 before 17,174 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   With possible home-ice advantage on the line, the Ducks ran into
a red-hot goalie in Steve Shields and allowed three third-period
goals.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied 1-1, Shields somehow got his glove up to rob
Paul Kariya's backhander on a breakaway 1{ minute into the final
period, and got just enough of another Kariya shot moments later.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Sharks took the lead for good. Jeff Friesen easily
banged home Magnus Ragnarsson's pass at 2:19 thanks to a pick that
Vincent Damphousse set on Jason Marshall, preventing the Anaheim
defenseman from getting to the other side of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks put the game away with a goal by Owen Nolan at 9:30,
and Joe Murphy made it 4-1 at 11:50 on an outnumbered attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks came out strong, outshooting the Sharks 9-1 in the
first nine minutes of the game. But Shields, who is 9-0-2 in his
last 11 games, made a key save on Kariya's wide-open bid from the
right circle 1{ minutes into the game and another on Teemu Selanne
while Anaheim was on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Ducks' recent first-period woes caught up with them.
The Sharks outshot the Ducks 12-4 the balance of the period and
took a 1-0 lead at 18:22 when Alexander Korolyuk beat Kariya to the
net and scored a power play goal after the young San Jose winger
had drawn a hooking penalty on Fredrik Olausson.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim has been outscored 10-4 and outshot 46-26 in the first
periods of its last six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks got on the scoreboard when Tomas Sandstrom, in a rare
shift as a point man, one-timed Marty McInnis' pass by Shields to
tie the game 1-1 at 8:19. It was the Ducks' NHL-leading 81st power
play goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim nearly took the lead moments later on a broken play. The
puck took a wild bounce in front of the net and went directly to
Kariya in front of Shields. But the San Jose goalie made a great
glove save on Karya's backhander.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks got two scoring chances in the final minutes of the
period. Nolan couldn't get his stick on Damphousse's centering pass
with four minutes left and Friesen was stopped by Hebert with less
10 seconds remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
