<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3059 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      04-10 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S STAND ON KOSOVO CARRIES RISKS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (ANALYSIS) 
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain's presidential prospects were
elevated by his early advocacy for a U.S. ground forces option in
Kosovo, but his challenge is to keep momentum from disappearing be
fore it begins to translate into campaign donations and improved
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's politically risky Kosovo position _ declaring that the
U.S. must be prepared for ground troops and casualties _ has
distinguished him from a GOP field of presiden tial candidates who
by comparison have seemed cautious. The popular perception is that
McCain, largely through his frequent television ap pearances on
Kosovo, has begun to leapfrog over some of the Republi can
presidential contenders in the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Now McCain finds himself in the forefront of a volatile
foreign-policy debate that certainly could heighten his White House
chances, but it could also damage them considera bly.
</P>
<P>
   After seizing the mantle of Ko sovo leadership, McCain is
planning several moves next week, not with out some risk, that are
likely to keep him out front. In the most important of those moves,
McCain is expected to encourage Senate Republican and Democratic
leaders to support a resolution on how the U.S. should proceed in
the complicated Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, not yet written, would likely endorse the use of
ground forces, if they were deemed necessary by the Clinton
administra tion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain just returned from meet ings in Belgium with NATO allies.
In a letter signed Friday, McCain and eight other lawmakers on the
trip encouraged President Clinton to urge NATO to plan for
additional military missions, including the use of ground forces if
needed to reverse ``genocidal actions'' against Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said NATO's mission of deterring Yugoslav President
Slo bodan Milosevic and his military capability could require
``many more weeks or months to succeed,'' and it warned that ``the
American public also needs to be better prepared for the likelihood
of alli ance casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is expected to lay out his latest Kosovo thinking at a
speech Tuesday to the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a Wash ington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, McCain's initial Ko sovo expressions, like a
double-word score in Scrabble, have man aged to achieve two goals
simulta neously.
</P>
<P>
   By indefinitely postponing his presidential announcement tour be
cause of Kosovo, McCain high lighted his principal campaign theme
that he can rise above politics when the national interest is at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   And his early call not to rule out ground forces illuminated his
per sistent criticism of the White House for seeming indecisive on
this and other foreign-policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   A former prisoner of war in Vietnam, McCain has traditionally
been hesitant about committing U.S. troops overseas with no
definitive end in sight. In Bosnia, for example, McCain long
opposed calling in American pilots.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had doubts about Presi dent Clinton's Kosovo policy, too,
but said that once the mission was under way, it was incumbent upon
the United States to do anything it could to win.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ``is, I think literally the only major political figure
in either party who is forthrightly addressing the issue and
providing real leader ship,'' said Mike Hellon, a member of the
Republican National Commit tee from Arizona. ``I have to tell you,
I think our own guys (in the GOP) haven't fared much better'' than
the Democrats, Hellon said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides said it was too early to assess any potential
political gain from his position on Kosovo because there is
traditionally a ``lag'' separating events from fund-raising and
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what this will do is give McCain a temporary boost,
because it will make more people think about him,'' said Arthur
Miller, a University of Iowa political scien tist. ``But if this
basically recedes from the forefront, I have a feeling that it's
hard to speak out on foreign-policy matters when there isn't
something urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now McCain is ubiqui tous, appearing on as many as seven
national television programs in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Opinsky, spokesman for McCain's presidential exploratory
committee, said Friday that the senator has not been consulting his
campaign advisers before adopting positions on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategic interests of Amer ica are far more important to
him than his own political short-term desires,'' Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain faces potential political hazards in supporting a mission
that could result in an untold number of U.S. casualties and that
many of his Republican colleagues consider ill-defined.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican senators are torn over Kosovo, Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., said in a recent interview,
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a very conflicted Republican (caucus) here which
supports NATO, which is as con cerned about humanitarian issues as
anybody, and which is not afraid to use American force,
particularly against dictators like Milosevic,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl added that he and other leading GOP senators were ``signif
icantly influenced'' by a private briefing they received before the
airstrikes in which former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger said
he could not support the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``His point was that, `Yes, if you don't do anything, there will
be a black eye for NATO because the threat was made,' '' Kyl said.
``But he balances that against the fact there is no national
security interest of the United States of any signifi cance. The
fact that you have a bad guy like Milosevic is not a reason to go
to war, because you've got a lot of bad guys around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kyl said, ``Kissinger believes, as do I, that this
adminis tration never had a good plan about how to achieve its
objectives, and in fact, the objectives have been changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl, unlike McCain, voted last month against authorizing Clinton
to initiate military operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But once the mission started, Kyl said that he, like McCain,
wanted to ensure the troops be given every chance to succeed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
