<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CELEBRITY-CHEFS-ART     04-10 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CELEBRITY-CHEFS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN:   Calif., Mass., Ga., Wash., Ore.)  
 MORE AND MORE CHEFS RELY ON IMAGE MAKERS  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BRYAN MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bob Thomas, a stocky, amiable 29-year-old chef,
stands in front of a green upholstered wall, a spotlight
illuminating his face and blue sweatshirt while a video camera
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A mock television hostess welcomes him to ``the show'' and says,
``Bob, tell us about your new computerized restaurant guide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's really fun to use,'' Thomas replies through a
mile-wide grin. ``You can find any kind of restaurant you want in
Boston, without having to push a single button.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the videotape is played back.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. OK. That's good, but there are a few things to keep in
mind,'' said David Kratz, president of Kratz &AMP; Jensen Inc., a New
York public relations firm. ``One, take your hands off your hips
and use them to gesture; two, be more enthusiastic and passionate.
Make friends with the host: `Hi, Nicole, it's so nice to be here
with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kratz belongs to the fast-growing field of chef publicists,
behind-the-scenes operatives who pump the bellows for hot and
want-to-be-hot kitchen celebrities. As well-known culinary figures
spend less time in the kitchen and more in front of cameras or on
book tours, publicists help them secure all sorts of
extracurricular activities, from kitchen-ware endorsements to
consulting, book writing and selling products (including
themselves) on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hot chef is the multimedia chef. ``When you get a job as
a chef, or a pastry chef, you start at a certain salary,''
explained Jacques Torres, the pastry chef at Le Cirque 2000 in
Manhattan. ``That salary will go up gradually; but if you really
want to make a better living, you have to get into consulting,
books, television and all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Through these activities, high-profile chefs, many of whom own
their restaurants, can easily double or triple their basic incomes,
which usually run around $70,000 to $100,000 in major cities. It
can also give their restaurants a lift, even when the chef is
hundreds of miles away shooting an ad for imported mustard.
</P>
<P>
   In its March issue, Forbes magazine for the first time included
five chefs among its ``Celebrity 100,'' the highest-paid and most
influential people in various professions. Leading the pack was
Wolfgang Puck, the gastronomic mahatma whose restaurant empire
spans the country and who also has a line of frozen foods. Puck's
income for 1998 was estimated at $10.5 million, followed by Emeril
Lagasse, the television sensation from New Orleans, at $2.4
million; Jean-Georges Vongerichten of New York ($2.1 million);
Nobuyuki Matsuhisa of Los Angeles and Manhattan ($750,000); and
Daniel Boulud, also of Manhattan ($700,000). All have at least one
publicist behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Torres has been garnering more press than the pinot noir grape
in recent years, partly owing to the efforts of his three
publicist-collaborators, Kris Kruid, Fern Berman and Tina Wright.
Torres is planning his second television series, has written two
cookbooks, has a Web site, lectures at the French Culinary
Institute in Manhattan and has been featured in countless magazine
and newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Splichal, a virtual unknown when he was the chef at Max
au Triangle in Los Angeles in 1983, received prodigious media
coverage, much of it organized by his wife, Christine. With his
suddenly heightened profile, Splichal began planning his own
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we were well-known, it was easier to raise money,'' he
explained. In 1989, with $650,000, he opened Patina on modish
Melrose Avenue in Los Angeles. Today he owns 13 restaurants,
consults for Windstar Cruises, runs a catering business, has
developed the commissary for 20th Century Fox, and is even, he
said, ``talking to the archdiocese of Los Angeles to develop food
service for their new cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the early 1980s, most chefs were cave dwellers in their
sweltering kitchens, and diners had little chance of, or interest
in, meeting them. If a publicity offer came their way, they handled
it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Chef publicists, who used to mainly send out news releases and
pitch stories to reporters, today are much more involved with their
clients' careers. They coach chefs on how to comport themselves in
interviews, send them to high-profile charity and industry events,
help them with book ideas, search out corporate endorsements, help
train restaurant staffs and even act as in-house critics. The tab?
From $2,000 to $6,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Kratz &AMP; Jensen has offices in New York, San Francisco, Chicago
and Los Angeles, with 50 employees and billings in excess of $6
million. It handles a diverse range of clients, from celebrities to
chief executives; chefs and restaurants represent about 30 percent
of its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a chef is on TV, it's not about food, it's about
entertaining,'' said Lou Ekus, a media trainer in Greenfield,
Mass., who has prepped culinary luminaries like Lagasse, Stephan
Pyles of Dallas and Bobby Flay of New York. Ekus charges $3,000
plus expenses for a two-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
   The chef-publicist business is dominated by individuals (mostly
women) who have a handful of clients they work with intensively.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Tamara Wilson, an independent publicist in Seattle,
represents a half-dozen restaurants in the city, including the
Painted Table, Tulio and Stars Bar and Dining, owned by Jeremiah
Tower, who also owns Stars restaurant in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   One recent publicity coup was arranging a fishing trip to the
Copper River in Alaska for Tower and Hubert Trimbach, a wine maker
from Alsace. ``It was something different, and we got a lot of
press,'' Ms. Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The publicists still spend a lot of time, of course, courting
the media _ through lunches, news releases and even gifts like
chocolate truffles at Easter. While some journalists grumble that
publicists overwhelm them with a Vesuvius of inconsequential
material, many say they can be useful.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to hiring a publicist is mounting a sustained
advertising campaign, something most restaurants cannot afford. A
substantial advertising effort costs an estimated 2 to 3 percent of
gross income. When a publicist books a chef on television or has
him written up in the print media, the attention is not only more
credible but can be less expensive in the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   A high-profile chef, though, can be a double-edged sword for a
restaurant. In general, the more renowned a chef becomes, the more
control or equity he wants. Often, that results in the chef's
leaving for a better offer, or opening his own place.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Dan Sachs opened Spruce restaurant in Chicago three years ago to
widespread plaudits for his chef, Keith Luce. Even though Luce had
a limited partnership in the restaurant, he decided last July to
leave for the Restaurant at Little Nell, a resort in Aspen, Colo.
``Publicity definitely had a role in my decision,'' Luce explained.
``The more status you get from the media, the better the offers
that come along.''
</P>
<P>
   For many chefs, the ultimate is turning themselves into a brand,
which often leads to corporate endorsements for everything from
kitchen equipment, chefs' attire and tableware to the likes of the
National Pork Products Council, Plugra Butter, Cervena Venison, and
Foods From Spain. Airlines also hire celebrity chefs to develop
menus.
</P>
<P>
   Cervena, the American marketing arm for New Zealand venison,
took on 15 leading chefs to publicize the product nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked very well for everybody for six years,'' said Mary
Anne Harmon, the company's marketing manager until the program
ended in March. ``We had a product that nobody was doing anything
with, so we wanted to gain credibility with a core group of
influential chefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The chefs, among them Kevin Rathbun of Nava restaurant in
Atlanta, David Holben of the Riviera in Dallas, and Charlie Palmer
of Aureole in New York, were paid only a few thousand dollars a
year for public appearances. But the important currency was in
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In return for being in the program, they received a lot of
media exposure,'' Ms. Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, chefs and publicists say it is difficult to quantify
the precise effects of public relations versus advertising. Some
successful chefs and restaurants eschew publicists, saying they can
do the job better themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got into business, I believed that the surest way
to stay out of the press was to have someone sending massive
mailings of packets and letters out,'' explained Danny Meyer, an
owner-partner in four successful Manhattan restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as chefs increasingly become celebrities in their own
right, they are expecting to be treated like stars, too. ``Chefs
have egos like everybody else,'' said Margie Korshak, a Chicago
publicist. ``In their restaurants they have always courted VIPs;
now they want to be one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
