<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-GRIZZLIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIZZLIES KNOCK OFF SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Dr. Jekyll one night. Mr. Hyde the next.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours after pulling off an impressive upset of the
Portland Trail Blazers, the Sonics were slapped with an equally
stunning 98-93 loss by the Vancouver Grizzlies Friday night at GM
Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said after his
team had once again fallen below .500 at 17-18. ``But give
Vancouver some credit. They made some plays down the stretch, and
we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, and somehow, the Sonics were in it at the frenzied end.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of 3-point baskets by Dale Ellis trimmed the Grizzlies'
lead to 90-88 with 1:35 remaining. But after Vin Baker rebounded a
rare missed shot by the Grizzlies' Shareef Abdur-Rahim, Gary Payton
threw the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   But the clincher came with 16.9 points remaining. Just when it
appeared the Sonics had made a defensive stop and would get the
ball with the Grizzlies clinging to a 92-90 lead, Terry Dehere
leaned around Ellis and tossed in a 3-pointer as the shot-clock
expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit a lot of big shots,'' Dehere, a 6-foot-4 guard, said
of his only basket in the game. ``This is definitely a big shot,
where we can win a close game down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side was the Sonics losing another close game down the
stretch to a team they should have, and could have, beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how our season has gone,'' guard Hersey Hawkins said.
``It's been crazy bounces, one after the other. We had the Dehere
thing, the rebound, loose balls. It doesn't matter. For some reason
we haven't been able to come up with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on the road, where the Sonics are now 4-13 entering
tomorrow's game against the Lakers in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the seventh win of the season for the Grizzlies, who
appeared as if they would be blown off their own court early in the
first quarter as Seattle stormed to a 19-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Grizzlies seemed to get more energized before a
sellout crowd of 19,193 as the Sonics struggled with their shooting
all evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never did have an answer for Abdur-Rahim, who scored
28 points, grabbed 11 rebounds and blocked three shots. Equally
impressive and effective was rookie Felipe Lopez, who scored 21
points and also had 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, meanwhile, shot 38.6 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished with just 13 points, nine below his average, and
was 4 of 17 from the field. Detlef Schrempf was 2 of 11 from the
field and scored just 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of guys we count on come up firing blanks most
of the game,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, at least, had an excuse. He was bothered during the game
by a sore back, but still managed to distribute 12 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is pretty stiff. His back was hurting him real bad
tonight,'' Westphal said. ``He won't say it, but I'll say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker had his second strong outing since returning from a
10-game absence because of a torn ligament in his right thumb. He
scored 15 points and had 11 rebounds. Ellis led the Sonics with 20
points and Hawkins had 17.
</P>
<P>
   But down the stretch, the Grizzlies repeatedly beat the Sonics
down the court, to the basket and to almost every loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   A ram-and-jam example came in the third quarter when the younger
Grizzlies outhustled the Sonics to take the lead and stretch it to
five points, 69-64. Cherokee Parks (two), Tony Massenburg and
Abdur-Rahim each had a hoop-rattling slam to ignite the surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little afraid at the beginning,'' Lopez said. ``We
went down 13-2, but we just came back like we've been doing all
this time. We did our job and stepped up and hit big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies' rim-rattling rally left Westphal frayed and still
searching for a remedy to the inconsistency that ails his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of big loose balls went their way. A couple of
buzzer-beaters went their way. We had a couple of turnovers,''
Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all adds up to a great win for them, a bad loss for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that another bad loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
