<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, April 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Four days after NATO approved the
deployment of two dozen American Apache helicopter gunships to
attack Yugoslav tanks, frustrated NATO and Pentagon officials now
estimate that it could take a month before the helicopters are
available to fly into Kosovo. By Steven Lee Myers. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HUNGER (Washington) _ About 700,000 ethnic Albanians have
been uprooted from their homes by the Yugoslavs and are still in
Kosovo facing the risk of famine as food stocks quickly dwindle,
administration officials said Friday. Officials have considered air
drops of food but rejected the idea as too dangerous for NATO
pilots, who would have to fly at low levels and risk being hit by
Yugoslav ground fire, an official said. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin did not order
Russian nuclear missiles to be retargeted at NATO countries taking
part in the bombing of Yugoslavia. Nor did he formally endorse the
joining together of Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia in a
geographically awkward Slavic union. But at a meeting Friday with
Gennadi Seleznyov, the Communist who is speaker of the Russian
Parliament's lower house, he unmistakably warned the West not to
push Russia into another war in the Balkans. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUGOVA (Undated) _ or most of the last ten years,
Slobodan Milosevic, as the main generator of aroused Serbian
nationalism, has been trying to ignore Ibrahim Rugova, the 53 year
old literary historian who until recently was the unquestioned
leader of Kosovo's Albanians. But now, after the NATO attacks on
Yugoslavia and the forced flight of Albanians from Kosovo,
President Milosevic has turned to the adversary he spurned for so
long, as if acknowledging him as a suitable partner for building a
peace. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SURVEIL (Brussels) _ Three days after Serbian troops
closed border crossing points from Kosovo into Macedonia and
Albania, NATO reconnaissance planes have failed to locate any of
the tens of thousands of refugees who were turned back from the
frontier. By Craig R. Whitney. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (Washington) _ The new partnership between NATO
and the U.N. refugee organization is bringing supplies and shelter
to hundreds of thousands who have fled Kosovo, but some fear it is
straining the traditional neutrality of aid groups. by working so
closely with one side's military in an ongoing assault, the U.N.
refugee organization may have crossed the line that allows relief
organizations to care fo the victims of both sides of a conflict,
some governments and aid organizations said. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The United States has quietly warned
Russia against providing military intelligence or assistance to
Belgrade, senior Western officials said Friday. The confidential
warning follows bitter complaints from Moscow about NATO's
airstrikes. Evidence that Russia was helping Belgrade would
undermine public support in the West for loans to Russia. By
Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ A look at why the WTO deal
didn't happen, and whether it had more to do with Congress, labor
or the Chinese. By David E. Sanger. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-PRESIDENT (Caracas, Venezuela) _ To the adoring,
impoverished masses who catapulted him to power, Hugo Chavez Frias
is El Comandante, their protector and benefactor, the bold leader
who will wipe out 40 years of inequality and corruption and
redirect this country's enormous oil wealth to better their lives.
To his opponents, the 44-year-old former army paratrooper who is
Venezuela's new president represents something unsettling, even
dangerous. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Susan McDougal's trial was
disrupted Friday when one of the 12 jurors deliberating her fate
brought a law book into the jury room. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HEALTH (Philadelphia) _ With Congress reconvening next
week, President Clinton went to Philadelphia Friday to try to whip
up public enthusiasm for the Democratic proposal to establish a
``patient's bill of rights.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-CHIEFS (Washington) _ Police chiefs meeting here to
examine how their officers could earn more public trust said Friday
that complaints about police misconduct were often valid and that
departments had far to go to meet demands for more accountability,
respect and courtesy. By Michael Janofsky. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPYARD-STRIKE (Newport News, Va.) _ Seething about what they
called stingy wages and pensions, more than 8,000 workers at
Newport News Shipbuilding are on strike in one of the largest
walkouts of this decade. By Steven Greenhouse. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-BABIES (New York) _ For those who somehow missed the
media hype and the water-cooler jokes, Friday night was the night
that doctors and statisticians had calculated would be the
equivalent of a rare fertility eclipse. It offered the chance to
produce the ultimate millennial accessory, a child born on Jan. 1,
2000. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-DOCTOR (New York) _ Nearly six months after a Buffalo,
N.Y., area doctor who performed abortions was shot to death at home
by a rifle-wielding sniper, law enforcement authorities reported on
Friday that they had found a rifle in woods behind the doctor's
house in Amherst, N.Y. While the finding of the rifle appeared to
be the biggest break in the case so far, it raised questions among
friends and relatives of Dr. Barnett Slepian as to why local police
and the FBI had not used high-technology methods to locate the
rifle much sooner. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THRIFT-SUIT (Washington) _ A federal judge will order the
government to pay nearly $909 million to a California thrift that
nearly went bankrupt after Congress and the Bush administration
imposed tougher accounting changes on the industry a decade ago.
The decision awarded to Glendale Federal Bank one of the largest
claims ever assessed against the federal government and is
significant for the legal precedent it may set for the more than
120 other similar cases filed by existing and moribund savings
associations and their shareholders. By Stephen Labaton. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Compaq Computer Corp. disclosed that
first-quarter earnings would be disappointing, in part because of
price-cutting throughout the industry. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRITY-CHEFS (Undated) _ Today's hot chef is a multimedia
chef. And as well-known culinary figures spend less time in the
kitchen and more in front of cameras or on book tours, publicists
help them secure all sorts of extracurricular activities, from
kitchenware endorsements to consulting, book writing and selling
products (including themselves) on Web sites. By Bryan Miller. With
photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TRADE (Hong Kong) _ For China, which has spent years
trying to claw its way into the world's club of trading nations,
the benefits of such an expanded reach and strong connections are
clear. But for Hong Kong, which has thrived as a middleman between
China's closed markets and the outside world, the possibility of a
more open China raises hard questions about the future. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BROKER-GUILTY (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney
announced Friday that Pasquale D'Onofrio, a former stockbroker at
Duke &AMP; Co., a defunct New York brokerage firm, pleaded guilty to
attempted enterprise corruption. D'Onofrio will be sentenced on
October 21 and faces up to 15 years in prison. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (London) _ NATO now has three irreducible war aims:
the removal of all Serbian military, paramilitary and police forces
from Kosovo; the return of all the ethnic Albanian refugees, and
their care and protection by an international force. In Britain, as
in the United States, Serbian atrocities have brought public
opinion solidly behind those objectives. But the leaders of NATO
are not so clear in stating them. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-BIOETHICS (Undated) _ Not since 1940 when City College
tried to hire an atheist and advocate of free love, Bertrand
Russell, has the appointment of an academic philosopher by an
American university created such an uproar. The choice of Peter
Singer, a world renowned animal rights advocate, for a chair in
bioethics at Princeton University's Center for Human Values, has
jolted this genteel college town as well as the field of bioethics.
Singer has defended, in certain circumstances, euthanasia, not only
for terminally ill adults but also for severely disabled infants.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION (Undated) _ A year after the Austrian
government agreed to return about $40 million worth of art and
objects that had been confiscated by the Nazis to the Austrian
branch of the Rothschild family, members of the 256-year-old
banking dynasty have decided to sell the collection, stripping many
leading museums in Vienna who have had them on display since World
War II. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   SERBS-ALBANIANS (Undated) _ Serbs vs. Albanians through the eyes
of Rebecca West in 1941. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS (Augusta) _ Shooting a blistering, bogey-free,
six-under-par 66, including a 32 on the back nine, Jose Maria
Olazabal left Augusta National Golf Club holding a one-stroke lead
over Scott McCarron heading into Saturday's third round of the
Masters. By Clifton Browne.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Augusta, Ga.) _ Sports of The Times column
on the second round of the Masters. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
