<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS IS UNLIKELY STAR AS NETS DEFEAT RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Keith Van Horn and Stephon Marbury were
the likely saviors. Van Horn had used his crossover dribble and
athleticism to work the former Knicks warrior Charles Oakley to
death. And Marbury, the brazen point guard, is always looking to
deliver in the fourth quarter. But Friday night, the unusual
happened at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Lucious Harris, who has battled injury and ineffectiveness all
season, starred for the Nets. Burying three long jump shots and
making 4 of 4 free throws over the last eight minutes, the Nets'
shy eighth man led them to their fifth victory in six games, 106-99
over the Toronto Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch shooting guard did not enter the game with
such high aspirations. After spending a couple of weeks on the
injured list with a bulging disk in his back, Harris, who finished
with a season-high 17 points, was happy just to be on the floor,
let alone throwing in big shots in the critical moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be on the court,'' said Harris, who averages
just under 5 points and 15 minutes a game. ``I've been the
forgotten man for a while with my back injury. But I worked hard
and stayed with it, and tonight I showed what I can do on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is all but impossible for the Nets (10-25) to earn a
spot in the post-season, the game was not without playoff
implications. Toronto, riding the lovely mix of veteran leadership
(Oakley and Kevin Willis) and youthful explosiveness (Vince Carter
and Tracy McGrady) to its best season, entered the Meadowlands in
the eighth and final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference,
one-half game ahead of the Knicks. But the loss, combined with the
Knicks' victory over the Atlanta Hawks, dropped the Raptors to
18-17 and moved the Knicks (19-17) back into a playoff slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were certainly not trying to do the Knicks a favor. In
fact, they will attempt to push the storied franchise that
perpetually overshadows them back out of contention Sunday when the
geographic rivals meet at 3 p.m. at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That one will be intriguing for numerous reasons: the Knicks,
despite Friday's impressive victory, seem to be on the verge of
self-destruction, while the Nets, far removed from their
nightmarish start, are playing some of the finest ball in the East,
and Marbury, the Brooklyn native whom the Knicks coveted, will play
against his hometown team for the first time since joining the
Nets.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, however, would not add to the drama surrounding the
game with a boastful comment Friday night. ``I'm not going to be on
the back page,'' Marbury said, referring to the New York tabloid
newspapers. ``It's just another game. ''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Nets, having starved for most of the season, are
hungry for any victory they can get, be it over the Knicks or the
Los Angeles Clippers. They are showing as much by playing with fire
and intensity whenever they take the court.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, they combined brute strength and crafty positioning
under the backboards _ they outrebounded Toronto, the league's
fourth-best rebounding team, by 52-42 _ with deftness in transition
to grab an 18-point lead, 77-59, late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn and Marbury had been dazzling, hooking up in the first
quarter for a resounding alley-oop slam on a pass that Marbury
threw from beyond the halfcourt line. Van Horn led the Nets to a
32-21 advantage in the third quarter by scoring 16 of his game-high
30 points. Marbury, who scored 20 points, had all nine of his
assists in the first three periods.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors' only answer to the Nets' show was the rookie
Carter, who scored 20 of his 26 points in the first half on jump
shots and wicked moves to the basket. But with the reserve guard
Dee Brown hitting three of his four 3-pointers in the final 13
minutes, Toronto pulled within 90-87 with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Harris, who had already made a 20-foot jumper and
assisted Marbury on a nice fast-break dunk in the quarter, hit a 21
footer to push the Nets' lead back to 5 points. Again, Toronto
pulled within 3 on a driving layin by McGrady. And again, Harris
answered with a 20-footer. The Raptors pulled within 3 points twice
more in the final minute, only to have Harris hit four free throws
to keep them at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephon said to me, `Just be ready to shoot the ball and when
it comes, don't hesitate,' '' Harris said. ``And I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The Nets have been in contact with the agent JIMMY SEXTON
concerning DAVID VAUGHN, a forward who played 15 games for the Nets
last season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
