u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-10 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS NEED HOT TEAM TO WARM FANS IN NEW BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Walking into the Kingdome nearing twilight Friday, the
new ballyard looming, something occurred to me:
</P>
<P>
   Man, was it cold.
</P>
<P>
   OK, not a great scoop. But as excuses go, it's a valid one most
April evenings in Seattle for staying inside.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the new ballpark is not inside. It's outside, of
all places.
</P>
<P>
   True, it has a gargantuan carport. But underneath, no heaters.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that always the case these days when you spend $517
million? Go cheap, and you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   As a factor in the playing of baseball, cold is nothing compared
to rain. Unless, of course, one makes a living hitting home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think Albert Belle left Chicago?'' Ken Griffey Jr.
asked in his usual mischievous manner before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming baseball's highest-paid player in 1999 ($11.9 million)
might have something to do with it. But Griffey would like to think
Belle's motivation included Camden Yards' shorter fences and
Baltimore's warmer springs.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey holds fast to the baseball belief that cold, heavy air
retards the flight of the ball. So if Friday night's Kingdome game
against Oakland had been held next door, the game definitely would
have been retarded, longball-wise.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Mariners' thick-armed offense is retarded, what would
be the point of sitting in 38 degrees for three hours?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what will happen to the ball over there,''
Griffey said of the new digs, ``but if the ball doesn't go, then
what?''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey chuckled at the prospect of bringing in the new park's
fences yet again. He speculated that in the space between the
fences and the bleachers, the Mariners can create a big picnic and
party area.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if moving the fences means yet another unexpected expense
for a stadium that may yet out-price the Kennedy Space Center, the
Mariners could simply be remade into a pitching-dominant team. That
shouldn't take any longer than paying off the stadium bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ball doesn't carry,'' Griffey said, ``how many
(big-hitting) free agents are you going to attract here?''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's musings about the new park came amid some curiosity
about the attendance numbers of the infant season. After a 13-year
low of 51,656 for an opening night, crowds of 20,435 and 21,050
finished out the White Sox series. Friday's game against the A's
drew 24,823, and the pre-sale for Saturday's annual Bat Night
promotion, normally a crowd in the 45,000 range, is about 28,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominous is that sales of season tickets, including the new
park, are 20,500, just a thousand more than the Kingdome
full-season record. The Mariners planned to cut off season ticket
sales at 24,000, but apparently the region's baseball fans saved
them the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the obvious factors of a young season and unglamorous
opposition, the Mariners did little in the run-up to engender a
buzz, new yard notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was our big story?'' Griffey asked in his series of
self-answering questions. ``Will Griffey and A-Rod re-sign?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, almost the entire winter discussion of the Mariners,
with the notable exception of Jay Buhner's remarkable
rehabilitation from elbow surgery, was about what they can't,
couldn't or won't do. Not exactly the kind of thing to set a
marquee ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner owners' disengagement from baseball's economic
battles, no matter how well-reasoned, has cast something of a pall.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 strategy thus far appears to rely exclusively on the
undeniable appeal of blue skies and green grass. The problem is the
honeymoon for the park may be far briefer than many imagined if
fans are allowed to spend their time the way the Mariner bosses
spent theirs _ coming up with reasons to disengage.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Don't get attached to Griffey; he'll be gone. Don't
get attached to A-Rod; he'll be gone. Mariner pitchers are too old
and too young. Tickets are too expensive. There's no parking. It's
too cold. It's too hot (OK, the last one was a reach). (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The tendency among some fans to avoid potentially futile
emotional investment is part of why Griffey called Mariner
president Chuck Armstrong in the off-season to suggest trading top
pitching prospect Ryan Anderson (``Space Needle,'' Griffey calls
him) for Roger Clemens, who subsequently went from the Blue Jays to
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Said Griffey: ``Imagine what people would be saying about us if
we had Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mariners have chosen rivets over Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the new park will be magnificent. But unless there is a
compelling team cavorting on its lawn, the possibility looms larger
that the region's baseball fans could let novelty wear thin
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how a succession of Mariner owners and execs insisted
that baseball would never work in an ugly indoor park during
gorgeous Seattle summers?
</P>
<P>
   That would be baffling news to the 8.4 million Mariner fans who
attended Kingdome games the last three years. The park, it would
seem, comes in second to the play.
</P>
<P>
   For $517 million, one would think they had thought of
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
