<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA CONNECTS IN FIRST TO POWER METS PAST EXPOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For much of last summer, Mike Piazza felt he was
pressing every time at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza would get one chance a game, if that, with runners in
scoring position. At the beginning of his tenure with the Mets, he
failed so often that the fans at Shea Stadium began to shower him
with boos.
</P>
<P>
   Those must seem like ancient times to Piazza. It seems as if
every time he comes up now, someone is on base. ``The key is that
guys are out there to drive in,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star catcher drove in five runs Friday night to lead the
Mets and Masato Yoshii to a 10-3 defeat of the Montreal Expos, a
team that has bedeviled them in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those runs batted in came during the Mets' four-run
first inning, when Piazza belted a hanging slider from Mike Thurman
over a cluster of television cameras beyond the center-field fence.
Through the first five games of the season, Piazza has had seven
at-bats with runners in scoring position. After going 2 for 2 in
such situations Friday, Piazza is 4 for 7 (.571) with two home runs
and seven r.b.i.
</P>
<P>
   One day after a frustrating loss here, everything was right
again in the Mets' world. Each member of the infield made at least
one terrific play on defense. Yoshii allowed two home runs, but
they were not costly, and he lasted seven innings. Even more
important, the Mets gave their starter something he rarely had last
season: runs to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is the start of something new,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Mets center fielder Brian McRae provided a
critique of the improving Expos, who were tough on the Mets last
season and again on Thursday. Montreal was 8-4 against the Mets
last year, which helped knock them out of a post-season berth. The
Expos also were 6-6 against the Atlanta Braves, the National League
East's champions, and 51-87 against everyone else. ``When they play
against us and the Braves, they play their best ball,'' McRae said.
``But they're not consistent. We get up for every game. Today will
be a different test.''
</P>
<P>
   Expos Manager Felipe Alou said before the game that he did not
believe his team was ready to contend, and added that the biggest
questions surrounding Montreal involved its starting pitching. One
of those question marks, Thurman, was pounded by the Mets on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman went to a 3-2 count on the first three batters he faced,
walking all three. Only two runners were on base for Piazza, the
cleanup hitter, because the rookie catcher Michael Barrett had
thrown out Rickey Henderson on an attempted steal. That proved a
break for the Expos as Piazza launched an 0-1 pitch for a homer to
center field.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Robin Ventura then followed with a shot over the
fence in right to give the Mets back-to-back home runs and a 4-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Yoshii on the mound, it was not the safest of margins.
Yoshii had been so shaky this spring that the Mets had spent almost
two weeks preceding the regular season trying to shore up their
starting rotation. And when Barrett hit a two-run home run to
center with one out in the second, the Mets' lead was cut to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, it was 4-3, after Montreal's right fielder,
Vladimir Guerrero, launched a shot that cleared the bleachers in
left.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets loaded the bases for Piazza with one out in the fifth.
The rookie right-hander J. D. Smart came on in relief of Thurman.
Piazza greeted Smart with a two-run single to give him five runs
batted in on the night, his most as a Met. Ventura followed with a
run-scoring groundout, and the Mets were able to coast the rest of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our lineup, we could have guys on a lot,'' Ventura said.
``And that's what you want with Mike coming to the plate. You want
guys to be on so you can't pitch around him.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Piazza has made it hard for anybody to pitch to him,
too.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   TOM SEAVER will throw out the ceremonial first pitch at the
Mets' home opener on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
