<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANKLE IS NOT ANGELS' ACHILLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's edition of The Sporting Muse, limping a bit in support
of Mo Vaughn: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While everyone in Anaheim holds their breath waiting for Mo
Vaughn's ankle to heal, let's take a minute to ask if Mo would have
been any help during losses Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels allowed nine runs in each game. Until ailing Chuck
Finley went six innings Friday at Texas, a starter had yet to last
five innings. Tim Belcher and Ken Hill went 4fr 1/3 and Steve
Sparks four Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Vaughn may be the clubhouse catalyst everyone
expected him to be, and he may shake off his ankle injury and post
numbers like .300, 30 and 100. But he can't pitch, and that's where
the team has unfortunately been weakest since Finley, Jim Abbott
and Mark Langston won 55 games between them.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have not had a pitcher win 16 games or more since
1993. The club has been modestly succeeding despite having failed
to produce a quality, dependable pitcher from its system since the
mid-80s, when Finley and Kirk McCaskill emerged. You can't say the
Angels developed Abbott since he went from college and the Olympics
to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, one of the most overlooked effects of inconsistent
pitching is the energy it demands of the lineup to always produce.
Most teams can feel secure that a four-run inning in the fourth or
fifth will stand up. Not the Angels. The only time they ever feel
safe is when Troy Percival is on the mound, and he may not get a
lot of save opportunities. ...
</P>
<P>
   I know Arizona manager Buck Showalter is supposed to have a
brilliant mind. But if I'm managing a team and the opposing catcher
is coming off surgery, like Todd Hundley, I run until he proves he
can make the throw without his arm breaking into pieces. ...
</P>
<P>
   The D-Backs are all of 2 years old, but they already have gone
through vast changeover from 1998. Only 10 players remain from the
inaugural D-Back team. This kind of changeover will only get worse
as free agency shatters whatever traditions there are left in
baseball. ...
</P>
<P>
   I think it's great that baseball has created an award in the
name of Hank Aaron. But once again, one has to ask why it took so
long. I mean, he's been the all-time home run king for 25 years.
...
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's award made me speculate on when Ken Griffey Jr. might
break it (assuming Mark McGwire doesn't beat him to it). Over the
last six seasons, five of which he hit 40 or more for the season,
Griffey has averaged one home run every three games.
</P>
<P>
   On a projection of Griffey playing 150 games a season and
keeping his one-in-three pace, he would hit home run No.400 in May
2000, No.500 in May 2002 and No.600 early in 2004, when he will be
just 34.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the second hitter to ever top 700 very early in
2006, pass Ruth's 714 in the summer, and likely begin the 2007
season needing just a handful of home runs to break the record. He
would then likely hit No.800 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Stats guys like Bill James use a protracted mathematical device
to compensate for statistical decline according to age. But the
upshot of any projection is that Griffey is the man most likely to
break it. By then, he might also be the first owner-player to ever
hold an all-time record. ...
</P>
<P>
   The NFL draft arrives next weekend, and the emphasis will be on
quarterbacks. The record for most quarterbacks chosen in the first
round is six, set in 1983, the class that produced Dan Marino, John
Elway and Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   If one slots teams according to need, the record would likely be
broken. Scouts say 21 teams are definitely in the market for a
quarterback, and more than half of those project a 1999 draftee
would start by 2001 at the latest.
</P>
<P>
   These teams would include Baltimore, Carolina (Steve Beuerlein),
Chicago (Erik Kramer), Cleveland, Kansas City (Elvis Grbac), New
Orleans, New York Giants (Kent Graham), Oakland (Rich Gannon),
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh (Kordell Stewart), St. Louis (Tony Banks),
Seattle (Jon Kitna) and Tampa Bay (Trent Dilfer).
</P>
<P>
   Several others, like Atlanta (Chris Chandler), Cincinnati (Neil
O'Donnell), Dallas (Troy Aikman), Miami (Dan Marino) and San
Francisco (Steve Young), have aging quarterbacks, making the
drafting of one something to at least consider.
</P>
<P>
   The teams not really shopping: Arizona (Jake Plummer), Buffalo
(Doug Flutie/Rob Johnson), Denver (Bubby Brister/Brian Griese),
Detroit (Charlie Batch), Green Bay (Brett Favre), Indianapolis
(Peyton Manning), Jacksonville (Mark Brunell), Minnesota (Randall
Cunningham), New England (Drew Bledsoe), San Diego (Jim
Harbaugh/Ryan Leaf), Tennessee (Steve McNair) and Washington (Brad
Johnson). ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the '99 crop shakes out with a week to go:
</P>
<P>
   Top five picks: Tim Couch (Kentucky) and Akili Smith (Oregon).
Smith is Combine man-of-the-year because he had all of the
attributes NFL teams love. But he has only one year of Division I
football behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Top half, first round: Donovan McNabb (Syracuse) is this year's
upgrade of Steve McNair or Kordell Stewart. McNabb isn't as
talented as McNair, but he's very experienced running a pro
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Middle, first round: Cade McNown's (UCLA) stock depends on who
you ask. Those scouts who believe all quarterbacks must be 6-4 and
have a deep arm don't like him. Those who see him as a natural born
winner pray he'll be available when it's their turn. Said San
Francisco personnel man and ex-Bruin coach Terry Donahue: ``I would
love to have him, but he'll be long gone by the time we pick
(27th).'' Those NFL teams that passed on McNair will seriously
consider Daunte Culpepper (Central Florida). He's 6-4 and has a
howitzer for an arm.
</P>
<P>
   Low first round/second: Tulane's Shaun King is just 6-0, but he
earned a lot of admiration at workouts. Ted White (Howard) has been
compared by some to Doug Williams. Ohio State's Joe Germaine was
considered better than Brian Griese, the heir to John Elway's job.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Kansas State's Michael Bishop went into freefall after
K-State's national title chase died. Scouts feel he's too raw.
Washington's Brock Huard tumbled because of a soft reputation, but
Husky bloodlines will get him drafted. New Mexico's Graham Leigh is
the other sleeper besides White. ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: Divorce papers are filed by Andre Agassi and Brooke
Shields. Reaction: Coming to a cineplex near you, ``The Ex-Husbands
Club,'' starring Agassi, Dennis Rodman and Evander Holyfield, with
a cameo appearance by Tom Arnold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
