<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDS AND KNICKS TAKE HAWKS' BEST SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chris Childs spit a tooth into his hand and fixed a
menacing stare on Dikembe Mutombo, who trotted away innocently. It
was all Childs could do not to dart toward the Hawks' towering
collection of pointy elbows and bony kneecaps and start swinging
away without regard to Mutombo's yard-long reach advantage.
</P>
<P>
   He'll save the retaliation for another game. It was too
important for him to keep his cool and stay in a game that had a
desperate, do-or-die feel to it. And Childs was too pivotal to the
outcome to let a flying elbow with four minutes left disturb the
uncommon poise the Knicks displayed Friday night as they broke
their three-game losing streak with an 86-78 victory at the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   It was an uncommon night. Too often the Knicks (19-17) have
failed on the road and unraveled with a lead in the fourth quarter.
This time, they leaned on Childs for smooth ball movement, some
timely rebounds and the kind of in-your-face defense that put out
the fire on Mookie Blaylock's 28-point night.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Childs lifted the spirits of his beleaguered
team, which inched its way back into a playoff spot by a half game
after Toronto lost to the Nets, 106-99. All because he stayed in
the game and refused to counter a blow that left his front left
tooth in a box in his locker afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get him back,'' said Childs, who was elbowed in
the mouth by Mutombo after he delivered a pass to Patrick Ewing,
who knocked down a jumper to give the Knicks an 80-71 lead with 3
minutes 59 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a 12-round fight. You can call Don King. It
was an intentional elbow. I'd already passed the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo just shrugged the broad shoulders on his 7-foot-2-inch
frame and waved off Childs' invitation the next time they meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what he says,'' said Mutombo, who finished with
21 rebounds but only scored 6 points. ``I don't get into those
stupid things. He can say what he wants. I didn't do anything to
him. I don't know what he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs was talking through a swollen lip. Although he was not
the team's primary scorer _ a right reserved for Latrell Sprewell's
18-point game on 6-for-15 shooting _ Childs delivered the kind of
energy the Knicks had been missing.
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks holding a 67-65 lead to open the fourth quarter,
Childs penetrated and tossed a behind-the-back pass to Larry
Johnson. Johnson swung the ball to Sprewell, who passed it to
Childs on the right wing. Childs then drove the baseline and
sneaked in a no-look pass to Marcus Camby, who popped up for a
dunk.
</P>
<P>
   In one play, the Knicks revealed a side they have seldom shown
this year: they were aggressive, decisive, patient and unselfish.
</P>
<P>
   And they showed confidence. Two minutes later, Childs pulled up
for a 17-foot jumper with eight minutes to go. It did not matter
that he had been 1 for 4 on the night; he was not going to miss it.
Childs topped that with a couple of rebounds down the stretch, one
right in front of Mutombo, to keep his team moving forward. Instead
of giving up their lead, the Knicks increased it to 10 points by
holding the Hawks to 22 percent shooting from the field and forcing
them into five turnovers in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our mentality was better,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
``Must win? Yep, since we won, we had to have it. I thought we
played well on both ends. We can't exhale and think everything has
been corrected because it hasn't been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks beat a good team on the road. The Hawks were missing
Steve Smith, but that did not take away from the way they closed
out the game. Without Smith, Blaylock was the threat. After
Blaylock had lit up Charlie Ward for five 3-pointers, Childs forced
him to miss his last three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris had a great game,'' Ewing said. ``I know Dikembe elbowed
me in the head, too. We're friends but when we get on the floor,
it's war.''
</P>
<P>
   A war may be in the works. Mutombo, who has already broken two
noses this year with his lethal elbows, could face the wrath of
Childs. Not that he's worried. Mutombo rolled his eyes at Childs'
bravado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not a playoff game because I'm going to get him
back,'' Childs said. ``But I held back tonight. It wasn't worth it.
We needed this game. Getting into it tonight wasn't going to bring
my tooth back. If it had been a blowout, I might have done
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see how he hits me when I'm standing toe to toe.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   MARCUS CAMBY returned after missing three games with a strained
groin. He seemed to find his groove pretty quickly. Camby finished
4 for 6 shooting and scored 9 points, grabbed 5 rebounds and had a
blocked shot in 19 minutes. ... ALLAN HOUSTON missed five of his
first six shots but finished 4 for 9 for the game and scored 10
points. ... The Knicks improved their road record to 5-12. ...
Before their victory against Atlanta, the Knicks had been 1-7
against the top four teams in the Eastern Conference (Orlando,
Indiana, Miami and Atlanta).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
