<P>
   _ By REED ABELSON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of Overcharging at Nuclear Cleanup Sites
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning up radioactive pollution at former nuclear weapons
plants has been tedious for workers and expensive for taxpayers,
although generally profitable for the contractors. Now an
accountant for two contractors at the Hanford nuclear reservation
in Washington state has filed a suit that says the contractors have
been illegally marking up their bills, adding overhead charges to
expenses that do not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors acted like a restaurant that pockets the
waitress' tips, according to the accountant, David Carbaugh, who
also claims he was fired for trying to alert the Energy Department.
The contractors, Fluor Daniel Hanford and Westinghouse Hanford Co.,
deny the charges, which were filed in U.S. District Court in
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Guilty Plea in the Kidnapping and Murder of a Gay Man
</P>
<P>
   In Laramie, Wyo., where the murder of Matthew Shepard six months
ago provoked national soul-searching over violence against gay
people, Russell Henderson pleaded guilty to kidnapping and
murdering Shepard, a college student. He was sentenced to serve two
consecutive life terms in prison.
</P>
<P>
   To escape the death penalty, Henderson may have bargained with
prosecutors to testify in August in the capital murder trial of his
former friend, Aaron McKinney. In court, Henderson said McKinney
was the mastermind of the crime, choosing the student as a victim,
and then beating him savagely.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming authorities have declined to classify the murder as a
hate crime or a murder motivated by hatred of gays.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney is expected to try to use the ``gay panic'' defense,
arguing that his uncontrollable anger was ignited by a sexual
advance by Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Denver television reporter, obtained letters
written from jail by McKinney. In one letter peppered with
isspellings, McKinney, a high-school dropout, wrote to a female
friend that Shepard ``said he was gay and wanted a piece of me.''
In response, he wrote, ``Being verry drunk and homofobick I flipped
out and began to pistol whip'' the student.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BROOKE
</P>
<P>
   Drastic Action to Seal Leaks of Nuclear Secrets
</P>
<P>
   The current furor over the Clinton administration's handling of
evidence of Chinese atomic espionage is now forcing the
administration to scramble to plug leaks at America's three major
nuclear weapons laboratories, where it has been accused of
responding sluggishly to security problems.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most dramatic actions taken since the spy scandal
erupted last month, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson ordered a
suspension of all scientific work on the computer networks
containing America's most sensitive nuclear weapons secrets at the
Los Alamos, Sandia and Lawrence-Livermore laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   He took the action because he was convinced that security
problems had left the computer networks vulnerable to espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Richardson decided to close down the networks for an
indefinite period after receiving an internal review that found
that security measures at Los Alamos and Lawrence-Livermore were
still below standard.
</P>
<P>
   Closing down the classified computer networks affects thousands
of workers at the weapons labs, and effectively halts most
classified work related to the maintenance of the U.S. nuclear
weapons inventory.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES RISEN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
