<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW-NY     04-10 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR TEACHES NATO WHAT ITS ROLE IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The leaders of NATO have long been planning
a summit meeting in Washington from April 23 to 25 to celebrate the
alliance's first 50 years and chart a new ``strategic concept''
defining its role in European security in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, that role is being defined in practice in
Kosovo, not on paper in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The role right now is that of a bulwark against the consequences
of ethnic instability in Europe's southeastern rim. For that, much
more than Russian nuclear bombs, is today the biggest threat to
European security, as it was a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   And if NATO cannot defeat the effort by President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia to drive the ethnic Albanian population out
of the historic Serbian province of Kosovo, the alliance risks
going the way of the League of Nations and other failed
20th-century attempts to deal with the same ethnic instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop this tragedy of great dimensions, caused by
somebody who has a name, Slobodan Milosevic,'' said NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana. As a young man during the Cold
War, he opposed Spain's entry into the alliance. Now, still a
socialist who describes himself as a Social Democrat, he defines
the purpose of the allied bombing campaign in Kosovo as ``a mission
of human rights and trying to preserve human values.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether NATO's chosen strategy of using bombs instead of ground
troops to stop the brutal Serb ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo can
succeed is highly debatable, at least outside the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic's unilateral ``cease-fire'' last week, and his
dickering over the freedom of three U.S. soldiers who were captured
on the Macedonian border, were signs of weakness rather than
tactical maneuvers for advantage, the allies have given themselves
a daunting task: to stop the Serb attacks against civilians, escort
nearly half a million refugees back to their homes in Kosovo, and
guarantee a lasting peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Many military experts believe it will take ground forces to do
the job, and this presents new complications for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of completely losing face, it will be necessary to
move to a combined air and ground operation,'' Gen. Maurice
Schmitt, a retired French chief of staff, wrote in the daily Le
Figaro last week. He suggested that it could be done with fewer
than 150,000 allied troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of ground troops, with its implications of
casualties, is the most sensitive political question for President
Clinton and other NATO leaders. Led by the United States, NATO
continues to insist that it will only go in after the Serb forces
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was conceived 50 years ago to prevent World War III, not to
face down tinpot tyrants in the Balkans. In the age of nuclear
standoff, its credibility was unquestioned, and it won the Cold War
without ever firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in taking military action in Europe, NATO has felt bold
enough to do what it could not think of doing in Hungary or
Czechoslovakia or Poland when the Soviet Union intervened. And
Milosevic, for his part, has done what Stalin and his successors
never dared to do, defying allied threats and then allied bombing.
Indeed, he used the bombing as cover for a long-prepared campaign
of military and police brutality against Kosovo Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   So, under their current strategy for preserving their
credibility, the allies will have to show continued stamina and
united resolve to keep punishing the Serb military and police
forces until they give up, a task that could take weeks or even
months.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's foreign ministers will try to demonstrate determination
by gathering in Brussels on Monday, but for some members _
particularly Greece, which has Orthodox religious ties with Serbia,
and Italy, which fears being overwhelmed by Albanian refugees _ it
has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   The sources of the current bind are not difficult to trace. Even
though credibility has always been NATO's most important asset,
NATO frittered away the credibility of its bombing threat against
Milosevic, menacing him with words so many times over the past year
of violence in Kosovo that in the end he concluded the alliance was
full of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. But NATO was also wrong if it thought Milosevic
would cave in after being hit by a few bombs. Milosevic gambled
that he could create an Albanian-free Kosovo faster than allied
conventional bombing could reduce the military and police forces he
was using to carry out his brutal sweeps. And with 10 days of bad
weather and NATO aircraft less effective than hoped against Serb
tanks and troops, he has come close to winning his gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The allies now hope the tide has begun to turn, but they will
have to do more than fight Milosevic to a draw to show that the
alliance has a credible role for the future.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 40 years of NATO's existence, Article 5 of the
North Atlantic Treaty, signed in Washington on April 4, 1949,
defined the core of the alliance as collective defense against
armed attack. But then the threat of armed attack from Russia
became secondary when communism collapsed; in its place, the
virulent nationalisms of the Balkans and the Caucasus that helped
spark World War I became wildly resurgent.
</P>
<P>
   This produced what the alliance calls ``non-Article 5''
missions, like the peacekeeping force in Bosnia and the air
operation over Kosovo. ``Preserving strategic stability in the
Euro-Atlantic area'' is probably the way the alliance will define
its reason for being in the new strategic concept to be approved in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has reminded the European allies that when security
problems in their own back yard require a rapid military response,
they need U.S. help. But the United States, as the allies see it,
wavers between wanting to drag them into distant confrontations in
places like Iraq and North Korea, and losing interest in a Europe
that ought to be able to take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   So they debate over things like how the European allies could
use NATO structures to conduct military operations without the
United States, or how the European Union could build a defense
structure of its own.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a lot of talking about such things in Washington
in two weeks. But none of it will mean much if the allies do not
get things right in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW-NY     04-10 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR TEACHES NATO WHAT ITS ROLE IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The leaders of NATO have long been planning
a summit meeting in Washington from April 23 to 25 to celebrate the
alliance's first 50 years and chart a new ``strategic concept''
defining its role in European security in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, that role is being defined in practice in
Kosovo, not on paper in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The role right now is that of a bulwark against the consequences
of ethnic instability in Europe's southeastern rim. For that, much
more than Russian nuclear bombs, is today the biggest threat to
European security, as it was a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   And if NATO cannot defeat the effort by President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia to drive the ethnic Albanian population out
of the historic Serbian province of Kosovo, the alliance risks
going the way of the League of Nations and other failed
20th-century attempts to deal with the same ethnic instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop this tragedy of great dimensions, caused by
somebody who has a name, Slobodan Milosevic,'' said NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana. As a young man during the Cold
War, he opposed Spain's entry into the alliance. Now, still a
socialist who describes himself as a Social Democrat, he defines
the purpose of the allied bombing campaign in Kosovo as ``a mission
of human rights and trying to preserve human values.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether NATO's chosen strategy of using bombs instead of ground
troops to stop the brutal Serb ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo can
succeed is highly debatable, at least outside the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic's unilateral ``cease-fire'' last week, and his
dickering over the freedom of three U.S. soldiers who were captured
on the Macedonian border, were signs of weakness rather than
tactical maneuvers for advantage, the allies have given themselves
a daunting task: to stop the Serb attacks against civilians, escort
nearly half a million refugees back to their homes in Kosovo, and
guarantee a lasting peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Many military experts believe it will take ground forces to do
the job, and this presents new complications for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of completely losing face, it will be necessary to
move to a combined air and ground operation,'' Gen. Maurice
Schmitt, a retired French chief of staff, wrote in the daily Le
Figaro last week. He suggested that it could be done with fewer
than 150,000 allied troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of ground troops, with its implications of
casualties, is the most sensitive political question for President
Clinton and other NATO leaders. Led by the United States, NATO
continues to insist that it will only go in after the Serb forces
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was conceived 50 years ago to prevent World War III, not to
face down tinpot tyrants in the Balkans. In the age of nuclear
standoff, its credibility was unquestioned, and it won the Cold War
without ever firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in taking military action in Europe, NATO has felt bold
enough to do what it could not think of doing in Hungary or
Czechoslovakia or Poland when the Soviet Union intervened. And
Milosevic, for his part, has done what Stalin and his successors
never dared to do, defying allied threats and then allied bombing.
Indeed, he used the bombing as cover for a long-prepared campaign
of military and police brutality against Kosovo Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   So, under their current strategy for preserving their
credibility, the allies will have to show continued stamina and
united resolve to keep punishing the Serb military and police
forces until they give up, a task that could take weeks or even
months.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's foreign ministers will try to demonstrate determination
by gathering in Brussels on Monday, but for some members _
particularly Greece, which has Orthodox religious ties with Serbia,
and Italy, which fears being overwhelmed by Albanian refugees _ it
has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   The sources of the current bind are not difficult to trace. Even
though credibility has always been NATO's most important asset,
NATO frittered away the credibility of its bombing threat against
Milosevic, menacing him with words so many times over the past year
of violence in Kosovo that in the end he concluded the alliance was
full of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong. But NATO was also wrong if it thought Milosevic
would cave in after being hit by a few bombs. Milosevic gambled
that he could create an Albanian-free Kosovo faster than allied
conventional bombing could reduce the military and police forces he
was using to carry out his brutal sweeps. And with 10 days of bad
weather and NATO aircraft less effective than hoped against Serb
tanks and troops, he has come close to winning his gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The allies now hope the tide has begun to turn, but they will
have to do more than fight Milosevic to a draw to show that the
alliance has a credible role for the future.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 40 years of NATO's existence, Article 5 of the
North Atlantic Treaty, signed in Washington on April 4, 1949,
defined the core of the alliance as collective defense against
armed attack. But then the threat of armed attack from Russia
became secondary when communism collapsed; in its place, the
virulent nationalisms of the Balkans and the Caucasus that helped
spark World War I became wildly resurgent.
</P>
<P>
   This produced what the alliance calls ``non-Article 5''
missions, like the peacekeeping force in Bosnia and the air
operation over Kosovo. ``Preserving strategic stability in the
Euro-Atlantic area'' is probably the way the alliance will define
its reason for being in the new strategic concept to be approved in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has reminded the European allies that when security
problems in their own back yard require a rapid military response,
they need U.S. help. But the United States, as the allies see it,
wavers between wanting to drag them into distant confrontations in
places like Iraq and North Korea, and losing interest in a Europe
that ought to be able to take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   So they debate over things like how the European allies could
use NATO structures to conduct military operations without the
United States, or how the European Union could build a defense
structure of its own.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a lot of talking about such things in Washington
in two weeks. But none of it will mean much if the allies do not
get things right in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
