<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GADHAFI-LOCKERBIE-REV     04-10 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADHAFI-LOCKERBIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA'S GADHAFI WEARIES OF THE COLD SHOULDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Highly placed visitors invited lately to the palatial desert
tent of Col. Moammar Gadhafi sensed in the Libyan leader's
conversation a yearning to be readmitted to the world. Me, a
terrorist? he would plead. Of course, he was always an
unpredictable loner and he did spend decades bankrolling
revolutionaries and guerrilla leaders, especially in Africa. But
why are they _ now often heads of government just as he is _
getting all the invitations to London and Washington while he is
left stranded in the sand?
</P>
<P>
   Arabs, Africans, a procession of international lawyers and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan have been telling Gadhafi for months
that only he can end his isolation, by turning over for trial two
Libyan intelligence agents accused of masterminding the bombing of
Pan Am 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, an attack
that killed 280 people. Last week, running out of hope for any
further concessions from Britain and the United States, Gadhafi
finally agreed to deliver the suspects to a former military base in
the Netherlands, where they will be tried under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   Was it Libya's oil-dependent economy, in a tailspin because of
world petroleum prices, that did it? Was it threats from Washington
that things could get worse for Tripoli if there was not a break in
the decadelong standoff? Was it that Gadhafi's options had run out
and that, like Saddam Hussein, he had failed to persuade his Arab
neighbors to defy international law and break sanctions on his
behalf? Or was his search for a new kind of Arab nationalism,
rooted in the 1950s and '60s, hopelessly out of date, rendering him
an irritant as well as an anomaly in the Arab world?
</P>
<P>
   No one explanation seems to suffice, say those who have dealt
with the Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the once-flamboyant Gadhafi _ who spent much of last
year in a wheelchair, on crutches or leaning on a cane after what
he brushed off as broken bones but what his critics suspect may
have been an ambush or attempted assassination _ had to battle his
own secret demons. A quixotic leader who 30 years ago transformed
an Arab monarchy into something he chose to call the Libyan Arab
Jamahiriya, or state of the masses, Gadhafi took a political risk
in turning over two citizens to foreign powers he had spent years
vilifying as enemies of his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very important step,'' said Hussein Hassouna, the
Arab League's representative at the United Nations. ``It will
change everything in the region.'' Arabs say Gadhafi was aware he
had boxed himself in with his refusal to cooperate in the Lockerbie
case and was being bypassed by developments in the Arab world and
the Mediterranean, where links between North Africa and the
European Union are expanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said to him, `Once you take that step, it will open
up a lot of potential; you have a lot to gain,''' Hassouna said.
Investors and tourists alike seem poised to pounce on the novelty
of Libya, a Mediterranean nation with historical sites as old as
Phoenicia.
</P>
<P>
   More important than advice, however, were the cover and strong
shoulders to lean on that Arab leaders, Annan and President Nelson
Mandela of South Africa gave Gadhafi. Mandela went to Libya more
than a year ago (to the annoyance of Washington) and honored
Gadhafi with South Africa's highest award for Libya's assistance to
the African National Congress during the long years of apartheid.
With trust established, Mandela was able to play a major role _
later to be joined by President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Crown
Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia _ in persuading Gadhafi to accept
the creative Arab proposal that the two Libyan agents be tried in a
third country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier to accede to the urging of Mandela than to be
seen to be surrendering to the United States,'' said Thomas Franck,
director of the Center for International Studies at the New York
University Law School. ``The main task in arranging an outcome like
this is to find a way that one of the most eccentric of leaders can
climb down the tree he's climbed up without appearing to be giving
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clovis Maksoud, a former representative of the Arab League at
the United Nations and now director of the Center for the Global
South at American University in Washington, said: ``Mandela assumed
a fatherly approach. Mandela said, `He helped us in the past, and
we will help him now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to suggestions that Gadhafi stalled because he feared a
foreign court he could not control, Franck said the Libyan leader
has been one of the most frequent users of the International Court
of Justice in the Hague, Netherlands (unrelated to the specially
created Scottish panel that will try the Libyans), and has abided
by its rulings _ not a claim that can be made by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyans allowed the international court, better known as the
World Court, to adjudicate sea rights in a dispute with Tunisia and
Malta, and also obeyed the court's order to return to Chad a strip
of territory fought over in a long and costly war.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, international sanctions on Libya, though not separate
U.S. restrictions on travel and trade, were suspended as promised.
As a result, Libya is now free _ assuming the suspension becomes
permanent in 90 days _ to reopen airline links with the rest of the
world, upgrade its oil industry, rebuild a decrepit communications
system, construct a railroad and pursue other long-delayed
development projects with the help of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people who have dealt with Gadhafi say it was not economic
considerations alone that made a settlement possible. The Libyan
leader is too complex for that.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions on Libya, imposed in 1992 and widened in 1993, bit
into the economy, but not too hard. Unlike Iraq, Libya was able to
continue selling oil and gas, its big money earners, and spend the
money on anything it chose except arms and certain equipment for
the petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Washington's threat of wider sanctions crucial, since it
was assumed that the Clinton administration would find it hard to
persuade the Security Council to take such a step, given
Washington's growing alienation from the United Nations and a
general wariness there about the long-term wisdom of embargoes,
with their unfortunate side effects on civilians. Moreover, the
United States is deeply involved in Kosovo and monitoring a
critical Israeli election and an unfinished war in Iraq, among
other crises. So Libya has slipped down the scale of policy
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A need to end his isolation and salvage his place in history may
have been the most important factor to Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has definitely got out of the cage he was in,'' Maksoud
said. ``But it is not a defeat for him or a triumph for the
Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GADHAFI-LOCKERBIE-REV     04-10 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADHAFI-LOCKERBIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA'S GADHAFI WEARIES OF THE COLD SHOULDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Highly placed visitors invited lately to the palatial desert
tent of Col. Moammar Gadhafi sensed in the Libyan leader's
conversation a yearning to be readmitted to the world. Me, a
terrorist? he would plead. Of course, he was always an
unpredictable loner and he did spend decades bankrolling
revolutionaries and guerrilla leaders, especially in Africa. But
why are they _ now often heads of government just as he is _
getting all the invitations to London and Washington while he is
left stranded in the sand?
</P>
<P>
   Arabs, Africans, a procession of international lawyers and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan have been telling Gadhafi for months
that only he can end his isolation, by turning over for trial two
Libyan intelligence agents accused of masterminding the bombing of
Pan Am 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988, an attack
that killed 280 people. Last week, running out of hope for any
further concessions from Britain and the United States, Gadhafi
finally agreed to deliver the suspects to a former military base in
the Netherlands, where they will be tried under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   Was it Libya's oil-dependent economy, in a tailspin because of
world petroleum prices, that did it? Was it threats from Washington
that things could get worse for Tripoli if there was not a break in
the decadelong standoff? Was it that Gadhafi's options had run out
and that, like Saddam Hussein, he had failed to persuade his Arab
neighbors to defy international law and break sanctions on his
behalf? Or was his search for a new kind of Arab nationalism,
rooted in the 1950s and '60s, hopelessly out of date, rendering him
an irritant as well as an anomaly in the Arab world?
</P>
<P>
   No one explanation seems to suffice, say those who have dealt
with the Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the once-flamboyant Gadhafi _ who spent much of last
year in a wheelchair, on crutches or leaning on a cane after what
he brushed off as broken bones but what his critics suspect may
have been an ambush or attempted assassination _ had to battle his
own secret demons. A quixotic leader who 30 years ago transformed
an Arab monarchy into something he chose to call the Libyan Arab
Jamahiriya, or state of the masses, Gadhafi took a political risk
in turning over two citizens to foreign powers he had spent years
vilifying as enemies of his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very important step,'' said Hussein Hassouna, the
Arab League's representative at the United Nations. ``It will
change everything in the region.'' Arabs say Gadhafi was aware he
had boxed himself in with his refusal to cooperate in the Lockerbie
case and was being bypassed by developments in the Arab world and
the Mediterranean, where links between North Africa and the
European Union are expanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said to him, `Once you take that step, it will open
up a lot of potential; you have a lot to gain,''' Hassouna said.
Investors and tourists alike seem poised to pounce on the novelty
of Libya, a Mediterranean nation with historical sites as old as
Phoenicia.
</P>
<P>
   More important than advice, however, were the cover and strong
shoulders to lean on that Arab leaders, Annan and President Nelson
Mandela of South Africa gave Gadhafi. Mandela went to Libya more
than a year ago (to the annoyance of Washington) and honored
Gadhafi with South Africa's highest award for Libya's assistance to
the African National Congress during the long years of apartheid.
With trust established, Mandela was able to play a major role _
later to be joined by President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Crown
Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia _ in persuading Gadhafi to accept
the creative Arab proposal that the two Libyan agents be tried in a
third country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier to accede to the urging of Mandela than to be
seen to be surrendering to the United States,'' said Thomas Franck,
director of the Center for International Studies at the New York
University Law School. ``The main task in arranging an outcome like
this is to find a way that one of the most eccentric of leaders can
climb down the tree he's climbed up without appearing to be giving
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clovis Maksoud, a former representative of the Arab League at
the United Nations and now director of the Center for the Global
South at American University in Washington, said: ``Mandela assumed
a fatherly approach. Mandela said, `He helped us in the past, and
we will help him now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to suggestions that Gadhafi stalled because he feared a
foreign court he could not control, Franck said the Libyan leader
has been one of the most frequent users of the International Court
of Justice in the Hague, Netherlands (unrelated to the specially
created Scottish panel that will try the Libyans), and has abided
by its rulings _ not a claim that can be made by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyans allowed the international court, better known as the
World Court, to adjudicate sea rights in a dispute with Tunisia and
Malta, and also obeyed the court's order to return to Chad a strip
of territory fought over in a long and costly war.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, international sanctions on Libya, though not separate
U.S. restrictions on travel and trade, were suspended as promised.
As a result, Libya is now free _ assuming the suspension becomes
permanent in 90 days _ to reopen airline links with the rest of the
world, upgrade its oil industry, rebuild a decrepit communications
system, construct a railroad and pursue other long-delayed
development projects with the help of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people who have dealt with Gadhafi say it was not economic
considerations alone that made a settlement possible. The Libyan
leader is too complex for that.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions on Libya, imposed in 1992 and widened in 1993, bit
into the economy, but not too hard. Unlike Iraq, Libya was able to
continue selling oil and gas, its big money earners, and spend the
money on anything it chose except arms and certain equipment for
the petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Washington's threat of wider sanctions crucial, since it
was assumed that the Clinton administration would find it hard to
persuade the Security Council to take such a step, given
Washington's growing alienation from the United Nations and a
general wariness there about the long-term wisdom of embargoes,
with their unfortunate side effects on civilians. Moreover, the
United States is deeply involved in Kosovo and monitoring a
critical Israeli election and an unfinished war in Iraq, among
other crises. So Libya has slipped down the scale of policy
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A need to end his isolation and salvage his place in history may
have been the most important factor to Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has definitely got out of the cage he was in,'' Maksoud
said. ``But it is not a defeat for him or a triumph for the
Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
