<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLDWAR-HEROES-REVIEW     04-10 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLDWAR-HEROES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DID YOU DO IN THE COLD WAR, DADDY AND MOMMY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How is a man of middle age supposed to feel when he is told,
some three decades after his inglorious stateside military service,
that he played an essential part in the defeat of godless
communism?
</P>
<P>
   How is he supposed to feel upon learning that Congress has, at
long last, recognized his contribution to the national defense with
something called the Cold War Recognition Certificate?
</P>
<P>
   The certificate took its place in the pantheon of military
honors last week, when the Defense Department began accepting
applications. Anyone who served in the armed forces or in one of
several federal government positions between Japan's 1945 surrender
ending World War II and Mikhail Gorbachev's resignation as
president of the Soviet Union at the end of 1991 is eligible to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., the certificate could
go to as many as 22 million people. It carries no financial
benefits or privileges whatever. But, oh, the glory!
</P>
<P>
   Bearing Defense Secretary William Cohen's signature, the
certificate looks and sounds not unlike an honorable discharge. A
Pentagon spokesman, Army Lt. Col. Tom Begines, said the brass did
not push for the certificate, but allowed that maybe it's not such
a bad idea. Government civilians who fought the good fight but have
no military discharges to show for it (foreign service employees,
Defense Department workers, people in intelligence agencies) might
be pleased to have a certificate, the colonel suggested.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Lazio, Mollie Conkey, said her boss got
the idea a few years ago while talking to the husband of one of his
aides. The man had spent eight years in the Army and knew full well
that victory does not always come on the battlefield, that victory
and glory do not always march in step.
</P>
<P>
   And so language creating the Cold War certificate was tucked
into a military-spending bill for the 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest triumphs of freedom and democracy ended
without so much as a parade or any formal recognition,'' Lazio said
last fall, in remarks timed to coincide the start of CNN's ``Cold
War'' series. ``The time has come to remind the world that the
American victory in bringing the Cold War to an end _ while
avoiding nuclear devastation _ is one of the greatest achievements
in the history of mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   But how is a middle-aged man to feel if he knows, in his heart
of hearts, that he wasn't trying to do much for mankind, that he
was just trying to get his military service out of the way?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his biggest hardships were, say, the broiling August sun
at Fort Knox, Ky., during basic training, then the winter damp at
Fort Gordon, Ga., where he learned to operate teletypes and code
machines, followed by five-and-a-half years of weekly reserve
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone desiring a certificate can write to Cold War Recognition,
4035 Ridge Top Rd., Fairfax, VA 22030. Information is available on
the Internet at coldwar.army.mil/
</P>
<P>
   Because so many people are eligible and not everyone may covet a
certificate, the Pentagon decided to send them only to people who
ask, Begines said. The operation has been budgeted at $600,000 for
the next fiscal year, with future spending uncertain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans' groups have been enthusiastic about the certificate,
Begines said, perhaps because veterans _ those who were shot at and
those who weren't _ have memories not just of fear and death, but
of being bored and tired.
</P>
<P>
   And homesick. ``For most of the Cold War, the United States
maintained a force of over 300,000 service people in Europe,
patrolling the borders and skies of our allies,'' Begines said.
They fought a war that lasted four decades _ ``a long twilight
struggle,'' in the words of President John F. Kennedy, who knew
what war was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people saved us from a nuclear holocaust,'' said Ms.
Conkey, the congressional aide.
</P>
<P>
   But the middle-aged man in question never went overseas, never
got shot at. If he were given a special commendation, it might
right read like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas he kept a stoic expression while enduring the
profanity of the master sergeant, and whereas he braved the grease
and sweat of countless hours of mess hall duty;
</P>
<P>
   ``And whereas during basic training he handled a rifle pretty
well and managed to throw a real, honest-to-goodness live hand
grenade without blowing up himself or his buddies, and whereas he
performed his clerical duties efficiently and conscientiously
thereafter ...''
</P>
<P>
   This middle-aged man doesn't think he did all that much, not
when he recalls standing amid acres of white crosses in the U.S.
military cemetery overlooking Omaha Beach, not when he remembers a
college classmate who didn't come back from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Let others who are more deserving get their Cold War Recognition
Certificates. I already have a piece of paper. ``This certificate
is awarded as a testimonial of honest and faithful service,'' it
says. My honorable discharge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
