<SLUG> BC-ECON-JOBLESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEMPLOYMENT IS DOWN. PRICES AREN'T UP. GO FIGURE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Meeting in February to review interest rate policy,
members of the Federal Reserve fretted, as they always do, about
the possible resurgence of inflation. But their discussion soon
turned to whether the central bank's system of spotting incipient
wage and price pressures might be malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   This early-warning system _ built around interrelationships
between unemployment, growth and inflation _ assumes that when
joblessness falls below a certain ``natural'' level, prices will
rise. As a forecasting and policy-making tool, the framework
provided a reasonably accurate way of knowing when inflation would
strike and enabling the Fed to head it off by adjusting monetary
policy. At least until the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment has been falling for seven years, and in March it
dipped to 4.2 percent, its lowest level in nearly three decades and
well below any mainstream estimate of the natural unemployment
rate. Economic growth, while slowing somewhat, remains robust. Yet
the predicted inflation is nowhere to be found. And although
theoretical economists have been debating the issue of a natural
rate for years, concern about the concept's reliability now are
beginning to change the way the Fed thinks about inflation and sets
policy.
</P>
<P>
   The sketchy minutes of the central bank's February meeting _ the
only account made public _ suggest that even Fed officials are
struggling to find answers. The combination ``over an extended
period of strong economic growth, very low rates of unemployment,
and the absence of any buildup of inflation could not be explained
in terms of normal historical relationships,'' the minutes said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Fed officials, according to the minutes, ``suggested
that the inflation process was not well understood and that
inflation forecasts were subject to a wide range of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed does not understand the inflation process? It is like a
conference of top cardiac surgeons deciding that it did not really
know how the heart works, or NASA admitting that it was not sure
what happens when the countdown reaches zero.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists believe that since the Fed has less confidence
in its ability to predict inflation, it will be less likely to act
pre-emptively against inflation _ its strategy through much of the
last several decades _ and more likely to wait for evidence that
wage and price increases are actually accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   The natural-rate theory, which is encompassed in such arcane
concepts as the Phillips Curve and the non-accelerating inflation
rate of unemployment, still has its advocates, including some Fed
officials. Even skeptics acknowledge that there is a long-term
tradeoff between unemployment and inflation. The question is
whether the tradeoffs are consistent enough in a rapidly changing
economy to be of any use in predicting inflation and setting
interest rates at the appropriate level.
</P>
<P>
   ``These various road maps or rules that we use are valid at
times,'' said L. Douglas Lee, chief economist at HSBC Securities.
``But what you always have to remember is that the U.S. economy is
a very dynamic creature and things don't remain fixed. What works
at one point in terms of understanding inflation may not work at
another, but then may change and work again.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick for policy-makers, Lee said, is to remain flexible and
to recognize when their old assumptions are no longer working _
something that he and many other economists credit Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan with doing well in the last few years. Greenspan has
consistently resisted pressure to raise rates over the past few
years just because the old models have been sending warnings
signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy-makers have to keep on top of what's going on, so they
don't use the old road map on a new road,'' Lee said. ``We've had
quite a lengthy period of time now where the economy has grown
faster and inflation has been less than the Fed's forecast
expected. The longer the economy surprises you, the more you have
to question your fundamental assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists have offered a raft of explanations for the apparent
breakdown in the old relationships between employment, growth and
inflation, some suggesting that the change is temporary, others
seeing it as emblematic of a fundamental shift in the way the
economy works.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the fundamental change camp, which includes an
increasing number of Fed officials, say that inflation is being
dampened by improved productivity in American business. Faced with
a shortage of labor, employers are paying somewhat higher wages.
But because of intense competition, at home and abroad, they are
unable to pass on the higher costs to consumers. So they are
investing heavily in computers and other cost-saving equipment, and
re-examining the way they operate to reduce expenses at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Although the statistics are fuzzy, economists increasingly
believe that the result has been the first lasting improvement in
productivity _ output per worker _ since it inexplicably turned
down in the early 1970s. Higher productivity means the economy can
sustain higher rates of non-inflationary growth.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship of inflation to unemployment, Greenspan told
Congress earlier this year, ``is clearly a far more complex
process'' than implied by the natural-rate concept. ``At some
point,'' he said, ``the general notion that a different type of
process is involved here is going to probably gain, in my judgment,
a majority view among economists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
