<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, April 11, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-RING (Los Angeles) _ When deputies stopped a Ford Bronco at
a crowded West Hollywood nightclub, TV actor Omar Gooding was
behind the wheel and three handguns with erased serial numbers were
on the seat. Using new, sophisticated technology, ATF agents
painstakingly traced back the guns to more than 1,200 an illegal
immigrant bought using a forged gun dealer's license. That led them
to a 365-pound Los Angeles man and two other illegal dealers who
had sold the guns to San Fernando Valley gangs, the Mexican Mafia,
drive-by shooters, a bank robber _ and Gooding. By Greg Gittrich.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVA-DEJAVU (Los Angeles) _ Silvia Martin can barely stand to
watch the TV news images of huddled refugees driven from their
homes, as they revive memories of when she fled on foot from Nazi
terror. ``It's us all over again. When I see a young girl I think,
`I was there too,''' said Martin, an 80-year-old Hollywood resident
who was sent to Auschwitz at age 22. Among Holocaust survivors,
reactions like Martin's to the scenes of the Kosovo crisis are
common, say psychologist who treat them. A European campaign of
``ethnic cleansing'' starkly evokes the Nazi era and is taking its
toll on many elderly survivors. By Sharline Chiang. (Will move in
the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
