<HEADLINE>
WINNIE MANDELA IS BACK IN SOUTH AFRICA'S SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct art note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOWETO, South Africa _ To those who wrote Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela's political obituary a couple of years back:
Look again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, President Nelson Mandela's former wife took a beating
at hearings of the country's Truth and Reconciliation Commission
and then suffered an embarrassing defeat in her bid for the deputy
presidency of the African National Congress. She got fewer than 150
votes from more than 2,000 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But when the African National Congress published its list of
candidates in late February, she was in the No. 10 spot, a position
that acknowledges her popularity and that virtually assures she
will be returned to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In case the next generation of party officials should
underestimate her support, her recent appearance at a campaign
rally here upstaged the man most likely to be the country's next
president: Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
   The ups and downs of Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela's private life are
also back in the news: She is locked in a bitter feud with Mandela
over the house where they once lived here and _ in a gesture that
flabbergasted the nation _ she gave away her wedding ring to the
13-year-old daughter of a former security officer who used to spy
on her.
</P>
<P>
   Her prominence on the African National Congress list drew a
storm of attacks from opposition parties who were all too glad to
point out that the ANC had promised to propose only ``clean''
candidates _ those with no history of ill discipline, corruption or
a criminal record of a nonpolitical nature. Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela
has been convicted of assault and kidnapping, and many similar
accusations are still being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the country's system of proportional representation,
voters do not cast votes for candidates but for a party, which
proposes its own candidates. Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela was not the
only ANC candidate on this year's list with a questionable history.
</P>
<P>
   After the list was produced by voting at local levels of the
party, Mbeki, the party leader, said it would be reviewed for
undesirables. But the party also made clear that Mrs.
Madikizela-Mandela would probably survive the culling process: ANC
officials were quick to spring to her defense, saying her behavior
in the past was due to the stresses and hardships she was subjected
to when apartheid-era security forces routinely harassed her.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties, however, countered that even her
post-apartheid behavior was questionable. Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela,
who leads the ANC's Women's League and is a member of Parliament,
rarely attends sessions or makes any contributions. She also owes
thousands of dollars to the government for unauthorized trips, cell
phones and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, she created a stir when it came to light that she was
traveling on a diplomatic passport, though she may no longer be
entitled to one. The subject came up when, on private business, she
tried to board a British Air flight to London with more than $1,500
in excess baggage. She could not pay the fees, and other
first-class passengers helped her pay the excess, it was widely
reported here. She wrote a furious letter to the airline management
demanding she be reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity, however, seems unquestionable.
</P>
<P>
   From the urban sprawl in Soweto to the rural areas of the
country's Kwa-Zulu/Natal province, Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela has
shown she can draw a crowd. She is a veteran politician, seen one
week in a church choir holding a Bible, the next bringing boxes of
food and donated clothing to crime victims. Yet within the party
she is seen as something of a loose cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Of late she has been toeing the party line, however, praising
Mbeki and predicting that he will have the brains and the will to
rid the country of crime and bring jobs to the millions of
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that her prominence on the candidates list is
a strategic move by the ANC to make sure that she does not leave
the party to start her own or to join her longtime friend Bantu
Holomisa and his fast-growing new United Democratic Movement.
</P>
<P>
   At the official opening of the ANC campaign in Soweto in March,
Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela stole the show. She arrived 45 minutes
late, as Mbeki was reading his speech. But the crowd cheered and
yelled so much that he had to stop to acknowledge her with a
traditional salute, ``Viva the president of the African National
Congress Women's League.'' Even then, however, the crowd kept
cheering and Mbeki labored through much of his speech unheard.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, who was also at the event, did not even greet his
former wife. Apparently, the two are back in court over the
four-room house here, where they lived together before he was sent
to prison for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the house has been under Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela's
control, and two years ago she opened it as a museum, charging a $2
entry fee. She raised eyebrows when she also encouraged visitors to
buy small vials of dirt from the property for $8. The dirt came in
a box labeled ``Heroes Acre.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, Mandela, who exercised his right to buy the
house from the government in 1997, gave it to the Soweto Heritage
Trust, a foundation that oversees some of Soweto's other landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mandela and the trust are moving to evict Mrs.
Madikizela-Mandela, and she is countersuing, contending that her
rights to buy the house, on Vilakazi Street in the Orlando West
section of Soweto, were ignored. The house is one of hundreds of
identical houses built for blacks under the apartheid government.
</P>
<P>
   While she may want the house, Mrs. Mandela is shedding other
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, she gave away the wedding ring that Mandela
had given her, calling it a gesture of reconciliation. She gave the
gold ring with two diamonds to the 13-year-old daughter of a former
security policeman, Paul Erasmus. Erasmus admitted during a Truth
and Reconciliation Commission hearing into Mrs.
Madikizela-Mandela's role in Soweto violence before 1990 that he
had spied on her and had taken part in efforts to spread malicious
information about her.
</P>
<P>
   But the two have remained friends. Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela gave
the ring to Candice Erasmus when she was attending a birthday party
for one of Mrs. Madikizela-Mandela's children. Erasmus said the
ring would be kept in trust and probably donated to a museum one
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
