<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HISTORY-NYT &LR;      04-10 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROLOGUE: CHRONICLE OF A WAR FORETOLD YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, EXCLUSIVE-DOWNED-F117, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-SUMMIT, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX, KOSOVO-HISTORY,
KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW, KOSOVO-MIDEAST-REVIEW, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE-REVIEW) 
 (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The French writer Andre Malraux once warned a Serbian
visitor of the danger of an ``Algerian war'' in Kosovo. He added,
``And your Algeria will not be on another continent, but in your
heartland.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 years after that prediction was made, it appears to
have come true. The resistance of an overwhelming majority of
ethnic Albanians fiercely opposed to what they see as colonial
Serbian oppression has passed beyond the intermittent rioting of
the 1980s to the war of today.
</P>
<P>
   The Algerian war, a brutal struggle for Algerian independence
from France, brought the fall of the French Fourth Republic.
Whether President Slobodan Milosevic's autocratic Yugoslav regime
can survive the fighting in Kosovo remains a question. But it is
already clear that, having provided the key to his rise to power,
Kosovo has the potential to be Milosevic's nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after driving several hundred thousand Albanians from
their homes, Milosevic reversed course _ at least nominally _ and
made what seemed a curious appeal. He invited Kosovo Albanians to
come back and share ``joint life, peace, unity and understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The language was strongly reminiscent of the official parlance
of Tito's Yugoslavia, a country always described as a ``socialist
federation of free and equal peoples'' based on ``the brotherhood
and unity'' of its ``nations and nationalities'' and on ``the
struggle for peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This use of the language of Tito's times has been a hallmark for
Milosevic since he rose to power in 1987, becoming the Serbian
leader after a long climb through the ranks of the League of
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the long and violent break-up of Tito's Yugoslavia, a
country of six republics, two autonomous provinces, at least five
distinct languages and three main religions, Milosevic has sought
to maintain the illusion that the country still existed. This
served to buttress his argument that Serbs merely wanted to remain
in their state while other national groups were causing the
bloodshed by wanting to leave it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Milosevic himself who played the leading role in
undoing the delicate mosaic of Tito's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With its multiple ethnic and national groups _ 36 percent Serb,
20 percent Croat, 9 percent Bosnian Muslim, 8 percent Albanian, 8
percent Slovene, 6 percent Macedonian, 2.5 percent Montenegrin _
this former Yugoslavia long governed by Tito hinged on elaborate
mechanisms of balance and self-government.
</P>
<P>
   But, opting to fill the vacuum of a crumbling Communist system
with the compelling but treacherous clamor of Serbian nationalism,
Milosevic smashed Tito's delicate equilibrium in the late 1980s.
Kosovo was the principal vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the ethnic Albanians of ``demographic genocide''
against the minority Kosovo Serbs _ a reference to the Albanians'
high birth rate _ and expressing the grievances of Kosovo Serbs,
who felt they had become aliens on Serbia's most holy land,
Milosevic quashed the autonomy that Tito had accorded Kosovo, and
in 1989 installed his own men to replace the province's
predominantly Albanian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Milosevic had already moved to secure his power by
mounting similar internal coups to gain control of Serbia's other
autonomous province, Vojvodina, and the republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the eight-member rotating presidency bequeathed by
Tito on Yugoslavia had become one in which Milosevic controlled
four seats _ those of Serbia, Kosovo, Vojvodina and Montenegro. The
Slovenes and Croats, who had long chafed at federal rule from
Belgrade, quickly dubbed Yugoslavia ``Serboslavia'' and wanted out,
just as the Kosovo Albanians do today.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Milosevic was aware, even a decade ago, that the
process he had set in motion would be violent.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, in 1989, he spoke of a ``humiliated'' Serbian people
that should throw off its ``inferiority complex'' to assume its
place as ``the big nation in this region'' and recover its ``its
state, national and spiritual integrity'' through ``armed battles''
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Those battles have now unfurled with such persistence and
violence that Milosevic's most recent appeal for ``unity'' and
``joint life'' with the Albanians appears to run counter to a
decade whose overwhelming characteristic has been the separation
and unscrambling of once-mixed Yugoslav ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' said Jonathan Eyal, a British foreign policy
analyst, ``an independent Kosovo, sooner or later, is probably
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there is not much ``joint life'' left in what was
Yugoslavia. Slovenia was always ethnically homogeneous _ with a
population more than 90 percent Slovene _ and it was therefore able
to extricate itself from Yugoslavia in 1991 with relatively little
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia, whose population was 12 percent Serbian before the wars
of Yugoslavia's destruction began, endured four years of conflict
before it gained independent control of all its territory, a
process that involved the eviction of most Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after the departure of about 300,000 Serbs, the Serbian
share of the population has fallen to about 5 percent and continues
to dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia, the most ethnically mixed of the former Yugoslav
republics, was 43.7 percent Muslim, 31.4 percent Serbian and 17.3
percent Croatian, according to the last Yugoslav census, taken a
year before war erupted there in 1992. It is now governed on the
basis of the de facto division of the country into three largely
ethnically pure regions under Serbian, Muslim and Croatian control.
</P>
<P>
   After the eviction of more than 800,000 Muslims, most of them
driven out in 1992, the Serbian area of Bosnia, covering 49 percent
of the territory, is now 94 percent Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim area, covering 32 percent of the territory, is now
more than 90 percent Muslim. The Croatian area, accounting for the
remaining 19 percent of Bosnia, is more than 90 percent Croat.
</P>
<P>
   In all, this unraveling of Tito's Yugoslavia has involved the
deaths of more than 200,000 people and the displacement of more
than 3 million _ including the hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians now driven out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Serbian province of Vojvodina, where
an ethnic Hungarian minority lives alongside Serbs, most
coexistence has been obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   Tito was always aware of the fragility of his postwar creation:
``a federal state having the form of a state community of
voluntarily united nations and their socialist republics,'' as he
once described it. He saw government essentially as a balancing act
in which he placed himself at the fulcrum.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has taken over some of the Titoesque trappings _ the
relentless state propaganda dedicated to his person, the official
language of ``unity'' and ``peace'' and ``friendship.'' Kosovo's
Albanians, at least, are likely to pay little heed to such
terminology in their press for independence. Kosovo's place in
Serbia and Yugoslavia, like Algeria's place in France four decades
ago, now appears acutely vulnerable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
