<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3154 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-10 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: COWBOY FEMINISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As that wacky Freud gloomily observed, ``My God, what does a
woman want?''
</P>
<P>
   When we were gatherers, we wanted hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Then we wanted clean-cut doctors and lawyers instead of hirsute
alphas in loin cloths.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the '60s. We wanted equal pay for equal work,
co-partners and zipless adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Then we wanted Mr. Moms, male nurturers to share the burden of
food-shopping and baby-diapering (alpha Alan Aldas).
</P>
<P>
   And now that we have feminized society and domesticated our men,
now that we have forced them to help pick Martha Stewart stencils
and watch Olympic ice dancing, guess what we really want.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Yup. Brawny, rippling, rawhide hunks who don't know a Flaubert
from a flambe, or King Lear from King Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboy Option is the perfect coda for a year when feminists
committed hara-kiri to defend their president, and when Hillary
Clinton was unmasked as a counterfeit feminist after she let her
man step all over her.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment scandal dissolved into a rabid demand for the
cherry lip glaze Monica wore during her interview with Barbara
Walters. (There's still a two-week waiting list for it.)
</P>
<P>
   The backlash against feminism offers a rich menu of alternatives
_ from Doris Day to Cosmo nymphet. Drew Barrymore is making a
big-screen version of ``Charlie's Angels.'' Conservative women urge
a return to modesty, while women's magazines pant with seduction
tricks. An April Glamour story interprets the shy, enigmatic
creatures: ``From His Refusal to Talk to His X-Rated Fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   And now comes Sara Davidson with a new answer to Freud's query.
A journalist who later became a writer and producer for ``Dr.
Quinn, Medicine Woman,'' Ms. Davidson wrote ``Loose Change,'' the
tale of three women navigating the revolutions of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s changed the world; the way men and women talk, the
way women look at themselves,'' she told The New York Times in
1977. ``Everything is utterly, utterly changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, everything is utterly, utterly changed again.
In her new ``fictionalized memoir,'' ``Cowboy: A Love Story,'' Ms.
Davidson asks why a woman can't be more like a man, and choose a
mate based on animal attraction rather than intellectual
compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old went to do a story on a cowboy poetry and music
festival back in 1993 and met Richard Goff, rawhide braider. Ten
years her junior, he knew how to use his hands. She calls him Zack
in her memoir.
</P>
<P>
   The only impediment to joy for Ms. Davidson was that she and
Goff did not share the same reference points. It's hard to believe
that someone who worked on ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman'' could find
someone intellectually and culturally inadequate. But she winced a
bit. He had never heard of Anne Frank, or even William Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, have other talents. ``We were two famished
souls and we were having a feeding frenzy,'' she writes, in one of
her tamer passages.
</P>
<P>
   In a Times interview last week with Alex Witchel, Ms. Davidson
struggled with the trade-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she sounded confident about ``fourth-wave feminism,''
where, she said, all the rules go out the window and women can
choose ``nontraditional'' men.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, she was defensive: ``Can I have a deep relationship
with someone who hasn't read Anne Frank?'' She is wrestling with
her elitism, hoping that literacy is not more important than lust.
</P>
<P>
   I asked my girlfriends what trade-offs they would make.
``Shakespeare and Fitzgerald are requirements,'' said Jill. ``But
I'd sacrifice a few lesser Henry James novels.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tough. What if he knows about Brutus' fatal blunders but
has never heard of ``Coriolanus''? Does he have to have experienced
the Norton Shakespeare, or will the Miramax version do?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboy Option is already giving men I know the jitters. They
are annoyed that just when we've trained them to be more like us,
we decide to be more like them. Just when we've impressed upon them
the shame of liking dumb, sexy girls, we pounce on dumb, sexy guys.
</P>
<P>
   What does a woman want?
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo and Juliet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-10 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SENIOR CITIZENS ON THE BREAD LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   (bl)  
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Getting enough to eat has sometimes been a
problem for Dolores Heuser. She lost an arm to cancer and her
savings are gone. While much of America was experiencing an
economic boom, she was making a demoralizing move from her
comfortable home in the Phoenix suburb of Youngtown to a low-income
residence in nearby El Mirage. Having reached her 70s (``I won't
tell you exactly how old I am,'' she said), Ms. Heuser, a widow,
frequently found herself without money for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a very bad situation,'' she said. ``I only had Social
Security coming in, and I couldn't get by on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunger is an awful, debilitating companion. You can test this by
missing a few meals. Ms. Heuser learned, like many thousands of
other elderly citizens, that after her essential monthly expenses
were paid, the money she would have spent on food had mostly
vanished. She was helped through her crisis by donations of food
distributed by the Second Harvest food-bank network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that, I don't know what I would have done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes of poverty-stricken Americans standing in bread lines are
standard in documentaries about the Depression, which ended more
than half a century ago. What is not generally acknowledged _
perhaps not widely known _ is that there are bread lines all over
the United States right now.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning older residents of El Mirage began lining
up at a senior citizens center for donations of food provided by
the West Side Food Bank in the neighboring town of Surprise. They
did not discuss their portfolios or the surging Nasdaq. The
heralded free-market economy had left them far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this helps, you know,'' said Carol Lorig, 80. ``I have
to take care of my son, who's ill and can't work. We don't have
enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   William Yakubik, 86, said: ``You cut down the food if you have
to. Eat less. The cost of living, you know how it is. Robbing Peter
to pay Paul. Feast or famine.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Ennis, one of the directors of the food bank, said the
elderly residents who line up for food supplies are especially
vulnerable to unexpected expenses. ``These are people who cannot
afford food if they experience an illness and have to buy medicine,
or if their car breaks down and has to be repaired, or if there is
some kind of unexpected housing expense, like a leaking roof or a
break-in. Then they are in serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A study a few years ago by the Urban Institute, a research
organization in Washington, found that nearly 2 million elderly
Americans had faced at least one of two terrible dilemmas: whether
to pay their rent or buy food, or whether to pay for medicine or
buy food. Those are choices no American should have to make.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the nation's population as a whole, Doug O'Brien,
the director of public policy and research at Second Harvest, said:
``We are finding a great deal of pain and anxiety and some
instances of malnutrition. Hunger is disguised in this country.
It's not like it is in North Korea, where people have to eat grass,
or in East Africa, where they just waste away. It's not
life-threatening in most cases. But it is a serious, insidious
problem that affects many million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hunger problem. And other Western industrialized
nations do not have a hunger problem. And that is just not
acceptable when we have such abundance.''
</P>
<P>
   Second Harvest is the largest nonprofit clearinghouse in the
United States for donations to soup kitchens and food pantries.
Officials said a recent comprehensive survey showed that over the
course of a year, more than 21 million people sought emergency food
assistance through the Second Harvest network. The officials
stressed that the 21 million figure referred to separate
individuals, not the total number of emergency meals served. And
they said they believed that there were many more Americans,
millions more, who did not have enough money to pay for an adequate
diet.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Heuser, whose situation is typical, is resigned to her
new circumstances. ``I can't go to a lovely restaurant,'' she said.
``I can't get my hair set anymore. But I am thankful for the
assistance. I'll go on Monday for a food box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
