<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-650&AMP;A     04-10 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIAN OFFICIAL TELLS OF PEACE TALKS AND DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Serious talks are under way to create an
interim government for Kosovo, a senior Yugoslav official said
Saturday. He also said that more than 300 civilians died and nearly
3,000 more were wounded in the NATO bombings.
</P>
<P>
   These are the most concrete figures for civilian casualties to
emerge since the airstrikes began, although they cannot be
independently confirmed. There has been virtually no information
about Yugoslav military casualties, which are considered a state
secret in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   The official also said that the moderate ethnic Albanian leader,
Ibrahim Rugova, is continuing talks with top Yugoslav officials on
an interim political solution, meeting again on Friday in Pristina
with two deputy prime ministers, Nikola Sainovic and Ratko
Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Nebojsa Vujovic, was the top-ranking Yugoslav
diplomat in Washington, and lived there for nine years, before the
war began and Belgrade broke relations with the United States and
several other NATO countries. He has just been appointed spokesman
for the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ``NATO propaganda and lies'' that Rugova is being held
against his will and forced into discussions, Vujovic said, ``Dr.
Rugova is not a hostage _ he's a free man who feels the heartbeat
of his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``His talks with us pull the rug out from under the
aggressors,'' Vujovic said, referring to NATO. President Clinton
and other NATO leaders say the bombing will go on until the Serbs
agree to provide Kosovo with a full measure of autonomy under the
protection of an international security force. Before the bombing
began, Belgrade had rejected the idea of 30,000 NATO-led forces
policing a Western-drafted plan in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The talks concern ``an interim government with joint
institutions of self-government representing all ethnic groups and
covering all branches of the local Serbian government,'' including
the police, Vujovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of an interim government with representation by
Serbs and Albanians has been agreed upon, based on a framework for
autonomy, he said, without adding details.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the framework was not specifically based on ``the
Rambouillet process,'' referring to negotiations in France earlier
this year that produced a Western draft plan for far-reaching
Kosovar autonomy. The plan was accepted by the ethnic Albanian
delegation, including Rugova, but rejected by the Serbian
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rambouillet was just a grand masquerade, not a real process of
negotiation,'' Vujovic said. ``Dr. Rugova was there but was just
pushed aside, even though he had been earlier received at the White
House and the State Department at the highest level, and the French
gave him a medal. But the U.S. found a new alliance with the Kosovo
Liberation Army, and Rugova's aware of that, and aware of what that
situation has brought the ordinary Albanians of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this correspondent could interview Rugova, Vujovic
said, ``That time may come,'' but insisted that Yugoslavian
authorities had concerns for Rugova's safety. He said that there
were ideas being floated that Rugova might travel to Moscow to show
that he was acting freely. He also said that Italy and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe had both asked
for him to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's most needed here to participate in the process right
now,'' Vujovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ministry officials regularly deny NATO allegations that
Serbian forces are committing atrocities in Kosovo. They say that
the Kosovo Liberation Army has been fighting a war against the
Serbs and that it is difficult to separate the rebels from the
civilians who support them. They have rejected accusations of mass
killings as well as the existence of an organized policy of
``ethnic cleansing,'' attributing the flight of Kosovo citizens to
fear of NATO bombings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked about an article in Saturday's New York Times quoting U.S.
officials saying that up to 700,000 ethnic Albanians are displaced
inside Kosovo and running out of food, Vujovic said the numbers are
``grossly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombings began, he said, ``I can guarantee you, there
were not 700,000 displaced people there.'' Vujovic went on to ask:
``Who makes the humanitarian catastrophe NATO says it is bombing to
prevent? The bombs themselves or Serbs chasing the people? Kosovo
has had the greatest bombings, and who would sit in their houses
when the bombs are flying?''
</P>
<P>
   He complained that when the Yugoslavian authorities ask the
ethnic Albanians to remain in Kosovo, they are accused of
endangering them. ``If they go, we are to blame. If they stay, we
are also to blame. It's a no-win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Vujovic noted with satisfaction that NATO had finally admitted
that one of its bombs had hit a residential part of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many other mistakes have they made that they have not
admitted?'' he asked. He said that 12 civilians had died from a
bomb that landed in the center of the town of Cuprija on Thursday
night, leaving 400 families homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Another 124 people were wounded _ with 23 still in the hospital,
six in intensive care _ when the Zastava automobile and munitions
factory was bombed in Kragujevac, said Milan Beko, the manager of
the factory, interviewed there on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wounded, visited in the local hospital, were
suffering blast and pressure wounds, with large hematomas and
internal injuries, said Dr. Slavica Djukic-Dejanovic, the head of
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A ``human shield'' of workers was used to protect the factory,
which is why the night attack hurt so many.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were not allowed to see the munitions part of the
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Such attacks only stiffen Serbian patriotism and resistance,
Vujovic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will defend ourselves, with help or without it,'' he said.
``We have no other choice. We're really in a corner, like a cat,
and our nails are out. We've got nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that some Yugoslavians express concerns about how long the
bombing will go on and what long-term damage it will do, Vujovic
said: ``This psychological nervousness will pass and be replaced
with anger, and this anger will grow. Each day, we're like a
porcupine rolling itself more and more tightly into a ball, with
our quills out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
