<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3172 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES     04-10 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO IS SET TO CONTINUE AIR ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO,
KOSOVO-SUMMIT, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX, KOSOVO-HISTORY, KOSOVO-CAMPUS,
KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW, KOSOVO-MIDEAST-REVIEW, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE-REVIEW) 
(lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ With NATO bombing of Yugoslavia now in its
18th day, a senior allied diplomat said here Saturday that the
alliance was prepared to continue air attacks ``for many more
weeks'' but that the idea of using ground troops was not being
seriously discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's agreement in the alliance that the air campaign is
having its effect, but that there's a lot more time left before it
has run its course,'' the official said. ``The issue of ground
troops is not being debated in a formal or serious way within the
alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other NATO foreign
ministers will meet here Monday, the alliance's spokesman, Jamie
Shea, said Saturday, to reaffirm the alliance's determination to
continue the air campaign with undiminished intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will go to Oslo, Norway, on Tuesday to talk with the
Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, about the possibility of
bringing Russia back into the search for a lasting peace settlement
in Kosovo, officials said, despite its firm opposition to the
allied bombing campaign and its sharp warnings to the alliance not
to try to go into Kosovo with ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook also had a 45-minute
telephone call with Ivanov on Saturday morning, and Doug Henderson,
the British armed forces minister, said in London on Saturday that
Ivanov had reaffirmed Russia's desire to stay out of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin indicated on Friday that Russia might
respond if the allies decided to fight their way into Kosovo on the
ground. Politically, that is still a forbidden topic for the
allies, and the foreign ministers are not planning to decide on
Monday to change that, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign will continue, the allies insist, until
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic calls off Serbian military
and police operations that have driven most of the 1.8 million
ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo, and agrees to let
international peacekeepers in to enforce a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that ``in the next few days'' NATO would be conducting
125 flights to ferry in some two dozen U.S. Apache helicopters and
their accompanying missiles and equipment. Although in Washington
officials said the helicopters' arrival could take a month,
officials here said Saturday that they may be ready for combat
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials here said that Serbian army and heavily armed
police units have continued attacks against the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army units near Malisevo and farther north near
Mitrovica, despite Milosevic's declaration of a unilateral
cease-fire early last week.
</P>
<P>
   NATO released an aerial photograph of the village of Prilea, an
Albanian settlement two miles from Decani in Kosovo, that showed
almost total destruction of its two-story concrete block homes.
NATO had not bombed the village at all, a military spokesman said,
and all the damage had been done deliberately by the Serbian forces
who drove the original inhabitants away. NATO says 200 villages and
towns have been destroyed by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian border guards on Friday night also reopened crossings
from Kosovo after three days, and ethnic Albanian refugees began
lining up to get into Macedonia and Albania again Saturday,
according to officials in the field and at NATO headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at Blace on the Macedonian border saw at least 200
ethnic Albanians moving into the neutral zone between Yugoslav and
Macedonian territory early Saturday and being checked by Macedonian
border guards, the Reuters news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, another group of 1,500 bedraggled Kosovo refugees
sheltered by plastic sheeting crossed into the northern Albanian
village of Morini, saying Serbs had chased them from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The allies also published a map indicating three large areas
inside Kosovo where they believe more than 200,000 people have been
forced to seek shelter in the rubble of their ruined villages or in
the fields and hills of the countryside. The map showed 70,000
people possibly scattered in a broad area east of Malisevo, 60,000
west of Pristina, and another 80,000 to 100,000 west of Podujevo
north of Pristina, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were trying to figure out if they could
effectively drop food and emergency supplies to them from the air.
But the officials indicated that they were skeptical of the idea
unless the few aid agencies allowed to operate in Kosovo could
help.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds and rain over target areas throughout Yugoslavia on
Friday night and Saturday significantly hindered the air campaign
against the Serbian forces. Those carrying out the attacks in
Kosovo have now largely dug in and taken cover in wrecked villages
or off the main roads, according to Col. Konrad Freytag, an allied
military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the few air-dropped guided bomb attacks that did take
place destroyed a microwave relay tower near Pristina, and knocked
Serbian state-controlled television off the air there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relay which has a dual use capability, and was mainly
used by the military,'' Freytag said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied civilian authorities have so far denied the alliance's
top military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, the authority he
requested to blast Serbian television towers and eliminate what he
believes to be insidious anti-NATO propaganda from the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, according to senior officials here, the allies
are all still agreed that a sustained bombing campaign alone can
force Milosevic to accept a settlement and allow international
peacekeepers in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people knew it could be a long campaign,'' one senior
diplomat said. ``They are pretty realistic about the fact that this
will probably go on for many more weeks. As we get closer to the
goal, I think his attitude will begin to shift.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies say they have destroyed half of Yugoslavia's fuel
supplies, half of its most sophisticated military interceptors, and
two out of the three main army headquarters that did the planning
for the Serbian campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
