<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3174 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2NDTAK     04-10 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS, Belgium: in Kosovo.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milosevic's plan to redraw the ethnic map of the province to
drive out most of the people of Albanian ancestry who lived there
was put in place last October, according to German Defense Ministry
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, code-named ``horseshoe'' or ``potkova'' in the Serbian
language, was launched last October, even as Milosevic was
promising to withdraw the police and military forces that had
already begun driving Albanians out of their homes, German Defense
Minister Rudolf Scharping said in Bonn last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our analysis of `operation horseshoe' sadly confirms what we
had inferred during the negotiations, which is that Milosevic
wanted to win time to prepare a systematic deportation,'' Scharping
said.
</P>
<P>
   Already under threat of NATO bombing last fall, Milosevic agreed
in October talks with Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. special envoy to
the Balkans, to withdraw the attacking Serbian forces. But he would
not accept an international peacekeeping force, so Holbrooke
settled for 2,500 unarmed observers from the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   These observers were never able to stop continued fighting or to
compel Serbian forces to conform to Milosevic's promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation began in November of 1998 in Kosovo,'' Scharping
said. ``It shows that in a certain part of Kosovo the Yugoslav army
and police planned and then began, between November of 1998 and the
beginning of the negotiations in Rambouillet, to expel people.''
</P>
<P>
   German diplomats said that NATO intelligence had observed the
military buildup north of Kosovo and inside the province, but had
wrongly concluded that it was aimed only at the Kosovo Liberation
Army, which has been fighting for independence but last month
accepted proposals for autonomy under Serbian rule, with a NATO
peacekeeping force to guarantee it, in the peace plan worked out in
talks at Rambouillet castle near Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's refusal to accept that plan or even discuss an
international peacekeeping plan was what sparked NATO bombing on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The only ground forces the allies planned for are 28,000
peacekeepers in case Milosevic accepts a settlement in Kosovo.
Diplomats here say that if the allies do decide to send in a ground
force, they could do so quickly, since allied military planners
last fall did some contingency planning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
