<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CAMPUS-ART-500     04-10 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAMPUS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT INSULARITY MUTES THEIR OUTRAGE TO BALKAN CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., N.J., Conn., Wis., Vt. Va.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. _ The students at Rutgers University lined
up to stuff their book bags with maps, time lines and other
handouts about the crisis in Kosovo, then elbowed their way into a
``teach-in'' that amounted to a crash course on the hundreds of
years of Balkan conflict that preceded NATO's bombing of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had set up seats for 80 students but wound up drawing
more than 400. Some tapped notes into their Palm Pilots; most
stayed through all four hours of lectures on Tuesday by experts on
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Light, 20, a junior majoring in history, came out
convinced that the human rights atrocities justified intervention.
``I'm not a violent person, but the way those people are being
attacked over there _ give me a gun,'' he said. ``If my
grandparents had NATO to protect them from the Nazis, I would have
an aunt. She wouldn't have died at Treblinka.''
</P>
<P>
   Light's outburst testified to a fascination with the Kosovo
conflict that has touched several of the nation's college campuses,
as this apolitical, post-Cold War generation tuned in to foreign
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A college freshman this year was probably in fourth grade when
the Berlin Wall fell in 1989, in fifth grade when the Persian Gulf
War was fought in early 1991. So for today's students, war is as
antiseptic and theoretical as a computer game. There is none of the
passion that inflamed a Rutgers teach-in on Vietnam in 1965 _ when
a rock sailed through a lecture hall's window _ but then there is
no draft, and no body bags, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a formative experience,'' said James
Miller, a political science professor on the graduate faculty of
the New School University who has studied social protests. ``This
is a generation that is serious-minded and is going to ask
pragmatic and practical questions. Campuses remain places where in
a moment of crisis, young people will take the time to think
through what is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   What students say have shaken them about Kosovo are television
pictures of American soldiers held captive, comparisons to World
War II and the Holocaust, and fear that a military quagmire lies
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies, food drives and speak-outs are being thrown together by
students who say they feel a moral responsibility to respond, but
have only a murky idea of what is happening. Like many adults, they
are not sure what to think, let alone what to do. So the new
activism seems heartfelt, but tentative. The flier for a
candlelight vigil at Elon College in North Carolina, for instance,
proclaims, ``The war in Kosovo demands our attention,'' but planned
action consists of a moment of silence ``for the people who are
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are, like, `Whoa! This is something really
important,''' said Vanessa Marvin, 20, a junior at Yale University.
However, Ms. Marvin said she was uncertain what course the United
States should follow, because she did not know the alternatives.
All she can be sure of, she said, is, ``I'm very against
genocide.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Charles Young, a Rutgers doctoral student in history, showed up
at the teach-in in his red ``People's Bookstore'' T-shirt, an
artifact of his days in Madison, Wis., a bastion of student
protests in the 1960s. Young, now 39, was 13 when the draft ended
in 1973. He calls himself a pacifist, but said he is stumped by
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once, imperialism is backing the victims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Chapman University in Orange, Calif., political science
students decided to help the local American Red Cross chapter with
a phone bank for refugee aid. Two University of Kentucky students
have started a relief drive. At the University of Vermont, art
students turned a collage assignment into a gallery of martial
images, including a tank made of plumbing parts, with people formed
from knives, forks and spoons emerging from the gun barrel.
</P>
<P>
   More cuttingly, Virginia Commonwealth University students
greeted visitors at the edge of their Richmond campus on Easter
with signs like, ``No Bomb Is Smart.'' At Rutgers, stenciled black
spray paint began appearing on sidewalks around the campus,
condemning NATO as the ``Nazi American Terrorist Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little new, of course, in students reacting with moral
outrage. ``Whatever else has changed, students are primed to
respond morally, even if an issue is remote from them,'' said
Richard Flacks, a sociology professor at the University of
California at Santa Barbara who has studied demonstrations for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Flacks said students' response to this crisis was likely to be
muted by their general disengagement from international affairs.
``To a lot of students, the whole world looks like Bosnia _ a
confusing, undecodable, highly messy set of happenings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after sitting through the Rutgers teach-in, Justin Main,
21, a junior who had a sketch pad tucked under his arm, still
grasped for basics. ``This Milosevic guy is Serbian, right?'' Main
asked.
</P>
<P>
   After a debate on Wednesday at Columbia University's School of
International and Public Affairs, students left with raging
ambivalence. ``You feel so disheartened by the whole thing,'' said
Rebecca Zimmerman, a sophomore majoring in political science.
``There doesn't seem to be any right answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree to which war is largely an intellectual exercise for
today's students was reflected in a chat on the way out of the
Rutgers teach-in. Hidekel Elivo, a freshman majoring in finance,
was saying the United States should back up its air power with
ground troops _ an idea that horrified Anna Tello, a sophomore
majoring in political science.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would send Americans to get killed?'' she asked
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to get killed,'' Elivo said. ``To help out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CONGRESS11-COX     04-10 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONGRESS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Off-limits? Some say Congress should leave IOC alone
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just as the bruises have begun to fade, the battered
International Olympic Committee is about to take another hit: U.S.
politicians are waiting in the halls of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the lords of the rings convened an emergency session
in the security of their marble-clad compound on the shores of Lake
Geneva for a little blood-letting and wound-licking _ and a promise
to press ahead with an ethical cleansing to purge its past of
secrecy and self-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), not one to shy away from
cameras or controversy, wasn't impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Tough bills in works
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a possible Republican presidential candidate who is
convening his own IOC reform session Wednesday before the Senate
Commerce Committee, said the IOC effort fell far short of what was
needed ``to bring transparency and accountability to the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans tough legislation to strip the IOC of its
tax-exempt status. And he hopes that hitting the international
organization where it hurts _ in its fat bank account will push the
IOC to take more action.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's view is that the IOC merely sacrificed a half-dozen
small fry, set up a couple of commissions chaired by its own
leader, Juan Antonio Samaranch, and washed its hands of the whole
unpleasantness. However, the senator was pleased that two big
names, Henry Kissinger and Peter Ueberroth, agreed last week to
serve on the IOC 2000 reform panel.
</P>
<P>
   McCain thinks Samaranch hasn't taken any of it seriously. Last
month, he closed the IOC meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland, by
proclaiming: ``We promised to clean house. We did it. We promised
reforms. We did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old Spaniard declined McCain's invitation to go
before the Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation to
discuss the culture that corrupted Salt Lake City _ and presumably
other cities bidding to host the Olympics. That refusal prompted
McCain to fire off a statement suggesting that Samaranch did not
``understand the gravity of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the IOC didn't even appear to notice the scandal until
nervous sponsors started withholding payments and calling Lausanne
last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics is a $1 billion-a-year enterprise, and much of that
money comes from corporations seeking to link their products with
the idealized image of the Games. If that image is tainted, it
isn't worth as much to the Coca-Colas and Kodaks that pay $50
million for sponsor rights every four years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's committee will hear proposed legislation from Sen. Ted
Stevens (R-Alaska) to limit tax deductions that U.S. companies can
take from their sponsorship fees and advertising expenses. For
those companies that claim the deductions, sponsoring the Games
suddenly becomes a far more costly proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also would limit the IOC's access to billions of
dollars in fees for television rights by giving negotiating power
to the U.S. Olympic Committee, which already receives more Olympic
revenue than any other national Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If more money were to come in to the U.S. and less would go to
other countries, that would cause some real anxiety and pain among
the other countries of the world and the IOC,'' said Bob Heussner
of Advantage International, Olympic marketing consultants based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic scholar John J. MacAloon went even further. ``The USOC
does not own the property,'' MacAloon said. ``This is the pirates
emptying the safe while the ship is on rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the world's premier Olympic scholars join the IOC in
opposing the U.S. government's intervention. The Olympics, they
say, operates outside of global politics, boycotts notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain is astute,'' said historian John Lucas of Penn State,
``but what he knows about the inner machinations of the Olympic
movement can be written on the back of a 33-cent postage stamp. It
would be presumptuous of me to go down to Washington and tell the
Finance Committee how to spend their money.''
</P>
<P>
   The historian thinks Congress has no credibility when it
scrutinizes a private, foreign organization but doesn't appear
interested in examining the United States' own Olympic committee,
the USOC, an organization over which it has jurisdiction under the
Olympic and Amateur Sports Act.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who has studied the Olympics for 45 years, acknowledges
that the IOC is in desperate need of reform. But he said, ``McCain
should have absolutely nothing to do directly or indirectly with an
organization that is European-based, international in nature and
mandated by the Swiss government as a nonprofit organization.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC backers to appear
</P>
<P>
   The USOC refuses to release the results of its own internal
investigation into what gifts its members received from bid cities.
It also will not divulge what actions it has taken against any
employees or board members, despite evidence that some probably
knew about Salt Lake City's million-dollar bribery campaign.
</P>
<P>
   MacAloon, a professor of anthropology at the University of
Chicago, said he thinks the USOC is setting the agenda for McCain's
hearings and will emerge unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to speak are USOC President William Hybl and members
of a USOC-appointed investigation commission headed by former
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine. The commission's
report, issued last month, criticized the IOC for lacking openness
and creating a culture of gift giving that is ``potentially illegal
and inevitably corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   If the hearings discuss the USOC's role in the scandal, MacAloon
said, ``Then it will be doing good service to the reform of the
Olympic movement. But if, instead, it holds hands with the USOC in
joyful IOC bashing, it will be a huge embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, an IOC member from Los Angeles, will represent
Samaranch. ``It is important for the IOC to be there and have it's
story come out,'' IOC Vice President Dick Pound said. ``And it's
better to have that come out of the mouth of a U.S. citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, a Canadian who headed the IOC's internal investigation,
said he thinks that McCain's hearing are too late. ``I think it was
a hot issue in February before the IOC began to look at the whole
issue of restructuring,'' Pound said. `` A good deal of what they
seem to be looking for, we've already done.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said sponsors should be upset about congressional
interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a Coca-Cola or Kodak or Xerox,'' Pound said, ``I
would wonder what Congress is proposing to do by monkeying with the
Internal Revenue Code, simply because there is some concern about
where a business expenditure is being directed. I would think that
kind of action would horrify the business community at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if McCain's hearing doesn't push the reform legislation
forward, the Olympics has more headaches to come.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department is expected to complete in June its
criminal investigation into Salt Lake City's bid tactics. Still
under investigation are questions about the commingling of personal
funds with Salt Lake bid committee accounts, the trail of money
from Salt Lake City to foreign destinations and alleged phony
corporations and contracts, according to reports in Salt Lake
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Utah attorney general has launched her own
probe into the Olympic bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   And two congressmen are pressing President Clinton to designate
the IOC as a ``public international organization,'' subject to a
treaty prohibiting Americans from bribing foreign officials.
Clinton is expected to act by Tuesday, the day before McCain's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Olympic pool was not a cesspool, it certainly had
infectious bacteria in it,'' historian Lucas said. ``It most surely
is being stirred up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
