<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-630     04-10 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRO TRYING TO RESIST SERBIA'S DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ The Yugoslav army wants Dragon Soc.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers bearing conscription notices have come to his house on
three occasions, most recently on Thursday morning, to demand that
he come with them to their barracks near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Soc said the draft notices are an insult and a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a kind of teasing _ it makes the tension here rise every
day,'' he said, adding that under Yugoslav law his refusal to join
the army makes him subject to imprisonment as a draft dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Soc ought to know. He is the minister of justice for the
Yugoslav republic of Montenegro. His government has declared that
it wants nothing whatsoever to do with the brutal expulsions and
destruction that the army, under the command of President Slobodan
Milosevic, is carrying out in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The justice minister's draft dodging is part of a power struggle
here that Western governments fear could spill over into civil war.
It pits the democratically elected government of Montenegro against
the Yugoslav army controlled by Milosevic, which has about 12,000
troops inside the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro and Serbia are all that is left of the six republics
that once made up Yugoslavia. With just 640,000 residents and a
leadership that is struggling to forge economic ties with the West,
Montenegro has emerged as the balky little brother in Milosevic's
dictatorial command of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The government here has not formally seceded, but it no longer
recognizes the legality of the federal government in Belgrade. The
republic's president, Milo Djukanovic, condemns what he calls
Milosevic's ``senseless policy of confrontation with the whole
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic on Thursday warned the commander of the Yugoslav army
in Montenegro, Gen. Milorad Obradovic, to order his troops to stop
breaking into the houses of citizens of Montenegro and forcibly
taking them into military service, said Branko Perovic, the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent days, besides trying to draft our minister of
justice, they are knocking down doors with armed police and taking
people away from their families by force,'' said Perovic, who said
that hundreds of Montenegrins had been drafted in that manner in
the last week, including several scores of people who run important
state institutions like schools and welfare centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president warned the general not to take any one of those
people who are important,'' said Perovic, adding that he did not
know what the army's response to the warning will be.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, even as he warned the army, Djukanovic went out of his
way to reassure the general that his government recognizes the
legitimacy of the army's role in this country, Perovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombings of Yugoslavia have forced the government here
to try to square a circle _ to stand up to Milosevic's military and
resist the emergency authority it is trying to impose under the
martial law imposed as bombings began, on March 24, but to resist
in a way that does not hand Milosevic a pretext for a coup.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bombs, things were simpler. As two recent elections
proved, a majority of Montenegrins, despite their historical and
religious ties to Serbia, were delighted with Djukanovic's
overtures to the United States and Western Europe. They seemed to
appreciate his scathing criticism of Milosevic. Since the bombing
began 18 days ago, though, Djukanovic has said that all bets are
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be very smart to understand that under these
circumstances it is very hard to speak about reforms and
democracy,'' Djukanovic told Corriere delle Sera, the Italian
daily, this week. ``It is now very easy for Milosevic to manipulate
Montenegrins.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army is now busy in Montenegro trying to carry out
the general call-up of reservists and new recruits that was ordered
by Milosevic as part of a declaration of martial law. The
Montenegrin government has been just as busy in the last 2{ weeks
trying to devise ways to give comfort, alternatives and excuses to
the large number of young men here who believe it would be insane
to serve in the Milosevic military.
</P>
<P>
   Such young Montenegrins are not hard to find. ``I am still
young, and I don't want to get killed,'' said Dejan Nikolic, 22, a
reservist who has received and ignored two notices demanding that
he report to an army anti-aircraft battery near Podgorica.
</P>
<P>
   There is an honored tradition of war in Montenegro. From the
14th to the 19th centuries, the main business of the tribal people
who lived here was fighting the Ottoman Turks, who never completely
conquered this mountainous republic. The Turks did conquer Serbia,
despite the best efforts of Montenegrins to help their Orthodox
brothers resist that defeat.
</P>
<P>
   All this history adds up to a relationship between Montenegrins
and Serbs that might be summed up as, ``I like you, but I think you
might be taking advantage of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrins have been more than willing to help Serbia fight
its battles. Beginning with Serbia's loss to the Turks in Kosovo in
1389, on through two world wars and finally during Milosevic's
losing battles in Croatia and Bosnia, Montenegrins did their bit
for Yugoslav solidarity. Indeed, Radovan Karadzic, leader of
Bosnia's Serbs during the 1992-95 war, comes from Montenegro, as
does the family of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But many Montenegrins say that in the back of their minds, there
has always been a sneaking suspicion that they were being played as
patsies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a saying that the Serbs will fight until the last
Montenegrin gets killed,'' said Velko Vlahovic, 30, a pilot who is
a reservist in the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin government has devised a system of excuses that
conscripts can show to the Yugoslav army to be legally exempted
from military service. It's called ``obligatory working duty.''
Under this system, a reporter at Montenegrin television, for
example, could get a note from his editor saying that he is doing
essential work.
</P>
<P>
   Momir Krivacevic, 26, a reporter at Montenegrin television, did
exactly that. He sent his exemption letter to the army. But the
army sent it back, saying he still must serve. Krivacevic said that
soldiers have come looking for him at the television station.
</P>
<P>
   What is he going do to?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the army, I have to go,'' Krivacevic said. ``If you
ask me, no chance. I don't recognize the federal army as legal
anymore in Montenegro. But if the Montenegrin police call me, I
will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Those police units, a force of about 8,000 that reports to the
Montenegrin president, have accepted as volunteers about a hundred
draft dodgers with military skills, according to a government
official.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, of course, is a draft dodger. Dejan Cvijanovic,
28, a computer specialist at the pro-Milosevic newspaper, Dan, has
volunteered to join the army and go to Kosovo to fight NATO. He
says he is awaiting orders. Cvijanovic says he is eager to fight,
and he believes the Montenegrin government is guilty of historical
and cultural treachery by backing away from the defense of Kosovo.
Sooner or later, he says, this treachery will force the army to
overthrow the government in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is our sacred place,'' he said. ``I didn't support
Milosevic before, but at this moment he is my president and my
leader. We will win, of course. God is on our side. Every bomb
dropped on Kosovo is a bomb dropped on Jesus Christ himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister of justice, meanwhile, is annoyed with the army's
temerity in upsetting what he said has been a longstanding Yugoslav
tradition of exempting elected officials from military service.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was elected to the Montenegrin Parliament in 1992, I
was a member of the army reserves and I had to resign from my
military position,'' Soc said. ``Now they are coming to a
minister's house and saying `come with us.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
