<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Partially engraved headstones will need Y2K fix
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You might call it the Y2K _ RIP problem.
</P>
<P>
   Families have long purchased headstones in advance, hoping to
spare surviving members additional expense after a family member
dies. They pay engravers to etch the century date in the stones,
with the last two numbers carved after death.
</P>
<P>
   But because so many people are now living longer than
anticipated _ and will likely pass the millennium mark in good
health _ local memorial companies say they'll have their hands full
correcting the ``19'' on the headstones to ``20'' after Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Why headstone purchasers made the presumption that they'd die
before 2000 is anybody's guess, although industry professionals say
that sparing relatives additional expenses down the line is a
common motive.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, partial date stones appear to be more common in
the Midwest than in other areas of the nation, said William Minozzi
of the Monument Builders of North America, an industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hopkins, superintendant of David's Cemetery, estimates
that at least 100 stones there have partial death dates.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies stopped including the partial death dates on
their pre-paid stones in the early '80s, Hopkins said. But that
still leaves perhaps up to 1 percent of all stones with partial
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing the stones won't be cheap. The process involves mixing
epoxy with granite to fill the numbers and then recarving the
stone. Carving just the year can cost about $100. More is charged
for full dates with month and day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
