<HEADER>
A3197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMENGOLF-NETWORKING1     04-10 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENGOLF-NETWORKING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women leverage the links
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You've snagged a precious four hours with a
potential client and serious golfer who _ if you signed her _ would
catapult your standing with the boss overnight. To make a good
impression, you take her out for a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   The first few holes go well, with a steady banter of friendly
talk about business, families and the like.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eighth hole, it all falls apart; you crack a joke
during her backswing and break her concentration. Your big title
and prestigious civic club memberships hurtle down the fairway of
professional failure.
</P>
<P>
   Networking with a 9-iron has been second nature for businessmen
for decades. Women, still relatively new at navigating the
corporate ladder, are at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   To alleviate that, the Kettering/Moraine/Oakwood Area Chamber of
Commerce on Friday (April 16) is hosting a Working Women's Luncheon
titled, ``Networking in Golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon, expected to draw more than 50 people, will include
a lesson with the golf pro at Country Club of the North, as well as
a presentation on how to use golf properly as a networking tool.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Molly Brown-Boula and Kim Grant come in.
</P>
<P>
   Founders of Executive Sport Networking, a corporate and
executive training company based in Brown-Boulay's Springboro home,
the women conduct seminars on using golf as an effective networking
tool.
</P>
<P>
   While neither woman claims to be any more than a novice on the
greens, both have done their share of circulating within golfing
circles. Grant is tournament coordinator for the Firstar LPGA
Classic. Brown-Boulay, who until April 1998 was interim director of
alumni relations at Wright State University and is now a free-lance
writer, has a background in event planning and management.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, Grant and Brown-Boulay have been developing
and holding seminars tailored to the needs of individual companies
or other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions do much more than assuage the fears of those who
are afraid of looking stupid on the course. ``If you're intimidated
by golfing, go out and watch the first tee; you will see some ugly
swings,'' Brown-Boulay said.
</P>
<P>
   They also address questions that a simple golf lesson can't
cover, such as: When do you conduct business on the course? Do you
actually bring a contract out to sign? Do you engage in gambling
games? Do you drink or smoke? What about tipping?
</P>
<P>
   Executive Sports Networking is currently working with a large
bank headquartered in Chicago to hold a seminar later this year for
nine of its top female executives, and has begun scheduling other
events to be held in and around the Miami Valley through fall.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Sports Networking has few peers. There are only about
a dozen other such organizations, mostly in large cities like San
Francisco, Washington, D.C., and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But with women making up almost 40 percent of all beginning
golfers in the country, according to the National Golf Foundation,
the need for such services has grown, said Nancy Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a competitive world, you need every advantage,'' said
Oliver, who founded the Executive Women's Golf Association in 1991.
``Women are finding that some of the tools they need to bring with
them include the ability to entertain corporate clients in the same
way men have.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who for a dozen years had been handling corporate public
relations accounts and organizing golf events around Florida, knew
that if she relied solely on lessons from a golf pro, she'd come
away knowing how to swing the club, but unaware of how to play the
game _ golf terminology, proper attire and how to behave on the
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to learn the game in a nonthreatening atmosphere, she
organized an eight-week clinic for local businesswomen. Today, EWG
has 90 chapters and 13,000 members in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   K/M/O Chamber executive director Michelle Hughes is encouraged
by the interest in the upcoming luncheon, part of a series of
topics aimed at female chamber members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time women have the opportunity for relationship building,
it's an advantage,'' Hughes said. ``We want to make it convenient
and easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
