<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOFT-MONEY-NYT &LR;      04-10 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TALK: SOFT MONEY AND SOME NOT-SO-HARD PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bookshelves in the capital are sagging with
countless handsomely bound, carefully researched, long-forgotten
reports proposing laws and policies that, were they ever to be
adopted, would affect millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One characteristic of these studies _ about Social Security,
taxes, health policy, education and dozens of other areas _ is that
the people who conduct them and make the recommendations often do
not themselves follow the prescriptions in their own daily lives
that they would impose on the body politic.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point involves the report advocating sweeping changes
in campaign finance laws published last month by the Committee for
Economic Development, an organization of business executives. The
report's principal recommendation is that soft money, the
unregulated donations that corporations can give to political
parties, should be outlawed. OK
</P>
<P>
   Corporations and unions have long been prohibited from giving
money directly to political candidates, but in recent elections,
they have gotten around the restrictions by donating large sums to
the parties.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 elections, corporations and business trade groups
gave a record $121 million in soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public cannot help but believe that these donors enjoy
special influence and receive special favors,'' the report stated.
``The suspicion of corruption deepens public cynicism and
diminishes public confidence in government. More important, these
activities raise the likelihood of actual corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference where the report was released, a
co-chairman of the subcommittee that conducted the study, Edward A.
Kangas, chairman and chief executive of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu,
the accounting and consulting firm, declared, ``Bad government is
bad business.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We fundamentally look at our campaign financing and
election processes, and we see many of the same fissures and cracks
in the foundation that led to the collapse of financial markets
elsewhere in the world, and we ask, `What might that hold for us
here in America?'''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he told a reporter, ``Until I understood the depth of
the problem, I was like a lot of Americans: I don't think I cared
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that Kangas' firm has no intention of
restricting its own soft money donations. For the 1998 elections,
Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the American subsidiary of Deloitte Touche
Tohmatsu, gave $185,300 to the Republican Party and $41,725 to the
Democratic Party, Federal Election Commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   Kangas was in Europe this week and told associates to say he was
too tied up in meetings to return a reporter's telephone calls. But
Ellen Ringel, the spokeswoman for Deloitte &AMP; Touche, provided this
statement: `` Kangas' views with regard to his participation in the
CED report are his personal views and do not necessarily represent
the views of Deloitte &AMP; Touche in the United States and will not
require Deloitte &AMP; Touche in the United States to do anything but
what is in the best interest of the partnership within the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ringel said Kangas had approved the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Kangas is not the first corporate executive to conclude that
soft money donations were a bad investment. In 1997, as a Senate
committee was exposing widespread abuses in campaign finance
practices by both parties, four large American corporations
announced that they were forswearing soft money donations.
</P>
<P>
   A review of Election Commission records shows that the companies
have basically kept their word, but three have reneged to a minor
extent. For example, General Motors, which gave more than $400,000
in soft money in the 1996 elections, gave no corporate money for
last year's races, but it allowed its political action committee to
donate $40,000 to the Republican National Committee after the 1997
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Political action committees are run by corporate officers, but
the money comes from ostensibly voluntary donations, usually from
executives. They are allowed to give up to $25,000 to political
committees set up by the parties. Presumably, the Republican Party
classified GM's 1997-1998 donations as soft money because they
exceeded that limit.
</P>
<P>
   Harry J. Pearce, vice chairman of GM, said in an interview that
the company's policy applied to corporate funds, not to the
political action committee. Pearce said that he was satisfied with
the self-imposed ban on corporate spending on politics and that it
would not be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Ameritech Corp., the Midwest telephone company, which gave
nearly $200,000 in the 1996 elections, gave about $60,000 in 1997
and 1998. Some of this was also from a political action committee.
Most of the rest, said Gary Lytle, head of the company's Washington
office, apparently resulted from executives around the country not
understanding what the rules were.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal, the aerospace company, which gave about $200,000
in the 1996 elections, gave $15,000 a year to the Republican Party
in 1997 and 1998. Ken Cole, vice president for government
relations, said that the money had been earmarked for conferences
of the Republican Governors' Association and that the company had
been assured that it would not be used for election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The one corporation that has completely stuck by its guns is the
Monsanto Co., which donated about $75,000 in 1995 and 1996 and has
given no soft money since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we said what we were going to do, we meant it,'' said
Philip Angell, spokesman in Monsanto's Washington office. As for
making an exception for PAC money, Angell said, ``Either you are or
you aren't, and we've decided we're not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
