<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDWARDS-FCC-640&AMP;ADD-N     04-10 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARDS-FCC-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPONENTS SAY TV STATION DEAL IS A RACIAL SHAM
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., N.C., Okla., Pa., Wis.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is hard to typecast Edwin Edwards, a black
businessman from Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   To his admirers, Edwards is a pioneer: the first black person to
own a television station in a top 20 broadcast market, Pittsburgh.
Owner of seven television stations in cities including Baltimore,
Raleigh, N.C., and Milwaukee, and in the process of buying others,
Edwards is the model of an entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   He is also active in the Boy Scouts, sits on the board of the
Pittsburgh Urban League and is co-sponsor of an annual affair for
African-Americans who have made significant contributions to the
black residents of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   His detractors, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, draw another portrait. To them, Edwards is a sham whose
company, Glencairn Limited, is little more than a black front to
enable a major white company, Sinclair Broadcasting, to evade the
federal ban on owning more than one television station in a given
market. They say this type of relationship undermines support for
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Edwards' critics are seeking to block a complex
deal in which Glencairn would acquire four television stations,
including one in Oklahoma City, where Sinclair already owns a
television station. Both Jackson's organization and rival station
owners have complained that the deal is nothing more than a means
to allow Sinclair to own two stations in the Oklahoma City market.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Jackson's group note that 97 percent of the stock in
Edwards' company is held by Carolyn Smith, the mother of David,
Frederick, Duncan and Robert Smith, the four men who control
Sinclair, or by their children. Ms. Smith and the children also
have an option to buy the remaining 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Glencairn owns the licenses of Edwards'
television stations, in each case he has, for a fee, ceded control
over programming, advertising and personnel, as well as buildings,
transmitters and other physical assets, to Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   All of Edwards' stations also are in markets where Sinclair
already owns a television station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glencairn appears to be determined to immortalize itself as
the poster child for sham ownership structures,'' lawyers for
Kelley International Licensing, a competing television company,
wrote in a complaint to the Federal Communications Commission last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and lawyers for Sinclair deny any subterfuge, saying the
commission has on several occasions approved Glencairn's ownership
structure and its purchase of stations in markets where Sinclair
already had stations. They also note that the stock held by the
Smith family consists of nonvoting shares.
</P>
<P>
   And they say it is strange that the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition is
trying to discredit an effort that has given a black man a foothold
in the overwhelming white club of television station owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of my relationship with Sinclair,'' Edwards
said in an interview on Thursday. ``It's a beautiful, beautiful
family whom I've worked with and who have helped me. Isn't that
what we're trying to say to other broadcasters in this day and age
_ reach out and help minorities gain a foothold in ownership
opportunities?''
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates for minority ownership of television and
radio stations worry that Edwards' relationship with Sinclair gives
affirmative action efforts in business a bad name. They note that
in 1995, Congress repealed a program that gave tax breaks to
white-owned companies that sold television stations to minorities.
Deals like those between Edwards and Sinclair, these advocates say,
hurt efforts to have such programs restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the danger of the Glencairn-Sinclair deal,'' said James
Winston, president of the National Association of Black
Broadcasters. ``It gives some in Congress the excuse not to promote
black ownership.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The questions about Glencairn and its relationship with Sinclair
give a racial twist to the issue of the growing number of
television station owners who agree to give up control of their
operations to other companies, sometimes companies that already own
stations in the same market.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC estimates that there are more than 100 of these
arrangements across the country. The commission is considering
whether companies that operate television stations under these
agreements, like Sinclair, should be considered de facto owners. If
they are, then the commission's prohibition against owning more
than one station in a market would apply.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wrinkle in the long-running dispute between Edwards
and Sinclair on one side, and several competing companies and the
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition on the other, involves the Oklahoma City
transaction. It is part of a complex deal in which Sinclair paid
nearly $100 million to merge with Sullivan Broadcast Holdings,
which owns 11 television stations. As part of the deal, four of
those stations, including KOKH-TV in Oklahoma City, were
transferred to Glencairn.
</P>
<P>
   Among those companies competing with KOKH-TV is KFOR-TV, a
station owned by The New York Times Co. The company has not filed a
formal complaint about the transfer of the station to Glencairn.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Glencairn agreed to cede day-to-day control
of nearly all of the programming on the Oklahoma City station to
Sinclair. In addition, both Sinclair and Glencairn used the same
bank, Chase Manhattan, and the same loan officer to arrange
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Glencairn paid nothing outright to acquire the four stations,
but did agree to assume a debt that had been held by Sullivan. At
one point, in papers submitted to the FCC, Edwards said the debt
amounted to $80 million. He later revised that figure, saying the
amount of the debt was actually about $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' detractors said his confusion over the amount of debt
he was assuming in a deal that would expand his television empire
by more than two-thirds was evidence that he was merely a
figurehead for his company and therefore unfamiliar with the
transactions that were being carried out in his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are the owner, at the very least you should know the
price you are paying,'' said Andrew Schwartzman, president of the
Media Access Project, which seeks to increase the number of radio
and television stations owned by minorities.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Edwards said he had made an honest mistake. ``If
this is the only thing the petitioners have to stand on, it's
laughable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a result of the protest raised by the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition and Kelley, the FCC last month asked Sinclair to provide
more details about the transaction. Federal officials declined to
comment on their requests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
