<HEADLINE>
AMID EQUITY CONCERNS, GIRLS' SCHOOLS THRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arlene Gibson, headmistress at the Spence School, a
private girls school on Manhattan's Upper East Side, remembers the
bad old days, the early '90s, when girls' schools had to convince
parents of the benefits of single-sex education.
</P>
<P>
   ``One used to have to make the case, especially to fathers, for
why girls' schools,'' she said. ``You don't have to do that
anymore. There is a sense now that they know the issue of girls and
computers, they know the research on who talks in class, there's a
general awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it has gone well beyond awareness, into a kind of
frenzy, for Manhattan's seven private girls' schools: Most had 10
applications for every $17,000-plus kindergarten opening for this
coming fall, more than the average for New York's private schools.
And the only public girls' school in New York City, the 3-year-old
Young Women's Leadership School in Harlem, has also been deluged
with applications.
</P>
<P>
   But the gender research and attention to girls' special needs
that have spurred increasing interest in girls' schools are also
reshaping the coeducational private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although coed schools defend themselves as being more in step
with the modern world and say they represent the most basic
diversity in education, over the last few years, most of the city's
private coed schools have made explicit efforts to ensure that
girls will not be overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   Many have started gender-equity committees and projects
reconsidering everything from the boys-chase-the-girls game at
recess to who controls the mouse during computer time _ and who
supervises the computer lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've videotaped teachers at different levels to see if there
are unconscious biases,'' said Elisabeth Krents, the admissions
director at Dalton. ``We've analyzed leadership roles to see if
they're divided among girls and boys. We don't say, `OK, boys into
the dress-up corner, girls into the block area,' but we build it
into everything we do. In second-grade, right now, they're studying
Grimms' fairy tales, analyzing the gender stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Applications at Manhattan's private girls' schools have
increased 69 percent since 1991, according to the National
Coalition of Girls' Schools, with many applicants coming from
beyond the traditional Upper East Side milieu. Nationally, the
coalition said, applications at girls' schools are also rising,
though at less than half the rate of the Manhattan schools. But no
other city has anything like the number of single-sex options that
Manhattan offers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the interest in single-sex schools has grown out of the
publicity following the American Association of University Women's
1992 research review, ``How Schools Shortchange Girls,'' which
concluded that girls face constant bias from kindergarten through
high school.
</P>
<P>
   And the coalition of girls' schools, founded a year earlier, has
touted the benefits of schools where girls get, as they put it,
``not just equal opportunity, but every opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The writings of people like Carol Gilligan and Mary Pipher, too,
promoted the idea that girls entering adolescence often lose
confidence in themselves and begin to falter in self-esteem and
fall behind in math, science and computer classes.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, a crop of new books on boys' emotional and
developmental needs has spurred interest in boys' schools as well,
though that is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent research shows that boys and girls both thrive
in good coed schools. But with everyone from politicians to
educators stressing higher educational standards and back-to-basics
learning, the rigor and traditional style of girls' schools _ and
those plaid or pleated uniforms that so many public schools are now
also adopting _ seem not impossibly old-fashioned but right in tune
with the times.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many parents have concluded that single-sex
schooling will help ensure that their daughters have room to shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to ruin my daughter's feistiness,'' said
Marion Markham Abood, an Upper West Side mother whose daughter is
in kindergarten at Nightingale-Bamford. ``I didn't want to chance
that her spirit would be quashed in any way at a coed school. If
she wants to be president of the country, who am I to ruin her
chance by having her overshadowed by some boy?''
</P>
<P>
   Preschool directors far from the Upper East Side have been
especially struck by the widening circle of applicants to girls'
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of our parents used to consider single-sex schools, but
there's been a significant shift in the past five or six years,''
said Sheila Wolper, the director of Beginnings, a nursery school
that sends about 35 children off to kindergarten each year.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that coed private schools are lacking for
applicants. They, too, have had a banner year, in what has become
an increasingly anxious admissions season, echoing the college
scene.
</P>
<P>
   While parents and admissions directors alike seem to believe
that kindergarten competition is getting more intense, the schools
will not release admission statistics, so it is difficult to assess
how much is reality and how much is nervous parents' applying to
more kindergartens than they used to _ sometimes upward of 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Educational Records Bureau, which tests children applying to
private New York kindergartens, said the number tested rose nearly
25 percent from 1990 to 1996, but has been relatively consistent,
about 1,970, for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last four years, interest in the Manhattan girls'
schools has grown so strongly that several were forced to add new
kindergarten sections when an unexpectedly large proportion of
students who were offered places actually accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more parents who might not have gone to
independent schools themselves, but who feel that girls' schools
promote a can-do attitude,'' said Concepcion Alvar, the admissions
director at Marymount School, which, like several other girls'
schools, sent out fewer acceptances this year than in the past,
took no one from the waiting list, and still ended up with a larger
kindergarten than they had planned for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the gender research deals with preadolescents
and older children, the girls' schools say that all-girls' classes
can be an advantage even for kindergartners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has to wait while the boys get settled? The girls,'' said
Barbara Root, the admissions director at Convent of the Sacred
Heart. ``Whose time is not always used as well as it might be? Who
can do more in a group where no one's thinking about throwing
blocks?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But administrators and teachers in coed schools are frustrated
that so many parents are ignoring the benefits of mixing boys and
girls _ and that many of them are actually misreading the gender
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look closely, all the research the AAUW reports is that
the best environment for girls is a cooperative, informal one where
children work in groups and collaborate, a place like ours,'' said
John Dexter, the head of the coed Trevor Day School. ``Most girls'
schools are formal, with uniforms, single individual desks and
frontal teaching, with the teacher standing up front and talking.
But we suffer, because people that might have come here are going
to single-sex schools, seeing that as preferable.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others point out that the research does not say that boys
and girls tend to learn differently and therefore should be
separated, but rather that boys and girls learn differently so
teachers should use approaches that work for both.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a report issued last year _ ``Separated by Sex: A
Critical Look at Single Sex Education for Girls'' _ the American
Association of University Women concluded that boys and girls alike
flourish in good coeducational schools, and that while many girls
prefer single-sex math and science classes, there is no evidence
that they do better in them.
</P>
<P>
   But while coeducation remains the paradigm of American
education, those who believe in teaching boys and girls together
are now having to make their case to parents.
</P>
<P>
   One girls' school headmistress, laughing, pulled out the
brochure for a conference, ``Coeducation: The best we can do for
our children?'' to be held in May at Phillips Academy in Andover,
Mass., a prestigious coed boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   ``While researchers have cited advantages to educating the sexes
separately, coeducation and its underlying assumptions have gone
virtually unexamined,'' the brochure says, promising that those who
attend the conference will come away able to ``articulate a theory
or philosophy that guides coeducational schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents shopping for schools this year said they felt that
the coed schools did not articulate a real philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have a compelling answer to why coed,'' said Molly
McEneny, who will send her daughter, Catherine, to a girls' school
for kindergarten next September. ``All they could say was `It's a
coed world.' I think girls' schools can teach to girls in a very
concentrated way at the younger ages, teaching the way girls learn
best. And at the older ages, girls get every opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The coed schools say that with careful attention they can, and
do, give girls every opportunity and are even more vigilant these
days about promoting equity between boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dalton and Ethical Culture, for example, brought in a
consultant, Catherine Krupnick, a lecturer at the Harvard Graduate
School of Education, who had videotaped classes at Harvard. She had
studied who talked and for how long, and found that boys dominated
discussion except where there was a female instructor and a
predominantly female class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's Harvard or preschool, boys have a quicker
reaction time, and the first hand up will usually be a boy's,'' she
said. ``If you want to give more people a chance to participate,
you need to create some waiting time, and not call on that first
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ethical, with Ms. Krupnick's guidance, teachers did extensive
videotape analysis of each kindergarten and prekindergarten class.
Much of what they found _ that boys spent more time in the block
area than girls, for example _ confirmed what they already knew.
</P>
<P>
   But the tapes also showed more subtle and surprising
differences. For example, one teacher who gave the children a math
problem and then went around the circle asking for answers noticed
that she allowed girls who demurred to pass immediately, but when a
boy wanted to pass, she would ask, ``Are you sure?'' before moving
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also saw that where a big group of very verbal boys sat
together, the teacher would orient her body language toward them,''
said Sara Adler, the principal of the lower grades at Ethical
Culture. ``Cultural biases become pervasive in your practice if you
don't keep tabs on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing what they were doing, Ms. Adler said, led teachers to
change their practices. ``When it's time to sit down for a meeting,
the teacher might say, `Today we're going to have a pattern: two
boys, then two girls,''' she said. ``We put children in
mixed-gender groups and say, `Today's your group's day with the
blocks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other coed schools took different actions to promote gender
equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked very hard for a woman who coordinates our
computers,'' said Dexter of Trevor Day. ``It's no accident that
four out of five math teachers here are women.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Country School, which is coed, trained its teachers to
give gender the same explicit attention as race. ``We noticed that
we had been letting sexual and homosexual epithets pass, which we
would never do for racial epithets, so we stopped that,'' said
Michele Sola, the director.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is not only to encourage girls to pursue
activities traditionally associated with boys, Ms. Sola said, but
to get boys to appreciate activities that girls tend to favor.
</P>
<P>
   It even came down to re-engineering boys-chase-the-girls: ``We
talked with the 4- and 5-year-olds about the feelings of always
being the chaser or always chased, about changing the rules so that
there can be mixed-gender groups, and a teacher intervening in the
middle, to announce that the chasers will now be chased,'' Ms. Sola
said. ``We really believe in equity.''
</P>
<P>
   All well and good, the single-sex schools say, but the girls'
schools, where every day is girls' block day, send a powerful
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one little 5-year-old,'' said Edes Gilbert, the
former headmistress at Spence, ``standing in the middle of the room
in her new uniform, who looked around on the first day of the
school and said: `Thank God! No boys in the block corner!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
