<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow will blanket the mountains of Southern California on Sunday
as a cold upper-level low pressure system arrives from the Pacific
Ocean. Meanwhile, a chilly rain will dampen coastal regions, where
1/2 inch of precipitation could fall near Los Angeles and San Diego
by evening. A few rumbles of thunder may accompany the rain as the
chilly air arriving at high altitudes renders the atmosphere
increasingly unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, offshore breezes will direct dry air toward the
Northwest Coast, providing much of Washington and Oregon with
mostly sunny skies and mild conditions. The remainder of the West,
including the Rockies, will stay mainly dry as ample sunshine
covers the region.
</P>
<P>
   High-altitude moisture streaming northeast from Mexico will
bring patches of high cirrus clouds to Texas and the Southeast on
Sunday. The only impact from these clouds will be to dim the sun at
times since the lower portions of the atmosphere will be too dry to
support any rain. Farther south, Florida will remain generally
sunny and very warm with a few locations surpassing 90 degrees over
the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture attendant to a team of low pressure systems will spread
a cold rain over the eastern Great Lakes and northern Middle
Atlantic States. Cold air filtering south from Ontario will cause
the rain to mix with snow along the northern shield of the
precipitation in northern Michigan and over northern sections of
the upper Middle West. Elsewhere, a narrow wedge of dry air will
promote sunny and cool conditions in central New England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tornado Damage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Experts have been surveying damage caused by recent storms in
the Middle West to confirm the areas where tornadoes were to blame.
When twisters are large and witnessed by many people, the job is
easy. In other cases, people sometimes confuse benign, pendulous
clouds with tornadoes. Moreover, damage thought to be caused by a
tornado is often the result of straight-line winds generated when
downdrafts in thunderstorms spread out rapidly after hitting the
ground. Experts look for spiral patterns in damaged trees and
buildings, strong evidence of the swirling winds of a twister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
