<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRUNFELD-A     04-10 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRUNFELD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUNFELD'S PERFORMANCE SCRUTINIZED AS KNICKS' PAYROLL AND LOSSES
MOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on Knicks' payroll vs rest of NBA is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the past eight years, Knicks Ernie Grunfeld has
left other general managers envious while he dips into the league's
largest revenue pool with a crane's scoop. But after seasons of
using cash piles to facilitate trades and patch up mistakes,
Grunfeld has helped turn an organization that once contended for a
title into a money pit.
</P>
<P>
   After spending $68.6 million on this year's team _ a payroll
that doubles the league average _ Grunfeld has collected a
hodgepodge of talents to revolve around an aging superstar
incapable of carrying the team on a nightly basis. Often choosing a
player's cache over chemistry, Grunfeld's decision-making is partly
responsible for a situation that has left the Knicks in a desperate
scramble to make the playoffs and provide some return on a payroll
that one Eastern Conference official called ``fiscal negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Knicks can salvage their season with a playoff run
starting with Sunday's game against the Nets, members of the
organization say Grunfeld's history of disingenuous relationships
with players and his meddlesome approach toward coach Jeff Van
Gundy has left him only thin insulation from being fired. While
core players like Patrick Ewing, Allan Houston and Larry Johnson
have rallied around Van Gundy, Grunfeld's management style has been
questioned by current players and former Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you something when the general manager could be fired
and the coach could survive,'' said one member of the organization,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``Usually, it's the other
way around.''
</P>
<P>
   To those within the organization, Grunfeld has made his position
more precarious by creating a mistrust between himself and the
players and coaches, a rift that manifested itself March 14. Just
hours before tipoff, NBC aired a report citing sources saying Van
Gundy could be fired if the team lost to Charlotte that day.
Grunfeld called the report ``ridiculous.'' But Van Gundy reacted as
if he believed the report was true and showed how hollow he felt
Grunfeld's support was.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the organization felt it was Grunfeld who
leaked Van Gundy's precarious job status in order to deflect
attention from himself. ``I resent any implication of any kind,''
said Grunfeld on Friday. ``If someone has something to say, they
should come and say it to me. But that's absolute bull.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue ruffled players, who wondered privately if Grunfeld
was trying to undermine Van Gundy. In the larger picture, the
situation is just part of a rift that has been growing between the
players and a team president they don't trust. Although no current
Knicks would comment publicly, several criticized Grunfeld off the
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're seeing a bad situation that has been created by
losing,'' said Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts. ``I
see a team that is losing more than they should. And that creates
everything you're talking about. People say, `Well, why is this?
Where does it come from? Is it the mix of talent? Is it practice
time? Are they too small to compete in the half-court East without
Charles Oakley? Is there a rift between players and management?' I
think it may be a combination of a whole host of factors. I don't
think any lack of trust or any rift is at the heart of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning tends to heal uneasiness and promote job security. These
are uneasy times for the Knicks. Even under the umbrella of an
ownership as wealthy as Charles Dolan's CableVision, Grunfeld and
Checketts will have to answer for a payroll that has thus far
produced a 19-17 team that is in danger of missing the playoffs for
the first time in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what we've invested, the results have been
disappointing,'' Checketts said. ``When the Knicks were in the NBA
finals, we were at $26 million on our payroll. So, yes, we've spent
a lot. I understand that. It hasn't worked out, and the
responsibility comes back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Checketts will decide whether Grunfeld comes back
next year. Grunfeld, an affable personality who is close to
Checketts, said he fully expects to return. Others wonder how he
can escape his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie has tried to build a team to challenge other teams _
like the Heat and the Pacers _ instead of putting good quality
people on the floor who complemented each other,'' said the former
Knick Buck Williams. ``When I first came, Ernie told me he wanted
to win with veteran players. They traded John Wallace, Walter
McCarty and John Thomas because they were committed to the
veterans. Then a shift in philosophy came. They dealt Charles
Oakley, and discounted chemistry. Oak sacrificed to make the team
better, and he helped make Patrick's life easier. And I'd say with
Patrick, why get younger until he retires?''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was traded to Toronto in June for the young and athletic
Marcus Camby. Then, Grunfeld worked behind the scenes to prod the
coach into giving the third-year pro more playing time so Grunfeld
could justify the six-year, $48 million extension he gave Camby in
mid March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camby is just another in a long list of players they've
overpaid to keep,'' one Eastern Conference official said. ``They've
been able to buy their way out of problems for years, and it's
going to catch up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are general managers who envy the Knicks'
seemingly unlimited funds. ``It'd be so much easier to build a club
and not worry about the bottom line,'' said Rick Sund, the Pistons'
vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld has paid and paid, costs which ultimately trickle down
to ticket holders who pay the highest prices in the league. When
the Knicks needed an insurance policy for Ewing, they re-signed
Chris Dudley to a $28 million deal that left other general managers
sniggering. When it looked as if Miami's Pat Riley _ who has
appeared to bait the Knicks into making several moves _ was going
to swoop down and sign Chris Childs in 1996, the Knicks forked over
$24 million for six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were bidding against Miami,'' Grunfeld explained. ``When
you're in a free-agent situation, sometimes you have to overpay.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Childs' deal allowed Charlie Ward to demand a
five-year, $27 million contract because he had supplanted Childs as
the starter. Over $50 million later, the Knicks still need a point
guard and tried unsuccessfully to land Stephon Marbury with an
offer of Allan Houston or Latrell Sprewell, along with Childs.
</P>
<P>
   Packed with high salaried players, the Knicks are viewed as a
team with locked-in pieces, although Grunfeld feels confident he
can make moves. ``They may have a couple of parts,'' one general
manager said. ``But it's not going to be easy to convince a team to
take Sprewell with his track record. It's hard to validate the
risk. The Knicks take risks other teams won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Risk is something general managers live with everyday. And most
don't have the assets the Knicks do. Sund is one of many general
managers finding success despite a tighter budget. The Pistons
payroll is close to $32 million and yet they have a 22-14 record
and are pushing the Pacers for the Central Division title. The
Orlando Magic, with a payroll of $40 million, has been able to
survive Shaquille O'Neal's departure and become contenders again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, more than ever, there is an eye on making the right
strategic moves with the right talent,'' said John Gabriel, the
Magic's general manager. ``That's part of why we're pretty good
today. We've stuck with the team instead of turning to every free
agent with new contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Grunfeld has shaken up his core group this year, a
strategy that has been open to debate. Nothing was more rattling
than the Oakley trade. In the aftermath of that deal, Grunfeld was
criticized and, at times, has responded in ways considered petty.
Upon Oakley's return to the Garden for the first time since the
trade, for instance, Grunfeld decided to air a tribute to Oakley at
halftime instead of before the game. Never a defender of
Grunfeld's, Oakley said the whole situation was embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had done that differently,'' Checketts said. ``You
have to put yourself in the place of a general manager, who, on the
one hand, would like to acknowledge the contributions of a player,
and on the other hand, does not want to spend so much time that it
detracts from the job at hand. And that's to go out and win a game.
It's not an easy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Traded players rarely praise management. But an unusually high
number of former Knicks have little regard for Grunfeld, like
Oakley, Derek Harper and Anthony Mason. Through them, Grunfeld is
portrayed as a bungling general manager who asked for their input
but cut them off in mid-sentence when it wasn't what he wanted to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   What becomes of Grunfeld's tenure isn't clear. Checketts said
he'll evaluate everyone at the end of the season, but has shown no
public indication that he is displeased with Grunfeld's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone out and got the players we thought could succeed,''
he said. ``We've had quite a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer of `96, Ernie traded and got Larry Johnson and
Allan Houston and Chris Childs, they were all solid moves,''
Checketts said. ``Since that time, we've picked up Kurt Thomas as a
free agent, then traded for Sprewell and for Camby. At the time, we
thought they'd all work out very well. At this point, we have to
conclude they haven't worked out very well. But I'd say Ernie's job
performance has been very, very good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
