<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHANGES FOR A BETTER MASTERS FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If the Masters really begins on the back nine on
Sunday, as so many here like to say, it will be an even more
difficult back nine this Sunday, particularly and possibly
poignantly because of changes on two of the four finishing holes.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 new loblolly pine trees resembling a line of sentries to
the right of the fairway on the 500-yard 15th; with the Eisenhower
Tree again creating a guardhouse to check the tee shots on the
17th, which has been lengthened to 425 yards, and with a subtle
touch of rough off every fairway, the leaders will have to do what
golfers would rather not do. Think.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 17th is going to be one of the great finishing holes
now,'' said Raymond Floyd, the 1976 winner. ``Instead of the very
birdieable-type hole it was with players' length today.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Masters' second-most-difficult hole through the first two
rounds, with a 4.307-stroke average, the 17th yielded only 12
birdies, far off the pace of the 39 birdies there last year when
Mark O'Meara birdied both the 17th and the 18th holes to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to play that 17th hole with the wind we had in the
first round,'' Colin Montgomerie said. ``When they put the pin on
the front over the bunker, it gets very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the final round, the flagstick usually is where
Montgomerie described it _ on the front of the green behind the
bunker guarding the green. In other years, most pros were hitting a
wedge or a 9-iron. Now it's a 7-iron, unless their tee shot has
clunked into the Eisenhower Tree, as David Duval's did Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the 15th should continue as the most perilous of Augusta
National's finishing holes, primarily because of the ponds in front
and behind the green where the hopes of Masters leaders often
drown. And with those new trees, the rough and no more mounds in
the fairway, the leaders won't be whaling away on the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best change to the course was what they did to the 15th
fairway,'' said Nick Price, alluding to the removal of the mounds.
``Now you have to hit an excellent tee shot to have a reasonable
chance for the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Those mounds acted like slingshots for tee shots, adding
anywhere from 20 to 40 yards. But without those mounds _ and
fearing both the the trees on the right and the rough, even at only
one and three-eighths inches _ it's a different mind set for the
big hitters. From that rough, they can't be sure of holding the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big change,'' Scott McCarron said. ``I used to hit up
on that hill and kick it back to the fairway. In the first round I
was trying to hit a 3-iron to the green and that's a club or two
different than it was for me in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In other final rounds, an eagle 3 at the 15th has sometimes
defined the winner, notably Jack Nicklaus in 1986. But halfway
through this Masters, there was only one eagle there, by Frank
Lickliter. With balls spinning back into the pond or skipping into
the pond beyond, that slippery 15th green has usually created more
problems than it solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what they did at the 11th with the new green,'' Price
said, alluding to the Masters officials, ``and they might want to
start thinking about doing something to the 15th green. Once the
ball starts spinning there, it could come back 25 feet and go in
the water. You're not safe with a sand wedge or a pitching wedge or
a lob wedge.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two rounds, the 11th hole, with a new, treacherous
back-left pin position available Sunday on its rebuilt green, has
emerged as the sixth-most-difficult hole, up from ninth last year.
</P>
<P>
   On this year's other altered hole, the second, where a new back
tee has stretched the downhill dogleg left to 575 yards, the pros
must think, too. Even a big hitter like McCarron, who had a par-5
there in each of the first two rounds. In previous years, he
invariably went for the green in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I'd take a driver and try to get it over the bunker
and get it down there, then hit a 5-iron or a 6-iron,'' McCarron
said. ``Now I'm trying to hit a 3-wood short of that big bunker on
the right, then hit another 3-wood up near the green. So it's a
three-shot hole.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 15th, where Gene Sarazen's double-eagle 2 put the
Masters on the map in 1935, is also a three-shot hole because of
its new trees to the right, its rough and the absence of the
mounds. And it's where the Masters could turn Sunday, as it so
often has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the people around that 15th green,'' Nick Price said
with a laugh, ``and I think, man, these people must like to see us
really battle here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
