<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 TOP LINEMEN COULD GO IN THE FIRST 2 ROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi looks at the group
of offensive linemen in next week's National Football League draft
and sometimes he can't believe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty impressive,'' Accorsi said. ``I can't say the
last time we had this many good offensive linemen. I can say this
group would be hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is such a good bunch, that as many as 10 top offensive
linemen could go in the first two rounds, most of them tackles and
many capable of stepping into a starting lineup soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many assume the Giants will take a tackle or a guard. The Giants
select 19th over all and, though a lineman is a priority, the
Giants' system still calls for the team to take the best player on
their draft board, even if it is a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants have apparently changed that philosophy by making
subtle changes in the way they approach the draft. They may lean
more toward their needs instead of stubbornly sticking to their
formula of drafting the best-rated player. Still, if the Giants
passed up a good lineman it would be like Jay Leno passing up a
good joke.
</P>
<P>
   Some scouts believe the best college tackle is probably John
Tait, a 6-foot-6-inch, 310-pound mountain at Brigham Young. Some
scouts love his maturity as a 24-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   There is little chance Tait will still be around by the time the
Giants pick, especially since the Chicago Bears, the Arizona
Cardinals and the Detroit Lions are all looking hard at him and
pick in the top 10. That means the Giants will have to settle for
the next tier, players like L.J. Shelton from Eastern Michigan,
Aaron Gibson from Wisconsin and Jon Jansen from Michigan. Given the
Giants' fondness for Big 10 players, Jansen or Gibson are likely
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton weighs 341 pounds, Jansen was nicknamed the rock and
Gibson can bench-press 485 pounds. Not a bad group.
</P>
<P>
   The best guard is probably Doug Brzezinski from Boston College.
At 6-3, 309 pounds, he is a solid player, but scouts question
whether he can block quick defensive tackles.
</P>
<P>
   A Background Check
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins are seriously considering drafting the
troubled running back Cecil Collins. Coach Jimmy Johnson has sent
scouts and other team officials to both of Collins' former
campuses, first at McNeese State, where he played last year and
then at Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that Collins is the most athletically
gifted back in the country. He is a solid 210 pounds and can run
the 40-yard dash in 4.4 seconds. He should be a guaranteed top-10
pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins has had problems off the field. He was arrested
following the 1997 season on a charge of breaking into a woman's
apartment. Then, at McNeese State, he tested positive for
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins are of course cautious, which is why they are
interviewing almost anyone connected with Collins' life and
checking court records to get a complete picture. Johnson believes,
at least for now, that he can work with Collins and keep him out of
trouble. Johnson also signed Lawrence Phillips, another running
back with a history of arrests, in 1997, only to cut him eight
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Salary-Cap Concerns
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys are not the only team being looked at by the
National Football League for possible salary-cap violations. The
league has other investigations underway, though it is unclear
which teams are being scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, several teams complained to the NFL regarding the
situation of three potential Dallas players. Some teams believe the
Cowboys have reached some form of agreement with center Mark
Stepnoski, wide receiver Raghib Ismail and linebacker Quentin
Coryatt. Once a signed agreement is reached, the contract must be
turned into the league office within 24 hours. The teams believe
the Cowboys are not turning in those three contracts because those
deals would put Dallas over the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys may be trying is not new, but in recent years
the NFL has seriously tried to crack down on such practices. If
teams can simply sign a player and report it to the league whenever
it chooses, then the salary cap means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   According to team executives, the Kansas City Chiefs and San
Francisco 49ers have been previously warned about such practices
after other teams turned them in. It is common for individual clubs
to police themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
