<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUSTY BAKER MAY BE KEY IN BEEFED-UP NL WEST COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers should be favored to win the National
League West, right? They certainly spent enough of Rupert Murdoch's
money, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but don't overlook the Colorado Rockies. They fired a
perfectly capable manager, Don Baylor, and lured Jim Leyland to
Denver by giving him $2 million a year for three years. This is a
guy who knows how to win. Look what he did two years ago with the
Florida Marlins, the last best team money could buy.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Arizona Diamondbacks? After only one year of
existence, they bought up all the pitchers on the free-agent market
(except the one the Dodgers got), figuring pitching was the fastest
route to respectability and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers, Rockies, Diamondbacks _ there's hardly room for the San
Francisco Giants. But the Giants have something none of those teams
have. That would be their manager, Dusty Baker. No one in the
division writes off the Giants with Baker driving their engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty will find a way to get them to overachieve,'' said Sandy
Johnson, the Diamondbacks' assistant general manager and one of
Baker's many admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland himself rates Baker highly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty Baker does as good as anybody,'' the Rockies' manager
said. ``They'll be right there in my opinion because that's just
the way he is. He won't let them not be there. Whether they win or
not, who knows? But they'll be there. You can take it to the bank.
He's too good. He's got those guys playing hard for him every day.
They respect him a lot. That's been obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won the division title in 1997, then missed the
wild-card spot last year in a playoff loss to the Chicago Cubs.
They started this season with the West's lowest payroll (even the
downsizing San Diego Padres are paying their players more) and five
victories in their first five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This division's so close,'' Baker said. ``An injury or two,
add a player or take a player away, that could make all the
difference in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' winter moves and their ability and readiness to
spend money to bolster their team have emboldened them to think
they will prevail in the division, but Baker has not jumped on
their bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they got it,'' the two-time manager of the year
said shortly before the season began. ``Let them think what they
want. I don't care. They still have to play. They were picked for
first five out of the last six years, weren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Baker added, the Dodgers have a good team. But he said:
``Who knows what's going to happen? Look at the Orioles. Look at
the teams everybody picks to win. You don't know what's going to
happen over there. Nobody knows. If everybody knew what's going to
happen, why start the season? Money makes you better, but money
doesn't necessarily assure you of winning. It helps. Talent
supersedes the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Anointed by Aaron
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. insists he is not a home run hitter, but a home
run hitter he greatly respects and admires has anointed him as one.
</P>
<P>
   With the 25th anniversary of his record-breaking 715th home run
commanding much attention recently, Henry Aaron has been asked if
he thinks anyone playing today could break his record of 755.
</P>
<P>
   ``One player who has a good chance of doing it,'' Aaron said,
``is Ken Griffey Jr. because of his age and the way he has hit home
runs the last few years. If he can stay healthy and stay focused
the way he has the last few years, he could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, the man who says he isn't a home-run hitter, has hit 56
home runs each of the last two seasons, joining Babe Ruth and Mark
McGwire as the only players who have attained the 50 plateau in
successive seasons. He began this season, his 11th, with 350 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting 50 or more in each of the next several seasons would
certainly put Griffey in position to reach Aaron, but no one can
expect him to maintain that pace.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can he be expected to play enough seasons to hit another 400
or so.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron played 23 seasons, his final one coming at age 42. Griffey
is 29, and 13 more seasons would give him 23 and have him playing
his last season at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron never hit more than 47 home runs in a season. His next
highest total was 45. He did not lead the National League either
year. Willie Mays beat him, 49 to 45, in 1962, and Willie Stargell
topped him, 48-47, in 1971. Aaron led the league four times, three
times hitting 44, his uniform number.
</P>
<P>
   A Legendary Temper
</P>
<P>
   When Henry Aaron and Bud Selig were in their 20s and working in
Milwaukee, they went to football games together. One game in
particular stands out in Selig's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd get sideline passes for the Packers games and stand
behind the Packer bench,'' related Selig, who grew up to become the
baseball commissioner. ``The Packers were playing the Rams, and
they were scuffling. Vince Lombardi got the offensive line together
and read them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank and I were so petrified we didn't know where to hide. He
looked at me and I looked at him. I said what should we do?
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of cowered off to the side and watched the rest of the
game from there. Both of us were absolutely petrified. Vince's
legendary temper got us and it wasn't even aimed at us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Long Purple Line
</P>
<P>
   And then there was one. At the end of the season's first week,
Derek Jeter of the Yankees alone remained standing among the Three
Musketeers of shortstops. Alex Rodriguez of Seattle had had surgery
for torn knee cartilage and will miss four to six weeks. Nomar
Garciaparra of Boston had a strained hamstring, and the length of
his absence was undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Their injuries are only two of a rash that has struck front-line
players. It started with Moises Alou of Houston, who tore a knee
ligament before spring training even began.
</P>
<P>
   During the exhibition schedule, Kerry Wood of the Chicago Cubs
and Matt Morris of St. Louis each tore an elbow ligament. They both
had ligament transplants, making Tommy John the most commonly heard
name in spring training. John was the first pitcher, 25 years ago,
to have such elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow John played with figured in the injury business, too.
That would be Achilles, as in Achilles' tendon. Carlos Hernandez,
the San Diego catcher, ruptured his midway through the exhibition
schedule and is gone for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have continued to plague key players. Mo Vaughn
suffered a severe high ankle sprain in Anaheim's opener and joined
two other Angels starters, shortstop Gary DiSarcina and center
fielder Jim Edmonds, on the disabled list. Pat Meares of
Pittsburgh, another shortstop, went on the disabled list with a
sprained wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr. of Baltimore, of all people, left the Orioles'
opener early, then missed the next two games with a stiff back, the
first time since August 1981 he had missed consecutive games. He
was back in the lineup Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Awestruck in the Dugout
</P>
<P>
   It's too early, Todd Stottlemyre said, to know if following
Randy Johnson in the Arizona pitching rotation will help him or
hurt him. ``I just hope I'm not the day off for the club that has
to face him the first day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he finds out about the order, though, the son of the
Yankees' pitching coach said he was looking forward to watching his
new teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one guy that when he faces a club, the opposing
manager makes a makeshift lineup because there are certain guys who
aren't going to play against Randy,'' Stottlemyre said. ``He has
great possibilities of doing something really special every fifth
day. Not that he will every fifth day, but to know that I have a
chance to sit in the dugout and watch the premier power pitcher in
today's game pitch will be awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it will be a lot like when guys used to be on a team
with Nolan Ryan, where he had a chance to throw a no-hitter that
day, or he had a chance to strike out a million guys that day or
whatever it was. When Nolan took the mound, there was a chance he
could do something special that day. I look at Randy in the same
way. Geez, what's he going to do today?''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, however, said he and his fellow Diamondbacks
pitchers would have to be careful not to get caught up in trying to
emulate Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know good and well I'm not capable of putting up Randy
Johnson numbers,'' the 33-year-old right-hander said. ``So for me
to try to keep up will take me into that arena where I'm trying to
do too much. It will be a mental challenge to remember, when you're
watching him blowing guys away, that doesn't mean I'll be able to
show up and do the same thing the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Tippers, Regardless
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are the first baseball team to open a season with an
average salary of $3 million. They disavow that distinction,
however, calling it meaningless. They say they do not have the
highest payroll in the major leagues, but are only No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   They are third, behind Los Angeles and Baltimore, but in the
luxury tax computations. Those payroll figures are based on the
average annual value of the contracts of all players on 40-man
rosters and determine which five teams pay the tax at the end of
the year and how much they pay. They are the figures, the clubs
feel, that count.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' $3 million average salary is based on figures for
this season alone. This method of computing average salaries has
been used for more than 30 years and is the only one that can put
salaries in perspective. But they don't cost the teams a penny
more. Whichever set of figures is used, though, it's a lot of
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
