<SLUG> BC-BKC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MAD RIOT AND A MATURE CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ March Madness bottomed out 16 days ago
after Michigan State lost to Duke in a semifinal game of the Final
Four. Minutes before the final buzzer in Florida, the first fire
was set here. Soon more than 5,000 people were rampaging through
downtown, drinking and shooting videos of each other breaking
windows, throwing bottles and vandalizing cars, including a police
cruiser. There was discussion that long night of calling out the
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   It was only briefly national news. It is still the subject of
agonized discussion here about the limits of official authority,
curfews, relations between town and gown, restrictions on alcohol
and the willingness of students who were not involved to identify
rioting classmates in photographs and videotape. There is much talk
of reclaiming the university from its own barbarians; the riot
spilled out of a hard-partying private apartment complex for
students called Cedar Village. The last time there was so much
passion on campus was a year ago when there was a riot against a
proposed alcohol ban.
</P>
<P>
   So what's sports got to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   I brought that up at lunch last week with six senior faculty
members, a mix of philosophy, English and history professors. They
became animated. Most had been engaged by the success of the team
and followed it through the season with some excitement and
pleasure. They were not eager to link the viciousness of the riot
with Spartan basketball or even intercollegiate sports.
</P>
<P>
   So was it just a mini-spring break? The weather had turned warm
enough for comfortable mooning.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't quite ready to let it go at that, which was about
their limit of consensus. Sports was clearly some kind of excuse, a
permission to go mad. Alcohol was a fuel, and this is the Bud Lite
generation to which beer, breasts and ball games are inextricably
bound. One professor thought that because of the fear of sexually
transmitted diseases, casual violence had replaced casual sex as a
campus release. Another thought that the student population had
``tilted'' away from the ``salt of the earth'' Midwestern strivers
to a cohort of entitled yet goalless children.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a metaphor _ at least one always emerges from such
a group _ it was ESPN. Several professors thought that for many
students, the all-sports channel had become the only news channel.
For some it might have also become a carrier of values about
winning and losing rather than growing and becoming. (ESPN also
reinforces, I suspect, the vulnerable viewer as the passionate
spectator of other people's performances, of a certain slobbish
maleness revolving around beer, fast cars and a post-ironic
jokiness that insulates him against real engagement with life.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a little like blaming the epidemic of American obesity
on Ben and Jerry. They wish. Nobody is supposed to find a
categorical imperative in ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, what's to make of the president of the University of
Connecticut, whose basketball team beat Duke in the championship
game, declaring that ``athletics has enabled us to grow
exponentially''? His predecessor, who had supported the men's and
women's basketball programs, was more specific. He credited the
success of the teams with helping to secure about $1 billion from
the state Legislature, pumping up alumni donations and student
applications and attracting hot professors.
</P>
<P>
   So how can we have it both ways, I wondered, especially since
only one team a season becomes a champion. UConn wins, and when the
final score flashes at Storrs, many of the 15,000 undergraduates
build a careful bonfire of pizza boxes and sing ``Kumbaya'' all
night. Five thousand Michigan State students, most of whom were not
born in 1979 when Magic Johnson led the Spartans to their last
Final Four, run amok in defeat. OK, professors, you have an hour to
fill a blue book.
</P>
<P>
   In the rare silence, I tried to lighten the mood. So, how about
that Derek Jeter? He was brought up in Kalamazoo, only an hour from
here. Early reports from spring training have him a combination of
Michael Jordan, Billy Budd (whom they all knew well) and Adam
Graves (whom most did not).
</P>
<P>
   They were not interested; baseball is a regional game, I guess.
They chuckled indulgently at my amazement that George Steinbrenner
could call anyone a fat toad, or that the Masters, the ``cathedral
of golf,'' could desecrate tradition by remodeling four holes.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the history professor Peter Levine, a runner and
former Columbia rower now beached by a bad knee, I was able to
cheer them with news of a new training aid: www.georgesheehan.com.
The running doc, who died in 1993 at the age of 74, has loped back
to us from cyberspace. The Web site, run by some of his 12
children, includes his classic mix of ideology and practical
advice.
</P>
<P>
   The best parts for me were rereading his instructions on
stretching and his 20 rules for runners. My favorite is still No.
14: ``Give dogs their territory. Cross to the other side of the
road and pick up some object you can brandish at them. Never try to
outrun a dog. Face the dog and keep talking until it appears to be
safe to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   We all took that as ideology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
