<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' TURNAROUND IS ALL ABOUT DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his first game with the New Jersey Nets, Stephon Marbury
sat in the visitors' locker room at Miami Arena and sulked. He and
his new teammates had just been crushed by 26 points, bullied and
outrun by the Miami Heat. With a bowed head and a solemn tone,
Marbury complained to reporters that the Nets did not have a
defensive clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is bad,'' Marbury said after that 102-76 loss on
March 14, the day before coach John Calipari was fired. ``Really
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, as he flew to Toronto on the team's chartered plane,
Marbury wondered how a club with such poor defensive ability had
won 43 games and made the playoffs the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they were winning last year,'' Marbury said
recently. ``Then they told me they weren't really stopping anybody.
They said they were just outscoring people, and I realized, `Yeah,
they were.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the Nets play host to the Knicks Sunday afternoon, Marbury
will have a different opinion about his team's capacity to shut
opponents down. Under the new coaching regime of Don Casey, Eddie
Jordan and Jim Lynam, the Nets have been remade defensively,
winning five of their last six games in a barrage of steals and
fast-break baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 11.3 steals over their last seven games _ the
Philadelphia 76ers, the league leader in steals, average 10.8 a
game _ the Nets (10-25) have beaten Atlanta, Miami and Toronto, all
playoff-caliber teams, and come within two points of defeating
Orlando, the Eastern Conference leader, in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like night and day,'' Marbury said. ``We're going out
with the intention of stopping people. Coach Jordan has been doing
a great job as far as making sure everyone plays hard every night
defensively. His defensive tactics have been awesome, and we've
been playing aggressive and that has allowed us to make our offense
step up.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that Jordan is behind the Nets' defensive
resurgence. As a player during the 1970s and early 1980s, Jordan
was one of the best defenders on his level. Jordan, the career
steals leader at Rutgers, led the Scarlet Knights to the Final Four
of the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament in 1976,
and two years later, as a point guard for the Nets, he was the
National Basketball Association leader in steals.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after taking over for Calipari on an interim basis and
hiring Jordan and Lynam as his assistants, Casey put Jordan in
charge of the offense and Lynam the defense. But Jordan, who was
released by Sacramento last August after going 33-64 as its head
coach, had been studying the Nets' defense on videotape since
getting the call from Casey. So he asked to be switched to the
other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that defense wins in the league,'' said Jordan, 44, who
played for four NBA teams before retiring in 1984. ``I played for
the Lakers and we had offensive players, but our coach, Pat Riley,
stressed defense. We won a championship in 1982 with different
types of presses. My defense is what enabled me to hang around the
league for seven years. So I was looking forward to teaching it to
these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the coaching change, the Nets did not appear
capable of becoming a defensive force. Their footwork was terrible.
Their rotations were slow. Their willingness to bang was in
question. And there was no commitment to buckling down and
defending for 24 seconds. Their only hope of winning was to light
it up offensively, but since they owned the league's worst field
goal percentage, that was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan, seeing a quick, athletic team, thought the Nets had
great defensive potential, despite their passive play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't disrupting the offense,'' Jordan said. ``They
weren't trying to make the offense do what the defense wanted it to
do. I saw the Nets not making the offense do things it didn't want
to do. So our thing the first couple of days after we got here was
that we have to change that and start disrupting the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have said that much of their defensive tentativeness
came from Calipari's constant shifts in strategy. He would change
his philosophy by the game, depending on the opponent's personnel.
Sometimes they would trap a pick-and-roll, sometimes they would
switch it, sometimes they would fight over the pick. And there were
other options, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable out there, and I don't think the
team did either,'' Keith Van Horn said. ``We felt like we were
always kind of confused, kind of lost out there. But I don't feel
that way anymore. We've got confidence because we're going into the
game knowing what we're going to do and we feel prepared.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; -2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: xxxx. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In giving the Nets a defensive facelift, Jordan emphasized the
importance of banging the offensive player before he bangs you.
Following those orders, the Nets, despite playing without the
injured Jayson Williams, outmuscled Miami recently when they
defeated the Heat, and Marbury limited Philadelphia's Allen Iverson
to 23 points on 8-of-23 shooting last week largely because he wore
Iverson down by bumping his upper body constantly when Iverson did
not have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also taught the Nets the value of slapping down at the
ball when it's in the opponent's grasp, leading the Boston Celtics'
coach, Rick Pitino, to call the Nets ``one of the best slap-down
steals teams in the league'' after the Nets made 15 steals in
beating his club on Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The most important change the Nets have made, though, has been
their strategic shift in defending the pick-and-roll, an NBA staple
that nearly every team runs consistently. Jordan has the Nets
defending it the way the Chicago Bulls did in winning last year's
championship against the Utah Jazz, the league's best pick-and-roll
team.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Nets see a pick-and-roll play coming, the man defending
the ball-handler, usually Marbury, pushes the dribbler toward the
baseline. The man defending the picker, usually Van Horn, drops
toward the baseline to stop the ball-handler from penetrating to
the basket. The two defenders then trap the ball handler, forcing
him to pass back to the top of the key. Anticipating the pass, a
roving Net, usually Kendall Gill, looks to make the steal and take
the ball in for a breakaway dunk.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the concept Philadelphia is using to lead the
league in takeaways. Making that play, in addition to slapping down
at balls in the paint, is what has enabled Gill to make 35 steals
over the past seven games, including an NBA-record-tying 11 against
Miami. Incidentally, Gill broke Jordan's franchise record of 10
steals in a game with that performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel rejuvenated by the defense that Eddie Jordan has put
in,'' said Gill, now the league leader in steals for the first time
in his career at 2.43 a game. ``Our new philosophy is that if we
play defense we're going to have fun. And we've been having a lot
of fun. Everybody wants to come to practice and come to the games
now, and our defense has a lot to do with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
