<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider blazes aimless trail in Portland
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite the mindless behavior of their most talented
player, the victories keep on coming for the Portland Trail
Blazers. They are the NBA's best team with one of the league's
worst characters _ the infamous Isaiah (J.R.) Rider, who gives new
meaning to the word distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Rider, as usual, has been a one-man annoyance, finding trouble
at nearly every turn. On a team less centered, he'd be the mother
of all adversities, taking away from a gifted team that's played
marvelously and unselfishly.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers, 21 games over .500 going into the weekend,
somehow seemingly ignore Rider's antics and plow ahead. And if
there's one thing that makes them scary come the playoffs, that
would be it: Their ability to stay the course in the face of
Hurricane Rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy admitted.
``I'm disappointed that we're a team that has the best record in
the league and we're having to fight through the things that we
shouldn't have to fight through.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Rider. In one whirlwind week, the 6-foot-4 guard
covered many bases afoul of the law and good sense. He was
suspended by the NBA for a game for charging a fan in the stands
who had gotten into an argument with his brother at Golden State;
it was learned he received his second multiviolation traffic stop
in Portland in five weeks; and, for good measure, Rider and the
Blazers were sued by a Detroit fan he spat on during a game last
season _ an incident that resulted in a three-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hopeful that this is the end of it for our whole
team, not just J.R.,'' Dunleavy said. ``Hopefully, nobody gets into
a situation they shouldn't be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Rider, clean up your act. Please.
</P>
<P>
   However, with a career checkered with suspensions _ three of the
one-game variety this season _ this reality is firm: What you see
in Isaiah Rider is what you don't want to get, but do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   To keep distracted from the distractions, Dunleavy manages a
roster that is among the deepest in the league. No one has had a
career year, but most of his players have been steady and
productive. Point guard Damon Stoudamire has had flashes of
brilliance, but not been the lightning rod of his first two years.
Rasheed Wallace brings energy on the front line; Walt Williams is a
versatile swing man off the bench; Brian Grant's a fierce rebounder
and inside scorer; Arvydas Sabonis is the deft-passing center;
Jimmy Jackson brings scoring off the bench; Greg Anthony is an
aggressive defender in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's former Atlanta Hawk Stacey Augmon doing things
defensively and in the open court, and Lithonia's Kelvin Cato
bringing big-man relief. That's a 10-man rotation, which is
virtually unheard of in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, but it's fun,'' Dunleavy said of dealing with all
that talent. ``You've got to keep guys _ I don't know if happy is
the right word. It's more like they've got to keep me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough of his players have done that. So much so, that no less
than Uneasy Rider said: ``We all feel like we're going to win every
game, even if we're not playing really good. Once we (Rider and
Stoudamire) start playing well, we will be deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   The most likely Blazer-killer is Rider. Portland has shown it
can overcome him. But for how long?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
