<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Thompson could be next Nets coach
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The third coaching casualty of the season sparked
widespread speculation around the league about future moves. Could
Maurice Cheeks be in for the Wizards, replacing fired Bernie
Bickerstaff? Is former Georgetown coach John Thompson be headed to
New Jersey? Or would it be Mike Fratello? And what of Jeff Van
Gundy with his floundering Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who several years ago turned down a chance to be coach
and general manager of the Denver Nuggets, is reportedly expected
to be offered the reins of the Nets, replacing interim Don Casey,
who took over for fired John Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets wanted to talk to New Jersey native Fratello, the
Cleveland coach, before they hired Calipari in 1996, but moved on
when the Cavs insisted on center Shawn Bradley in return for
interviewing Fratello.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson seems to be getting pushed for the job by none
other than agent David Falk, who has clients Stephon Marbury, Keith
Van Horn and Kerry Kittles on the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Hudson River, it's getting more and
more tight for Van Gundy. The Knicks went into the weekend out of
the playoffs. Someone has to pay for that. Asked if he believes the
decision on his fate already has been made, Van Gundy told Newsday:
``I don't know. . . . And I couldn't care less. What I mean is, I
think I've been through a lot, and I don't think necessarily I've
always been, uh. . . . I think it's something that comes sometimes
from my own organization. I've sort of been put out there on a limb
a little bit. And I know I can do this job and will do this job
better than anyone they get. So I say, (forget) it. I don't care.
If they decide they need to do something else? Well, they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheeks, the former Philadelphia point guard and now 76ers
assistant coach, was interviewed last week by the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando coach Chuck Daly summed up the coaching carousel: ``It's
the business. You never hear of anyone in the league office losing
their job. You rarely hear about a general manager getting fired.
And scouts are pretty secure, too. There's a hot seat with every
franchise, and it's usually where the coach sits.''
</P>
<P>
   It ain't my fault
</P>
<P>
   Reviled in Chicago as the man who broke up a dynasty, Bulls
general manager Jerry Krause said last week that he was not
responsible for Michael Jordan, coach Phil Jackson, Scottie Pippen,
Dennis Rodman, Luc Longley, Steve Kerr and Jud Buechler leaving in
the dismantling of the six-time champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody chased them away,'' he said. ``They left on their own.
And the team? It simply got old. And when a team gets old, you have
to make changes. Nobody wants to win more than I do. And nobody
hated to see Michael retire more than I did. The dynasty never was
going to last forever. It had to change.''
</P>
<P>
   It was speculated the Bulls would pursue possible free agents
Kobe Bryant, Allen Iverson, Antoine Walker, Zydrunas Ilgauskas or
Stephon Marbury, but each re-signed with their teams, making them
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys, meaning the media, missed a very important point
here,'' Krause said. ``You guys linked up us with players that we
were not even interested in. Just because a guy is a good player
does not mean that he will be our kind of player. And when some of
these good players re-sign with their own teams we don't see that
as a loss because we never wanted him anyway,'' Krause said.
</P>
<P>
   Who, then, does Krause want? Oliver Miller?
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I don't use the term that loosely,'' Dallas coach Don
Nelson said about his early-season proclamation that Michael Finley
would elevate to a ''great'' player.
</P>
<P>
   ''How do you defend him? You don't. You end up on the bench (in
foul trouble),'' Golden State's Jason Caffey said about guarding
Utah's Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To the Denver Nuggets. After 17 road losses in a row this season
_ and 25 spanning last year and this _ they won a game away from
Colorado. It was in Vancouver, which isn't exactly the Delta
Center, but it counts.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To the New York Knicks. They made a series of moves to upgrade
themselves, but have apparently quit on embattled coach Jeff Van
Gundy. If the playoffs started this weekend, the Knicks would be
out. They have better talent than that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
