<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jazz showing steel for stretch run
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's see how much the Jazz have left for the stretch
run. Starting Thursday they faced 16 games in 23 nights, quite a
chore for an old team. The good news: 10 are at home, six on the
road. Says Karl Malone: ``You try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, you have to focus on playing one game at a time.
You only worry about tonight's game, not tomorrow night's game,''
John Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult task: ``Staying mentally ready,'' Bryon
Russell said. ``You'll be all right physically, because there's
always time to get your rest but it becomes a mind over matter kind
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz showed how tough they are by ripping the Lakers down
the stretch Tuesday with Atlanta native Shandon Anderson scoring
all of his 12 points in the final 9:48 against a clueless Kobe
Bryant. Anderson went to the hoop and took passes from the Mailman,
who was out on the wing entertaining Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Discord among the Lakers
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in Tinseltown, the Lakers are very upset about
their defense and fingers pointed at Bryant for free-lancing and
losing track of Anderson. Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal, not
naming names but sounding ominous: ``The school I came from, a guy
isn't doing his job, you just take him out _ immediately.'' . . .
Rick Fox, sounding increasingly unhappy with his decision to return
to the Lakers: ``Bottom line is they beat us playing their game.
And they took us out of our game. To be quite honest with you, I'm
not sure what is our game is.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC unlucky for Rockets
</P>
<P>
   When the Houston Rockets completed a practice in Seattle, NBC's
Bob Costas bet he could make eight of 10 free throws, offering $100
to anyone bold enough to challenge him. He made six and paid up.
That's the least he can do, since Houston is awful in NBC games,
1-12 the last two years, with three more Sunday dates coming up,
starting with today's return visit to the Delta Center and the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers weighs on Clippers
</P>
<P>
   If they don't win two more games, the Clippers will finish 5-45,
a .100 percentage, which is even worse than the '72-'73 76ers'
record .110, making the Clippers the worst team ever. Poetic
justice there. One reason is Rodney Rogers' dismal campaign. After
posting career numbers (15.1 ppg., 5.6 rebounds) last season, he
showed up for his free agent year too heavy, went to the bench and
is averaging 8.4 ppg. and 4.6 rebounds. ``I really didn't think
that we were going to play (because of the lockout),'' Rogers said.
``That was dumb on my part. I should have been getting myself
prepared. My contract year and coming in not ready to play really
hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's passing phase
</P>
<P>
   After committing three turnovers in the first quarter of
Tuesday's game in Los Angeles, Jason Kidd complained the game ball
was too flat. After committing three turnovers in the second
quarter with a new ball, Kidd decided this one was too bouncy. But
after throwing the ball away three more times in the third quarter.
Kidd finally came to more logical conclusion. ``It was me. I was
horrible.'' So staring into the abyss of losing to the then-3-27
Clippers, Kidd decided to stop passing in the fourth quarter just
to see what might happen. The result: 15 points in the last 12
minutes and a 88-83 win.
</P>
<P>
   Payton vs. Baker
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton and injured power forward Vin Baker got into a
verbal battle during a Seattle scrimmage in Sacramento. Baker took
the worse end of an exchange that lasted 10 minutes. Payton, an
accomplished trash talker, told Baker that he is ``out of shape,''
``soft,'' and told him to ``put on a uniform.'' Baker was activated
Thursday after being on the injured list with a partially torn
thumb ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
