<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DL worth a reach to Reeves
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NFL draft is six days away, and coach Dan Reeves
continues to say the Falcons have put a premium on getting a top
defensive lineman and/or defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite subscribing to the ``best player available'' theory,
Reeves, like every NFL coach, sometimes picks a player to fill a
need even when there are other players available who rate higher.
</P>
<P>
   So it's possible that when the Falcons' first choice, No. 30,
rolls around, they could take a defensive lineman ranked, say, No.
40, over a cornerback ranked No. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because there don't figure to be many quality defensive
linemen left when Atlanta picks again, late in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, Reeves has gambled and lost. In 1988, Reeves
and current Falcons college scouting chief Reed Johnson selected
Syracuse nose tackle Ted Gregory in the first round. Gregory never
played in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 with the Falcons, Johnson and Reeves tabbed Indiana
defensive tackle Nathan Davis early in the second round. Davis did
not have a tackle as a rookie and quit on the first day of training
camp last summer. He's with the Cowboys now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest mistakes I've ever made were defensive lineman
we were trying to make into players,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia defensive end Patrick Kerney and LSU defensive tackle
Anthony McFarland are expected to be gone by the time the Falcons
pick. Florida defensive tackle Reggie McGrew is a possibility, as
is Florida State defensive end Tony Bryant. West Virginia defensive
tackle John Thornton and Saginaw Valley State defensive end Lamar
King also intrigue Atlanta, but probably not enough to invest a
first-round choice. Not shopping for a RB
</P>
<P>
   Might the Falcons consider looking for a running back in the
middle or late rounds while Byron Hanspard continues his recovery
from two torn knee ligaments? ``No,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Moving soon?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons should know within six weeks where their new home
will be next year.
</P>
<P>
   The sites under consideration, all roughly 15-30 acres, are in
Gwinnett, Hall, Forsyth and Barrow counties, including a site at
Chateau Elan. Also, officials at Stone Mountain Park in DeKalb
County have been swapping ideas with the Falcons. Workout news
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson, free safety Eugene Robinson, right
guard Gene Williams, wide receiver/return man Tim Dwight,
cornerback Elijah Williams and practice-squad tackle Greg Studdard
have not participated in the offseason conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Gene Williams' wife recently had a child. Dwight,
Elijah Williams and Studdard are finishing college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has between $1.5 million and $1.6 million left to spend
under the salary cap. ... The Jacksonville Jaguars are scheduled to
scrimmage Atlanta on Saturday, Aug. 7 at Furman University. ... The
Falcons have 59 players on the roster, and can take 80 to training
camp. ... There has been no significant talks in two weeks between
Falcon officials and the agent for Anderson about a contract
extension. ... The Falcons' third preseason game, Aug. 27 at
Tennessee, will be televised by ESPN at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
