<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thoroughly NFL pedigree in secondary
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NFL scouts often describe cornerback prospects in
terms associated with champion racehorses. The thoroughbred
comparisons might be more appropriate than usual for the 1999
draft, which features its share of family ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like with horses, there may be something to the whole
issue of good bloodlines,'' said Southern Cal cornerback Daylon
McCutcheon, whose father is former NFL running back Lawrence
McCutcheon, the second-leading rusher in Rams history and still a
scout for the team. ``Look at the guys (at the combine) who have
some NFL legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cornerback position is stocked with players with
NFL-pedigree blood. Chris McAlister of Arizona is the son of former
Philadelphia and New England tailback James McAlister. Alabama's
Fernando Bryant has a pair of uncles, wide receiver Ray Griffin
(Detroit) and cornerback Don Griffin (San Francisco and Cleveland),
who played in the league. Fred Vinson of Vanderbilt is a cousin of
Arizona cornerback Corey Chavous.
</P>
<P>
   Even the premier cornerback prospect, Champ Bailey of Georgia,
can claim an NFL connection. Older brother Ronald Bailey, a former
Bulldogs cornerback, was an undrafted free agent in camp with
Dallas last summer, recently signed with Tampa Bay and is playing
in the NFL Europe League.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister acknowledged recently that he feels an advantage over
other players because of his NFL family ties. ``My father can sit
and talk with me on all the good things about the league,''
McAlister said. ``And about all the other things, too, like being
able to overcome adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister is considered the No. 2 corner prospect but viewed by
many scouts as having better mechanics than Bailey. The Arizona
standout already has demonstrated an ability to handle tough times.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA flagged his SAT scores when he was coming out of
Pasadena (Calif.) High School. Instead of enrolling at UCLA, his
father's alma mater, he wound up at San Antonio Junior College for
a year before signing with Arizona. The elder McAlister had a
similar problem at UCLA. Chris McAlister also was suspended for one
game last season for a student loan that the NCAA deemed improper.
</P>
<P>
   Through the difficult times, he persevered, and his size and
speed have made him a hot commodity and probable top 10 selection.
McAlister is one of the few cornerbacks with the kind of size that
scouts like; a shortage in this draft will force teams to look at
such players as Antwan Edwards of Clemson at corner first.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been the past few years, the draft is thin at safety.
A safety might not be taken until the late second or early third
round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
