<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No. 1 hopeful Couch gets second audition
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is the day of reckoning for Kentucky quarterback
Tim Couch, who for the second time in a month gets the chance to
convince the Cleveland Browns he should be the No. 1 overall choice
in the NFL draft. In addition to the Brown's top two football men _
vice president Dwight Clark and coach Chris Palmer _ owner Al
Lerner and club president Carmen Policy will be among the team's
11-man contingent in Lexington for the private session this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to put him to the test,'' said Palmer, who will
conduct the workout. At a March 11 session in which tutor Larry
Kennan set the agenda, Couch threw just 46 passes. He can expect to
throw 75 to 80 today. An interesting stat on Couch: The Browns
dissected each of his 553 pass attempts from 1998 in Hal Mumme's
four-wideout set and found that two-thirds of them traveled 10
yards or less.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their kind words for Heisman winner Ricky Williams after
last week's session, the Browns aren't likely to take the Texas
tailback and the choice probably boils down to Couch or Oregon
quarterback Akili Smith. Cleveland was less than wowed by Williams.
While he weighed in at 224 pounds, down 20 from what he was at the
combine, Williams still looked soft to scouts. And his 40-yard
times _ 4.6-4.7 against the wind and the low 4.5s with it _ were
not eye-popping.
</P>
<P>
   Much ado about . . .
</P>
<P>
   League vice president of labor relations Harold Henderson will
investigate salary cap maneuvers by Dallas owner Jerry Jones, but
don't expect even a rap on the knuckles from commissioner Paul
Tagliabue. The Cowboys have reached agreements with center Mark
Stepnoski, wideout Rocket Ismail and linebacker Quentin Coryatt but
have yet to execute the contracts. They need to clear cap room by
redoing the deals of quarterback Troy Aikman and cornerback Deion
Sanders. Teams have complained about the Cowboys' tactics, but it
is commonplace. Tennessee did the same thing with linebacker Eddie
Robinson and fullback Lorenzo Neal. The Titans reached a verbal
accord months ago with guard Bruce Matthews but the contract still
hasn't been filed with the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is interested in free agent defensive end Derrick
Alexander, a five-year veteran from Minnesota. His agent has
exchanged proposals with Falcons GM Harold Richardson, but the team
might prefer to wait until after the draft. Alexander also is
talking with Cleveland but would prefer to play here. ... Seattle
will sign free agent wideout Sean Dawkins on Monday. ... Add Dallas
to the teams now interested in Rams quarterback Tony Banks. The
Ravens also have investigated Banks as an alternative to signing
Warren Moon as a backup. The Cowboys called at least one NFC West
team to see if they would be interested in trading for wideout
Michael Irvin. ... Jets coach Bill Parcells would deal third-down
back Leon Johnson for the right price. ... Pittsburgh offensive
right tackle Justin Strzelczyk re-injured his knee while leaping
over a bar during a tavern brawl. Strzelczyk is done for the
season. The Steelers, who last week signed Rams free agent Wayne
Gandy to play left tackle, are considering Bengals free agent
Anthony Brown for the right tackle spot. ... Look for Jacksonville
to fill its hole at middle linebacker by drafting Tennessee's Al
Wilson in the first round. ... Miami coach Jimmy Johnson wants to
deal out of the first round and take McNeese State tailback Cecil
Collins in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
