<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHING-WOMEN11-COX     04-10 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-WOMEN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The bass tours' reel women
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pam Martin might be one of the most skilled Georgia
anglers of either gender, but she doesn't necessarily look at
herself as a trailblazer. At the same time, she wouldn't mind being
thought of that way.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 36, has made a mark on tournament bass fishing in her
dozen years of competing in top-level events. The all-time money
leader and two-time angler of the year in the now-defunct Bass'n
Gal tournament circuit, the Bainbridge angler, who first began
honing her skills as a child on weekend camping trips with her
parents and grandparents to Lake Seminole, is one of a handful of
female pros standing out in the male-dominated sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd call myself a trailblazer, but I would
hope in my 12 years of fishing I have influenced someone to at
least get out and enjoy the outdoors,'' said Martin, also an avid
turkey hunter. ``I'm not one of the founders or the first ones, but
having met some of the goals I've made, I would hope someone would
look at me that way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet someone is, especially with Martin's
credentials. Along with the Bass'n Gal accomplishments, she is one
of the leading competitors on the relatively young Women's Bass
Fishing Association. She was third in points standings and second
in the season-ending championship. She also has competed alongside,
and beaten, men in big tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Martin fished three years on the Wal-Mart FLW Tour, one of the
two major professional circuits that attract most of the sport's
top anglers. In 1997, she finished 25th in the Forrest Wood Open on
Lake Minnetonka, Minn., and was 10th in another event, on Lake
Seminole, her home lake, after leading the field for the first
round. Her abilities have attracted several sponsors who typically
back her male counterparts, such as Ranger boats, Evinrude outboard
motors and All-Star rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 12 years, (tournament fishing) is all I've known, but I've
seen an acceptance by the general public that it's OK for women to
compete in tournaments,'' Martin says. ``And, you know, the bass
don't know if you're male or female.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishing against men never dissuaded Martin nor the others who
have followed former Bass'n Gal champion Vojai Reed, the first
woman to enter a major men's tournament when she competed in a
BASSMaster event in 1991. Until the 1990-91 season, the Bass
Anglers Sportsman Society rulebook had specified that only men
could compete in its tournaments. When the Montgomery, Ala.-based
company changed the wording in the rulebook, it in essence opened
the door to women to try their luck in bass fishing's top events.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven female professionals as listed by the
Association of Bass Professionals who compete in BASS events. The
most notable of the group is Sherrie Brubaker, last year's WBFA
champion, who competed in the BASSMaster Central Division this
season. Marcia Fann of Florida finished 47th in the Eastern
Division points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Results are showing on the stat sheets at male-dominated
tournaments. Last March, Wanda Rucker, a 48-year-old Cocoa, Fla.,
grandmother, became the first woman to win a Red Man tournament _
after more than 2,500 Red Man events since 1979. Rucker has noticed
more women in Red Man tournaments since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last (Red Man) tournament at Lake Okeechobee, there
were like 15 women in the field. There were never more than five or
six before,'' said Rucker, who won there last year. ``So what does
that tell you? Maybe they're either trying to get my butt or
they're following my lead and think they can (win), too. ... I
really do feel I've encouraged some women.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the successes has come acceptance from the male
anglers. ``Maybe at first, the men, when they saw the women in the
crowd, they may have thought, `Oh, no. What if I get a woman (as a
partner)?''' Rucker said. ``But most of the men I've fished with
have become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucker still holds the women's record for the one-day stringer
she caught in a Red Man tournament in 1997; it was 22 pounds, and
she finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Martin says that fishing has always been a part of her life, and
she's had hundreds of opportunities to fish with men.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as fishing with men is concerned, that's never been a
problem,'' she said. ``I've been fishing long enough that a lot of
these guys know me. I've always felt right at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the crossover successes of Martin, Rucker and others,
the state of women's professional bass fishing is still in the
developmental stage. Attracting sponsors can be difficult. In fact,
even though Bass'n Gal existed for more than 20 years and had more
than 30,000 members, it closed its doors in January 1998 partly
because it was tough to get sponsors. ``It's proving hard to
attract sponsors because it's perceived as a man's sport,'' said
WBFA President Willie Cook, who points out that more than 13
million women in the United States buy fishing licences every year.
``My saying is that the gender stops where the line begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The WBFA, which started in 1997, has been received pretty well
in the industry so far. ``This circuit's coming on strong,'' said
Martin. ``They're out there to really promote the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Martin has her sights set on the big trails, where six
figures and lucrative endorsements await the winners. ``Whether
it's FLW, EverStart or BASS, I will definitely be fishing something
other than (the WBFA).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
