<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stefan still No. 1 in draft, but doubts emerging
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News ServiceCzech Republic native Patrik Stefan
<TEXT>
remains the consensus top player in the June entry draft, but teams
_ including the Thrashers _ might be starting to have second
thoughts about selecting him. Stefan, who has been playing with the
Long Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL, suffered at least his second
concussion of the season last week and will miss the rest of the
season. The 18-year-old, who missed 38 games earlier this season
with a concussion and spinal injury, last week was knocked
unconscious for nine minutes when he collided with the knee of Las
Vegas forward Kevin Kaminsky. Kaminsky suffered a torn knee
ligament. Although the decision to sit out the remainder of the
season is somewhat precautionary, long-term effects of the
concussions and Stefan's durability have come into question. He
also has had groin and knee ailments. Tampa Bay adviser Cliff
Fletcher already is making comparisons to Brett Lindros, the
brother of Eric Lindros, who retired after just 51 NHL games
because of repeated concussions. ``Everybody is going to have to do
their homework on him,'' Nashville general manager David Poile
said. Stefan told a Long Beach newspaper that he is still having
headaches. ``I was so excited to be back, and then this happens,''
he said. He did not question the check by Kaminsky but said, ``I
think these players in the league want to give me something.'' The
Thrashers will pick first, second or third in the draft, depending
on the result of a lottery next month.
<P>
