<P>
   THRASHERS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   As general manager Don Waddell scouts amateurs in Europe,
goaltending consultant Andy Moog is continuing to critique NHL,
minor-league and draft-eligible goalies. Moog, who lives near
Dallas, says he has filed reports on 15 to 20 players and sees two
to three games a week. ``It's just my own observations on a guy,''
said Moog, who can't discuss NHL goalies publicly, because of
tampering rules. ``I've never done this before, so I don't know if
it reads like an official scouting report.'' Asked if he felt
confident that the Thrashers would land a strong goaltender in the
expansion draft, Moog said, ``That's not up to me. I know there's a
surplus of goaltenders right now. But it depends on what all the
teams do (with their protected lists). There could still be some
trades.
</P>
