<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions about ailing Lindros
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few lingering issues during Eric Lindros' recovery
from a collapsed lung:
</P>
<P>
   1. Philadelphia's initial suggestion that Lindros could return
for the playoffs was misguided. Lindros had approximately three
liters of blood, or half that in his body, seep into his chest
cavity. It will take three to four months just for that blood to be
regenerated. That doesn't take into account time for conditioning
and the star's emotional rehabilitation. He has been told that if
he had taken the team flight from Nashville back to Philadelphia
instead of checking into a hospital, he might have died on the
plane. Is Lindros going to be ready to step back onto the ice this
year?
</P>
<P>
   2. Lindros has only a handshake agreement on a contract for next
season. Given his history of injuries and a now uncertain future,
specifics of that deal might be re-visited.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lindros's absence gives the Flyers an excuse if they exit the
playoffs early. The question is whether owner Ed Snider will let it
affect his critique of GM Bob Clarke and coach Roger Neilson.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warning
</P>
<P>
   Carolina backup goalie Trevor Kidd wasn't lured into a false
sense of security when he signed a two-year, $4 million contract
extension recently _ and his fears were reaffirmed when the
Hurricanes signed No. 1 goalie Arturs Irbe to a three-year deal
totaling $5.8 million. Kidd almost certainly will be exposed in the
expansion draft to the Thrashers. By selecting him, Atlanta not
only could strengthen its goaltending but also weaken that of a
Southeast Division opponent. ``If they're going to make a decision
now based on stats and games played,'' Kidd said, ``then you don't
have to be a rocket scientist to figure out that I'm going to be
the odd man out.'' There are advantages and disadvantages to
leaving Carolina, he said. ``This is a great place to play,'' he
said. ``My family enjoys it here. But I'm not going to be Mr. Nice
Guy again next year, playing 22-24 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr criticized coach Kevin Constantine in
a Czech Republic newspaper: ``I don't like the way he prepares the
team, and I'm not the only one among the players. His communication
with us is just awful. Either he yells at us or he just hides
somewhere.'' The two aren't saying much publicly about the remarks.
... Carolina coach Paul Maurice on gripes that the slumping
Hurricanes will be afforded the No. 3 playoff seed for winning the
Southeast Division: ``We don't make the rules.'' ... Tampa Bay was
so happy to dump high-salaried backup goalie Bill Ranford that it
will receive nothing in return if Ranford plays in four or fewer
playoff games. The Lightning gets a fifth-round pick if Ranford
plays in at least five postseason games or a fourth if he plays in
10 or more. ... Boston's Byron Dafoe became only the sixth goalie
since the expansion era, from 1967-68, to record at least 10
shutouts in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
