<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson talks way out of L.A.
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a Hall of Fame player and someone who always lhad
the respect of his players, Larry Robinson is picking a strange way
to end his coaching tenure in Los Angeles. Robinson now concedes
that he doesn't know if he wants to continue behind the bench,
although indications are that Kings ownership already has decided
to make a change. An emotional guy, Robinson ripped his players and
seemed to wash himself of all responsibility when the Kings lost
for the sixth time in seven games and were cropped from the playoff
picture. ``Some of them are just playing it out,'' he said.
``That's what it looks like. I don't have anything to lose, but
some of these guys are playing for their contracts, for their jobs
next year. ... If they don't care to play on the ice, why should I
care? I'm not the one losing.'' Robinson continued his verbal
assault, saying, ``It was easy to play last year when things were
going well, but you really see the true colors of a person when
there's some adversity. Ones that can step up and play through
adversity, those are the ones you want to have around. The others?
Let them go. Cull those out. You're only going to make yourself
better.'' Two days later, Robinson turned the focus back on
himself, saying he already has had discussions with general manager
Dave Taylor about staying in the system as a minor-league
instructor. But he might have talked his way out of that job.
</P>
<P>
   Grading Crawford
</P>
<P>
   Marc Crawford is 7-22-5 (.279) since replacing Mike Keenan
(15-24-6, .467) as Vancouver's coach, but he seems to have the
support of his players during this painful transition period.
Crawford has won their respect with more teaching and less
intimidating than Keenan. ``This was a club that under Mike was a
high energy club that forechecked a great deal and really tried to
create havoc,'' Crawford said. ``We've tried to add a little bit
more structure to our play and play with a little bit more purpose
offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie Patrick Roy upset Edmonton players when he took
four shots down ice at an empty net in an attempt to score his
first goal. Mike Grier called it ``selfish.'' Roy's response: ``I
guess they respect my shot because there were all ready at the blue
line.'' ... Dallas' power play _ 9 for 80 _ has dropped from first
to sixth in the rankings. ... Change of scenery: Goalie Bill
Ranford was 3-18-3 with a 3.90 goals-against average with Tampa
Bay. He is 2-0 and 2.50 with Detroit. ``It's like a new life coming
here,'' he said. ... Edmonton GM Glen Sather says rumors that he is
headed to San Jose are untrue and a year old, adding, ``I'm not
going. You've even got (Sharks GM Dean) Lombardi thinking I'm going
to take his job.'' ... You might have to scratch San Jose's Steve
Shields as a potential unprotected goalie for the Thrashers.
Shields has played so well for the Sharks down the stretch that
it's possible the team will protect him and expose veteran Mike
Vernon. Shields made 33 saves in a 1-0 win over Phoenix on
Wednesday to drop his GAA to 2.16.
</P>
