u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-500&AMP;     04-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REFUGEES REPORTEDLY HUNTED AND HERDED INTO TOWN GUARDED BY
SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, EXCLUSIVE-DOWNED-F117, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-SUMMIT, KOSOVO-ORTHODOX, KOSOVO-HISTORY,
KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW, KOSOVO-MIDEAST-REVIEW, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE-REVIEW) 
(rk) 
 By   DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Serbian forces are hunting down ethnic
Albanians hiding in woods and villages in southeastern Kosovo and
herding them into Urosevac, a sizable town roughly 30 miles from
the Macedonian border, refugees arriving from Kosovo said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the roughly 100 Kosovo Albanians who managed to cross
into Macedonia Saturday said that about 5,000 ethnic Albanians are
in Urosevac, where they reportedly live under a strict 7 p.m.-to-7
a.m. curfew and face shortages of food.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily armed Serb civilians patrol the streets of the town, and
some Albanians are ordered to leave their doors open for spot
police checks, some of the refugees said. Their accounts could not
be independently confirmed because foreign journalists, aid workers
and monitors were expelled or evacuated from Kosovo just after NATO
bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ethnic Albanians in Urosevac are unsure whether to
stay or to flee, refugees who talked to reporters said. Many stores
have been looted, they added. This means that ethnic Albanians who
have stayed in their homes, and new arrivals hounded from the
countryside into the town are forced to live in abandoned homes and
rely on dwindling stocks in kitchens, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have anything to eat back there!'' Idiriz Sejeva, a
35-year-old refugee shouted to reporters from a bus window just
after crossing the border where Macedonian guards organized the
refugees' departure for what officials said were refugee camps.
``There are a lot of soldiers! You can't even go buy bread! There
is no food!''
</P>
<P>
   Ramiz Ramadani, a 52-year-old teacher, expressed frustration
with the lack of aid for people trapped in the province. ``No one
is doing anything about the refugees in Kosovo,'' Ramadani said.
``At least get them some food by helicopter or at least let them
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials and the U.N. refugee agency have expressed
strong concern about the fate of hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians still in Kosovo. Food drops have been considered, but
rejected as too dangerous for the NATO pilots who would have to fly
low to make the drops, risking Serbian anti-aircraft fire. There
would also be no guarantee of the food reaching the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadani said that Serbian forces came to his small village near
Urosevac several days after NATO's air campaign began and told the
villagers they would be safe. But the following day another group
of soldiers arrived and residents fled in fear, he said. The
soldiers killed five elderly people, including two confined to
wheelchairs, he said, and looted and burned homes.
</P>
<P>
   He said he, his wife and three sons fled into the hills with
other villagers, but they were captured by Serbian soldiers.
Jewelry was taken from some of the women and the group was ordered
to enter Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all empty houses and no food,'' he said. ``The Serb
civilians, even the kids, were carrying machine guns.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even though the curfew allowed him to walk the streets between 7
a.m. and 7 p.m., Ramadani said he only dared venture outside twice
in the town. He was told that the border was closed but he also
heard that trains to Macedonia were running.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving early this morning with a few dozen other people from
the town, he boarded a nearly empty train for the border. Serbian
police, who earlier this week reportedly forced refugees back into
Kosovo as President Slobodan Milosevic declared a ceasefire, tried
to talk Ramadani's group out of leaving, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The police urged the group to turn back, and said the only way
into Macedonia was to walk down railroad tracks mined on either
side, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of our group turned back,'' he said. ``They were
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramadani and his family headed down the tracks. Upon arrival,
they waited several hours to be processed by the Macedonian police
before being taken to join the 18,000 other refugees in a sprawling
refugee camp built by British NATO soldiers in the town of Brazde.
</P>
<P>
   Sejeva, a longtime resident of Urosevac, said that he fled into
the woods from his home in the town when NATO bombing began, but
returned to the town several days later when his pregnant wife
needed medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Four days ago, Serb soldiers raided the small tent area in the
woods where he and his wife initially hid, and the couple decided
to trek through the woods, hoping to get to Macedonia. He and a few
dozen others who made it were held by Macedonian police when they
arrived this morning before being bused out.
</P>
<P>
   Genc Rexha, a 28-year-old architecture student who also lived in
Urosevac, recounted a life of horror in the town that, if true, is
reminiscent of tactics used by Serb paramilitaries in the 1992-95
war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Rexha, who arrived with Ramadani, said that houses of local
Albanian leaders were targeted for destruction. Albanians were
dragged into the street by masked men and then forced to watch as
their homes were looted, he said. And last Friday, Serbs shot dead
a young Albanian for no apparent reason as he walked down the
street at 1:30 p.m., Rexha said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people are getting ready to try to escape,'' he
said. ``But they don't know the way. They are scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
