u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKATE-SCANDAL-ART-117     04-10 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-SCANDAL-ART-1170(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S PREMIER FIGURE-SKATING COACH IS ACCUSED OF IMPROPER
SEXUAL CONDUCT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Colo., N.Y., Pa.) (Exclusive)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. _ For two decades, Richard Callaghan and
Craig Maurizi worked together in the sport of international figure
skating. Callaghan was first Maurizi's coach, then his colleague,
and the two together coached some of the most promising skaters in
the United States. They enjoyed considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   Having begun working with Callaghan when he was 13, Maurizi rose
through the ranks of pairs skating to finish fifth at the 1986
national championships. And in 1998, with Maurizi assisting
Callaghan, Tara Lipinski won the Olympic gold medal in Nagano,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Maurizi has come forward to claim that his
relationship with Callaghan, one of the dominant figures in
skating, was much more complicated, even exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, 36, who has recently embarked on his own as a coach and
taken Lipinski with him, has said in a series of interviews in
recent weeks that Callaghan engaged in inappropriate sexual conduct
with him when he was 15, and later abused his position of authority
to initiate a full sexual relationship when Maurizi was 18 and
barely out of high school. The sexual relationship, Maurizi claims,
continued, off and on, until two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, who never reported any misconduct by Callaghan during
the 21 years of their collaboration and friendship, registered a
complaint last month with the U.S. Figure Skating Association. He
said he had only recently been able to talk about his sexual
relationship with Callaghan, and had, with the help of a therapist
and the support of his wife, come to the conclusion that the
relationship had been wrong, and that Callaghan needed to be
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan, who has retained a lawyer, vehemently denied that he
ever had sex with Maurizi and dismissed any suggestion that he had
engaged in any improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent, four-hour interview here at his lawyer's office,
Callaghan contended that Maurizi's charges were part of an effort
to rob him of his skaters and thus enhance his former protege's
professional and financial standing. Maurizi and Callaghan
separated as coaching colleagues last year after a tense Olympic
season, with Lipinski choosing to work with Maurizi.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, referring to his years with Callaghan, said: ``At the
time, I thought the sex was consensual. Now, when I look back, I
don't think it was consensual. I don't care how old a student is,
whether it's a boy or a girl, a coach should never have sex with a
student. The coach is the person the athlete looks up to for
leadership and to be a role model. I don't think coaches understand
the influence they can exert over students. People need to be more
aware of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Disbrow, president of the U.S. Figure Skating Association,
said that Maurizi informed him last month of his allegations
against Callaghan, but added that the association would not act
until it received a formal written grievance. Maurizi said he
planned to submit his written complaint within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan, 53, who is married with a grown daughter, resigned as
director of competitive skating at the Detroit Skating Club in
early March and said he planned to retire from the competitive side
of the sport. Callaghan's decision _ he plans to continue serving
as a consultant to his skaters _ surprised the skating world, for
he is the most successful coach in the country, having produced an
Olympic champion, two world champions and seven national titles.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan said his resignation was unrelated to the allegations
made by Maurizi, and was instead the result of having, after 27
years, grown weary of the relentless travel and daily grind of
international coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked my butt off to be successful,'' Callaghan said. ``I
think I've got the right to cut back. I'm proud of what I've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with four dozen skaters, coaches, officials, agents
and parents, including more than a dozen of Callaghan's current and
former students, have produced differing portraits: For some, he is
a consummate, if tough and exacting, professional; for others, he
is an authoritarian presence who could bully female skaters and
make unwanted sexual advances to male skaters under his care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he has done so much for my career,'' Todd Eldredge,
27, said of Callaghan. Eldredge, who has worked with Callaghan
since he was in elementary school, has won five national titles and
was world champion in 1996. Eldredge said that across two decades
of work with Callaghan he had seen no evidence of misconduct of any
kind. ``He's been like a father figure,'' Eldredge said. ``His
style is that he wants things right. He'll push you to get the
results he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eddy Zeidler, 28, a former student, said Callaghan exposed
himself to him in a hotel room in 1992. And Roman Fraden, 24,
another former student, said that Callaghan made inappropriate
sexual remarks to him in 1994, and Fraden's parents said they
confronted Callaghan over the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Agle, who coached with Callaghan in Philadelphia in the
early 1980s, said that three different male skaters approached her
in 1986 and said they had witnessed or been subjected to sexual
advances by Callaghan. And the former managers of the San Diego
rink where Callaghan worked in the early 1990s said two young
skaters complained in 1991 that they had witnessed Callaghan
kissing an adult male student during a workout at the rink.
</P>
<P>
   The managers ultimately sided with Callaghan, believing the
girls or their coach might have misconstrued what they saw or made
up the story.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, though, is sure: no formal complaint has ever before
been filed against Callaghan for any kind of misconduct. Officials
with the figure skating association said Maurizi's allegations were
the first of their kind. Officials at private rinks in Buffalo,
N.Y.; Philadelphia; Colorado Springs, Colo.; San Diego, and
Detroit, where Callaghan has worked, said he never left any job as
a result of concerns over improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan, for his part, said some of his former students were
attempting to blame him for unfulfilled careers. Zeidler, he said,
left Detroit owing him and the skating club several thousand
dollars, a claim confirmed by Drew Paterson, a former president of
the club.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan said that he made no inappropriate remarks to Fraden,
and that Fraden's parents never raised the issue with him. Of
Agle's allegation, he said it was consistent with a pattern of
unfounded claims made against him over the years. Regarding the San
Diego incident, Callaghan said he was choreographing a routine for
an upcoming competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reasons I don't understand, people love me or
hate me,'' Callaghan said. ``I have no clue why. In almost 30
years, I've taught about 500 kids. I don't understand this. The
allegations are awful. I can't believe I worked my butt off for
kids to be successful in skating to be better people, and this
stuff happens.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKATE-SCANDAL-ART-117     04-10 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-SCANDAL-ART-1170(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BLOOMFIELD HILLS: stuff happens.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The son of a fencing salesman from Rochester, N.Y., Callaghan
began skating at age 9 or 10. He showed a rare versatility,
competing in singles, pairs and ice dancing. He finished fifth at
the national championships in 1965 at age 19, and then toured with
the Ice Capades and Holiday on Ice shows for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Always, though, he wanted to teach. ``I protected myself, so I
would be able to teach whoever walked in the door,'' he said,
referring to his preparations to master different aspects of figure
skating.
</P>
<P>
   As with gymnastics, many figure skaters leave home as
adolescents to take lessons from the best coaches, sometimes moving
with one or both parents, sometimes moving alone. A skater might
spend four hours a day practicing, and with frequent travel to
competitions coaches can essentially become guardians, chaperons
and advisers as well as shapers of careers.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi began taking lessons from Callaghan as a 13-year-old in
1976 in Buffalo. What began with simple lessons between coach and
student, Maurizi says, evolved into a long, complex partnership
that included success on the ice and an unhealthy, but effectively
unbreakable relationship off it. Maurizi, over the years, took
lessons with his coach in Buffalo, Philadelphia and Colorado
Springs, and later coached with him in San Diego and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Callaghan moved with his family from Buffalo to work in
Philadelphia, and Maurizi, then 18, followed him, as skaters often
do with their coaches. It was there, Maurizi said, that the
relationship with Callaghan became sexual, and their encounters
occurred at his own apartment, at Callaghan's home, in hotel rooms
and at a skating rink, usually after nights of drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The skater said that he felt uncomfortable, but that his fear of
disappointing Callaghan overcame his sense that something was not
right.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when he was 23 and had moved to Colorado Springs to
continue taking lessons with Callaghan, Maurizi said he told his
coach he was uncomfortable with the sexual relationship and wanted
it to end, but that Callaghan interfered with his attempts to date
women. It was not until 1989, when he met his wife, Chaundra, that
he had a steady girlfriend, Maurizi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had the guts,'' Maurizi said in explaining why he
never broke from Callaghan until last winter. ``I didn't want to
experience his wrath, or hurt him. I still feel some remnants of
that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he left Callaghan, Maurizi said, he has been able to tell
his wife and certain friends about the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan said he believed that Maurizi, having already taken
Lipinski, is making the accusations to lure other skaters and gain
bigger paydays. Lipinski's parents said she left Callaghan because
they felt she was not getting adequate attention and because he had
become intrusive in trying to dictate all aspects of Lipinski's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Groulx, Callaghan's lawyer, said: ``Mr. Maurizi has
certainly not enjoyed the coaching success that Richard has. Until
a short time ago, he was making significantly less than $100,000 a
year. Now, by swaying certain prominent members of the Detroit
Skating Club through these allegations to come under his tutelage,
he has the opportunity to earn upwards of $250,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi said he told Callaghan on Feb. 19 at the Detroit Skating
Club that he had begun to speak openly of their relationship. He
said Callaghan blamed him for being the aggressor in the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was extremely sad and disappointing to me,'' Maurizi
said. ``He seemed to be blaming me. It was an awful thing to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan denied the subject ever came up and said the meeting
had been amicable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
