<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-720&AMP;ADD-NY     04-10 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE VISITOR PLAYS TO THE MANY AUDIENCES IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Calif.) (lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Chinese leaders, tutored by their own experts and
legions of ``foreign friends'' who pass through Beijing, have
learned a lesson over the years: The United States is not a
one-party dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Simple though it sounds, it has taken the Chinese government the
better part of the quarter-century to digest that fact. The United
States, especially when it comes to the volatile subject of China,
is not one state, but 50. It has 435 political factions, each with
its own seat in the House of Representatives. The media, academia
and the corporate world rarely toe the ``party'' line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to believe that if your president and our leaders can
trust one another, then there is no problem,'' said a Chinese
Foreign Ministry official in the delegation of the visiting Chinese
prime minister. ``That is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   This has led to the remarkable spectacle of Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji, trained in the Communist Party system, cajoling members of
Congress, rallying businesses, courting the media, and now, as he
brings his whistle-stop tour of America to Denver, taking his case
to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, though deeply disappointed that he was unable to seal a
deal for China's entry into the World Trade Organization last week,
hoped but never assumed that President Clinton would deliver on the
trade deal that the two sides have been negotiating in recent
weeks, senior Chinese aides said in interviews on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Especially given what they describe as the ``bad political
environment'' in relation to China these days, Zhu and his advisers
felt that even if the accord was signed, the prime minister would
still have to ``campaign'' vigorously to help Clinton get it
through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The idea marks a sea change in the way China deals with the
United States. Chinese officials have long lamented that their fine
working relationships with presidents, dating back to Richard
Nixon, often do not ensure stable relations.
</P>
<P>
   Now China is trying to build bridges to a more diverse group of
U.S. political and business leaders. The campaign seems unlikely to
generate a public groundswell of support to get China into the
trade group. But for the Chinese strategy to work, Zhu need not
necessarily do that, his aides say. It is enough to persuade a
cross-section of political, media and academic leaders that the
United States can do business with China, and specifically with
Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister quipped at his joint news conference with
Clinton on Thursday that he is a neophyte in the glare of media
spotlights in Washington. But he appears not only to tolerate the
rough and tumble of American politics but also to enjoy it, showing
off his ability to make jokes and speak off the cuff.
</P>
<P>
   The apparently tireless 70-year-old Zhu, unruffled despite
several late-night strategy sessions and a brutal travel schedule,
delved into environmental policy at a forum with Vice President Al
Gore on Friday. The prime minister pointedly departed from his
prepared text to detail environmental problems in China, moments
after Gore, who is campaigning for president, delivered remarks on
the subject read verbatim from a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late into the evening, Zhu spoke extemporaneously and took
questions from an audience of China scholars and diplomats at a
Washington hotel, expounding at length on his disappointment over
the failure to close the trade deal. He sounded crestfallen at
times, even suggesting that he could suffer politically at home for
compromising too much. But the audience loved the performance,
which seemed to be the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went back to China and talked about all these concessions
I have made, I could be kicked out of office,'' Zhu said, a slight
grin suggesting that he is confident this is not about to happen.
``The problem is not that I am afraid of this, but that the Chinese
people will never accept too many concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   It is almost as though Zhu, in a role reversal, wants to
negotiate the trade accord in public while his U.S. counterparts
prefer to settle matters privately. He warned his dinner audience
that the concessions China has made to date are not set in stone
until the two sides agree on an interim joint statement, a matter
he says is still not final despite U.S. suggestions to the
contrary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like any campaigner, Zhu is careful to praise his friends.
Speaking of greatly expanded opportunities for foreign insurance
companies in China if it joins the world trade group, he recalled
the pioneering experiences of Maurice Greenberg, chairman of
insurance giant American International Group, who received the
first foreign license to sell policies in Shanghai, China, years
ago. Then he joked that he had received ``no favors'' from
Greenberg in exchange for this privileged access to the China
market.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he has laid bare the strategy for his U.S. visit.
Speaking in Chinese to a group of Chinese-Americans last week, he
played on the Chinese word ``qi,'' which, depending on context, can
mean ``anger'' or ``morale.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that amid allegations about Chinese human rights abuses
and spying, the best he could expect on this trip was to reduce the
``qi'' that many Americans felt toward China by accepting their
criticism. Then he added, his voice rising, that he also hoped to
increase the ``qi'' of all Chinese-Americans, calling on them to
help promote better bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Zhu seems almost to be engaging in his own version of
pork-barrel politics. He agreed to separate from the trade
negotiations a side accord liberalizing Chinese import rules for
U.S. wheat and citrus fruit. The reason: California and Florida,
two of the most important states politically, are big citrus
exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., seemed to validate that tactic.
Hastings, who had breakfast with Zhu at Blair House on Friday
morning, said the citrus agreement solved his biggest requirement
for China's entry into the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that we need to hammer away at them all the
time,'' Hastings said. ``Congress should stop looking for demons.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's performance is by no means perfect. Several
people who watched his news conference with Clinton, for instance,
faulted him for referring to Abraham Lincoln and the U.S. Civil War
as an analogy for China's policy toward Taiwan, an off-the-cuff
remark that sounded aggressive and prompted a rebuke from Clinton.
Several others said he appeared unwilling to engage in serious
discussion about human rights, despite promises to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But halfway through his U.S. tour, some China experts are
comparing Zhu to Chou En-lai, the prime minister who served loyally
at Mao Tse-tung's side before and after the communist revolution.
Like Chou, Zhu focuses on carrying out policy effectively, not
debating ideology. And like Chou, Zhu is rapidly becoming the
public face of China, at least to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is selling himself as the intelligent, sophisticated, Chou
En-lai guy,'' said James Lilley, a former ambassador to China.
``He's post-Tiananmen square, Shanghai not Beijing, economic
reform, free market, MIT and science and all that. All very
effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
