<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEDTURNER-BISON11-COX     04-10 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEDTURNER-BISON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eat more bison? Industry faces a hard sell
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No, it doesn't taste like chicken and it certainly
doesn't look like it.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking bison, an animal that Ted Turner is trying to
establish as a healthy culinary alternative to beef.
</P>
<P>
   It's an uphill fight, but what else is new for Turner, who
helped build the cable TV industry with his TBS and CNN news
channels.
</P>
<P>
   As with his cable TV company, Turner's bison operation will
succeed only if the country's small and struggling bison industry
does, too. That means, once again, Turner must build an industry to
support his fledgling company.
</P>
<P>
   R.E. ``Teddy'' Turner Jr. heads his father's bison marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Turner estimates his bison operations are already
among the largest in market value and herd size. While a tough sell
now, he is convinced bison can work as a business. ``Bison are more
profitable than cattle right now. Cattle prices have fallen sharply
while those for bison are going up.''
</P>
<P>
   While it looks like beef, bison meat differs in makeup and
taste. Bison is almost as lean as turkey and is best served rare.
Most restaurants overcook bison, which tastes wonderfully sweet
when prepared correctly. It's more expensive than beef, typically
two or three times higher in price.
</P>
<P>
   The market
</P>
<P>
   Today, naturalists consider bison the proper term for this
woolly range denizen. Buffalo refers to a cattlelike species that
lives in parts of Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there are about 250,000 bison herded for commercial
meat. The number is growing by about 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   But the bison market is small compared with that for beef. About
20,000 bison a year are slaughtered for meat compared with 120,000
cattle a day.
</P>
<P>
   Turner has about 17,000 bison on nine of his 16 U.S. properties.
He expects to grow his herds to 30,000 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The bison operations are part of Atlanta-based Turner
Enterprises Inc., a private company. Turner sells his marketable
bison, mostly male calves, to the North American Bison Cooperative.
He owns 10 percent of the cooperative, which was formed to pool
industry supply and set common quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperative slaughters and packages the bison, but the
marketing of the product is left to the individual companies. For
Turner, that company is U.S. Bison Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a sales and marketing company focused on the
Southeast,'' says Hansell Roddenbery, U.S. Bison's president and
chief executive. Teddy Jr. is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Roddenbery explains that U.S. Bison doesn't buy meat from
Turner's ranches but from the cooperative. In that way, ``we are
helping all the members of the cooperative.'' Right now, Turner's
ranches aren't big cooperative contributors because his bison are
young and not producing many marketable calves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long-term investment,'' says Teddy. ``It won't be
profitable for the first couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge
</P>
<P>
   Developing the commercial market is a major hurdle. There's good
demand for bison steaks in fancy restaurants. But demand for lesser
cuts such as hamburger and hot dogs is almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   That's a problem because most of the 400 pounds of meat from a
bison are better suited for hamburger and hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 30 percent to 40 percent of all bison meat goes into
cold storage. ``It doesn't do us any good to keep pushing
tenderloin,'' says Teddy. ``Our job is to sell more hamburger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs and hamburger don't have steak's high profit margins so
Turner will have to sell a lot of bison hot dogs to become
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   While the plan is to eventually reach supermarkets, Teddy is
initially marketing to restaurants because people are more apt to
try something new when eating out.
</P>
<P>
   If people like a bison steak, he reasons, they'll be more likely
to buy the hamburger meat later on.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant effort is off to a strong start. Roddenbery, who
does the selling, is signing up restaurants weekly. Among those in
metro Atlanta are Nava, Jocks &AMP; Jills, the Downtown Capital Club,
the Ritz-Carlton Buckhead and downtown, the Marriott Marquis, the
Commerce Club and the Piedmont Driving Club.
</P>
<P>
   Roddenbery has also struck a deal with Turner Field, which is
now selling bison hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of places are sampling bison,'' says Teddy.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is Turner's famous name behind the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Dad,'' says Teddy. ``That's a huge advantage. His
name is a marketer's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
