<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-10 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CROSSROADS MOMENT IN THE WNBA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before she graduated from Notre Dame law school and worked
on both sides of the employee-relations street, Coquese Washington
understood the repercussions of a labor war. She grew up in Flint,
Mich., and her parents worked for General Motors, in rebellious
union shops. Her father went on strike. Her mother was laid off.
Families went broke. Familiar stores became boarded-up shells, and
her city the backdrop in ``Roger and Me,'' Michael Moore's bitterly
anti-corporate film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor strife is nothing new to me,'' said the 28-year-old
backup point guard for the New York Liberty, knowing the fallout
may not be pretty, no matter how right you are.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when risks and odds must be ignored, when the
line in the sand, or on the hardwood, should be drawn. Now may be
one of them, because it happens to be a crossroads moment for women
in professional team sports. The 2-year-old Women's National
Basketball Association has all the leverage in its first collective
bargaining stare down. But the time has come to ask: Are the women
to be real players with legitimate jobs, or marketing pawns,
symbols of synergy, in the expansive universe of powerful men like
David Stern?
</P>
<P>
   ``We look upon this as a rite of passage,'' said Val Ackerman,
the WNBA president, handpicked for the position by Stern. ``Unions
are an accouterment of major-league sports. To that extent, it's
not a surprise we're in bargaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, after the way Stern dealt with the men, the
league's idea of bargaining has thus far been in the form of one
offer, take it or leave it, with a new round of talks scheduled to
begin Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of retaliation, implicit or otherwise, begins with a
defunct league of very good players, potential scabs, waiting
outside the lines for another opportunity to work. The WNBA
veterans, Washington said, may not have much more than the moral
high ground to stand on, the rare sports union the public can't
call greedy. That is more than the men had in their recent
confrontation with Stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very mindful of the fact that this is a young league,''
Washington, a member of the women's negotiating team, said late
last week. ``But we also want some kind of commitment that shows
the players are as important as the marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   As a WNBA rookie last summer, Washington made the minimum,
$15,000. The American Basketball League paid her $40,000 the
previous season, a livable wage, but the ABL folded last December,
leaving Stern's annex as the only game around.
</P>
<P>
   The upstart rival crushed, the summertime concept proven to be
the best way to go, the ball is now with Ackerman and Stern. They
can push the players around, have it their way, or they can stop
throwing out optimistically averaged packages that are more
propaganda and move off their $20,000 minimum salary offer. They
can demonstrate that the advancement of the women's game is more to
them than a politically correct means of promoting the NBA name and
licensed products for 12 months a year.
</P>
<P>
   Winning with class means showing some compassion, allowing for a
negotiated settlement that will make the players rush back with a
smile. It is already unfortunate enough to have the WNBA players
fighting hard to limit the number of ABL players being signed.
Another $1 million into the pot _ what Stern uses to cater the
breakfast buffet at All-Star weekend _ would avoid the unseemly
prospect of ABL players walking past WNBA pickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, probably sooner, Darwin will win out. The most
gifted players will inherit the league. The WNBA, which has far
exceeded startup projections, will continue to grow, or it won't.
It should be obvious that the best chance it has to become an
indisputable revenue producer is to not make players exhaust
themselves all winter, playing in Europe and Asia, because they
can't make enough back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told the whole idea was to create jobs in the States,
so we wouldn't have to go running all over the world to make enough
money to live,'' Washington said. ``People might say, `Get another
job.' How many jobs can you get where you pick up in May and say
you'll be back in October?''
</P>
<P>
   Washington practiced litigation and real-estate law for the New
York firm Rubin Baum Levin Constant &AMP; Friedman after last season.
She left in February, accepting the cold reality that the number of
jobs in the women's game was now half what it was.
</P>
<P>
   The players are smart enough to know that you do not go to a
competitive training camp after leading a sedentary 40-hour work
week, with executive lunches and a quick trip to the gym. Val
Ackerman and David Stern should know you don't grow a sport with a
handful of stars under personal-services contracts, while the rest
of the players get a stipend, not a salary.
</P>
<P>
   That is not promoting women's sports as much as it is convincing
people that the wrong league won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
