<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREAKNIK-ATLANTA11-CO     04-10 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-ATLANTA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik '99: Is the party ending or just changing?
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Freaknik '99 rolls into town this week, Andrea
Harvey will lock herself in her dorm room. She learned her lesson
four years ago while a junior at Cedar Grove High School in
Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to work at a drugstore in South DeKalb Mall,''
recalled Harvey, now a student at Agnes Scott College, where she is
student government president.
</P>
<P>
   What she saw in the mall's food court could easily have been a
scene from a strip club.
</P>
<P>
   Women were atop tables stripping, guys were groping and police
were arresting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy pulled me and asked if I was going to strip for
him,'' said Harvey. ``The more insistent he got, the larger the
group got.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Harvey found herself surrounded by at least 40
guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They engulfed me. Pulled my dress off. Groped me in places,''
said Harvey. ``I was pretty hysterical, but no one heard my
screams.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said security rescued her, and she never reported the
assault to police or even talked about it for years because she was
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   One thing she did do was avoid Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   ``In theory, Freaknik was probably a very good idea,'' said
Harvey. ``But it has changed from what it was. Now, the general
atmosphere lends to behavior of disrespect and degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like Harvey's are what many people think about when
Freaknik, the 18-year-old spring break gathering for black college
students, comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of spring break?
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik began in 1982, when a small group of Washington, D.C.
natives, who couldn't make it home from Atlanta colleges for spring
break, decided to have a picnic in the park. What started out
innocently has morphed into a roving and oftentimes unwieldy street
party, rife with images of sex and violence. ``Freaknik is a
mockery to our ancestors,'' said Eric Abercrumbie, director of the
African-American Cultural and Research Center at the University of
Cincinnati. ``They want to do things that are exciting to them or
on the edge, but it turns into an embarrassment. There are people
who have died so we can walk on the streets of Atlanta and they are
doing this on those very streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Some feel Abercrumbie's assessment is too harsh. They point out
that the arrests and reported assaults are minuscule, compared to
the number who attend.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics provided by the Atlanta Police
Department, only a small percentage of Freaknik participants are
actually arrested during the event. In 1994, when Freaknik reached
its apex of 200,000 people, arrests totaled 143.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's gathering drew just 50,000 people, and fewer than
500 arrests were reported, not even 1 percent of the estimated
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what goes on at Freaknik may be typical of what goes on
at locations all over the country _ from Virginia Beach to Daytona
Beach to Venice Beach _ during spring break. As MTV has proved with
its spring break specials, students, white or black, are going to
trash hotel rooms, clog up intersections, get drunk and act rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaknik is looked at with more scrutiny because it is a black
event,'' said Robin Hughes, a 23-year-old native of Mobile, Ala.,
and a Clark Atlanta University graduate. ``But for the most part,
we have to accept some of the blame, because we do get out of hand.
There are some things that you just can't do in the middle of
downtown, and just because they do it doesn't mean that it is right
for us to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Brinson, a psychology professor at North Carolina Central
University, said Freaknik demonstrates the sudden and unpredictable
nature of crowds. Brinson said students and young adults may lead
regular, quiet lives at home, only to come to Atlanta to strip on
the roofs of cars or chase women down Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things start off innocently enough, then they turn violent. It
might have something to do with people trying to express their
frustration. Whatever that may be,'' Brinson said. ``It is a
complex, disturbing matter to me personally and professionally, and
it is played out almost daily in our court system when people cross
the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinson believes that unlike youth of the 1960s and 1970s, when
individuality was stressed, young people are now content with being
part of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a security issue here,'' said Brinson. ``People go
along with this because there is protection in numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said that when she was attacked in 1995, although most of
the faces were unfamiliar, she saw at least two people she knew
from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't talk about it for a while,'' she said. ``Now, when
the discussion comes up, I'll talk about it. I don't know if I
would advise people not to go, but I would advise them on the
situation they put themselves in by just being there.''
</P>
<P>
   `With a name like Freaknik'
</P>
<P>
   Angel Crawford, a major with the Opa-locka (Fla.) Police
Department, gladly welcomes that kind of advice. She said she
hadn't really heard about Freaknik until her 20-year-old daughter
mentioned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaknik? I asked her what kind of spring break she was going
to with a name like Freaknik,'' said Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   She e-mailed a sorority sister in Atlanta to find out more. Now
her daughter, Porshe, will be staying home in Opalocka during
Freaknik, Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have concerns as a parent for a child that is going to go
away _ especially a young lady. When (my sorority sister) wrote me
and told me about the assaults and the type of women who come up
there, I said absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Porshe Crawford said she and her friends were just looking for a
cool place to go for her first spring break as a college student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it was just people having fun . . . maybe sort of
wild. I didn't know it was about that,'' said the Broward Community
College freshman. ``Some of the things she was saying about some
girl getting stripped in the street, all those men, it appears to
be pretty wild. I didn't know it was to that extreme. I just
thought it was fun. It did change my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she won't attend Freaknik, she may attend the Black
College Reunion in Daytona Beach this weekend, one of two major
events, along with the Kappa Beach Party in Galveston, Texas, that
rival Freaknik for attendance by African-American college students.
</P>
<P>
   The events in Daytona Beach and Galveston may explain why
Freaknik attendance has dropped each year since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrumbie cited numerous reasons for Freaknik's decline,
including poor planning and a lack of a significant adult
supervision. But there is an even more basic problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name started it and suggested the behavior,'' Abercrumbie
said. ``A new name and a new design would help. The cry is that
young people want something to do. How do you channel that in a
positive way? When you think of Freaknik, you want to see freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are struggling to change that image. Although it is
commonly known as Freaknik, it is technically the Black College
Spring Break. Locals have voiced their concerns, and up to 500
Atlanta high school students will be wearing red ``Don't Freak No
Mo'' T-shirts during this year's event to show the city that not
everyone who attends Freaknik is a freak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaknik, and what it has become, is an event that the city
and the citizens of the city do not welcome,'' said Atlanta native
Byron Amos, a newly appointed member of a municipal committee
examining the event. ``We are trying to convert Freaknik into Black
College Spring Break, which is a more productive and respectable
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Amos, a senior at Clark Atlanta University, said that in order
to do that, they will focus more on the positive side of the event,
like the accompanying Sweet Auburn Festival and job fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can bring that to light, we can overshadow some of the
negative,'' said Amos, 26.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that only the partyers can change the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really hard to get around the negatives. It all falls
back on the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
