<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-QUARTERBACK     04-10 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-QUARTERBACKS-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACKS ARE THE TALK OF THE NFL DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even if your NFL team yearns to draft a linebacker, a
cornerback or a wide receiver though your club may need a safety or
a tenacious tackle, its selectors cannot help but notice that one
position keeps surfacing this year like a life
preserver: &UR;  &LR; quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tempting lot. There are more high-quality quarterbacks
to choose from than in any recent NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   So many, in fact, that when the draft kicks off Saturday at the
Theater in Madison Square Garden, expect a record number of
quarterbacks to be taken in the first two rounds. There have never
been more than six selected in the first two rounds (in 1983, six
went in the first round and none in the second); this year there is
a solid chance that at least seven will be selected in rounds 1 and
2.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that the record of six quarterbacks selected
in the first round will be matched. And consider this: Quarterbacks
could be chosen with the first three picks, which has happened only
once, in 1971. Ponder the possibility that four of the top six
selections could be quarterbacks and that as many as 14 to 18 could
be drafted overall, compared with eight last year.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks color the personalities of their teams. And
quarterbacks color the personality of the 64th NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This draft is rich in quarterbacks, and the question is, What
is the quality of the wealth?'' said Carmen Policy, president of
the expansion Cleveland Browns, who own the No. 1 pick. ``Four of
the top six picks possibly being quarterbacks says a lot; that is
quite a number. But are they superstars, or busts? The hardest
position to project is the quarterback position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will sit down early next week and discuss all of the
information we have compiled and begin to make decisions. Our
people have worked around the clock. They are just worn out. But
they're supposed to be. It's draft time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go the running back route and draft Ricky Williams.
We could make a trade, drop down and take a chance on one of
several quarterbacks. But the consensus is the top two quarterbacks
are Akili Smith and Tim Couch, and the proper order is up for
grabs. We are looking to fall in love. We've got our banking
account in order. We've got a fresh haircut. Our suit is on. We're
hoping to be smitten by one of these guys. And we want true love _
not a tawdry affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy wants a quarterback, a franchise quarterback, because the
previous 79 NFL seasons have showed that championships and Super
Bowls are not won without one.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few seasons ago, however, NFL teams were howling over the
dearth of good college quarterbacks. What changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``The college game has changed,'' said Ozzie Newsome, the
Baltimore Ravens' vice president for player personnel. ``College
football has gone to four and five wideouts. There is more of a
passing emphasis. It used to be that you could run, run, run on
offense and play defense and win a national championship. Now teams
like Florida State and coaches like Steve Spurrier have implemented
pro-style passing offenses, and others have followed suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich McKay, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' general manger, is
co-chairman of the league's competition committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was brought to us four years ago,'' he said. ``Teams asked
what could we do about developing quarterbacks in college? We
looked at the history of it and decided that half the teams every
year in the NFL lose. And quarterbacks get the blame. It is the
nature of the game and the position. But this is a very unusual
draft. People should enjoy this as far as the quarterbacks are
concerned because the way it might fall, well, it hasn't ever
happened before. And it may never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Couch are joined by Donovan McNabb and Daunte
Culpepper as the projected quarterback elite. They will be the
first four selected. But what about the others?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some quarterbacks who can jump in and play, and
there are some who show some tools and need developing,'' said
Michael Huyghue, the Jacksonville Jaguars' senior vice president in
charge of football operations. ``There are some quarterbacks who
show natural intelligence, and others who exhibit football
intelligence. Those traits appeal to different people in different
ways.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Huyghue says to look for where Cade McNown of UCLA, Ted White of
Howard and Michael Bishop of Kansas State fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``McNown has been seen in a good offense,'' Huyghue said. ``He
played in an offense that put points on the board. He is athletic
and moves well. With White, the knock is he is from a small school,
but he is big, has the arm strength and is developing. A team is
going to take a chance on him and maybe find it was worth it.
Bishop is intriguing because he won. Give me a quarterback that won
games. That is one of the strongest selling points of the
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Green, the Minnesota Vikings' head coach, said that he
would continue to build his teams through the draft and that though
his team was quarterback rich, he would not rule out drafting
another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony Wright from South Carolina _ his team wasn't very
good, but this guy might be,'' Green said. ``Brian Kuklick from
Wake Forest threw for a lot of yards. Joe Germaine out of Ohio
State is worth looking at; he is good enough to be a No. 3
quarterback and maybe can work his way higher. Shaun King at Tulane
won a lot of games. You can zero in on these guys and if you make
the right pick, you set your team on a steady stream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
