<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY INMATES ARE SHACKLED IN CHILDBIRTH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - PREGNANT-INMATES-775&AMP;ADD-NYT   By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nine years ago, after reports that pregnant inmates
were being kept in shackles during labor and delivery, a federal
court ordered the New York City Department of Correction to stop
the practice. It also prohibited the routine shackling of inmates
after they had given birth, requiring the department to consult a
physician before using restraints.
</P>
<P>
   But now, prisoners and their advocates say, female inmates who
are taken to Elmhurst Hospital Center in Queens are again being
shackled routinely after giving birth, and, in some cases, during
delivery, in violation of the court decree.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International reported last month that in the first half
of 1998, six female inmates from Rikers Island had been shackled
while waiting to give birth, some of them during delivery. The
Prisoners' Rights Project of the Legal Aid Society, upon reviewing
recent Department of Correction records, which indicate a sharp
rise in the number of inmates shackled after delivery, has asked
the department to re-evaluate its restraint policy.
</P>
<P>
   Dori A. Lewis, a lawyer with the Prisoners' Rights Project,
which brought the suit that led to the court decree, said she hoped
that the city would respond to advocates' concerns. ``If not,'' she
said, ``various options are open to us, one of which is seeking
court intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   While a spokesman for the department, Thomas Antenen, defended
the use of restraints in hospital recovery rooms as a
``common-sense security practice,'' he emphatically denied that any
women had been restrained at Elmhurst during labor or delivery, and
called the Amnesty report ``inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't do it,'' he said. ``Once they go into the labor
room or the delivery room, any restraints they may have on them
would be removed, and that is policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But advocates say accounts by current and former inmates suggest
otherwise. In one example, Sabrina Jefferson, 28, of Mount Vernon,
N.Y., who served six months at Rikers for violating probation last
year, said she was left alone in a labor room at Elmhurst on April
26, 1998, with her left leg shackled to the bed and her hands
cuffed together. When her baby arrived, she said, she was unable to
reach the call button to summon a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 3:41 a.m. when the baby came out,'' she said. ``When
the nurses and the doctor came into the room it was 3:45 a.m.
Nobody was there when I had the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Another former inmate, Tanya L. Watson, 31, of Brooklyn, said
that when she gave birth to her son at Elmhurst in April 1996, just
27 days after her arrest on a charge of selling drugs, her leg and
wrist were shackled to the hospital bed throughout childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital and the Department of Correction would not discuss
either woman's case, saying patients' medical histories are
private.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for inmates and human rights groups say the
accounts are troubling. ``It still happens,'' said the Rev. Annie
Bovian, executive director of Women's Advocate Ministry Inc., a
nonprofit group in Harlem, who interviewed inmates for the Amnesty
report.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians say shackling presents serious health risks to
new mothers, including an increased likelihood of blood clotting,
which could lead to a pulmonary embolism, blocking lung function.
Robert L. Cohen, who was director of Rikers Island health services
from 1982 to 1986, said restraints should be used only if there are
no alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to care for prisoners in a hospital setting,
you maintain a secure area where there's no need for shackling,''
said Cohen, who is a member of the National Commission on
Correctional Health Care, a standard-setting group.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Elmhurst Hospital, unlike Bellevue Hospital Center in
Manhattan or Kings County Hospital Center in Brooklyn, where male
inmates from Rikers receive medical care, has no secure ward for
jail inmates receiving regular medical care, although there is a
secure psychiatric ward for inmates. Antenen said most female
inmates from Rikers receive their care at Elmhurst, but there are
not enough of them to warrant a separate ward. One or two guards
accompany each pregnant inmate to the hospital and remain posted
outside the door when the inmate enters the labor or delivery room,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse who works in the Elmhurst delivery room and who spoke on
condition of anonymity said Rikers inmates were always placed in
restraints in the recovery room, which is in the public part of the
hospital. She said she had simply assumed that the practice was
Department of Correction policy. ``They follow their procedure and
we follow ours,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Legal Aid Society said jail records kept by correctional
officers from Nov. 1 to March 1 indicate that two pregnant women
were shackled at Elmhurst during labor in December, and at least 20
inmates were restrained after they gave birth.
</P>
<P>
   Antenen said the jail records did not necessarily mean that the
inmates were shackled during labor. ``They might have been
restrained because they went right into the delivery room,'' he
said, explaining that pregnant inmates are transported to the
hospital in shackles. But he added, ``They were not restrained
while giving birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's director of external affairs, Dario L.
Centorcelli, said about 100 Rikers inmates are admitted each year
for delivery and are usually escorted by one or two guards. He said
that as far as he knew, no inmates were shackled during labor and
delivery. But he added, ``Afterwards, they are treated as a normal
prisoner, and it's up to Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors prefer the patients not to be in handcuffs, but these
are prisoners, and Corrections has their guidelines to protect
against escape, and we have to bend with them,'' Centorcelli said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lewis said the use of restraints after birth was so
routine that it seemed as if medical and security concerns were not
being weighed properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been input from the doctor as to whether a woman
who had a Caesarean or an episiotomy should be shackled'' while in
recovery, she said. ``Some of the women were in on a misdemeanor,
and putting those factors together, we would question the
appropriateness of those women being shackled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis helped monitor jail records for several years after
the decree. She said she had found that no inmates were shackled
during labor or delivery and very few were restrained after
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been happening very consistently in the last several
months,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
