<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FIGHTING-11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BORDER AREA FIGHTING ESCALATES, ENDANGERS KOSOVO REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania One of the world's nastiest border zones became
even more dangerous Saturday when Serb forces and ethnic Albanian
guerrillas escalated fighting and created new perils for the Kosovo
Albanian refugees trying to flee to safe haven here in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been machine gun fire, rifles, sniper fire,
artillery, mortars, even heavy artillery at some stages,'' said
Andrea Angeli, spokeswoman here for the 55-nation Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE monitors, expelled from Yugoslavia before the latest
ethnic cleansing campaign against Kosovar Albanians, now are posted
at border positions. The monitor team confirmed the continuation of
hostilities that began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not far from refugee crossings,'' Angeli said, placing
the skirmishes at about 12 miles north of a border post used by
ethnic Albanians escaping what the refugees describe as threats and
harassment from Serbian Yugoslav police and militia.
</P>
<P>
   The border area fighting carries the danger of broadening the
Balkan conflict, should Albania itself come under heavy attack.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Information Minister Musa Ulqini said at least two and
as many as six mortar shells originating in Yugoslavia landed on
Albanian soil Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting today continued to be very harsh,'' Ulqini said at a
briefing Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He said that on Saturday the Albanian government removed 10,000
refugees from the more than 100,000 refugees who have been located
in the region's biggest camp at the the northeastern Albanian
border town of Kukes. The effort to relocate the Kosovar exiles has
become more urgent since the build-up of troops on both sides of
the border began this week.
</P>
<P>
   The major fighting between Serb troops and guerrillas of the
Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) is about 30 miles from the primary
border crossing used by refugees heading to Kukes. But Angeli said
the exiles have been making their way into Albania at a number of
border locations.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the OSCE reported that four KLA fighters were
killed and two wounded. Angeli had no reports of casualties
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Western intelligence sources in the region said Saturday that
KLA elements, after remaining for weeks in mountain redoubts in
northern Albania, crossed back to their home country to renew
fighting against the Serb-dominated Yugoslav government after it
closed the border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas may have resumed combat in an effort to protect
Kosovar refugees blocked from crossing out of Kosovo into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Until refugees were trapped inside Yugoslavia, the KLA had kept
a low profile. The main border crossings into both Albania and
Macedonia were closed Wednesday, although a few hundred were
permitted to leave Yugoslavia in the early morning hours Saturday.
Afterward, the border apparently was closed again.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA and the Serb-led Yugoslav government were principals to
the Yugoslav peace talks brokered by the United States in February.
The guerrilla leaders reluctantly agreed to accept a package that
would give the Kosovo province of Yugoslavia the status of
autonomy, but not independence.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA also would have laid down arms under the agreement, and
an international peace force would have been stationed in Kosovo to
protect the population both ethnic Albanians and ethnic Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serb-led government would not agree to the plan,
resulting in the ethnic cleansing campaign that apparently started
just before NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA may retreat back across the border again to hideouts in
Albania if NATO steps up its military campaign against the Yugoslav
government, as has been promised once the weather clears and more
NATO air power arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
