<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AROUND-ALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRIBUTE, SOLDINI ATTEMPTS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would seem that victory in a single-handed yacht race around
the world would merit a nap in an Alpine meadow, or a walk in the
park at least. But for Giovanni Soldini, the Italian likely to win
the Around Alone sailing competition, another sea adventure is on
the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   When the global race is over, probably in early May, Soldini
will be off to New York City. He plans to bring FILA, the 60-foot
sailboat he built for the Around Alone, to the docks at Chelsea
Pier. And as soon as the weather turns blustery, he and a small
crew will set sail in an attempt to beat the nine-day
trans-Atlantic record from New York to England.
</P>
<P>
   The voyage brings with it a measure of unfinished business for
Soldini, who failed in a similar attempt two years ago. At that
time, a fierce storm undermined his effort less than 400 miles from
the finish. But more to the point, his closest friend, Andreas
Romanelli, was washed overboard and vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I try that record,'' Soldini said in a telephone
interview last week, ``I lost one of my best friends to the ocean
in an accident. So now, we want to try again. This racing is a very
big walk in your life. But I think the sea and sailing teach you
how to live _ not to be too nervous and to understand what's
important in life.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Soldini was one of nine solo sailors setting off
Saturday from Punta del Este, Uruguay, the third and last stopover
in the 27,000-mile Around Alone competition. With 5,751 miles to go
to Charleston, S.C., the race starting point last September,
Soldini has a commanding lead in the round-the-world event. He is
12 days ahead of Marc Thiercelin of France, the next closest
competitor in the Class I division, for 60-foot sailboats. And he
is 10 days ahead of Jean-Pierre Mouligne of France, the top racer
in Class II, for 50-foot boats.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-won victories are within the grasp of both Soldini, in
Class I, and Mouligne, in Class II. ``It's almost too good to be
true to be this far ahead of the others,'' Mouligne said last week
of the seven-day lead his boat, Cray Valley, has in Class II.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not really relaxed about it. The only way I could lose
is with a catastrophic failure on the boat, so I am checking its
rig carefully. My first goal is to win the race overall, but I
would like to win the last leg, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mouligne is being dogged by two Class II competitors, Brad Van
Liew of Los Angeles, the only American left in the race, and Mike
Garside of England. Both men are hungry to beat Mouligne in at
least one stretch of the competition, a prize that has eluded them
in the first three stages.
</P>
<P>
   The race has been a long ordeal for all the competitors. Sixteen
solo sailors began the competition, but calamity rode shotgun on
several of the hulls. Mike Golding, of England, as well prepared as
anyone, struck a sandbar outside New Zealand at the end of the
second leg and lost the use of his boat.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to Cape Horn at the tip of South America during leg
three, Josh Hall and Thiercelin, two leading skippers in the
60-foot class, lost their boats' rigs and with the spars, almost
any chance of winning. In another leg-three mishap infused with
drama and heroics, Isabelle Autissier was rescued after capsizing
2,000 miles from nowhere in the South Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout from that episode eventually took on its own tale of
strife. Soldini, who temporarily dropped out of the race to save
Autissier, became an international hero. But Thiercelin, who had
been slow to respond, was criticized for his lack of dependability.
</P>
<P>
   Thiercelin had been having mast problems on his 60-foot boat,
somewhere, when Autissier's mayday was reported. But race officials
concluded that such personal problems did not warrant disregarding
a life-and-death situation involving a fellow competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Soldini said last week that the episode clarified solo sailors'
overall responsibilities to one another. ``When you are alone in
the Southern Ocean,'' he said, ``it is very easy to make a bad
decision. But it is important to recognize the need to make right
value judgments all the time. The next time this kind of thing
comes up, nobody will have to think twice about whether to go or
not to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
