<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUY WHO HASN'T WON A MAJOR AMONG THE GIANTS WHO HAVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Scott McCarron quit golf after graduating from
UCLA in 1988 and went into business with his father. At that time,
McCarron knew he was not good enough to play on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, McCarron has a chance to win the Masters,
starting Sunday's third round at 7 under par, one stroke behind the
leader, Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I'm surprised a little bit by where I am,''
McCarron said. ``But once I turned pro, I had very high goals for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron recommitted himself to golf in 1992, and he has not
regretted the decision. Despite the imposing names that were on the
leader board, like Greg Norman, Lee Janzen, Nick Price, Davis Love
III and Bernhard Langer, McCarron said he would not be intimidated
playing in Sunday's twosome with Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, Nick Price was sitting there, the guy who never
won a major,'' McCarron said. ``At one time, Greg Norman was the
guy who never won a major. Just because you haven't won a major
doesn't mean you're not going to win one. It just depends on how
you handle yourself down the stretch, and handling yourself at the
Masters down the stretch is going to be very difficult. That, I'm
looking forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and Rivals: Price and Norman
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price and Greg Norman are good friends, but that
relationship will be put on hold this weekend as both try to win
the Masters, one of the major championships that has eluded them
both.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Norman wants to win the Masters more badly, Price said:
``I don't know, I'm not inside Greg's head, so I can't tell. I
can't speak for him. I know how much I want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said that if he and Norman were paired together Sunday, so
be it. ``We've been there before,'' Price said. ``He who plays best
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tougher, the Better
</P>
<P>
   When today's best players are mentioned, Lee Janzen's name does
not always come up, but he was in position to win his third major,
starting Sunday at 5 under par, only three strokes off the lead.
With two U.S. Open championships, Janzen has won more majors than
Tiger Woods, David Duval, Phil Mickelson or Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think I'm underrated sometimes?'' asked Janzen, repeating
a question. ``Yeah, sometimes. Why? I don't know. Maybe because
I've never had the one breakthrough year, like David Duval, or
Tiger Woods, or some other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, 34, has proven his ability to win on difficult golf
courses, and he believes that a tougher Augusta National Golf Club
this year has improved his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard there was going to be a little rough, I was
excited,'' Janzen said. ``The difference this year is I haven't
tried to hit any heroic shots, which a lot of times got me in
trouble. I'm more relaxed. I'm not as gung-ho to hit the ball right
next to the hole every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Putter Fails O'Meara
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, the defending Masters champion, was almost out of
contention after two rounds at 2 over par, 10 strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the speed of the greens all day,'' O'Meara said
after his 76 on Friday. ``The key is you have to putt well here,
and I didn't. I just didn't feel comfortable. I never really put a
good stroke on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience About the Process
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, who entered the third round at 1 under par,
thought he would have to work on his patience. ``I'm thinking about
the end result, instead of going through the process,'' Mickelson
said. ``I need to think about the process instead of the final
number. If I ultimately want to win, that's what I have to do. The
challenge is to relax and let the shot be created, instead of being
forced.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Climb Ahead
</P>
<P>
   Bob Estes was still within striking distance at 1 under par
after two rounds, but he admitted that it could be intimidating to
look at a leader board filled with major winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have the resume that the rest of the guys
have,'' Estes said. ``I would feel a lot better if I were 8 or 10
ahead of them. Thirty-six is a lot of holes, and on this course,
you can go in either direction. But it is a lot easier to go in the
wrong direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
