<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DAILY-NEWS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL SETBACKS BRING SENSE OF DISTRUST AT THE DAILY NEWS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Helen Kennedy, The Daily News' reporter in the
Balkans, is heading home. On-the-spot coverage of the war and
refugee crisis in Kosovo is more than her newspaper can afford
right now; its newsroom budget has just been trimmed by 5 percent.
She is returning to a newsroom where no raises will be given this
year and where reporters must get approval before taking a source
to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News, the in-your-face tabloid that in the early 1990s
survived union confrontation, revolving-door ownership and
bankruptcy, has been knocked back on its heels by a series of
financial reversals.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the newspaper was ready to print a snazzy new color
edition, balky pressroom equipment scuttled the attempt. The
newspaper's owners, Fred Drasner and Mortimer B. Zuckerman, have
had to pay more than $2 million for replacement parts and overtime
by its pressmen in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Just when The News had amicably reached terms with its eight
craft unions, a labor arbitrator a month ago gave a ninth union,
representing the drivers, a far more expensive settlement. Since
the craft unions are entitled to the same raises, the paper faces
unexpected costs of $18.5 million in 1999 alone, News executives
say, and millions more in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the paper was unveiling its expanded Sunday edition,
in which it is investing about $2 million, the new Sunday staff
finds itself coexisting with colleagues who are on a severely
restricted financial diet.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not a reprise of the paper's near-death experience
less than a decade ago. But the financial pinch is making the
paper's owners testy, its journalists angry and its union leaders
nervous. ``If you're asking, is the timing exquisite,'' Drasner
said dryly, ``the answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Drasner and Zuckerman said they will ask for help from all
the newspaper's constituencies _ from employees to advertisers to
suppliers. But such assurances do not resonate in a newsroom
already bruised by cutbacks, low raises and the departure in the
last 18 months of ``enough colleagues to make up a baseball team,''
as one reporter put it.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's editor, Debby Krenek, said the problems are
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the key is to be very judicious about what you spend your
money on,'' she said. ``You can do that. It's not fun. But it's
just managing things a little tighter. And if you do that, you
don't have to make the major cuts none of us want to make.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no layoffs, she said, and no cuts in the space
that the paper devotes to news.
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of explanations can dispel the suspicion and
resentment the latest cutbacks bring. For nine months, the monthly
budgetary bulletins from The Daily News have seemed an exercise in
division. Spend. Cut. Spend. Cut. Look, we are really investing in
the Sunday paper. Look, this labor arbitration award is going to
cost a lot _ we will have to make some real cuts.
</P>
<P>
   And while all newsrooms are riled about something at any given
time, ``riled'' is too mild to describe the feelings at The Daily
News, the country's sixth-largest newspaper, where anger and
financial unease have made the place seasick.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the nausea has been provoked by unforeseen reversals _
or, from a less forgiving perspective, failed gambits.
</P>
<P>
   The paper might have gotten more relief from the pressroom labor
and equipment bills if it had not lost a lawsuit against Goss
Graphic Systems, which supplied the $62 million press. It might
have faced lower labor costs if it could have reached accommodation
with the drivers' union two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is appealing the March award to the Newspaper and Mail
Deliverers' Union of New York, which represents 418 drivers who
ferry 723,000 copies of the paper across the five boroughs and into
the suburbs every day.
</P>
<P>
   These unexpected bills come on top of significant investments
the owners have made in the paper over the years. A new Unisys
newsroom computer system is costing at least $4 million, and
hundreds of thousands of dollars are supporting two extra reporters
and seven extra pages a week devoted to Brooklyn and Queens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's most heralded investment _ an expanded Sunday
section, for which the newspaper hired a marquee editor, Edward
Kosner, and planned to spend close to $2 million _ was upstaged by
the most stinging reversal, the labor arbitration agreement. The
Sunday expansion added about six people to a newsroom staff of
about 370. Zuckerman said he has increased the newsroom budget by
50 percent since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   All the upheaval has left the newsroom bruised. And what makes
the chronic discontent far worse, some on the staff say, is their
belief that the pain is not being shared equally. For all the
demoralizing cuts in the rest of the newsroom, Kosner's Sunday
budget appears untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best reporting we have on the story of the year is being
yanked,'' said one senior newsroom executive of the Balkan
coverage. This person, like all but two of the newsroom employees
interviewed extensively, spoke on condition of anonymity. The
cutbacks ``send an extremely unfortunate psychological message,''
the executive added. ``It suggests that we don't have the money to
gather the news in the traditional way. Internally, the
juxtaposition of this and the Sunday launch is sending people into
orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who resent the Sunday staff's special status
readily concede that the new section, with its expanded opinion
pages and pull-out feature sections, is clean, well-packaged
journalism that may pull in more readers. And an emphasis on the
Sunday paper would appear to make economic sense, since Zuckerman
says it brings in about one-third of the newspaper's advertising
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But when reporters and editors learned that the Sunday staff had
held a congratulatory dinner for 24 people _ employees and some
others _ at the pricey restaurant Cite on Wednesday, they were
quick to calculate how many days of Kosovo coverage that money
would have bought.
</P>
<P>
   Kosner, who said he had paid for the dinner himself, said that
the Sunday staff was already ``very lean.'' He added, ``I haven't
been approached about cuts, and I'm not making them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In December 1995, after the demise of a rival, New York Newsday,
The News' Sunday circulation reached about 1 million. By last
September, it was 815,000. The clear culprit in the decline was the
Sunday edition of The New York Post, the tabloid owned by Rupert
Murdoch. Its original price was 25 cents _ much less than The Daily
News, which responded by cutting its Sunday price to $1 from $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   But the readers still drifted away. At a time when all three
city dailies _ The Post, The News and The New York Times _ were
losing circulation, The News suddenly started hemorrhaging Sunday
readers. More than 20 percent of the circulation disappeared in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The decline coincided with the period of rapid-fire newsroom
turnover, as Martin Dunn, the editor, left in 1996, to be replaced
by Pete Hamill, whom Zuckerman ousted nine months later. Zuckerman
then selected Ms. Krenek as editor, but after a little more than a
year, he diluted her authority by naming Kosner to run the Sunday
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never viewed the world of journalism as static,''
Zuckerman said in an interview. ``It's always ongoing. I never have
been satisfied and will never be satisfied with any work in
progress. We've worked to improve it year after year after year. I
haven't taken money out of these entities. I've put money into
them. The editorial product is more important than anything. More
of the money has been invested in the editorial side of my products
than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the month since the bad news on the labor front, no one in
management has publicly uttered the words ``bankruptcy'' or
``sale.'' ``Those are the least agreeable options,'' Drasner said
in a telephone interview last week. If The News had the corporate
equivalent of galloping pneumonia with its strike, sale, bankruptcy
and resurrection in 1990 and 1991, the current situation is ``a bad
cold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the two owners of this privately held company have little
inclination to open their books. Zuckerman says that the paper's
advertising revenues have risen every year. Drasner says that ``The
Daily News was profitable from the time we acquired it until we
began experiencing significant production problems resulting from
breaking in the new plant'' in late 1997 and early 1998. ``These
problems negatively affected distribution and circulation,'' he
added, in a reference to the balky printing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Drasner added, ``The recent arbitration decision will have a
substantial adverse affect on our profitability going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a public balance sheet, it is impossible to know how
badly the labor arbitration ruling could hurt the business. People
are treading cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the eight labor unions that make up the Alliance of
Printing Trades, whose battles with previous owners were visceral
and violent, say almost nothing about the current situation, on the
record or off. Those eight unions already have negotiated wage
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But as they were negotiating, all were aware that the one
maverick union, the drivers union, had reached an impasse with
Zuckerman and Drasner, and that the parties had entered binding
arbitration in April 1997. The craft unions' agreements stipulated
that whatever the drivers got, the craft union members would get as
well. Those ``me too'' clauses added millions of dollars to the
total labor bill when the arbitrator's award was announced.
</P>
<P>
   A tenth union, the Newspaper Guild, has no part of any of those
agreements, and the journalists in it are less hesitant to
criticize management. ``I think that the owners of this paper have
given short shrift to the people who produce it day in and day
out,'' said Tom Robbins, a reporter who covers labor. ``I think
that Mort and Fred take a lot for granted in this newsroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters have asked one another if savings could not be
achieved by cutting back on contracts with suppliers, particularly
since some of them are companies in which Zuckerman and Drasner
hold an interest.
</P>
<P>
   One of these, Applied Graphics Technologies Inc., helps prepare
advertisements for publication for clients like General Motors,
Walt Disney Co., The New York Times _ and The Daily News. For
several years, Applied Graphics personnel have created ads for the
newspaper and helped digitize its photo library, services that cost
$6 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Such dealings between companies with common ownership are legal,
providing that all the services are provided at market rates.
``Whatever we do, we do on a market-based basis,'' Zuckerman said.
``One of the things you learn in business is you don't subsidize
one company with another.''
</P>
<P>
   If newsroom employees are concerned about such matters, Drasner
said, they would be better advised to worry about their own work.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on the paper's journalism is not immediately evident.
The newspaper that offered a ground-breaking series on the spread
of asthma among inner-city children a year ago is also breaking
ground on aspects of the Amadou Diallo shooting. The Washington
columnist, Lars-Erik Nelson, is probing to find the appeal of
potential presidential candidates like John McCain. And reporter
Helen Kennedy, through this weekend, was putting a face on the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But that kind of coverage is less affordable than it used to be.
And, as Ms. Krenek observed: ``When we covered the war in Bosnia we
didn't cover the war the entire time. And for the amount of time we
did cover it, we ran up a bill of $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not giving up on the commitment to cover'' the Kosovo
crisis, Ms. Krenek said, ``but we're trying to be judicious about
it. Helen went over on a relief flight. She's coming back on a
reasonably priced commercial flight. If the United States sends in
ground troops, we'll send somebody back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
