<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SECURITYBREACH1     04-10 1624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECURITYBREACH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security breach penalty stuns Air Force
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ U.S. Air Force officials were embarrassed by how
easily a Chinese computer programmer penetrated a critical weapons
database. Now they are shocked by how little prison time he faces.
</P>
<P>
   The database, managed from Wright-Patterson Air Force Base,
advises commanders on the combat readiness of weapons systems, such
as F-16 fighters and B-2 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Zhangyi ``Steven'' Liu's hacking of the $148 million Reliability
and Maintainability Information System set off alarms at the
highest levels of the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   Liu, 26, born in Shanghai and hired by a subcontractor, gained
access to passwords that gave him the power to create, change or
delete any file in the system.
</P>
<P>
   One top Air Force official described it as the most serious
security failure in decades, according to recently disclosed
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials were shocked by two things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Liu did it easily, since the weapons maintenance computer
system had virtually no security checks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Liu could not be charged with a felony. He faces at most one
year in prison if convicted of gaining illegal access to an Air
Force computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the most serious nonviolent crime committed
within the past 20 to 30 years, and there are no laws that cover
this type of crime,'' said Rick DeNezza, the Material Systems Group
executive director, according to U.S. District Court records in
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Liu, who faces trial May 17, plan to argue that
the Air Force is responsible for the security breach. The Air
Force, they say, allowed nearly a dozen programmers from China to
service the system without ever telling them what they couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   The trial may carry major risks for Liu as well.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's jury will be selected amid national focus on suspicions
that China stole nuclear weapons designs through espionage at the
Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American computer scientist at the New
Mexico lab, is the focus of that investigation. He was fired March
8 for violating security regulations, but has not been charged with
a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department said Tuesday it had suspended all
scientific work on sensitive computer networks computers at Las
Alamos, Sandia and Lawrence-Livermore national nuclear weapons
laboratories over fears that security lapses made the computers
vulnerable to espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's case appeared to be resolved in March 1997, when he
pleaded guilty to two misdemeanor counts of gaining illegal access
to REMIS.
</P>
<P>
   Col. William J. Colmer, who manages more than 170 information
systems for the Air Force, testified at a sentencing hearing that
Liu's penetration of REMIS led to a review of thousands of other
Air Force information systems across the world ``to search for
similar vulnerabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the real fear'' of Liu's intrusion ``was not that Liu had
discovered something helpful to a foreign government,'' said one
federal official who asked not to be identified. ``The fear is that
he was in a position to put bugs in the program and cause the
program to go down at a critical time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens,'' this source asked, ``if you can't fly planes
because nobody can tell the status of the planes?''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Michael R. Merz sentenced Liu in May 1998
to 6 months in jail and fined him $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Merz recently permitted Liu to withdraw his plea, concluding
he had not fully cautioned Liu of all of its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief seeking a new trial, Liu's federal public defender,
Randolph W. Alden, noted that on the eve of Liu's plea, the Air
Force Office of Special Investigations issued its report of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That report, Alden stated, ``showed that levels of access (on
REMIS) had not been established, therefore, it was impossible for
Liu to have exceeded his authorized access.''
</P>
<P>
   High grades, low pay
</P>
<P>
   Liu, born in Shanghai, the People's Republic of China, is the
only child of poor parents.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of several scholarships, Liu obtained a
bachelor's degree in electronic engineering in 1994 from Shanghai
Jiao Tong University, where he was rated an ``excellent student''
in the top 10 percent of excellent students at the university,
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   He landed his first job in 1995 at Shanghai Tandem Software
Systems, a subcontractor used by a Litton Industries Inc.
subsidiary, Litton PRC of McLean, Va., the prime contractor for the
REMIS system.
</P>
<P>
   Court records and other sources said Liu earned only a fraction
of what U.S. computer programmers would be paid _ $500 a month,
which he sent to his parents. He also received about $35 per diem.
The company also paid his rent (up to four at a single apartment),
utilities and medical insurance and provided an older car for
several employees to drive to work.
</P>
<P>
   Liu and 10 other Chinese foreign nationals were brought to
Dayton to debug and improve REMIS' developmental side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came with a dream to succeed in the land of opportunity,''
Liu told Merz.
</P>
<P>
   Then, twice in 1996, while seeking to review a performance
evaluation, Liu said he accidently discovered the ``super super''
passwords file for the system administrator. The file had the
passwords of more than 400 REMIS users.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the passwords, Liu gained access to REMIS'
operational side, which performs the day-to-day logistical
functions of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Liu said he felt ``like a kid who found a toy... I found
Pandora's Box.''
</P>
<P>
   He has told court officials that people of his nationality
should not have been allowed to work on the system; security was so
lax, he concluded ``it was not a concern here.''
</P>
<P>
   No shields
</P>
<P>
   Liu drew support from Dale E.S. Blommendahl, who designed
Safeguard, a software security program provided to the Air Force to
secure REMIS and encrypt the passwords.
</P>
<P>
   Blommendahl, who now employs Liu at his XYPRO Technology Corp.
of Simi Valley, Calif., said REMIS security was so lax that
``anybody could have put in anything at any time. It just wasn't
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the lack of audit logs would have led him to conduct an
audit of 2.5 million lines of computer code going back to the
beginning of the system. The first phase of REMIS became
operational in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Liu said he was ``allowed to walk in a room of secrets. They put
the tools in the room without ever telling me not to use them, and
just expecting that I wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   When Liu's intrusion was discovered during routine maintenance,
it set off ``quite an uproar'' at the highest levels of the Defense
Department, said one source close to the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show investigators feared the worst _ that Liu was
a cyberwarrior bent on espionage.
</P>
<P>
   These concerns weren't allayed after Liu and five of the other
Chinese programmers flunked lie-detector tests in which they were
asked if they had provided the passwords to anyone, downloaded the
password files to steal them for personal gain and used the
passwords files to gain access to other computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Such tests, however, are not admissible in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials declined comment on why they did
not prosecute other Chinese programmers who also admitted they
gained unauthorized access to REMIS, and allowed them to return to
China.
</P>
<P>
   And now that Liu has been allowed to withdraw his plea, their
testimony may no longer be available.
</P>
<P>
   `Scapegoat'
</P>
<P>
   Col. Colmer said it cost Litton and the Air Force $358,000 to
secure REMIS, including changing all passwords, installing
Safeguard and performing two painstaking reviews to determine what
Liu had done. He said those reviews determined that Liu had not
changed data or installed a ``Trojan Horse'' or back door through
which he could continue to enter the system.
</P>
<P>
   Blommendahl said the Air Force should foot the bill for securing
REMIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Liu had never set foot in Dayton, Ohio, all of the
code analysis and security upgrading would have needed to be done,
and would have been done at some point in time when the security
deficiencies in the REMIS system became apparent,'' Blommendahl
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven is a scapegoat for their own stupidity and laziness,''
said Dayton attorney Gary W. Gottschlich, who previously
represented Liu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just simply economic,'' Gottschlich said of foreign
nationals' access to such systems. ``There are many foreign
nationals from around the world working on such projects. They're
available and they're cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, Liu received a small severance. His only
assets were a Packard Bell computer valued at $1,500 and his
checking account, with a balance of $213.
</P>
<P>
   ``His employer, which has brought him to the U.S. from China,
abandoned him in Dayton with nothing more than a $700 severance
payment,'' said Dayton attorney Richard A. Maresca, who has also
represented Liu. ``He lost his car; he lost his apartment; he lost
his way home. His employer physically segregated him from his
co-workers, the only friends he had....
</P>
<P>
   ``He has lived for one year in confusion and terror over a law
enforcement and judicial system whose workings he cannot
comprehend.''
</P>
<P>
   What is REMIS
</P>
<P>
   _ REMIS contains, by tail number, the mission capability of all
Air Force aircraft. It also shows maintenance data such as parts
requirements and reveals what location each aircraft is assigned.
The data also include the communications, electronics and missiles
with which each aircraft is configured, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
