<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKS OF ART FOR CLEMENS ON THE MOUND AND FANS IN STANDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens will inspire the imagination of Yankee
Stadium's decorators like no other pitcher in club history. While
he made his debut as a Yankee here Saturday, a half-dozen amateur
artists tried to keep up with Clemens' strikeouts, in varying
fashions. Hanging from the grandstands, there were K's in script,
K's in medical tape and, in honor of Clemens' nickname, rockets
hung by one fan.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens struck out eight and allowed three hits in pitching
seven-and-two-thirds shutout innings in the Yankees' 5-0 victory
over Detroit. Clemens has not suffered a lost since May 29 of last
year; his 16 consecutive victories are one short of the American
League record, shared by Baltimore's Dave McNally (in 1968-69) and
Cleveland's Johnny Allen (1936-37). Carl Hubbell set the
major-league record of 24 for the New York Giants during the 1936
and 1937 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit hitters were 0-for-7 with runners in scoring
position against Clemens; the Yankees' starting pitchers' have held
opponents to just one hit in 18 at-bats with runners in scoring
position in 342/3 innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis and Scott Brosius each hit home runs for the second
consecutive afternoon, and the Yankees won their fourth consecutive
game with Don Zimmer, the interim manager, in charge. When Manager
Joe Torre, recovering from prostate cancer, visited with the
Yankees' general manager, Brian Cashman, before the game, Cashman
asked jokingly: ``What if Zimmer starts the season 20-1? We might
not want you back.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clemens stretched and warmed up, a handful of Tigers pitchers
watched from a distance. Clemens has his own routine, unique to him
_ for instance, Clemens will mimic the motion of fielding a
grounder and then firing to first base several times _ and if he
had not won a Cy Young Award or two along the way, his habits might
be seen as eccentric. But conventional wisdom is that Clemens does
everything for a reason, so others watch and learn.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lesson in how Clemens pitched to Tony Clark,
Detroit's towering first baseman. After throwing a curveball away
with his first pitch to Clark _ the big guy leaned over the plate
to get a closer look _ Clemens buzzed an inside fastball past
Clark, who flinched a bit. With Clark alerted to the real
possibility that he might step into a 94-mile-per-hour fastball,
Clemens subsequently pitched outside, and Clark waved weakly,
fouling off two fastballs and striking out on a splitter in the
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's next at-bat occurred in the fourth; the Tigers' hitters
had compiled a single hit and four strikeouts by then. Clemens
continued to pitch outside to Clark, who seemed to be waiting for
Clemens to throw something inside. Clemens threw two curves for
called strikes, then uncorked a split-fingered fastball that Clark
flailed at unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Guidry set the Yankees' single-season record for strikeouts,
with 248 in 1978, and in a sense, that mark is already in jeopardy:
Clemens has struck out more than that in each of the last three
years, and there aren't any signs of a let-up. He was completely
dominant against the Tigers. He allowed just a single hit in the
first four innings, and did not permit a walk until the seventh.
After going to a 3-ball, 1-strike count on Gregg Jefferies in the
first inning, Clemens did not reach his second three-ball count for
another 23 batters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He did not throw more than 13 pitches in any of the game's first
six innings, finally reaching 19 pitches in the seventh. He threw
strikes to get ahead in the count, prompting the Detroit hitters to
chase other pitches out of the strike zone. Detroit's best chance
for runs came in the seventh, when Damion Easley led off with a
double, and with two outs, Bobby Higginson drew a walk _ probably
because Clemens chose to pitch around him.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto pinch-hit for the shortstop Deivi Cruz, and
Clemens dispatched him with three pitches, the last a fastball over
the outside corner. Clemens pumped a fist, and the crowd of 42,058
cheered along with him. After Clemens was replaced in the eighth,
fans stood and roared, Clemens acknowledging with a tip of his cap
and a wave of his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Moehler, Detroit's starting pitcher, was arguably the most
effective pitcher against the Yankees last season, compiling a 3.10
earned run average with a 2-1 record _ not too many folks can say
they compiled a winning record against the Yankees in 1998 _ in his
unspectacular style, throwing strikes with an OK fastball, changing
locations. When asked about Moehler Saturday morning, Derek Jeter
said he could remember Moehler was a good pitcher with great
control, but he could not recall exactly what sort of pitches he
throws.
</P>
<P>
   But once the Yankees reacquainted themselves with the
right-hander, in their pregame examination of video and scouting
reports, they put together some runs. Davis hit his home run to the
opposite field in the second, Brosius smashed his in the fifth, and
Derek Jeter drove a two-run triple in the seventh before Moehler
was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, who pitched eight shutout innings Wednesday in a
start made in place of Hideki Irabu, will start again Tuesday,
according to Don Zimmer, the interim manager. Zimmer said he did
not know how long Mendoza will remain in the rotation, or how long
Irabu will remain in the bullpen, but he was sure Mendoza deserved
another start. ``This guy has done everything the Yankees have
asked him to do,'' said Zimmer, who will face a quandry if Mendoza
continues to pitch well: Zimmer believes the staff is better with
the versatile Mendoza in the bullpen. ... A day after being ejected
by the home plate umpire, Garu Cederstrom,the pitcher David Cone
visited with Cederstrom and apologized for yelling at him after
being relieved in the home opener, explaining that he simply
snapped after a long day of pitching in mushy conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
