<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SELLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHER JOHN SELLERS, BLUES AND JAZZ SINGER, DIES AT 74  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Miss., Ill.)   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brother John Sellers, a singer known for his raw and
earthy rendition of blues, jazz and gospel music, died on March 27
at his home in Manhattan. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, who suffered from diabetes and high blood pressure,
died in his sleep, said a spokeswoman for the Alvin Ailey American
Dance Theater, with which he was long associated.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers learned to perform by watching minstrel singers like
Robert Johnson and Blind Lemon Jefferson on the streets of
Clarksville, Miss., where he was born. By age 5, he was dancing,
singing and playing the tambourine in tent shows put on by the
Sanctified church, whose worshipers were known as Holy Rollers.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later he was discovered by the gospel singer Mahalia
Jackson, who took him away from the bordello where he lived after
being abandoned by his parents. He went to Chicago, where he lived
with Jackson and with relatives of his mother. He began to sing
with Jackson, who was becoming famous, and sometimes filled in for
her on concert dates. He also attached himself to the blues singer
Big Bill Broonzy, with whom he studied informally.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, Sellers made two well-received recordings for
Vanguard Records' new jazz line, working with musicians like Sonny
Terry, Johnny Johns and Jo Jones. In 1958, he went to Europe with
Broonzy to perform and record, and enjoyed a huge success. Not long
after, he became a regular at Folk City, a new nightclub in
Greenwich Village where singers like Joan Baez, Bob Dylan and Paul
Simon and Art Garfunkel got early exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers was singing at Folk City one night in 1961 when a young
choreographer named Alvin Ailey wandered in, drawn by the sound of
his voice. The artists were soon collaborating on Ailey's ``Blues
Suite'' and ``Revelations,'' whose scores were arranged by Sellers
and incorporated his music.
</P>
<P>
   His singing reminded Ailey of his childhood in rural Texas. ``A
mans blues _a solo man _ (maybe Ailey, maybe not),'' the
choreographer wrote in a poem called ``John Sellers Sings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellers' last performance with the Ailey company was in 1997. At
the time of his death he was in litigation with the dance company
over royalties and the copyright to ``Revelations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellers also performed on Broadway in Langston Hughes'
``Tambourines to Glory.'' During his years with the Ailey company,
he continued to sing in Europe and in the Far East and performed in
the late 1950s and 60s in lectures with Studs Terkel, a longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother John had a light tenor voice that was very strong,''
Terkel said, adding that ``the sinful and the secular'' could be
heard in his singing. ``He was no Mahalia, no Bill Broonzy, but
there was a clarity and a sense of urgency. When Brother John sang
`Wading in the Water,' for example, you got the feeling of the
young preacher inviting the people into the shallow waters, that
they had to do it because if they did, they'd be found, they'd be
saved. Brother John had this way of making things come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECOND-HOMES-REAL-880     04-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECOND-HOMES-REAL-880(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SECOND HOMES, NO VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Conn., N.J., Mass., R.I.)  (lb) 
 By MARY McALEER VIZARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ken Davis has been looking for a second home in
Vermont for several months now, but hasn't yet found what he wants
at the right price. ``I've put bids on a few properties,'' he said,
``but they weren't my dream houses, so I could afford to let them
go.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the nice weather coming, he is getting a little
anxious. ``My intention is to have a place in 30 to 60 days,'' he
said. ``I want to take advantage of the low interest rates now and
have the house to enjoy in the summer and fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers say that the problem for Davis and other
buyers is a pronounced lack of inventory in certain desirable
categories in almost all markets from as far north as Vermont and
the Adirondacks to as far south as the Jersey Shore and Bucks
County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of inventory in turn reflects several seasons of strong
markets in popular second-home areas. In the Town of Southampton on
Long Island, the dollar value of property sales last year was $1.4
billion, more than half again the figure for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut's Litchfield County, sales were up 20 percent in
1998 over the previous year. And brokers report that, whether in
the Berkshires, the Jersey Shore or the second-home market in the
northern reaches of Westchester County, demand is especially strong
at the highest end of the market, with regular sales of second
homes carrying price tags of over a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his wife, Margie, are prepared to spend $200,000 to
$225,000 for a four-bedroom house, with cathedral ceilings, a
winding driveway and spectacular views. ``My ultimate dream,''
Davis said, ``is to sit out on the deck with a cigar and a glass of
Grand Marnier, maybe barbecue, and watch the world go by.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time the couple thought about postponing their
second-home purchase in favor of buying a larger permanent home or
upgrading the four-bedroom bilevel they now have in Franklin Lakes,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we decided that we really want to get out of the daily
grind and have a place to go to decompress,'' said Davis, who works
as a manufacturer's sales representative. ``Instead of having my
money sitting in a bank or mutual fund, it's better to enjoy it,
and buying a second home helps diversify your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Thomas, a sales agent with ReMax Star Properties in
Manchester, Vt., has been working with the Davises and is clearly
frustrated. ``We're out of inventory in their price range,'' she
said. ``What we have people don't want, like the dated chalets with
avocado appliances and the harvest-gold shag carpeting.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of those available, Ms. Thomas said. She
now has one under contract, a three-bedroom, two-bath chalet, with
a deck and hot tub, that sold for $101,000. They can even go as low
as $59,000 for a small two-bedroom, one-bath A-frame. ``That's not
what most people want today,'' Ms. Thomas said. ``They're really
for the bargain hunters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Davises represent, in many ways, the typical buyers now
coming through her door, Ms. Thomas said. ``They're primarily young
families in their mid-30s,'' she said. ``They're more
sophisticated, less bargain hunters. They have a very specific idea
of what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that he was concentrating his search in and around
Manchester ``because I like that it's near skiing.'' (The closest
areas are Stratton and Bromley.) ``But there are also other
activities, like fishing, hiking and biking. I plan to use the
house year-round.''
</P>
<P>
   Manchester is, in many ways, a traditional New England
community, with an idyllic Colonial-era town center comprised of a
collection of white clapboard buildings. It is the kind of place
where, in the evening, soft amber lights glow from the windows of
historic inns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything slows down when you get up there,'' Davis said.
``You can really feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Manchester is also known for its outlet shopping centers,
which have been designed to fit in with the prevailing
architecture, and attract large crowds, especially on the weekends.
``I like the shopping and activity level,'' Davis said. ``I want a
country house, but I don't want to to be in the middle of
nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the people who walked into Ms. Thomas' office were
looking primarily for properties priced from $100,000 to $150,000.
Now, she said, it's $200,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers in many second-home markets say they find people are
ready to buy, and that money is not their first concern. Rather
it's finding what they want. In some areas, with higher-priced
housing stock, the high end of the market has really taken off, say
brokers, even for properties over $1 million. But those, too, are
in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a reflection of interest rates,'' said Nora
Preusser, who owns a real estate agency in Garrison, where the
market for second homes has moved up sharply in the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are realizing that the time to buy is now,'' Ms.
Preusser said. ``Trouble is, we often can't accommodate them
because we don't have the listings. In the 20 years I've been in
the business, I've never seen inventory this low. It's one-half
what it was a year ago. We have twice as many buyers as properties
available.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the lake communities in the Adirondacks, interest has spiked
in the last year and a half for ``large houses with waterfront
property,'' said Roger Friedman, a principal of Friedman Realty, in
Schroon Lake. ``But we don't have the product,'' Friedman said.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventory isn't low in all categories, only in the ones people
seem to want,'' Friedman said. ``People are interested in houses in
the low $200,000s to mid-$300,000s. The majority of our listings
are for cottages, selling for $170,000 to $190,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The lowest listing now is for a small three-bedroom shorefront
cabin for $119,000. ``There's very little over $200,000, that's the
problem,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman Realty's sales area encompasses five lakes, including
Schroon, Loon, Brant, Friend's and Paradox. His office recently
sold a four-bedroom contemporary with 250 feet of waterfront
property and 4.8 acres on Schroon Lake for $495,000, which is the
area's high end. ``It sold for the asking price,'' said Friedman,
``which is happening more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondacks attract a particular kind of buyer, said
Friedman's brother, Joel, a partner in the business. ``What
distinguishes us is the abundance of lakes we have and natural
beauty,'' he said. The residential properties are part of a state
park, with six million acres of mostly untouched wilderness, with
little development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's in its natural state here,'' said Joel Friedman.
``You have to like the outdoors. Buyers up here are more
conservative, not as tied in to the stock market and interest
rates. They're buying a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   David Smith and his wife, Mary, decided to buy a house on
Paradox Lake after visiting last summer. ``It was the Fourth of
July weekend, and there were maybe three boats on the water,''
Smith said. ``We thought, `Wow, we're less than four hours from
Manhattan and look at this,'''
</P>
<P>
   The couple bought a three-bedroom, ranch with a knotty pine
great room and an 8- by 42-foot screened-in porch, ``which is
important during black-fly season,'' said Smith, who owns an
insurance company in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to spend about $200,000 and realized that this
same house would be $450,000 on Lake George or Bolton's Landing,''
he said. ``Even if I could have afforded it I wouldn't have wanted
those areas because they are insanely busy in the summers and one
thing we definitely wanted was peace and quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   The commute to the Adirondacks can be off-putting to some, but
some actually find it restorative. ``When I turn off the Northway
and the trees come together over my car,'' said Emilio Locascio, a
Yonkers contractor who owns a house on Schroon Lake, ``I feel like
I'm entering the enchanted forest.''
</P>
<P>
   On most Fridays, the ride takes him about three hours and 40
minutes, he said. ``The 40 minutes you drive past Lake George is
the price you pay for privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five-lake region, only Schroon Lake has a downtown, a
main street with one supermarket, a convenience store and a few
other shops. ``For so long Schroon Lake was considered primarily a
summer resort,'' Roger Friedman said. ``But now people are
discovering it for winter recreation as well.'' Just this year, the
only movie theater in town installed its first heating system.
</P>
<P>
   Such rustic surroundings don't appeal to everyone, which is why
some buyers prefer to stay closer to New York City, where the
market for second homes has been booming. From the mid-'90s, the
second-home market in Columbia County has improved between 30
percent and 50 percent in the areas that are considered the most
popular, said Esther Anderson, who owns a real estate agency in
Kinderhook.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are primarily interested in the southern section of the
county,'' she said. ``There's also interest in the eastern section
bordering Massachusetts. Most people don't want to go north of
Kinderhook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventory is so low that people are now buying properties that
have languished on the market for years because they need work, or
they're on the main roads,'' she continued. ``Most people want
homes priced between $200,000 and $500,000. Bidding wars are common
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales in Litchfield County, Conn., were up 20 percent in 1998
over the previous year, according to Elyse Harney, who owns a real
estate agency in Salisbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best selling year in 10 years, since we came out of
the 1987 slump,'' Ms. Harney said. ``In 1997 things started to sell
and it hasn't slowed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Most houses go for $300,000 to $500,000, she said, although it's
possible to get something for less. One current listing is for a
converted schoolhouse in Norfolk, Conn., with three bedrooms, two
baths and cathedral ceilings on 3.4 acres. It is priced at
$195,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another area that has benefited from its proximity to New York
City is Westchester County, where the second-home market has picked
up in recent years, according to Ebie Wood, manager of the Pound
Ridge office of Houlihan/Lawrence. ``Some of our communities, such
as Pound Ridge and Bedford, even though they're only one hour from
Manhattan, are completely different environments,'' Ms. Wood said.
``It's an alternative from the Hamptons. We're getting people who
couldn't stand the commute.''
</P>
<P>
   People looking for a second home in Westchester want a unique
property with some acreage, Ms. Wood added, noting that the houses
tend to start at $650,000 and go into the millions. Second-home
buyers are ``not looking for a traditional colonial,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Garrison and Cold Spring, in Putnam County, ``60 percent or
more of my customers come from the city and use the houses here as
second homes,'' said Ms. Preusser, who owns a real estate agency in
Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is a third better than a year ago,'' she said. ``It's
hard to find anything below $350,000. We're also very low in the
$500,000 to $700,000 categories. Then it jumps to $1 million and
up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Berkshires, brokers are getting a lot of requests for
houses that sell for more than $3 million, said Charlotte Isaacs,
who owns a real estate agency in Stockbridge, Mass. ``Years ago we
used to sell one or two in the $1 million-plus category,'' she
said. ``In the past year we've sold a dozen.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The high end has also been booming in the ocean communities.
``It's wild here,'' said Cheryl Vetovick, manager of Diane Turton
Realtors, in Spring Lake, N.J. ``Most listings are staying on for
only a week or two,'' said Ms. Vetovick, who sells mostly in Spring
Lake, Sea Girt and Belmar. ``Bidding wars are common. A house
listed at $600,000 recently sold for $100,000 over the asking
price. I haven't seen a market like this in the nine years I've
managed the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Her office recently sold a house in Sea Girt for $3.9 million.
``That's the highest house price we've ever had and it sold in 10
days,'' Ms. Vetovick said.
</P>
<P>
   Million-dollar properties in Cape Cod have also started to move,
according to Larry Peters, co-owner of Cape Shores Real Estate in
Wellfleet, Mass. ``Everyone, it seems, wants to be near the
ocean,'' he said, ``but there's not a whole lot left.'' Peters
sells properties in Truro and Wellfleet. ``We're seeing
million-dollar all-cash deals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, New Yorkers have increasingly been opting for
houses in coastal Rhode Island. ``It's like we've been
discovered,'' said Raymond Mott, owner of Properties Unlimited in
Charlestown. ``We have people coming in pounding their chests with
money,'' Mott said. ``They want something by the water, and we have
nothing for them. It's a lot less active a mile away from the
water. The price range of $300,000 to $500,000 seems to be the most
comfortable zone for most people.''
</P>
<P>
   The east end of Long Island seems almost impervious to the
normal fluctuations of the market elsewhere. In the Town of
Southampton, for instance, property sales totaled $822 million in
1997, and rose to $1.4 billion in 1998. ``The market has gone up 1
to 1.5 percent per month during that time,'' said Tim Cunningham,
president of Cunningham Real Estate in Southampton. ``All price
ranges are active. The buyers are in their early 30s to mid-50s, at
the peak of their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, buyers are more particular about being on
streets with little or no traffic and they tend to use the houses
all year long, not just in summer. ``They're making a high
investment,'' Cunningham. ``I guess they feel compelled to use it
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales so far this year have also been healthy on Fire Island,
said Rose Ann Larson, who has an agency in Saltaire and also sells
in Kismet. ``In the last 12 years, sales were a little bit late, at
the end of the season,'' Ms. Larson said. ``Sales have already
started this year. All price categories are moving, from a low of
$225,000 to over $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bucks County, Pa., doesn't have the ocean, it does have
the Delaware River and canals, and is a 75-minute commute from
midtown Manhattan. ``It's been a wonderful market,'' said Troy
Baker, director of sales for Kurfiss Real Estate in New Hope, Pa.
``At the end of March, we did $60 million of business, which is
exactly the same as the first half of last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``weekender,'' Baker said, wants acreage and a
swimming pool. ``The high end here is $1 million. Anything at the
low end, or $200,000, hardly lasts a week,'' he said. ``For that
you'd get an attached duplex house or town house, not a
single-family home. Most people want a three-bedroom single-family
home with a couple of acres for $300,000.''
</P>
<P>
   People come to Bucks County for a rural feeling, the
recreational opportunities of the Delaware River and the canals,
Baker added. ``We get a lot of artists and writers,'' he said. ``We
have the Bucks County Playhouse. Sally Jessy Raphael just sold her
bed and breakfast, but still maintains a home here.'' Popular towns
include New Hope and Solebury.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers are now also looking into the northern part of the
county more than they used to,'' Baker said, ``places like Durham
and Riegelsville. Nine months out of the year we have mild weather.
It's a very short winter here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not for the winter-sports enthusiasts. But if you love
canals and recreating by a river, then this is your place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
