<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-MONTREAL-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 ALOU THINKS THE EXPOS WILL STAY IN MONTREAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Olympic Stadium sit-in lasted only one day.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Montreal Expos had their biggest crowd,
43,918, in nearly three years for their festive 1999 home opener _
a 5-1 victory over the Mets _ things were back to normal Friday
night. The announced crowd was 12,386.
</P>
<P>
   The big-budget Mets pounded the low-budget Expos, 10-3, behind
Mike Piazza's five runs batted in. The banners bashing the Montreal
team president Claude Brochu were at a minimum. It was as if the
town had slipped into a collective hangover, knowing that the
antiquated track-and-field stadium might have hosted its final home
opener.
</P>
<P>
   But the message from the night before was clear: there are
baseball fans in this French-speaking city, and they want the Expos
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be here,'' Montreal manager Felipe Alou
said Friday afternoon. ``And the players believe we're going to be
here. Until I and the players see a significant move announced,
this club will be here. But I don't believe it has anything to do
with attendance. I don't believe it has to do with managing, or
wins, or how many fans show up anymore. There's been too much water
under the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd last night was significant. It sent a good message
that if you do things right, there will be people here. But I don't
believe the fans will save this franchise. They've never been given
a chance before, so why now? It's up to everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Like financing a new downtown stadium, an official arbiter for
many franchises' survival these days. If the city can find the
financing within the next six weeks, there is a good chance that
the Expos, who have been here 31 years, will stay. If not, they are
likely headed for northern Virginia or Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, wherever the Expos call home next season, there is
a good chance that they will be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in the eight years that I've been
managing here that we didn't lose any significant players,'' said
Alou, who has had to endure yearly fire sales. ``And it looks like
we won't lose any next year. Now, the question is, are we going to
stay here or leave? Will there be a new stadium here or not? Will
there be more money invested here or not? Those are the players
now. It's a whole different game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the game is being played, as Alou was trying to get across,
not just on the field or in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the fans made a statement with their presence.
``I have the feeling that the people who came and the people who
couldn't come and wished they could have been here, they want the
club to stay here,'' Alou said. ``Otherwise we would have had
15,000 people or 10,000 people for our opening day.''
</P>
<P>
   And what the fans saw was a team with the pieces falling into
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this club is getting better,'' Alou said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 23-year-old right fielder Vladimir Guerrero, the Expos have a
top young player.
</P>
<P>
   Mets catcher Mike Piazza said of Guerrero, ``The ball makes a
different sound coming off his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero pounded a double and a home run in Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Complementing Guerrero in an improving lineup are left fielder
Rondell White; first baseman Brad Fullmer, who was seventh in the
National League in doubles last season with 44; and the rookie
catcher-third baseman Michael Barrett, the team's most highly
regarded prospect, who drilled a two-run homer Friday night on the
first pitch he had seen at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing holding the Expos back from contending this year,
Alou said, was the development of their young pitching staff. After
the opening-day starter, Dustin Hermanson, there are questions.
``But there are no questions about their arms,'' Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any question that in Ugueth Urbina, the Expos
possess one of the most dominant closers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   These Expos seem poised for a return to the success they enjoyed
earlier in the 90s. In 1994, the Expos had the best record in
baseball before the players went on strike; and in 1996, they were
eliminated from post-season contention on the next-to-last day of
the season. The stars of those teams _ Larry Walker, John
Wetteland, Ken Hill, Pedro Martinez, Marquis Grissom and Moises
Alou _ were basically sold off in waves. No one knows the fate of
this year's team yet.
</P>
<P>
   Alou said his team and the fans deserve better, but he also
knows they can only do so much to preserve Montreal's baseball
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if Guerrero wins the MVP,'' Alou said. ``That's
not keeping the team here. Pedro Martinez won the Cy Young. And if
we win the division or the wild card, that's not going to keep the
team here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't tell me you like baseball today and then you don't
like it next year. I don't believe it. It's just that hopes were so
high and then you don't see Wetteland, Hill and Walker. And there
were others I don't remember.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
