<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 SUSPECT IN SLAYING OF JERSEY POLICE OFFICER ARRESTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man has been arrested in connection with Thursday's
fatal shooting of an Orange, N.J., police officer, although no
charges have been filed against him yet, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County Prosecutor's
officer, said the man ``is a serious suspect,'' whom investigators
were still questioning Saturday. The man was arrested Friday night
after scores of police officers spent 24 hours scouring the streets
of Orange, a 2.2-square-mile city of 29,000 residents northwest of
Newark, and nearby communities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the prosecutor's office and the Orange Police
Department declined to identify the suspect or to discuss the
circumstances of the arrest. ``If and when he's been officially
charged, we'll go through that,'' Weiss said, adding, ``the
investigation is continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   The slain officer, Joyce Anne Carnegie, 38, was shot in the head
and abdomen at close range after approaching a man who matched the
description of a robbery suspect, the authorities said. The
victim's younger sister, Gayle Carnegie, said the police called
Saturday morning ``to say they have the guy in custody and they
would be getting back to us with the details of the arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just so overjoyed to know that they caught the guy so
quickly,'' said Ms. Carnegie, a nurse's aide who lives in Newark.
``We know that the police do their job, and we know that they love
one of their own fellow police officers. They were out there all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the officers searching for Carnegie's killer worked
through the night, canvassing the streets, backyards and parking
lots of the normally quiet town in patrol cars with their sirens
blaring. The police director, Richard Conti, was said to have
stayed in his office from Friday until about 7 a.m. Saturday; his
assistant left at 1 a.m., only to return later in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residents dropped bouquets at a makeshift memorial
near the site of the shooting, and friends and family lovingly
recalled a woman who took seriously the role of the beat cop as
guardian of a community.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie was the first member of the Orange Police Department to
die in the line of duty in 33 years, and the second female New
Jersey officer ever killed on the job. Her death sent the
113-member police force into emotional turmoil, and members of the
City Council spent Saturday morning at police headquarters
consoling grief-stricken officers.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie lived with her mother in North Plainfield. She
discovered a love for law enforcement while working as a security
guard at a Sears department store, according to her mother, and
continued to work part-time as a guard at a clothing store when
off-duty.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral has been scheduled for 11 a.m. Thursday at St.
Matthew's Church in Orange, Ms. Carnegie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
