<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HETTICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR M. HETTICH, EXECUTIVE WHO GUIDED POPULAR MAGAZINES, DIES AT
73  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass. )   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arthur M. Hettich, a retired senior executive for The
New York Times Co.'s magazine group and a former president of
Family Circle magazine, disappeared on Monday while swimming off
Grand Turk Island in Turks and Caicos and is presumed drowned,
according to his family. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Hettich's quick climb through the magazine world began in 1967,
when he became editor in chief of Family Circle, then owned by
Cowles Communications, and soon made it a hit by emphasizing
practical, how-to articles for women from all walks of life. Within
a year, the magazine's circulation had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, Hettich rose through the ranks of the magazine,
becoming editorial director in 1975, senior vice president in 1982
and, in 1985, president of Family Circle, which The New York Times
Co. bought in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Hettich became senior vice president of The New York
Times magazine group, which included Golf Digest and Tennis and a
number of women's magazines. (The company has since sold most of
its magazines, but continues to publish Golf Digest.) After his
retirement from The Times Co., he continued to work as a
consultant, editor and writer.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Brooklyn, N.Y., Hettich served in the Navy
during World War II. He received a bachelor's degree in English in
1949 from Amherst College and earned a master's degree in English
in 1950 from Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Hettich was a reporter for The Daily Mirror in New
York and an assistant promotion manager for Redbook magazine. In
1957, he started his own publishing company Magabooks.
</P>
<P>
   From 1960 to 1967, Hettich worked at Cowles, rising to vice
president and director of public relations, before moving to Family
Circle.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Mary Elizabeth Fitz
Randolph; three children, Michael, of Miami, John, of Katonah,
N.Y., and Elizabeth, of Brooklyn; a brother, Robert E. Hettich of
Westford, Ma., and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
