<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-MILSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILSTEIN'S FAILED BID FOR THE REDSKINS IS BAD NEWS FOR THE
ISLANDERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Islanders' seemingly perpetual ownership mess,
which has seen the team fall even further from respectability this
season, probably will not be straightened out before next season.
Howard Milstein's failed attempt to purchase the Washington
Redskins made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   When Milstein, the Islanders' co-owner, withdrew his $800
million bid to buy the Redskins last Wednesday, knowing that he did
not have the votes to be approved by the National Football League's
owners, groans could be heard from every corner of Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Milstein will not be rushed to sell the Islanders, whose
record (22-46-10) is the second worst in the National Hockey
League. Now, Milstein can take his sweet time, wait for bidders to
make offers and accept the highest amount. That could take months,
lasting through the summer, through the free-agent signing period
and into next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does concern me,'' Islander forward Bryan Smolinski,
whose contract is up at season's end, said. ``Personally, I would
like to make this my home. But I don't know what's going to happen
with the offer sheet. All of this could be resolved by July. But I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   While most players said they have not spent much time worrying
about the ownership mess, veterans like Smolinski and others who
have contracts to work out this summer (Trevor Linden, the
Islanders' captain, is another) have followed the situation
closely. Smolinski said he would like to see the two Milstein
brothers and Steven Gluckstern keep the Islanders, although that
does not seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hope they keep the team and really want to do
something with it,'' Smolinski said. ``I think this is better than
the Redskins' organization. We're at rock bottom, but we have a
chance to really make this respectable again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Islanders cannot be respectable until there is stable
ownership. That clearly is not the case now. On Thursday, one
high-ranking Islanders' official asked a reporter, ``Who are the
owners?'' He did not know because a report earlier in the week
suggested that Howard Milstein sold his 45 percent stake in the
Islanders to his brother, Edward, more than a month ago. The
transfer was never announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Milsteins and Gluckstern, who also owns 45 percent of the
Islanders, have put the team back on the market. They will
entertain offers of $150 million or more, according to an
Islanders' official. They paid $195 million for the Islanders and
the team's lucrative cable contract in February 1998. But it is
unlikely that they will get back what they paid for the team
because of the problems getting a new arena in Nassau County and
the unfavorable lease with SMG, the company that manages Nassau
Coliseum. The Islanders' front office would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of problems,'' said the Canadiens' Scott
Lachance, who was traded by the Islanders to Montreal last month
after eight seasons on Long Island. ``It goes from ownership to the
players. The instability is frustrating for everyone. Thankfully,
I'm not in a position where I have to worry about that stuff
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want all the guys to be happy,'' Lachance added. ``But
that's not going to happen until you get some stability in the
front office. I didn't realize until I got traded to Montreal the
difference. When you go to the locker room, you're just happy to be
there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Islander goalie Felix Potvin, who has not played since Feb. 24
because of a torn right groin muscle and sat on the bench for last
Thursday's game against the Canadiens, wanted to start last night's
game against the Carolina Hurricanes. Potvin, who is 1-6-1 since
coming to the Islanders on Jan. 9 from Toronto in exchange for
defenseman Bryan Berard, said he wanted to play before the season
ended. Coach Bill Stewart, however, said he would not play Potvin
unless the goalie's groin muscle was 100 percent stable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
