<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-BIRDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ZONING FOR VISITORS THAT FLY IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CAPE MAY, N.J. _ To tourists, the way to Cape May is
nothing more than the two southbound lanes of the Garden State
Parkway that eventually peter out in a local street and end at a
liquor store on West Ferry Road.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the bird's-eye view, says Patricia Sutton, the
education coordinator for the New Jersey Audubon Society's Cape May
bird observatory. To a thrush or warbler or flicker beating south
against the approach of winter, New Jersey's sharply tapered cape
is a migratory trap, a funnel of land that gathers and focuses
flocks of southbound birds into the southern tip of the state until
suddenly the land ends at the Delaware Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shock,'' Ms. Sutton said. ``Cape May Peninsula is the
first major land's end the birds encounter on their way south, and
suddenly there's 13 miles of Delaware Bay to cross. It may seem
like nothing, but it's a pretty major hop.''
</P>
<P>
   So, tired, hungry and thirsty, the birds see the land give way
to water, they hit the brakes, and start looking for a likely place
to feed and to rest before heading over open water. Many end up in
Barbara Freels' big back yard here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the birds _ I can't begin to tell you how many we get,''
said Mrs. Freels, a lifelong resident of West Cape May. ``We had a
whiskered tern show up all the way from Africa last year, so that
should give you an idea of how important we are for birds down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mrs. Freels showed up at West Cape May Town Hall with about
100 other voters last week to support borough ordinance 268-99, the
Landscaping and Vegetation Plan, which is intended to keep the
borough bird-friendly, even as all those other tourists funnel down
here and buy up open space for retirement homes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new ordinance, which West Cape May expects to adopt
next month, the newcomers would have to give up their habit of
cutting down trees on their lots and putting in pebble lawns of
crushed rock or shells where dune grass, goldenrod and wild plum
bushes once sheltered and fed migrating birds.
</P>
<P>
   Cape May City and Cape May Point have already adopted the new
rules under a state order that they do so in exchange for fresh
water from a new desalinization plant. West Cape May is under the
same order. And the rules are clear: Cut down a tree to build a
house and you must plant one or two elsewhere; 35 percent to 45
percent of the land must have plant life, depending on the zoning,
and in all cases there must be efforts to retain as much natural
vegetation as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all put plants in our yards,'' Ms. Sutton told the West
Cape May Board of Commissioners last week. ``We put trees in, we
put shrubs in, so let's get used to putting in plants that have
fruit, cones, catkins or seeds. A red cedar will feed 35 different
kinds of birds, but if you go to a nursery they'll try to sell you
arborvitae. Well, zip birds feed on arborvitae.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those in the audience seemed to be on the side of the
birds, but the sentiment was not universal. Although it is changing
as newcomers move in, West Cape May is still the conservative farm
neighbor of glitzy Cape May City to the east, and many longtime
landowners are counting on making a lot of money from development.
None of them are keen on having the state tell them how to
landscape their property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 878 acres total in town, and 300 acres are wetlands,
so that's a third for the birds already,'' Tom Douglas, a local
landowner, complained.
</P>
<P>
   James Roney, a town commissioner, said: ``I do feel that this is
a case of the state holding a gun against our heads, and that this
is something being imposed on us by the bureaucrats sitting up in
Trenton in their ivory towers. But I have nothing against birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jackson, a professional fishing guide, cheered Roney up
when he said that birds increase property values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birds do?'' Roney exclaimed with a mischievous grin. ``Birds
increase property values? Well, when we have our assessment, we'll
have to bring that into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
