<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-GIRL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSMATES, PARENTS AND POLICE SCOUR MANHATTAN FOR MISSING
SCHOOLGIRL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 70 volunteers fanned out through Manhattan
Saturday with cars, cell phones and posters in a community effort
to find a 14-year-old girl who disappeared Thursday night after a
dentist's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, Maureen Lynch, is a ninth grader at the Convent of the
Sacred Heart, a school for girls at 91st Street and Fifth Avenue,
and the searchers included classmates and their parents, as well as
officers from the 13th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anything worse,'' said Monica Merrill, one of
the parents, fighting back tears. ``It's a universal fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who has a medical problem that causes fainting spells,
may have been sighted by a West Side doorman early Saturday,
Detective Pat McGovern said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the police distributed fliers in Central Park and in
every police car and precinct in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Maureen went on a class trip to the Black Rock
Forest, a nature preserve in Cornwall, in Orange County, and may
have been light-headed from sun exposure, her father, Robert Lynch,
said. That afternoon at the office of her orthodontist, Dr. Vincent
LaBruna, she appeared pale and light-headed and was urged to drink
fluids, the dentist told her parents later. At 7 p.m. when she had
not come home, her parents called the police and reported her
missing.
</P>
<P>
   She is 5 feet 8 inches tall and weighs 140 pounds, with red hair
and brown eyes. She was wearing either blue jeans or black Adidas
running pants and probably had on a blue fleece pullover jacket,
her mother, Mary, said. Her medical problem, known as
hydrocephalus, causes a chronic buildup of fluid in the brain, Mrs.
Lynch said, but it does not affect day-to-day activities.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, a doorman at Columbus Avenue and 62d Street called 911
to report that at approximately 1 a.m., he saw a girl resembling
Maureen. Suspecting that she was in trouble, he encouraged her to
call her family. When she declined, he gave her $5 and a subway
token, McGovern said.
</P>
<P>
   While that report raised hopes, it also deepened the mystery.
Standing with volunteers who assembled for supplies and
instructions at the Monsignor Farricker Parish Hall of the Church
of the Epiphany, Lynch said, ``I just want my daughter back
safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, an actuary for the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., and
his wife, have another daughter, 8.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance ruptured the sense of security among
classmates at Sacred Heart and their parents. ``It makes it more of
a shock because it's such a beautiful school,'' said Ciro Scotti,
who volunteered to help search and whose daughter is one of 57
girls in the ninth grade. The children feel safe there, and by
extension, he said, parents feel that their daughters are safe in
the city. Former students include Caroline Kennedy.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
