<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3359 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      04-10 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A DECISION LOOSENED CLINTON'S BURDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the days leading to NATO air raids over
Yugoslavia, President Clinton was having trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does not tend to sleep much anyway, aides said, and they
attributed his recent restlessness, and the bags under his eyes, to
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   But once the bombing campaign began, Clinton was full of energy.
He would stride from the Oval Office to the situation room, or pop
in on one White House office or another.
</P>
<P>
   His days were full of meetings with foreign policy advisers,
telephone calls to world leaders, briefings from strategists, and
the requisite public statements to build support for the military
action _ while juggling domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's involvement in the finer details of the military
operation was such that sometimes he personally checked off targets
NATO should hit because, one Democratic operative close to the
White House said, ``He knows that both God and the devil are in the
details.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bombing campaign now well into its third week, and as
the uncommon has become patterned, Clinton's aides say the demands
of commanding the war have eased.
</P>
<P>
   The political demands, however, may be on the rise. Congress
returns from its spring recess this week, and aides are voicing
determination not to allow Kosovo to become a new excuse, after the
impeachment, for Congress not to act on the president's agenda on
taxes, health care, and preserving Social Security. Fresh lines
were drawn Saturday, as Clinton focused his weekly radio address on
welfare reform, but Republicans responded in their message with
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides say that with US involvement in Yugoslavia
unlikely to end soon, the president is trying to strike a balance
in paying proper attention to the biggest foreign policy crisis of
his presidency, while also tending to other government issues and
to politics, especially helping Vice President Al Gore to succeed
him as president.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for the first time since NATO launched strikes on
March 24, Clinton ventured outside Washington to promote a domestic
initiative. At a rally Friday in Philadelphia, he pushed for a
patients' bill of rights when dealing with health maintenance
organizations. In the speech, Clinton admitted that the event was
unlikely to make the evening news because of Kosovo, despite the
presence of dozens of members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organized forces of the status quo will do nothing,''
Clinton said about changing the HMO system. ``They will say, `Oh,
well, the president went to Philadelphia, and he brought all the
Congress members here, and there were 100 members of Congress
around the country, but they probably can't break through on the
evening news tonight because of Kosovo. That's another excuse we'll
have to let this thing slide,' '' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Clinton plans to resume his fund-raising for
Democratic candidates. After canceling a fund-raising swing through
Cincinnati, Las Vegas and Sacramento on the week the bombing began,
he now plans to attend Democratic fund-raisers Friday in Detroit
and Boston. He also will make a fund-raising appearance in Austin
on April 21, in a visit to dedicate a new airport.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lewis, a senior adviser to Clinton, said that it would have
been inappropriate to attend fund-raisers as the NATO bombing
campaign began. But now, ``it is important to make clear that we
are in for the long haul,'' in Yugoslavia, she said. ``Therefore,
the work of government is going to go on at every level.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior aide said that Clinton continues to worry about
the Kosovo outcome, and that he is not treating it as ``just
another event'' in days that, on two occasions including Saturday,
have included time for golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some concerns to make sure this comes out well,'' the
aide said of Kosovo. ``This is certainly a serious matter _ it's
the thing that we probably start each day thinking about and end
each day thinking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides say that Clinton has read newspaper coverage of the
conflict, some of it more closely than others. They say he is
acutely aware of the criticism of his methods and objectives in the
Balkans, especially given the personal nature of some comments
about his status as the first baby boomer president who also had
protested the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic source familiar with his thinking said Clinton
believed he could not stand by while ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
were being killed and driven from their homes. He said Clinton has
buffered himself against the criticism by believing it was his job
to take a larger view beyond the pundits.
</P>
<P>
   This source said Clinton thought some of the early criticism,
especially from Republican presidential candidates, was
``politically motivated and was the kind of criticism that did not
attach itself to his predecessors in similar contexts.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas B. Sosnik, a Clinton aide, described his boss's attitude
thus: ``We had a series of tough options, none of them particularly
attractive. We're proceeding on it; it seems to be working. It's
going to take some time, and we haven't looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talks to Gore every day about Kosovo. Gore calls the
president for updates, even while on the road campaigning for the
nomination. Aides for both men say that political considerations
are not a factor in the administration's decision against sending
ground troops, at least at this stage of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a straight-up, do-the-right-thing'' kind of
conversation, a Clinton aide said. ``If you get tangled up in
trying to figure out all the politics, you are going to lose sight
of what you are trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic operative said: ``The political considerations
are indirect. I don't think Al Gore or anyone on his behalf is
arguing that we don't want to deal with this next year, so let's
not send in ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom, the strategist said, the White House political
strategy is being driven by then-General Colin L. Powell's doctrine
of using force: ``Let's do what we can do that we feel confident we
can generate long-term public support for.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategist said that while polls show growing support for
the use of ground troops, the backing could easily and quickly
evaporate when you ``start shipping home body bags.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTPRES-FAULKNER11-COX     04-10 2117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTPRES-FAULKNER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faulkner earns both high grades, hard knocks as UT president
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The elite group of high school students invited
to visit the University of Texas shuffled to their seats and waited
for UT President Larry Faulkner to deliver the inevitable hard
sell.
</P>
<P>
   It never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``This setting probably isn't the right setting for every one of
you,'' Faulkner flatly told them, arms folded across his chest, as
they snacked on cookies and Cokes. ``It's very important for you to
find a place where you are well-matched.''
</P>
<P>
   This scene on a recent Friday was classic Faulkner: direct,
low-key, no frills.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year heading the nation's largest university,
Faulkner's style and approach are under the microscope. He's
getting grades ranging from ``A plus'' to ``incomplete.'' Not all
of his chores have been as pleasant as courting students like
Dalton Newsom, an East Texas high school senior who said Faulkner
won him over.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office April 13, 1998, Faulkner has faced ongoing
protests from staff over their pay, an overnight takeover of the
Main Building by angry students and the skepticism of
high-technology executives he wants badly to woo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take all this personally,'' he said. ``People who are
involved in all of those things are raising issues that are
important to them, and they're important to me. My responsibility
is try to find practical ways to address them. That often is a lot
tougher than people recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner, who got a doctorate in chemistry from UT in 1969, just
three years after earning his bachelor's degree, approaches
problems with cool, scientific reserve. He gathers information,
analyzes it and then stakes out a position. It was that studied
approach that caused him to realize the value of acquiring the
exquisite $35 million Suida-Manning art collection for UT, a
triumph he considers his biggest achievement. He avoids making
dramatic statements on impulse, and the few times he has, he's been
stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it rough,'' he said in a measured voice of his
first year as a university president. ``I would say it's been very
full.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such a tough act to follow,'' English Professor Alan
Friedman said, referring to Faulkner's friend and predecessor, the
charismatic and eloquent Robert Berdahl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing well under difficult circumstances,'' said
Gretchen Ritter, an associate professor of government. ``I wouldn't
say he has had a honeymoon, in light of the extremely high regard
people held President Berdahl. People expected good things, and
there's a deep sense of loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are waiting to see how things are going to turn out
under President Faulkner.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner ultimately will be judged on how well he protects the
quality of a school that is not as financially robust as he
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the thick of a seven-year campaign to raise $1 billion
from private donors by 2004. He also is trying to persuade
lawmakers to provide a larger chunk than one-fourth of UT's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This university is not nearly as muscular as I thought it
was,'' Faulkner said in an interview at his office, its south
windows framing the Capitol dome. ``This university is working on a
per student basis with one half . . . to two-thirds of what most of
the other major competitors are working with. What that translates
to is better student-faculty ratios at other places, better staff
support for students at other places and better ability to attract
and hold graduate students.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same Friday he spoke to Newsom and the other students,
Faulkner met with lawmakers on the budget, spoke to several campus
committees _ including one he told several times to get its act
together _ accepted a $75,000 check to UT from Phillips Petroleum
executives, attended a reception at the Music School and spoke at a
banquet of math and science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   During that 13-hour day, Faulkner laughed frequently but did not
avoid delivering sobering news. He told a campus advisory committee
UT needs an additional $66 million over the next two years to pay
faculty, staff and graduate students salaries that are more
competitive with the best public universities, including the
University of California at Berkeley and the University of
Michigan. He's been told to expect a maximum of about $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several leading legislators said that if Faulkner doesn't get
all he wants, it's no reflection on his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very skilled advocate,'' said state Sen. Bill Ratliff,
the Mount Pleasant Republican who chairs the powerful Senate
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, an engineer known for his methodical demeanor, added
that he likes Faulkner's low-key style. ``Frankly, I appreciate
someone who tells me their case and trusts me to treat him
fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner _ whom observers called a quick study with a deep grasp
of UT's complicated budget _ told the Faculty Council last month
that he is committed to raising pay, even if it means cutting
programs, hiring fewer people and shrinking enrollments. ``Why does
he have to pirate the staff to do it?'' asked Sue Gamel, an
academic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner said his options are limited. ``I don't have the
ability to print money.''
</P>
<P>
   He has created seven study groups to work on priorities he
carved out last fall, including higher salaries. Other groups are
examining ways to make UT more accessible to students, financially
stronger, more closely tied to the high-tech community, more
involved in public schools, No. 1 in Latin American studies and
better-suited to undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben McDaniel, a professor of management science and
information systems, said Faulkner's frank talk is refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed somebody who could look at people square in the eye
and say we are not going to be a first-class university without
more resources,'' McDaniel said. ``It's been wonderful to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the financial worries, Faulkner has had to grapple
with the fallout from the federal court's 1996 Hopwood ruling,
which led to a dismantling of affirmative action programs. The
issue is not going away as Texas shifts from a state dominated by
Anglos to one in which Hispanics and blacks together will outnumber
non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   Students involved in the Anti-Racist Organizing Committee who
occupied the Tower overnight in October have continued to object to
Faulkner's stance on affirmative action. After agreeing to hold a
series of forums with the students, Faulkner said that while he is
committed to diversity, he intends to follow the law and seek new
tools to diversify the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say he doesn't care,'' said Felicia Enuha, a
junior majoring in biochemistry. ``It seems to me he's doing what
he's being told to by the higher-ups, and that's where his
priorities are.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmund T. Gordon, an associate professor of anthropology who
moderated the first forum, praised Faulkner for taking part but
said students and faculty expect more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to continue that process and go further in finding
innovative ways to increase diversity and foment a respect for
differences on the campus,'' Gordon said. ``Even after a year it's
not quite clear where he stands on the issues important to me. . .
. He needs to have more contact with the rest of us commoners and
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gobert, co-chairperson of the Graduate Student Assembly,
said she has easy access to Faulkner and sees him soliciting a
range of views.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be I was the one minority sitting around the
table,'' said Gobert, who is black. ``Now, there are two or three
others sitting around the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner, whose career included many chemistry awards and
teaching jobs at Harvard, Illinois and even briefly at UT, during
the 1983-84 school year, wants the university to be closer to the
community and state it serves. A campuswide open house March 6 drew
at least 20,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a start, he said. He also wants better ties with the
high-technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner appeared on a panel in January before high-tech
executives but left them riled when he said UT ``will be here after
a large number of enterprises in this room are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Summit organizers had instructed panelists to be provocative,
but some said Faulkner went overboard, prompting audience members
to boo and toss whiffle balls his way. Lt. Gov. Rick Perry demanded
an explanation. Faulkner, who said the incident was retold with
more ``built-in rancor than actually existed,'' sent Perry and some
of the executives a five-page letter, not counting attachments, on
UT's work with high-tech businesses and its plans to expand work
force education and industry interactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dr. Faulkner has gotten a bad rap,'' said Bill Bock,
CEO and president of Dazel, an enterprise software company. ``I
frankly believe we finally have somebody who really does care about
this and will make change happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are skeptical, including the high-tech entrepreneur who
was on the panel with Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, Dr. Faulkner has fallen into the status
quo'' of isolating UT from the community, said Andrew Heller,
founder of INT Labs, a networking startup in Lakeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been here a year and started with more positive
discussions than he's ended it with,'' Heller said. ``I wouldn't
give him a failing grade, but I wouldn't give him more than a C.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Faulkner has won many admirers his first year, including
the secretaries he inherited at UT. His executive assistant, Nancy
McCowen, worked with him nine years in Illinois and came to UT,
even though it means living away from her family for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met a man who is a better teacher, is more humble,
has more integrity and allows someone to do their job the way he
does,'' McCowen said.
</P>
<P>
   When Faulkner headed to the kitchen to rinse his coffee cup, he
wouldn't let her take it from him because the handle was wet.
</P>
<P>
   Although he often mentions his wife and their two adult
children, he does not display any family photographs or personal
mementos. There is nothing in his office or on his desk that says
Larry Faulkner works here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why that's true,'' he said. ``I have never taken
time to do anything of that kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has been at a premium this year. He was off-campus nearly
half the time, meeting donors, alumni and elected officials. Now,
with many important contacts made and $344 million raised toward
the $1 billion campaign, he plans to spend more time learning the
campus and the community.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to have the full support of UT regents and Chancellor
William Cunningham, who had a strained relationship with Berdahl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a president at a major public university has the most
difficult job in this country because he has so many different
constituencies that he has to satisfy or pacify,'' said Austin
lawyer Larry Temple, chairman of the Ex-Students' Association.
``I've watched with admiration and appreciation the way Larry has
acquitted himself in that role. . . .I give him an A plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner said the hardest part is finding time for himself and
his family. During football season, he worked six nights a week, as
alumni, donors and others came to town during the week for
meetings, receptions and other activities. ``I was ready to
collapse by Christmas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, he and his wife, Mary Ann, almost never eat dinner at
home more than once or twice a week. He hasn't had time to exercise
in months. Fortunately, he said, ``I've never been terribly prone
to stress.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked late on the Friday he spoke to the students so he
could meet people at the Music School reception and welcome the
science and math teachers at their banquet.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some of the three or four dozen people at the reception
might have been surprised to learn later Faulkner had been there.
He stood in roughly the same spot and chatted amiably with some of
the guests for nearly an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Patrick Oxford, a Houston attorney, said Faulkner's
personality ``is a little bit of a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first start talking to him, he comes across in the
first instance as a little bit of a chemist _ reserved in
judgment,'' he said. ``But if you just poke around a little bit,
there's huge passion in there, and that's what's surprising. He's
not the kind of person who walks in a room and everyone looks at.
But if he does say something, he's the one everyone is looking
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
