<SLUG> BC-FAULKNER-QUOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Up close and personal with Larry Faulkner
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some things you might not know about Larry
Faulkner:
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a chemist to have a favorite molecule:
``Anthracene,'' Faulkner said. Made up of carbon and hydrogen,
``it's beautifully symmetric, and I published my first paper here
at UT on the study of light generated from actions involving
anthracene.''
</P>
<P>
   He drives a 1996 Olds Cutlass, and its color is described in the
owners manual as orange-red. ``Just don't call it maroon,''
Faulkner said, referring to the Aggie color.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school student in Shreveport, La., he used to sail in
competitions with his father, James Clifford Faulkner Jr. He still
loves sailing but doesn't own a boat.
</P>
<P>
   He's ``probably not'' related to writer William Faulkner, he
said, but his dad used to visit Mississippi often, and some people
used to ask him if he was William Faulkner. ``We called him Uncle
Bill,'' Faulkner said.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh-grade teacher inspired his interest in science. He got
a telescope for Christmas in the eighth grade and became fascinated
with astronomy. He still has the telescope but said, ``I haven't
gotten it out of the box in quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman at Southern Methodist University, Faulkner tried
to follow his father and grandfather into civil engineering. But he
had a terrible time using a Leroy, a stylus device civil engineers
use to make block letters. It's designed for right-handed people,
he said. He switched to chemistry, a passion since high school.
</P>
<P>
   He's reading Michael Dell's book, ``Direct From Dell: Strategies
That Revolutionized an Industry.'' Next up is UT Professor Jim
Magnuson's ``Windfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner married his high school sweetheart, Mary Ann, who got a
teaching degree from SMU. Their daughter, Susan, 21, is at the
University of Illinois combining both her parents' interests: a
teaching degree with certification in chemistry and physics. Their
son, Brian, 27, has a chemistry degree and works for Dow Chemical
in Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
