<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shot for over-40 club
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ NASCAR biannually brings its Winston Cup circus
to this small town tucked away in the Smoky Mountains, on the
border of Tennessee and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   While the spring and fall dates at Bristol Motor Speedway afford
locals an opportunity to herd in their livestock and milk racing
fans for camping and parking, it also gives some of NASCAR's
veteran drivers a legitimate shot at finding victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 25 qualifiers in today's Food City 500 at Bristol, 15
drivers are over the age of 40. Pole-sitter Rusty Wallace and
veterans Bobby Hamilton, Robert Pressley and Darrell Waltrip, all
starting inside the first six rows, will make their best starts of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   On this half-mile oval, the second-shortest track still used on
the Winston Cup circuit, experience and mental concentration often
are more valuable than horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tough, very demanding race,'' said 58-year-old
driver Dave Marcis, who will make his best start at 22nd. ``Just
the bouncing around and the jarring around here, and the speed and
concentration level you have to maintain, will wear you out.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still some familiar names in the front rows as
Wallace, Jeff Gordon, Bobby Labonte and rookie Tony Stewart took
the top four starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the drivers near the top of the points standings _
Jeff and Ward Burton, Terry Labonte, Mike Skinner and Jeremy
Mayfield _ will start near the back and pit on the back
straightaway, leaving them at a disadvantage on green-flag
pitstops.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the first six weekends of the Winston Cup
schedule on superspeedways, drivers like Marcis are looking forward
to an upcoming stretch of three short-track races in the next five
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will disagree, but I think short-track racing needs to
remain a part of NASCAR,'' Marcis said. ``It's important. You can't
take everything away. You can't take the apples out of an apple
pie. It ain't going to be good anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only three tracks less than a mile in length _ Bristol
and Martinsville and Richmond _ that have six dates on Winston
Cup's 34-race schedule. Nashville and North Wilkesboro, N.C., two
other short tracks, lost their Cup races to superspeedways, which
allow track owners to build more seats around larger facilities.
``If everybody built one-and-a-half mile speedways, and that seems
to be kind of the trend these days, there wouldn't be anything to
this series,'' said Paul Andrews, crew chief for Mayfield. ``All
you would be doing is going from this market to that market to do
the same thing, week in and week out. That's not racing. That's
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, one of five Cup drivers who started their career on
the short tracks around Owensboro, Ky., agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where just about all of us came from,'' he said.
``Working your entire life to get to the top of motorsports and
then not having any short-track races would be like going home to
your mom's house and saying, `Why don't you bake that chicken
instead of frying it?' You still get the chicken, but it's just not
the same. I can't imagine NASCAR without short tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
