<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monte Carlo debut pushed back again
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bristol, Tenn. _ Chevrolet will delay the debut of its 2000
Monte Carlo race car until next season, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet officials said NASCAR hasn't approved the model. The
car was to debut at the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte next month then
was pushed back to the Brickyard 400 Aug. 7 in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at Chevrolet are disappointed that NASCAR has not yet
approved the Monte Carlo for use in Winston Cup competition,'' said
Kurt Ritter, Chevy's marketing general manager. ``This lengthy
approval process has been a major distraction to everyone. It has
now reached the point where time has run out for us and our
Chevrolet teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter said Chevrolet introduced the model to NASCAR more than a
year ago. NASCAR officials tested six cars _ two Chevys, Fords and
Pontiacs _ at the wind tunnel at Lockheed Martin in Marietta after
the Cracker Barrell 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway on March 14.
NASCAR officials compared that data to the new Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further changes were requested by NASCAR and, as before, we
compiled with their requests,'' Ritter said. ``As it stands today,
NASCAR is asking us to make changes that, when compared to the
current '99 Monte Carlo and to other brands, would make the new car
uncompetitive on the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough break for Earnhardt
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, who is 16th in points and mired in a 38-race
winless drought, caught another bad break Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the happy-hour practice following the Busch race, Earnhardt
lost control of his No. 3 Chevrolet and hit the wall in turn 1.
Earnhardt's car had extensive damage in the front and was removed
by a tow truck. He went to a backup car, so he'll start 43rd
instead of 34th.
</P>
<P>
   Close call for Buckshot
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup rookie Buckshot Jones of Tucker qualified for
today's race in dramatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the ninth of 10 drivers to run in second-round qualifying
Saturday, knocked Ernie Irvan off the bubble for the 36th starting
spot. Jones had an average speed of 122.984 mph on his first lap,
and then his No. 00 Pontiac spun out in turn 4 on the second.
</P>
<P>
   But rookie Stanton Barrett, the final driver attempting to
qualify, couldn't beat Jones' time and missed the race. Joining
Barrett with DNQs were Rich Bickle, Derrike Cope and Carl Long.
</P>
<P>
   Changes for Junior
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr., who will run five Winston Cup races this
year before jumping to the circuit full-time in 2000, has dropped
the Oct. 17 Winston 500 in Talladega, Ala., this season. Instead,
Junior will drive in the Exide Batteries 400 at Richmond, Va., on
Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd hoped to build a new superspeedway car for Talladega that
we could also use next year,'' said Dale Earnhardt, owner of his
son's No. 8 Chevrolet team. ``Unfortunately, the new Monte Carlo is
not going to be racing by Talladega, so we've had to make a change
in our 1999 plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior won the Busch event at Richmond in September and finished
second at the track in June.
</P>
<P>
   Pit stops
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd seems close to hiring Joe Garone as crew chief.
Garone left Bill Elliott's team after the Primestar 500 at Texas on
March 28. ``We'd love to have Joe, but we gotta make sure it's
gonna work for everybody,'' Rudd said. ``But he'd be a big asset to
the race team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
