<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-DAYTONA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Live from Daytona, it's Black College Reunion
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Spring break is alive and well in Daytona
Beach. At least that is the case for the 100,000 African-Americans
who have converged there this weekend for Black College Reunion,
the annual street party that attracts people from all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But as the crowds stretched Saturday across the miles of white
sand and cruised down Atlantic Avenue, the popular consensus was
that Atlanta's Freaknik, set to being late this week, may be on its
last legs.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they thought Freaknik, long the king of black college
spring break events, was already dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumor has it that it has been canceled and moved to Los
Angeles,'' said Barnesta Porter, who came down from Birmingham,
Ala. ``They told us that the mayor didn't want it there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is mind-boggling,'' said Afalabi Mega, an Atlanta vendor in
Daytona Beach hawking Black College Reunion and Freaknik T-shirts.
``People think it is not going to happen. I am down here serving as
an ambassador. We are letting people know about Freaknik.''
</P>
<P>
   While BCR's attendance has continued to grow, Freaknik observers
are expecting a crowd smaller than last year's 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The miles of beach vs. Peachtree Street's asphalt is only one
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, they block all the exits off. The police will get
you for playing music too loud, for cruising, for everything,''
said Wallace Copeland, a native of Atlanta. ``Here, even though
they are being hard on us, at least they let us represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, in Atlanta, the unpredictable nature of Freaknik makes it
difficult to judge where people will be from one night to the next.
</P>
<P>
   In Daytona, everybody is either on the beach or on Atlantic
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weekend started in controversy with the city's
attempt to block off traffic along the beach, the first two days of
BCR have been low in incidents and high on fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``In comparison to the two, Daytona Beach is a much better
event,'' said Melinda Tenn of Norcross, Ga., a Freaknik veteran.
``Here we have wide open spaces for these kids to run free.
Freaknik is necessary, but they need to find a way to control the
crowd and to make them feel more welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
