<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREAN-PRESBYTERIANS-     04-10 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-PRESBYTERIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KOREAN CHURCH LOOKS TO ENGLISH LANGUAGE MINISTRY TO STOP THE
`SILENT EXODUS'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hundreds of people who fill the main sanctuary of
the Korean American Presbyterian Church of Queens in Flushing every
Sunday sit stiffly as the senior pastor, the Rev. Young Choon
Chang, preaches the ways of God to them in Korean. They murmur
solemn hymns, following the lead of string musicians and a robed
minister who waves his arms in broad strokes to keep time.
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall in a small chapel, a twenty-something crowd of
about 150 sways to the melodic strains of gospel tunes pulsating
from an electric guitar and drums. They are just as rapt as their
elders when the preaching begins. But here, it is in English, and
they erupt in laughter whenever John Choi, a 26-year-old
seminarian, makes a point in a worldly way _ like when he stopped
to tell them about the great time he had at a concert by the Trash
Can Sinatras.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two congregations make up one of the biggest
Korean churches in the metropolitan region, with 3,500 members. The
Korean and English ministries also illustrate the two halves of a
familiar immigrant story. There are the first-generation
immigrants, who cling to the church and to one another in their new
country; and then there are their children, who grew up here and
struggle with just how much of their parents' culture to hang on
to.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders hope that the English ministry will help solve
one of their community's biggest problems: the potential loss of an
entire generation _ a phenomenon that experts on Korean immigrants
refer to as a ``silent exodus.''
</P>
<P>
   While Korean churches mirror the Roman Catholic parishes of
Italian and Irish immigrants and Jewish congregations at the turn
of the century, one major difference is that the earlier immigrants
brought their religion with them, while many Koreans adopt
Christianity only after arriving here. Only 25 percent of the
population in Korea professes Christianity, compared with more than
70 percent of Korean-Americans, say clergy members and academics.
</P>
<P>
   That is in part because Korean Christians are more likely to
immigrate, since they tend to live in cities and are more
westernized. Many Korean immigrants, too, convert to Christianity
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   S.Y. Park, who immigrated from Seoul, South Korea, five years
ago, said her family joined the church ``because it's the only
place where our children can learn the customs of Korea.'' She and
her husband enjoy the chance to share a bowl of steaming noodles
with fellow immigrants in the church basement every Sunday, but
they are even more comforted by the knowledge that their teen-age
son is studying Korean in one of the school's 40 classrooms
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   The church has long sent children toddler- to high-school age to
separate, fairly informal Sunday services at which both English and
Korean are spoken. But before the English ministry, the only option
adulthood provided was joining the more austere, strictly Korean
congregation. College students and young professionals often felt
they had little in common with that congregation, a generation of
immigrants who worked long hours running grocery stores and
dry-cleaning shops.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the church had provided simultaneous English
translation at Korean services with headphones, but it was still
losing more than 50 percent of its young members when they reached
college age, church leaders said. So five years ago they created
the Queens Presbyterian English Ministry, nicknamed Q-PEM, to stem
the tide.
</P>
<P>
   While Q-PEM is influenced by the Korean church, members say it
is much more casual _ in a phrase, much less Korean. Instead of a
receiving line of ladies who bow as you enter the church, a greeter
at Q-PEM looks you in the eye, smiles and points you toward a seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interactions are definitely a lot more Westernized,'' said
Charles Paek, a Florida native who moved to New York about four
years ago. ``It's very Korean to have a sense of hierarchy, but at
Q-PEM, we call each other by our first names and we're all more or
less equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Chi, who at 29 is one of the oldest members of Q-PEM,
said he felt more at ease at Q-PEM, but staying connected to the
church of his childhood was also important to him. ``Even though I
don't really understand Korean that well, I'm still not totally
Americanized,'' said Chi, who immigrated with his family when he
was 5.
</P>
<P>
   Although the second generation may feel more at home in their
own ministry, the English ministry has by no means completely
bridged the gap between generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Korean congregation looks at the English ministry as the
children's church and treats it that way too,'' said Richard
Colligan, one of the few non-Korean members of Q-PEM. Colligan's
wife, Christine, is Korean-born and very active in the Korean
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The English ministry is financially dependent on the Korean
congregation and is governed by the Korean ministry's board. A year
ago, for example, Q-PEM proposed that some of its members be named
deacons, but leaders of the Korean congregation turned them down,
saying the candidates were too young and inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   Paek said that the relationship between the congregations is a
complicated and evolving one. ``It's not that the Korean
congregation gives us a lack of respect, it's more that in Korean
culture, we're supposed to respect and defer to them,'' he said.
``The tension is there because I don't think we completely
understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Pyong Gap Min, a Korean-born sociology professor at Queens
College, said that while most first generation Korean-Americans
attend a Korean church every Sunday, only about 30 percent of
second generation Koreans do. ``There's a big drop because the
first generation goes to church for networking and for
fellowship,'' he said. ``But the second generation is more
assimilated and doesn't need that as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Min said that many Korean-Americans also have criticized their
church leaders for focusing their energies only on church programs
and not playing a more significant role in the larger immigrant
community. The Korean clergy generally defers to business leaders
on political issues.
</P>
<P>
   Korean-American churches, primarily Protestant congregations,
have existed in New York since the early 1920s. Korean immigration
to the region has increased steadily ever since immigration quotas
were lifted in 1965, and there are now about 400,000 Korean
immigrants here, according to the Korean Association of New York.
Korean church leaders estimate that there now are more than 600
Korean churches in the area, up from about 150 in 1980. The highest
concentration is in Queens, which has more than 200 churches.
</P>
<P>
   The churches have thrived because immigrants have relied on them
for services. Larger churches provide citizenship classes, help
finding apartments and jobs, and Korean schools and seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders at the Korean American Presbyterian Church of Queens
are aware of the church's role in dealing with the tensions between
the generations, said the Rev. Brian Inbum Song, who oversees the
church's English ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all immigrant groups, we hope our traditions and our
Christian life style will continue with our children and their
children,'' Song said. ``Fifty years from now, if we have failed,
it will be because we didn't plan well now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1835EDT &QL; 
