u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-DRAFT-485&AMP;AR     04-10 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DRAFT-485&AMP;ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 57TH PICK, JETS APPROACH DRAFT QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two years of running a vacuum cleaner through
the college player draft to restock a failing franchise, the
resurgent Jets will go quietly into the annual selections next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They do not make a pick until the virtual end of the second
round _ No. 57. Overall, they have a total of eight choices,
including extra selections in the sixth and seventh rounds.
</P>
<P>
   They may have lost a first-round choice, but they gained Bill
Parcells. The NFL's commissioner, Paul Tagliabue, awarded the
Patriots the Jets' first-round pick for 1999 two years ago, when
Parcells was permitted to join the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Now Parcells is living with that decision, which in any event
has worked out better than owner Leon Hess could have imagined. The
Jets are coming off a 12-4 season, which ended with a loss in the
AFC championship game to the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells wants a first-rounder. Who doesn't? He didn't
get one last year either, when he compensated the Patriots for
nabbing free agent Curtis Martin. ``I don't have the ammunition to
move up next week,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be moot. The Jets have strengthened themselves with
off-season free-agent moves that improve the punter position (Tom
Tupa), outside linebacker (Roman Phifer), free safety (Steve
Atwater) and tight end (Eric Green).
</P>
<P>
   Now, they go into the draft looking for a guard, a cornerback, a
burly fullback, a speed receiver and, with luck, a quarterback of
the future. There is college depth at guard. And the Jets did
produce a remarkable rookie tackle last year in Jason Fabini, a
fourth-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Among the interior linemen the Jets might still see at No. 57,
there are Doug Brzezinski of Boston College, Derrick Fletcher of
Baylor, Anthony Cesario of Colorado State and Brandon Burlsworth of
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done extensive research of this offensive-line
group,'' said Parcells. ``I just can't tell you how much work we've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line produced spectacular protection for
quarterback Vinny Testaverde last season; after one victory he
pronounced it the best of his career. But the line often messed up
on the running game. Blown assignments _ some involving tight end
Kyle Brady _ and less-than-sterling execution contributed to Curtis
Martin's low average of 3.5 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is leaving nothing to chance despite his low draft
pick. He even had running backs' coach Mo Carthon, and the Jets'
security chief, Steve Yarnell, investigate the controversial but
game-breaking Cecil Collins. He was expelled from Louisiana State
and McNeese State after legal run-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Would Parcells take him?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to wait and see that,'' said Parcells with a grin.
``Obviously I wasn't sending those guys down for practice. I'm not
going to say what I would do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Parcells does say that he wants depth at cornerback and a speed
receiver. Yet, unless a rare find is uncovered at receiver, or a
Fabini-type emerges for the line, no potential draftee at the other
Jets' need positions could offer immediate help. And in any event,
a quarterback so far down would be a project.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Parcells plans to look at Chris Miller, the former Rams'
quarterback who left football two years ago following a series of
concussions. But Parcells believes several more quality veteran
backups at quarterback will be available in June.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his pessimism about getting a higher draft pick,
Parcells admits he would listen to trade talk that included draft
choices, especially involving his running backs. Excluding Curtis
Martin, the backs currently on the Jets are Leon Johnson, Robert
Farmer, Richie Anderson or Jerald Sowell.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atwater's arrival has repercussions for two Jets:
Kevin Williams, the rookie who started at free safety the early
part of the year, and Scott Frost, the former Nebraska quarterback
who saw limited action at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will be a backup cornerback, and Frost will be groomed
at free safety. Because of Frost's size _ 6 feet 3 inches and 219
pounds _ and football skills, Parcells drafted him on the third
round last year and saw visions of a marauding free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to learn under Atwater,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Frost is one of 16 players from Parcells' first two drafts still
on the Jets and is a performer who the coach fantasizes can be an
impact player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
