<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILLIAMS SYMBOLIZED THE NETS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine you're an impressionable kid out of the
University of Maryland in the early 1980s, looking for friends with
similar interests at your new job. You're reliable, responsible and
mature for 22.
</P>
<P>
   Your new friends are, well, not quite there yet.
</P>
<P>
   You are Buck Williams, in the passenger seat of a speeding
vehicle driven by that rascal Micheal Ray Richardson. Your tardy
teammate is approaching 100 miles an hour down Route 17 en route to
Newark Airport, chatting away. Inches from the divider, you are in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike!'' you yell. ``Stop looking at me when you talk. Look at
the road, you fool. I'll talk. You drive.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are blessed and lucky, you make it to the team plane _
where that mischievous Darryl Dawkins is informing anyone who will
listen that he is not of this Earth, but instead from ``Lovetron,
baby. You know the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, to be an 80s kind of Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``You needed strong parents to stay sane,'' Williams said,
laughing last week. ``Those were crazy times,'' he added. ``Crazy,
but fun times. Good memories, too. All good.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are indeed blessed and lucky, you play 17 more seasons in
the NBA, buy those strong parents their dream home, send your son
to the same Greenwich, Conn., private school that President Bush
attended and retire with the same dignity you came into the league
with in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets will raise Williams' No. 52 jersey to the Continental
Arena roof Sunday. Fittingly, the team Williams finished his career
with _ the Knicks _ will be in attendance. And some kid with a
Stephon Marbury jersey will ask some kid with a Keith Van Horn
jersey, ``Who's that?'' You only hope their parents will tell them.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming an NBA finals cog in Portland and an invaluable
role player in New York, Williams was the Nets. Eight years, 635
games, 10 team records and more than 10,000 points and nearly 8,000
rebounds. More than that, he was a rock, a stabilizing force for
every team on which he played.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for those wacky kids off the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl should have done standup comedy,'' Williams said of the
colorful center. ``He was a real approachable guy, an ambassador. I
learned a lot from him about dealing with people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows he used to call himself `Chocolate Thunder.'
But the nights he didn't play well, we'd say he was Chocolate
Blunder.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams calls Richardson, the All-Star shooting guard who was
suspended from the league for drug use and still plays in Europe,
his most loyal teammate. He does not remember a more flammable
player than the Richardson, who took the court against the 76ers in
1984, the season the Nets shocked the defending world champions in
a first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   There are other memories: Larry Brown's beckoning him after
practice in those first seasons, saying, ``Young fella, we need to
work on some low-post moves.'' Stan Albeck's giving him and his
teammates the freedom to create on the floor. And that revolving
roster that always kept turning around Williams, the one grounded
player, the descendant of share-croppers who rose from the cotton
fields of Rocky Mount, N.C., and grew into one of the game's
premier rebounders.
</P>
<P>
   His desire to claim a loose ball was trumped only by his
professionalism and class at a time when the NBA sorely needed
both.
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony Sunday, Williams will be accompanied not only by
his wife, Mimi, and their two boys, Julien, 9, and Malek, 6, but
also by his three siblings, Cynthia, Ann and Clyde Williams. He
wishes his parents could be there, too.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Moses Williams, died two years ago at 83, three
years after Buck's mother, Betty, who was 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at your peers and then you see how you turn out, and
you reflect back and realize what kind of people they really
were,'' he said of his parents. ``That's the one missing element.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Buck, they were workers, picking cotton and tobacco when
they both were young. Moses, one of the smartest men Buck knew, had
but a third-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really bright, but he was left-handed,'' Buck said.
``In those days, they wouldn't allow you to write left-handed. The
teacher would crack him on his left hand every time he tried. He
became so frustrated. They needed help on the farm. So he left
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Moses became a concrete finisher and Betty a homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   In a better story than any he could cull from his playing days,
Buck related this one:
</P>
<P>
   His father was working on a set of cement steps outside a new
deluxe home in Rocky Mount, leveling off the concrete just so. The
supervisor of the construction firm, who was white, told Buck's
father not to be so fussy and perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it, Moses,'' he said. ``You won't be living
here. It's too expensive for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Moses Williams, proud he had given Buck a better life than he
had himself, told his grown son this story 17 years ago on those
same concrete steps. That day, with money from his first
professional contract, Buck had bought the home for his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get him to sell the house for years and move into
something bigger, but he wouldn't do it,'' Buck said. ``Too much
sentimental value, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
