<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-CREDENTIAL11-     04-10 1728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-CREDENTIAL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students taught by properly certified teachers tend to pass
TAAS, study shows
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Elementary students in schools with properly
certified teachers _ those teaching in their licensed fields _ were
more likely to pass the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills than
their peers in schools that employed uncertified teachers or those
teaching out of their field, a new statewide analysis shows.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the first in Texas to explore the relationship
between teacher certification and student performance on the TAAS,
does not prove conclusively that a student's ability to pass the
test is directly tied to teacher certification. But researchers who
performed the analysis say it suggests that there is a link.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is pretty clear that teacher certification
matters,'' said Uri Treisman, director of the Charles A. Dana
Center at the University of Texas. Treisman conducted the analysis
and will brief legislators Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are likely to influence major educational policies
Texas lawmakers are considering _ from bills to end social
promotions and increase teacher pay to proposals requiring schools
to tell parents when their children are taught by improperly
certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all this push for accountability, and we've been
leaving out the teacher,'' said Rep. Dianne White Delisi
(R-Temple), who has introduced several bills aimed at enticing more
people into teaching.
</P>
<P>
   About a fifth of the state's students _ 760,000 out of 3.8
million _ were in classes where teachers were not certified in the
1996-97 school year, the analysis showed.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, that meant teachers teaching outside their fields
_ English teachers teaching algebra, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But it also includes professionals embarking on a second career
without formal instruction in education and teachers who have not
yet received their certification.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis by the Dana Center, based on 1996-97 school year
figures provided by the State Board for Educator Certification and
the Texas Education Agency, examined certification of teachers in
elementary, middle and high school and TAAS passage rates for
students in grades three through five.
</P>
<P>
   It showed that at elementary schools where all of the teachers
were properly certified, students tended to pass the TAAS at higher
rates than their peers at schools where significant numbers of
teachers were uncertified or improperly certified.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis also found that the shortage of properly certified
teachers was more acute in some courses, such as bilingual
education and computer classes.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the students in bilingual elementary classes and
secondary computer science classes were taught by uncertified or
improperly certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And high schools with large populations of low-income students
were less likely to have certified teachers than schools with fewer
low-income students, Treisman concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Treisman's analysis comes in the wake of several national and
state studies that increasingly point to the teacher as a major
factor in student achievement. Some researchers are now saying the
teacher is the single most important influence in learning,
surpassing even socioeconomic factors once held out as the key
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that unquestionably matters most is good teachers,''
said Kati Haycock, director of the Education Trust, a Washington
research and advocacy group for low-income students. ``It's the
single most important variable in instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, teachers groups and school administrators have
debated whether it makes a difference if students are taught by
properly certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Education leaders have downplayed the problem in Texas, where
hundreds of thousands of students every year are in classrooms
taught by improperly certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one is required to tell parents when their children are
taught by teachers the state says are not adequately prepared. And
administrators are not volunteering the information for fear of
setting off alarms among parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is telling parents that schools are employing teachers
who are not credentialed in their fields,'' said Haycock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This the deep, dirty secret of American education.''
</P>
<P>
   Because schools with more affluent students are more likely to
get certified teachers than campuses with poorer students, Treisman
said the analysis raises ``very deep and profound questions about
equity: Whose children have access to which teachers?''
</P>
<P>
   In his freshman calculus class, Treisman said, he sees the
results of uncertified or improperly certified teachers among
students who graduated in the top 10 percent of their high school
class. Students with access to certified or experienced math
teachers took advanced math classes in high school, including
calculus, he said. Students with lesser-qualified or uncertified
math teachers took fewer honors math classes primarily because the
schools did not have teachers to instruct those classes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That trend is not unique to Texas. Nationally, schools with high
enrollments of low-income students tend to get the most uncertified
teachers or those who are teaching out of their field, Haycock
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see very clearly is, the poorer the school or the
more kids of color, the less-qualified teachers are,'' she said.
``We routinely are taking the kids who are most dependent upon
their teachers for content learning and we're systematically
assigning them teachers with the weakest content base.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers groups say the analysis confirms what they've known for
years. ``These kids are hit with a triple whammy,'' said John Cole,
president of the Texas Federation of Teachers. ``They are in a
low-wealth school district from an impoverished family and end up
with a teacher who stays one chapter ahead of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi teacher Adrian Fernandez can tell you how it
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Fernandez stepped into his first classroom ready
to use the reading-instruction skills he spent four years honing in
college. But Woodlawn Elementary School needed a third-grade math
teacher. Fernandez, hired as a reading teacher, became a math
teacher by default. That also is how the inexperienced teacher
became the curriculum director for all third-grade math
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had less than two weeks to prepare for my first math
lesson,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Treisman stopped short of saying certified teachers are the most
effective teachers, and no one is claiming certification trumps
experience or other training. But he and others say certification
is a key indicator of a teacher's qualifications and preparation
for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every student who fails to learn is the result of bad
teaching,'' Cole said. ``But you can't teach what you don't know.
That is why certification matters.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials say they prefer to hire properly certified
teachers because they are typically better-trained in their field
than other teachers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a certified high school math teacher has completed
18 semester hours of college mathematics courses, about six
courses. But schools can hire an English teacher who has completed
only six hours _ two courses _ in math to teach an algebra,
geometry or calculus class.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is there aren't enough certified teachers to go
around. A booming economy has compounded the teacher shortage,
especially of certified math and science teachers, who are trading
the classroom for offices _ and fatter paychecks _ in the high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with those factors, lawmakers are not likely to eliminate
exemptions that allow uncertified or improperly certified teachers
_ and in some cases totally unqualified teachers _ into Texas
classrooms. Principals would be unable to open many classrooms each
year if exemptions were outlawed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``School districts aren't hiring uncertified teachers by choice;
they are doing it out of necessity,'' said David Dunn, a spokesman
for the Texas Association of School Boards.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Delisi said superintendents in her Central Texas district
recruit heavily, even outside Texas, but still can't fill their
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are using teachers who may not hold the right
certificate, or in some cases, worse _ substitutes,'' Delisi said.
``And you know what the qualifications are for subs _ nada.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers groups are pushing for legislation requiring schools to
tell parents when their children are being taught by uncertified or
improperly certified teachers _ a move they hope will spur
legislators to address what they say are the root causes of the
teacher shortage: low pay and poor benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents need to be told when an uncertified teacher is
teaching their child so they can rally with us to fix the
problem,'' said Amy White, president of the Association of Texas
Professional Educators.
</P>
<P>
   A similar measure is pending in Congress, which would require
school districts receiving federal dollars to provide parents that
information.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little desire to pass such legislation in Texas
this session, several state leaders said. ``It's not racing through
the Legislature,'' said State Board of Education member Will Davis
of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   To attract and retain more educators, teachers' groups want
legislators to approve a $6,000 across-the-board pay raise to bring
their average $33,648 annual salary from 38th in the nation to the
national average. That proposal has not taken off, either, though
Senate Education Committee Chairman Teel Bivins has proposed a
measure that would give teachers about $2,000 more in take-home pay
by reducing their contribution to their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   And Delisi has introduced a package of incentives aimed at
attracting more college students to the teaching profession and
encouraging teachers to contain their training throughout their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Some say more is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason we have been unwilling to bite the bullet, to
pay the salaries, provide the benefits, to do what it takes to get
our children qualified teachers,'' said Jane Conoley, dean of the
Texas A&AMP;M University College of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
