u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ABORTION-PROTEST-N     04-10 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP LEADS ABORTION PROTEST ON LONG ISLAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHTOWN, N.Y. _ Signaling his willingness to maintain a highly
visible role in the fight against abortion, Bishop James T. McHugh,
the new spiritual leader of Long Island's 1.3 million Roman
Catholics, led a peaceful rally here Saturday morning outside a
Planned Parenthood clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The protest began with a morning Mass at St. Patrick's Roman
Catholic Church here, where McHugh called on 700 members of the
congregation to pray for an end to abortions and ``for the removal
of this dark stain that has cast a blight across our great
country.''
</P>
<P>
   He then led a procession of 250 parishioners from the church to
the clinic. Along the way, the marchers prayed the rosary and
intoned readings from the Stations of the Cross and the ``Prayer
for Life,'' which speaks of ``the vast number of children who have
not been born.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that Bishop McHugh is now with us,'' said Mary
Murphy, of Central Islip, who pushed a stroller carrying her
3-year-old daughter, Megan. ``Abortion is a terrible sin.''
</P>
<P>
   They marched down East Main Street, past the Smithtown Library,
then turned left onto Maple Avenue, where they stopped in front of
the Planned Parenthood medical center. There were 20 patients
inside, said Francine Stein, the president and chief executive of
Planned Parenthood Hudson Peconic, which operates 15 centers in
Suffolk, Putnam, Rockland and Westchester Counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We honor their right to have different beliefs,'' Ms. Stein
said as she watched the prayer vigil from a second-floor window of
the clinic. ``We have no problem with people who protest
peacefully. It's a reaffirmation of the pluralism in our society,
one of freedom and tolerance. We only object when they interfere
with our patients and when they frighten and anger them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein said three patients who had been scheduled for
Saturday morning decided to reschedule because of the protest.
``This is not an ordinary Saturday morning for us,'' she said. ``We
usually have a group of about two dozen protesters, but they only
occasionally bother the patients. Sometimes we even take them
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein was joined at the clinic by six members of a group
called Clergy for Choice, who expressed their support for the work
of Planned Parenthood, which serves more than 33,000 clients at its
15 centers, providing contraceptives, pregnancy tests and
counseling, tests for sexually transmitted diseases, breast exams,
Pap tests, prenatal care and first-trimester abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moral decisions like this cannot be legislated,'' said Clark
Berge of the Episcopalian Society of St. Francis Little Portion
Friary in Mount Sinai. ``The right to choose is sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Noelle Damico of the Congregational United Church of
Christ in Mount Sinai said that Planned Parenthood clinics provided
a variety of services for women. ``Abortion is only one of those
choices, and one that should be considered as a last resort.'' she
said. ``But women should have that choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's protest marked the first active leadership role at a
Long Island abortion rally by McHugh, who was appointed by the
Vatican last December as the coadjutor bishop. He will eventually
succeed the Most Reverend John R. McGann as the bishop of the
Diocese of Rockville Center, which comprises Nassau and Suffolk
Counties.
</P>
<P>
   McHugh was formerly the director of the Family Life Bureau and
the Pro-Life Office of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
in Washington and is credited with developing the church's
political and legal opposition to Roe vs. Wade in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he joined McGann and six other bishops in condemning a
lawsuit filed by New York State Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer
aimed at keeping the antiabortion group Operation Save America from
blocking access to abortion clinics in western New York during a
weeklong protest April 18-25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit denies the right of free speech and denies the
right of public assembly,'' McGann said in a statement distributed
at this morning's service in St. Patrick's Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``All people have the right to express their positions civilly
and peacefully on issues affecting human life,'' he said, urging
the parishioners to join the morning's march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
