<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENVIRONMENT-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FINDS ALLIES IN SEEKING EASIER ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP RULES IN
NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's business leaders have long worked with
their Republican allies in the Capitol in an unsuccessful campaign
to scale back rules requiring companies to conduct extensive
cleanups of polluted industrial sites that they want to develop.
</P>
<P>
   But now business has found a new ally: black and Hispanic
Democrats from poor inner-city neighborhoods where developers say
they would transform abandoned industrial sites into attractive
commercial properties if it were not for the state's stringent
environmental rules.
</P>
<P>
   While business groups and minority leaders differ over the
details of the changes they support, there is growing agreement
that the environmental rules may be stifling economic growth in the
state's inner cities as well as other industrial centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see these properties languish when we have such needs in
our community makes you question the principles that we have
operated under with regard to environmental protection,'' said
Jeffrion L. Aubry, a prominent black Democratic assemblyman from
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to maintain standards of protection for your
community,'' he added. ``But at the same time you want to see these
properties put back into some economic use. So the question is: how
do you spur development of these properties in our community and at
the same time retain the public protections?''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is expected to be one of the most hotly contested
environmental matters the governor and the Legislature take up this
year. The main element in the state's effort to clean up hazardous
waste sites, the Superfund program, is running out of money, and
business leaders are pushing to overhaul its rules and standards as
part of any final agreement to refinance it.
</P>
<P>
   The budding alliance involving minority politicians, business
leaders and civic leaders threatens to fracture the traditional
Democratic alliance with environmentalists and give momentum to
those who want to see the standards eased.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and their allies in the environmental community
have generally held that polluted former industrial properties,
known as brownfields, should be cleaned to a fairly high standard
and that the companies that own them should pay the costs, even if
a previous owner was primarily responsible for the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Business, in turn, has argued that a high cleanup standard is
not needed for brownfields that will be used for factories instead
of homes and that holding property owners fully responsible for the
cleanup costs, no matter their role in the pollution, is sure to
inhibit investment. As evidence, they point to thousands of
industrial tracts that they say have been shunned by developers
because of concerns over legal liability for pollution and
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over brownfields comes as aides to Gov. George
Pataki, a Republican, are preparing legislation to overhaul the
laws governing liability and cleanup standards, ranging from sites
with relatively little toxic waste to those deemed hazardous enough
to qualify for money under the state Superfund program. Pataki and
his aides said he intended to introduce a bill in the current
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The major questions in the debate over brownfields include
whether prospective developers should be granted liability
protections from unforeseen cleanup costs and whether the state
should continue to require all polluted properties to be cleaned to
a single high standard or instead should make the standards
dependent on a site's eventual use. Put another way, does a
brownfield being used to build a gas station need to be as clean as
one being used for a nursery school?
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Shepard, the executive director of the West Harlem
Environmental Action Group, said she supported many of the changes
being sought by business leaders because the current laws are not
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who argue that brownfields should be
cleaned up to pristine conditions,'' Ms. Shepard said. ``And in a
perfect world, we would like to return some of them to pristine
conditions. But I think the bottom line should be a cleanup that
protects public health while promoting economic development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
