<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULKNER-QUOTES-1STLEDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The quotable Faulkner
 &HT;    (EDs: Replaces first version FAULKNER-QUOTES11-COX.)
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Some comments from Larry Faulkner during his first year as
president of the University of Texas:
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what you get. I think I'm fairly
straightforward.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March 26, interview
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas as a society places a greater emphasis on athletics than
other societies, more than Illinois but maybe not more than
Michigan. The trick is to carry it out without corrupting the
character of the institution. Athletics is very powerful as a tool
for unifying a community. That's why universities put up with all
that they do.''
</P>
<P>
   March 26 interview
</P>
<P>
   ``As many of you are aware, when students are gone is one of the
nicest times on a university campus.''
</P>
<P>
   To members of the American Astronomical Society visiting UT
during winter break, Jan. 6
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bet this university will be here after a large number
of enterprises in this room are not.''
</P>
<P>
   To high-technology executives at the Alpha.360 Summit, Jan. 5
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that America and Texas will be healthier if we can
find methods that do not involve race as a criterion in admissions
or financial aid, yet succeed in promoting inclusion and diversity
as well as (or better than) the established race-sensitive
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Written statement on affirmative action, Nov. 16, 1998
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us make this place more than a university of the first
class. Let's take it to the head of the class. . . . Our
competition is intelligent, experienced and visionary. We must not
deceive ourselves that we will be able to compete consistently,
year after year, for the talent and facilities that Texas needs
against the best universities in America with 70 percent of their
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   State of the University speech, Oct. 6, 1998
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real jewel of a university, and my priority as its
president will be to keep it that way and to help the people of
Texas understand what they have in this marvelous place.''
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 16, 1997, the day the regents voted to hire him
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
