<HEADER>
A3380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-CERTIFICATION     04-10 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-CERTIFICATION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher certification requires degree, tests
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To be certified, or licensed, to teach in Texas,
candidates must:
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   _ Complete a state-approved teacher-education program at a
university or an alternative program run by some colleges, large
school districts and Texas Education Agency regional service
centers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pass certification exams testing their knowledge of their
content area and of teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching without certification
</P>
<P>
   School districts are allowed to hire uncertified teachers for
specific assignments. The districts must obtain special permits:
</P>
<P>
   _ Emergency permit: The teacher is not certified at all or not
certified at the correct grade level. Good for up to three years,
depending on how much training he or she lacks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Temporary classroom assignment permit: Teacher is certified
but not in the subject area in which he or she is teaching. Good
for one year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nonrenewable permit: The teacher has completed most
requirements for certification, except passing certification exams.
Good for six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Temporary exemption permit: The teacher's previous assignment
no longer exists because of fluctuations in enrollment or course
offerings. Valid for one year.
</P>
<P>
   _ School district teaching permit: Issued by school district to
``unique, highly qualified persons.'' Requires a bachelor's degree
and work experience to match what will be taught. May be denied by
the state education commissioner. Valid indefinitely, but not
transferable across districts.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute teachers
</P>
<P>
   Districts can hire substitutes to teach classes temporarily or
for the long term when a teacher cannot be found. Districts often
use retired teachers or college graduates. But in many cases,
districts hire high school graduates who have little or no college
education.
</P>
<P>
   Source: State Board for Educator Certification, staff research
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
