<P>
   (NYT8) NAPLES, Fla. -- April 10, 1999 -- SKATE-SCANDAL, 4-10 --
Former skater Craig Maurizi, 36, who is now Tara Lipinski's coach,
has come forward to claim that his working relationship with
Richard Callaghan, one of the dominant figures in skating, involved
inappropriate sexual conduct with him when Maurizi was 15.
Callaghan, who has retained a lawyer, vehemently denies that he
ever had sex with Maurizi. ``I don't care how old a student is,
whether it's a boy or a girl, a coach should never have sex with a
student,'' says Maurizi. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 10, 1999 -- NY-GIRLS-SCHOOLS-2, 4-10 --
At the coeducational Manhattan Country School, teachers are trained
to give the same attention to gender issues as they give to race.
Although recent research shows that boys and girls both thrive in
good coed schools, many parents with daughters have concluded that
single-sex schooling will help ensure that their daughters have
room to shine. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- April 10, 1999 -- NY-GIRLS-SCHOOLS-1, 4-10 --
Kindergarten girls at Marymount School in Manhattan have a science
class all to themselves. At Manhattan's seven private girls'
schools, competition is high for kindergarten openings that cost
$17,000 a year or more. Although coed schools defend themselves as
being more in step with the modern world and say they represent the
most basic diversity in education, most of the city's private coed
schools have made explicit efforts to ensure that girls will not be
overshadowed. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- April 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CAMPUS-2,
4-10 -- Students waiting their turn to ask questions at a
``teach-in'' on the Kosovo crisis at Rutgers University in New
Brunswick, N.J. Organizers had set up seats for 80 students but
wound up drawing more than 400. For many students the ``teach-in''
amounted to a crash course on the hundreds of years of Balkan
conflict that preceded NATO's bombing of Serbia. (Laura Pedrick/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- April 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CAMPUS-1,
4-10 -- Academic experts leading a ``teach-in'' on the Kosovo
crisis at Rutgers University in New Brunswick, N.J. Organizers had
set up seats for 80 students but wound up drawing more than 400.
For many students the ``teach-in'' amounted to a crash course on
the hundreds of years of Balkan conflict that preceded NATO's
bombing of Serbia. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- April 10, 1999 -- CALIF-GAS-PRICES, 4-10
-- Gasoline prices, rising nationwide, are highest in California,
much to the dismay of drivers like Jonni Mae in Los Angeles. In
late February, fires and production problems at refineries in the
state, coupled with the overall increase in crude prices, began to
drive up the price. ``The prices are astronomical,'' says Mae, 46,
a business owner, after paying $9 for five gallons of
super-unleaded gas. ``I have to spend the money. But I hate to
spend the money.'' (Ed Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 10, 1999 -- BBO-STOLEN-BAT, 4-10 --
Jason Grimsley, a relief pitcher with the New York Yankees, holding
a picture of umpire Dave Phillips confiscating the illegally corked
bat of Grimsley's 1994 Cleveland Indians teammate Albert Belle.
Grimsley acknowledges that it was he who crawled through the
innards of Chicago's Comiskey Park into the umpires' dressing room
on July 15, 1994, to exchange an illegally corked bat of his
Cleveland Indians teammate Albert Belle for one that was cork-free.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BEIJING -- April 10, 1999 -- CHINA-SEX, 4-10 -- Qiao Yue,
38, stocking his new ``adult health store'' in West Beijing.
``People used to think that once they had their kid, that was it,
sex was over. But people's attitudes toward sex have changed
dramatically,'' says Qiao. ``Customers used to throw money on the
table and run out embarrassed. Now it's more like buying clothes.
They ask questions. Can they return merchandise? Is there a
warranty? That sort of thing.'' (Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
