<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTERS-ROPES11-COX     04-10 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTERS-ROPES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans stake their claims in Augusta land rush
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ You don't have to go to Spain for the running of
the bulls. Just show up at Augusta National Golf Club a few hours
before the gates open.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of fans from all over the world congregate along
Washington and Berckmans roads, waiting for the gates to open and
their perennial sprint to their favorite spot on the course. For
diehard spectators, the best observation points are claimed hours
before the first player tees off.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Rogers flew in from San Francisco and stands inches away
from the green door just before 7 a.m. Saturday, just as he has for
five Masters. He clutches two chairs, one to sit on at the first
tee, the other for later at the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as much tradition as anything,'' he says. ``But I don't
know if I want to tell my secrets to the newspaper. Then everyone
will know.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd around him grows belligerent, pointing to their
watches, peeking through a gap in the gate to yell at the Pinkerton
guards. ``Hello! Hello!'' they shout. ``The other gates are open!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the donuts we gave them didn't work,'' one fan
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Once allowed in, they hurriedly march through the parking lot,
only to wait another 30 minutes at the club entrance. The course
opens at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell y'all not to run,'' says an exasperated
security guard, ``but y'all are going to run anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be competitive,'' Rogers confides. ``They've said
`no running' for years, but people start to run anyway. And that's
a real bummer. When there was never anyone running there was an
equal chance to get your chairs set.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone clutches at least one folding seat, most of them green.
Next to the Masters badge, it's a fan's most critical accessory.
Fast feet help, too. A legend circulates about a 77-year-old man
who measured the distance between the entrance and his favorite
spot, and practiced running that span for several months. He got
there first.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's got their strategy. ``You don't want to get boxed
out,'' says Drew Hoffman. He and three buddies grip a couple dozen
chairs destined for the 18th green, where clients of their Ohio
relocation service will sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My future,'' adds Hoffman's coworker Tim Hinkley, ``depends on
that first row.'' It seemed inevitable that the popularity of the
Masters would spawn the corporate chair-saver.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the guards stand back and the fans pour forth. The
guards yell at them to walk, but after a few steps, they take off
again. In five minutes, there's a ring of seats six deep on the
18th green.
</P>
<P>
   Others make a beeline to the first tee, or fan out to the back
nine. They blow by the newcomers still clutching their maps, trying
to figure out which hole to go to. They are sweating and huffing
and puffing as they pop their seats up.
</P>
<P>
   Soon there are more folding chairs than at a college graduation.
At 8:21 a.m., it's hard to find a decent spot around the large,
par-3 16th green. Even though it's still being mowed and the hole
hasn't been cut, veteran spectators know Saturday's traditional pin
position is back right, and they cluster there.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have sat in the same spot so many years that they've
put down roots. Bland Massie, 71, of Fort Valley, kept up with the
vacations, children, divorces and deaths of nine friends he made in
20 years near the 15th green.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition ended this year when trees replaced the mound
where his group sat, and they scattered to other spots. Massie now
sits farther back on the 16th green, partly because he can't get
there as quickly. ``I ran until I was 69,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Once set up, a chair is more grounded than a pioneer's stake in
the Oklahoma land rush. Spectators move about freely in the hours
before the players appear, knowing that no one will move their
seat. It's a tradition as revered as the green jacket, because
everyone respects the perspiration and strategy involved in getting
it there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
