<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SHOULD TAKE A LONG LOOK AT SHORT AGGIES LINEBACKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ History is on Dat Nguyen's side. So is
geography. So, obviously, are college credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a long story for the Cowboys, and the short version is
this: They blew it years ago on Baylor's Mike Singletary, who
wasn't tall enough by Valley Ranch computerized standards.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, it was Texas Tech's 5-foot-10 Zach Thomas who
failed to measure up to the ``mike'' (middle linebacker) minimum of
6-foot-1.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Ranch management of another era had to eat a load of crow
as Singletary was playing his way into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame. Gil Brandt is still wondering how that much heart was crammed
into a 5-10 frame. It simply didn't compute on Gil's P.C.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary was 90 miles down the road in Waco. The Cowboys had
four college seasons to watch him, but they never looked beyond
Singletary's supposed lack of height. In that same 1981 draft that
the Bears took Singletary in the second round, the Cowboys went
heavy for linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you remember the likes of Scott Pelluer, 6-1; Derrie
Nelson, 6-2; Danny Spradlin, 6-1; Paul Piurowski, 6-2. When that
kind of tall-enough talent is available, why gamble on a runt from
Baylor?
</P>
<P>
   Three Aprils ago, Zach Thomas was still undrafted in the fifth
round when Jimmy Johnson grabbed him for the Dolphins. Even in his
rookie season, it was obvious the rest of the league screwed up on
Thomas, a bona fide football player. But again, he was in the
Cowboys' back yard, making the local miss doubly bad.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Texas A&AMP;M's linebacking machine, Mr. Nguyen.
Along with many of the top college players in the country, Nguyen
was a Valley Ranch guest on Friday as the Cowboys were sizing up
talent for next weekend's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Among the linebackers, Rahim Abdullah of Clemson was here. He's
6-5. So was the highly acclaimed Chris Claiborne of USC, at 6-2.
And Northwestern's Barry Gardner, a tick under 6-1. And the huge
Andy Katzenmoyer of Ohio State, standing over 6-3. Another hot name
was Jevon Kearse of Florida, who is nearly 6-5 and also plays end.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was ``little'' Dat. Barely 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   So how do the Cowboys play this in the draft? Do they take a
blood oath not to miss out on another high-profile linebacker from
a Texas college, just because he's 5-11 instead of 6-1?
</P>
<P>
   But if they want Dat Nguyen, and every indication is they do,
then do you ``reach'' in the second round? Would he still be there
in the third? Could they wait until the fourth?
</P>
<P>
   One Valley Ranch voice said when the entire Cowboys draft team _
coaches, scouts and Jerry Jones _ broke down on film every
available linebacker, Nguyen was rated the most ``productive''
college player of all. But are the Cowboys scared of 5-11? Sure
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lacewell, the team's director of scouting, said, ``Here's
the deal on Dat Nguyen _ no matter what round he goes, the draft
gurus will immediately say it's too high, that it's a reach. But
wherever we take him, I don't care what the gurus will have to say
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after three months of intense personal scrutiny for this
draft, Nguyen could still laugh Friday when asked if he was weary
of being labeled ``too short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave me 5-11 and told me that's what I had to work with,''
he replied. ``Actually, I'm proud of it. I'd like to be able to
stretch out to that prototype NFL size of 6-4, but there has never
been a perfect physical specimen in football. Even if you are 6-4,
there's always something that doesn't measure up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen has been college football's special story. The son of
Vietnamese refugees who settled on the Texas coast, he will be the
first of his nationality ever to play in the NFL. And was only the
second to play major college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as a miracle ride so far, and no matter what
happens on draft day, some team is going to give me a chance. ...
at least I hope so,'' said Nguyen. ``In what round you are drafted
is obviously important. But for me, getting the opportunity is the
big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen is currently 230 pounds, and despite some NFL clubs
saying he played at 215 at A&AMP;M, he laughed when told there were
reports he ``beefed up'' for the draft. So did R.C. Slocum, his
college coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dat was 230 here,'' said Slocum. ``Shortness is the only knock
any NFL team can have on Dat. He has the size, just not the height
the NFL likes. But all the other football credentials are there.
Plus, there will not be a player of higher personal character
involved in this or any other draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want Dat Nguyen, 5-11 and all. By the draft's second
round on Saturday, we start finding out how much they regret
Singletary and Thomas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
