<HEADLINE>
RACE IS RIGHT ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALLEN WOLFE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ There's something fishy going on with the
Long Beach Grand Prix course this year.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing sinister or suspect; it's just that the downtown
Long Beach street circuit has been modified and lengthened since
last year's race, so a portion of the track will loop around the
new Aquarium of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic change is in the turn 1 area at the end of the
Shoreline Drive straightaway. Instead of turning right into the
Pine Avenue parking area, drivers will take a sharp left turn and
proceed in a loop around the aquarium complex. Seven new turns had
to be created to complete the process before linking up with
Seaside Way.
</P>
<P>
   The revised city-street circuit is now 1.85 miles and 11 turns
as opposed to last year's configuration of 1.59 miles and eight
turns. Surprisingly, only grandstands 2, 5, 6 and 7 were affected
by the change.
</P>
<P>
   It took nine weeks for Dwight Tanaka, vice president of
operations for the Grand Prix Association of Long Beach, and his
four foremen and crew of 30 to build the circuit. In addition to
the concrete barriers and safety fence, the track also features 21
spectator grandstands, six spectator-pedestrian bridges, 12
television/photo towers, eight big-screen vision boards and 61 VIP
corporate hospitality and viewing suites.
</P>
<P>
   This race marks Tanaka's 21st year as construction supervisor
and it proved to be one of his most challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally had to build a city within a city, with an
infrastructure capable of supporting 300,000-plus people,'' said
Tanaka. ``We take great pride in providing a world-class facility
for our competitors, sponsors and spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new course should be an exciting circuit for the drivers
and fans. With a longer front stretch down Shoreline (Drive), an
opportunity is present to reach higher speeds, then going into turn
1, drivers will have to brake hard to turn left and go around the
aquarium's parking facility. The additional turns will also make
for more competitive racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many interested parties had to be satisfied before the project
could go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to work closely with many city entities to decide what
the most challenging, exciting and safest course would be for
all,'' said Chris Pook, president and CEO of the Grand Prix
Association of Long Beach. ``This is the first change we have made
to the course since 1992. Officials from the City of Long Beach,
Aquarium, Shoreline Village, Oliver McMillan (developer of the
Queensway Bay project) and SMG (operators of the Long Beach
Entertainment and Convention Center) provided input.''
</P>
<P>
   The circuit safety system is unique and at the cutting edge for
city street events around the country. The basic safety elements
have remained unchanged since they were developed and introduced by
Dr. Peter Talbot, a Menlo Park doctor, for the first race in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit is lined by 1,800 concrete blocks, each one 12 feet
long and weighing 8,100 pounds. All are fitted with debris fence
poles on which 10 miles of cable is tightly strung. Three miles of
catch fencing is then strapped in place above the blocks; the
result is a safety system that protects competitors and fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Also lining the circuit are 250 tire crash barriers (64 tires
per pallet) that are strategically positioned at turns and runoff
areas. Dr. Talbot referred to the energy-absorbing tire piles as
``spherical elastic attenuators.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRAND PRIX COMPONENTS
</P>
<P>
   __ The course is 1.85-miles with 11 turns.
</P>
<P>
   __ Crews used 14,580,000 tons of concrete blocks to construct
the course.
</P>
<P>
   __ Circuit perimeters are made of 1,800 concrete blocks, each 12
feet long and weighing 8,100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   __ More than three miles of catch fencing line the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   __ More than 10 miles of steel cable are used to support the
debris fencing.
</P>
<P>
   __ 250 tire barriers with 64 tires per pallet are positioned in
key areas around the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   __ Six spectator-pedestrian bridges cross the race circuit, some
up to 120 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   __ Twenty-one spectator grandstands seat 63,000.
</P>
<P>
   __ Twelve television/photo towers around the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   __ Eight vision boards, ranging in size from 11 feet by 14 feet
to 20 feet by 30 feet, for spectator viewing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sixty-one VIP corporate hospitality suites.
</P>
<P>
   __ Approximately 30 hospitality tents are erected around the
circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
