<HEADLINE>
MOCHA EXPRESS ONE OF STARS FROM '98 BACK FOR RETURN TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Every year at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie, new horses become stars.
</P>
<P>
   But for 1999, many stakes heroes from last year will be
returning for encores.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express was chosen horse of the meeting for last summer's
thoroughbred season, and is preparing to run April 18 in the Texas
Mile at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Marlon St. Julien `` has been working him, and he seems
to be doing really good,'' trainer Tim Harder said.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express won the Lone Star Park Handicap and Assault Stakes
last season, and recently won a stakes on grass at Turf Paradise in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Artica, owned by Royce Roberts and trained by Tony Richey, is
expected to defend her Irving Distaff title on opening weekend. She
also won the Fort Worth Handicap at Lone Star last year.
</P>
<P>
   Richey is also bringing back Allen Bogan Memorial winner Chief
Three Sox, who recently took a fast allowance at Oaklawn Park.
</P>
<P>
   Mastery's Gamble is another being pointed for the Irving
Distaff. The 7-year-old mare notched victories in the Two Altazano
Stakes and Texas Legends Stakes a year ago at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a hard-knocking old gal,'' trainer Tommie Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Again expected to be among the top filly-and-mare turf runners
is the consistent come-from-behinder Sarah Lane's Oates, coming off
a productive winter at Fair Grounds. Also back for more is
Spiritbound, the gutsy sprinter who won the 1997 Crescent Stakes
and 1998 Grand Prairie Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Dallas Keen, who tied with Jim Gaston atop the races-won
standings last summer, could have one of the best older handicap
horses on the grounds in Allen's Oop, a long shot third-place
finisher in the New Orleans Handicap while only a neck behind Real
Quiet. He is scheduled to run next in the Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Keen stakes runners are 3-year-old filly Keenski and
3-year-old Valhol, a maiden who ran fourth in the Louisiana Derby
and was scheduled to compete yesterday in the Arkansas Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The stables of trainers Steve Asmussen and Mike Stidham should
again pack a powerful punch.
</P>
<P>
   Asmussen's stakes horses include turf mare Swearingen,
3-year-old filly Dreams Gallore, and female sprinters Little Sister
and Western Bowl. Stidham won three Texas Champions Day races last
fall with Letterhead, Lone Star Derby candidate Desert Demon and
Waynes Classy Girl, and they are expected to be joined at Lone Star
by Razorback Handicap winner Desert Air.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for Texas-bred sprinter Beverly Greedy, a winner of three
consecutive races at Oaklawn, to surface in Texas-bred stakes
races.
</P>
<P>
   And trainer Donnie Von Hemel could be loaded this summer, if
everything works according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank, Lone Star's champion grass horse of 1997, is in
training and will be ready to resume his career in early-season
Lone Star races.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a break over the winter and took it easy down in
Florida like rich people do,'' Von Hemel said.
</P>
<P>
   Other familiar Von Hemel horses that could appear in stakes
races are Sir Tiff, Illusive Ghost, Leave A Legacy and Toll Booth
Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Custer, who took the Alysheba Breeders' Cup Stakes last May
before he was sidelined by surgery for a condylar fracture of a
leg, has suffered another training setback and probably won't be
seen until the latter part of the meeting, Von Hemel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get them all to the races,'' Von Hemel said, ``they
could be a force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
