</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-MARTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY EDDIE MARTIN BETTER THAN EVER AFTER MISHAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie fans saw jockey
Eddie Martin, he lay motionless on the infield grass course.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was thrown from his mount in a gruesome chain-reaction
spill last May 31. He hit the ground hard, and then apparently was
kicked in the head and trampled by a trailing horse.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the grandstand who witnessed the accident feared the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying, `Man, that dude's dead,' '' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Unconscious but alive, Martin was hurt badly enough that he
needed four months of recuperation and therapy before doctors
permitted him to return to the saddle. Despite those unpleasant
memories from his first Lone Star season, Martin, a 35-year-old New
Orleans native, is returning for the 1999 thoroughbred meet
beginning Thursday. He's not only competing again; he comes into
the Lone Star meet as one of the hottest jockeys in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ranks ninth nationally in races won, 75, and 12th in
purses earned, $2,084,695. He finished second in the standings at
Fair Grounds in New Orleans with 98 winners, compared with 44 for
Marlon St. Julien, Lone Star's leading jockey last summer. Martin
also notched the biggest win of his career last month, guiding
Precocity to a New Orleans Handicap upset over Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are really booming right now,'' Martin said. ``I've got
quite a few clients to work for, so I'm just hoping the Fair
Grounds meet can carry over into Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was doing well last year, too, before I wiped out.'`
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who ran third at the Fair Grounds a year ago, has no
memories of the spill that nearly killed him. He has no
recollection of a conversation with trainer Bobby Barnett minutes
before the sixth race, or of leaving the gate aboard
Nightstargazer, whose legs became tangled with another horse
running into the first turn.
</P>
<P>
   When paramedics arrived at his side, Martin was unconscious. His
protective riding helmet was cracked in half, his shoulder was
dislocated, his nose was shattered and his face and head were
beginning to swell.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Dottie, who was six months pregnant at the time, had
spent that afternoon birthday-shopping in New Orleans for their
10-year-old son, Beau. When they returned to their house in Kenner,
La., their Caller ID unit registered 40 telephone calls from
friends in Kentucky, Illinois, West Virginia and even Canada who
had been watching the Lone Star race via simulcast.
</P>
<P>
   As the wife of a jockey, Dottie Martin said she ``pretty much
knew what had happened before I returned the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Dottie was given only sketchy details of her husband's condition
over the phone. She couldn't get a flight to Dallas until 9 p.m.
When she finally arrived at Methodist Hospital, she was so
traumatized at the sight of her husband that she went into false
labor that night and had to be treated with medication to stop the
contractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on a ventilator,'' she recalls, ``and he was one big
bruise from head to toe. I wasn't expecting that. Even the whites
of his eyes were swollen. I didn't know the whites of someone's
eyes could be swollen over the pupils, but they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors diagnosed Martin with severe swelling of the two frontal
lobes of his brain, the rough equivalent of a massive concussion.
He was fed intravenously and kept in a drug-induced coma for two
weeks to calm his movements and permit his injured brain to heal
properly.
</P>
<P>
   He responded only to an emergency-room nurse named Nicole, who
had been the first voice he heard upon arriving at the hospital.
She visited Martin to feed and shave him, even on her days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he finally came out \Rof the coma\S,'' Dottie said, ``at
first he was calling me Linda and Marilyn and Madison. He never did
get the name right. It's a good thing I don't know any of those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As a younger rider, Martin had overcome occasional battles with
substance abuse, but coming back from these injuries was a far
different challenge. He was airlifted to a hospital in New Orleans
after coming out of his coma, and when finally released a month
after the accident, he was weak from inactivity. The reflexes so
important to his profession were as slow as those of a punch-drunk
fighter because of the nature of the injury and the heavy doses of
morphine he had received.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse told Martin that a bedridden person loses a percentage
of their strength for each day they are on their back.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I laid on my back for a good 25 days,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star's insurance company picked up the medical bills for
Martin, which totaled about $100,000. Still, the family went four
months without a paycheck, other than $275 weekly provided by
insurance and the Jockey's Guild. Martin said he was fortunate that
he had done well enough in the previous months to put money away as
a contingency.
</P>
<P>
   Martin underwent physical and occupational therapy during July,
August and September.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst part of all, getting him to calm down and
relax,'' Dottie said. ``Eddie's an active person, and he wasn't
allowed to drive or do anything physical, not even sweep outside.
He was real angry, thinking he was OK and they were telling him,
`No, you're not.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I could have returned a lot sooner than I did,''
Eddie said, ``but I had many neurosurgeons and doctors who were
very cautious about my recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   At last, Martin made it back to the races, riding a horse for
owner and trainer Louis Roussel on Sept. 28 at Louisiana Downs in
Bossier City. Two days later, daughter Alexandra was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a beautiful baby, and everything has worked out all
right,'' said Dottie, who nevertheless wishes her husband would
find a new line of work.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a happy ending that will get even happier this summer
if Martin can keep his hot streak going. At Lone Star, he is
expected to ride many of the horses trained by Roussel, Sam David
Jr., Tom Amoss and Troy Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no hard feelings against Lone Star, and I'm looking
forward to returning,'' he said. ``A lot of people from the track
visited me in the hospital, and they even bought my son tickets to
Six Flags. Lone Star is first-class, and puts on a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin seems most concerned that others at Lone Star who saw the
Memorial Day weekend wreck might feel sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't like that,'' he said. ``People have to understand
that my job is so dangerous, things like this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin could avoid pity by carrying with him a copy of the
latest national jockey standings.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
