<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     04-10 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ACCUSED OF DOING WHAT MANY TEAMS DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No teams have admitted to ratting on the Cowboys and none are
likely to, either, since most have been guilty of the same thing
Jerry Jones is doing. Getting a verbal agreement, then working to
free up cap room has been common practice since the advent of NFL
free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Examples:
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans agreed to terms with linebacker Eddie
Robinson on March 1. The contract wasn't filed with the league
until March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Panthers agreed to terms with defensive end Antonio
Edwards on Feb. 20. It was officially reported on March 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys are doing what a lot of teams do,'' said an NFL
personnel director who asked for anonymity. ``There's nothing
wrong. We all do it. You're trying to find ways to clear money
before you actually sign the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Quentin Coryatt has spent a lot of time at Valley Ranch,
but this off-season isn't the first time that's happened. Coryatt
and Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith are best friends and former
college roommates at A&AMP;M. Coryatt has spent time living at Smith's
home and has accompanied him to work out at Valley Ranch on many
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret, however, that Coryatt and Rocket Ismail are
indeed house-shopping in the Valley Ranch area.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual signings of linebacker Coryatt, wide receiver
Ismail and center Mark Stepnoski will mark this off-season as the
franchise's biggest ever. The Cowboys have never before added three
bona fide star free agents, never added three starters or paid this
type of money at one time to multiple players.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the Cowboys have focused on re-signing their own
free agents. These three players will fill three of the most
pressing needs on the team and will allow them to go into the draft
in position to take the best player available rather than drafting
for need as they have so often in the past.
HANSEN REALLY UNPLUGGED
</P>
<P>
   Dale Hansen, whose one-hour special Friday night on WFAA/Channel
8 was billed as the show that ``might get me fired,'' was livid
with his bosses after one of his wisecracks was cut from the final
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the heck does the Dow Jones go from 7,500 to 10,000 in
six months,'' Hansen asked his live audience, ``and Belo \Rthe
company that owns Channel 8\S drops a buck and a half?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a mild titter from the audience, which set up Hansen's
real punchline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry, you don't have to laugh,'' Hansen shot back.
``That'll never make the air anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may get over this,'' Hansen fumed after learning of the cut,
``and I may not.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, the promo might still be right on the money.
NO HOME SWEET HOME
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth minor-league hockey scene is in disarray after
Fire owner Dave Elmore closed down his franchise, ostensibly
because of a ludicrous lawsuit filed by the Brahmas over the Fire's
grade-school program. Lawyers say the suit was sure to be thrown
out of court, but it gave Elmore, a reluctant owner anyway, the
perfect excuse to dump a franchise that had never made money in its
seven years here.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the city to the Brahmas and Andy Moog _ the
franchise's majority owner is a New York broker named Stuart
Frasier, but Moog, the former Stars goalie, is the high-profile
minority owner _ but that's still an uneasy situation.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the city seems to give a hoot. The Brahmas have been
forced to play some of their playoff games in Plano and even in
Reunion Arena because the city has booked so many dates at either
the Convention Center or Will Rogers. The Brahmas have a right to
feel like orphans. They are essentially without a home.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be too shocked when Moog dumps this little experiment.
Most people in and around the situation say he is in this to gain
experience with hopes of jumping to the NHL and a nice front-office
position.
NOT JUST A NUMBER
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates was a backup Braves catcher in 1974
when Hank Aaron hit his record-breaking 715th home run. He was
standing just to Tom House's left when the then-Braves reliever
caught the most famous home-run ball in history.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was paying much attention when Aaron later hit No. 726 in
Atlanta toward the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball hit the back wall \Rof the bullpen\S and rolled
away,'' Oates recalled. ``Nobody went after it. I strolled over and
put it in my back pocket, because I'm thinking, `Hey, this might be
his last one.' But he hit another one in San Diego, No. 727, into
the stands.'' (The next season, Aaron went over to the American
League with the Brewers and hit 22 more before his retirement.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I have that ball at home in my den _ I've only kept maybe
half-a-dozen things through the years _ and all it says on it is
the number sign and `726' that I wrote under the label, Official
National League Baseball.'''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON, WE HAVE A PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   Former Ranger Mike Stanley, now with the Red Sox, was sitting in
his hotel room in Kansas City last weekend when ``I went into the
bathroom and water was streaming out of the ceiling above the light
fixture. I called up the front desk and said, `Houston, we have a
problem.' '' It seems that Red Sox rookie Lou Merloni, who had the
room just above Stanley, had turned on the hot water in the shower
to steam the wrinkles out of his pants. One problem: He didn't open
the drain before leaving to spend 40 minutes working out in a
health club.
</P>
<P>
   NEVER `LEFT' OUT
Two quotes emphasizing the importance of training your male
children to throw left-handed:
</P>
<P>
   Oakland and former Rangers pitcher Kenny Rogers: ``I don't want
to pitch until I'm 50, but I'm left-handed, so I guess I almost
could if I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin on prospect Mike Venafro:
``Tom Schieffer asked me if he could pitch in the majors. I said,
`He's left-handed, and he's 23. He's got 17 more years to prove it.
He's got at least until he's Tony Fossas' age, doesn't he?''
DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   Close friends of both say there's still been no reconciliation
between former Rangers and longtime friends Larry Parrish and Buddy
Bell after the relationship foundered once Parrish replaced Bell as
Tigers manager. ... Yankees owner George Steinbrenner still won't
return Don Zimmer's calls after the two clashed over whether Hideki
Irabu should be replaced in the rotation by Ramiro Mendoza. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ever the diplomat, former Ranger Will Clark made sure that two
cases of Bud Light were loaded on the Cuban bus after the Orioles'
exhibition game in Havana. ... Clark's wearing No. 12 with the
Orioles because his favorite number, 22, was once worn by Jim
Palmer and has been retired.
</P>
<P>
   TCU has joined the bidding on the WAC baseball tournament with
the idea of bringing in lights to attract more fans to the Frog
diamond. ... Vladimir Jaksic, the sharpshooting TCU hoops forward,
plans to spend the summer back home in Croatia. He says he won't be
in the war zone, but you can imagine the nervousness his decision
has caused at TCU. ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers rookie Fernando Tatis is off to a terrific start
(three homers in the Cardinals' first three games) following an
ugly winter season in Puerto Rico, which included rumors that he
was spending too many late nights out on the town. ... Addendum to
last week's note on Steve Busby doing the postgame call-in show on
KRLD: Buzz is working with Kate Delaney following home games; Jack
Lazorko, who works for the Rangers, will continue to join her
following road games.
</P>
<P>
   REVO'S RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Problem with WFAA/Channel 8's Dale Hansen taping an hour-long
special at Las Colinas hotspot Cool River, as he did Thursday for
Friday night's show, is that his bar tab afterward _ he's a
generous host _ invariably blows out the station budget. Or at
least it would if Hansen didn't pony up out of his own pocket. He
won't say how high it went, but with seven bottles of Dom Perignon
on the tab and a $464 tip, you do the math.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Chipper Jones, watching Tiger Woods struggle to
hit batting practice pitching during an appearance in the Braves'
camp this spring, turned to Atlanta first baseman Ryan Klesko and
said, ``I can play golf better than he can hit.'' Maybe so,
Chipper, but more important, Tiger can play golf better than you
can hit.
</P>
<P>
   _ When EA Sports ran 50 PlayStation simulations using its March
Madness 99 game, Duke reached the Final Four 34 times, the
championship game 31 times and won the title 29 times. Goes to show
you that a virtual lock doesn't always translate into real time.
</P>
<P>
   _ The judge in the Dennis Rodman-Carmen Electra divorce case
faces a difficult decision in splitting up community property. Who
gets the Frederick's of Hollywood lingerie collection?
</P>
</TEXT>
