<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, IN DIG AT GORE, SAYS HE THINKS BIG 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley cast himself
Saturday as the candidate of big, ambitious ideas in a
not-so-subtle contrast with Vice President Al Gore, who has
recently put forward several relatively small-bore policy
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   At a convention here of the New Hampshire Democratic Party,
Bradley, thus far the only rival to Gore for the Democratic Party
presidential nomination, recited a litany of bold accomplishments
led by his party, from Social Security to the Marshall Plan to
racial integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the small things but the big challenges,''
Bradley declared to nearly 500 people gathered in the state that
holds the first presidential primary. ``We must remember: We've
done the big things in the past. We can do the big things in the
future.'' He added, ``The role of the President is not to shrink
from challenges but to confront challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention here was the first event of the 2000 campaign
that drew large entourages from the Bradley and Gore camps,
including caravans of exuberant college students. Gore's aides said
he had a previous commitment, but his wife, Tipper, appeared in his
place.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Mrs. Gore would not talk specifically about
Bradley's comments about her husband, saying, ``probably Senator
Bradley has his own ideas, and I respect that.'' But she lauded the
vice president's proposals as touching issues that people ``feel
deeply in their daily lives.'' As the campaign progresses, Mrs.
Gore said, her husband will have more time to spell out his vision
on foreign policy, education and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley took care not to mention Gore by name, his
advisers said the theme of big versus small ideas may emerge as a
central one of his campaign. In his speech, Bradley, a former
senator from New Jersey, touched on ambitious goals like improving
race relations, restoring trust in government and cleaning up the
way campaigns are financed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been criticized by some Democrats, as well as by
Republicans, for following the example of President Clinton in the
1996 campaign and advancing popular but relatively narrow measures
not traditionally the province of a president, like requiring
better passenger service on airlines and taking steps to alleviate
traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Whouley, a senior adviser to the Gore campaign, was more
direct than Mrs. Gore in responding to Bradley. ``Senator Bill
Bradley is a very intelligent man,'' Whouley said. ``But for
someone who's short on specifics but eloquent in rhetoric, it's
interesting that he has taken shots at our specifics when he hasn't
articulated any of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Gore at a news conference after the speech, Bradley
expanded upon his vision for a president with big ideas. ``The
issue is what is your focus?'' he said. ``It's not how many
positions you have on how many issues. And my focus is on big
things.'' But, noting that he had ``been on a lot of planes
lately,'' he joked that he might go along with Gore's airline
passengers' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   In her only jab at Bradley, Mrs. Gore acknowledged ``all the
Princeton kids who are here.'' The Bradley campaign had arranged
for students from Princeton, his alma mater, and other schools to
be driven in to show their support.
</P>
<P>
   After recognizing the American soldiers involved in the conflict
in Yugoslavia, Mrs. Gore recited her husband's biography and
accomplishments. Recalling, for example, that soon after they
married, Gore went to Vietnam to be a member of the Army press
corps, Mrs. Gore said of the troops in Yugoslavia, ``I know there
is no more difficult a sacrifice to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley followed much the same pattern, mentioning Kosovo, then
delving into his background, including how he burst upon the
national scene as a star basketball player at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore mentioned Clinton only once _ and in passing _ and
praised her husband for an economy that she said was creating
12,000 jobs a year in New Hampshire. ``If anyone,'' she said, ``my
husband understands how to keep that prosperity going.'' She
described him as ``the best vice president this country has ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, apparently, by the furor caused recently when Gore, in
a television interview, incorrectly credited himself with having
created the Internet, Mrs. Gore said that her husband had ``worked
hard to bring the Internet to our homes.'' Asked whether her
husband had misspoken as he himself has acknowledged to advisers,
Mrs. Gore accused the news media of misstating what he said.
``People should have been more precise in their reporting,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a far bigger political infrastructure in this important
primary state than Bradley. In fact, a good share of the delegates
at the convention here have already signed up with the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley presented himself as a fresh leader who could offer
voters an alternative to eight years of Clinton and Gore. He
emphasized the importance of restoring trust in political
institutions, repairing the way campaigns are financed and pressing
for ``tolerance and racial understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said later that his comments about trust were aimed at
Clinton, not at Gore. The former senator seemed to relish his
underdog position.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Bill Russell used to say,'' he said, referring to the
former pro basketball player, ``it's easier to become No. 1 than to
stay No. 1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
