<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-11-COX     04-10 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER 3,000 MISSION, NATO AIR CAMPAIGN IS ESCALATING BUT THE
OUTCOME IS UNCERTAIN
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 750.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON After nearly three weeks and more than 3,000 sorties,
the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia has become an escalating
mission of uncertain duration and unpredictable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Operations have swollen far beyond their original dimensions,
requiring almost daily additions of warplanes. The Pentagon said
Saturday it would add 82 more bombers, fighters and refueling
tankers to the NATO force, on top of six additional fighters
announced the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting decisions have become increasingly aggressive, testing
consensus and resolve in the 19-nation NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Bombing runs continue to be badly hampered by thick clouds,
pilots are in frequent risk of being shot down and military
priorities are competing with the need to feed and shelter half a
million refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The province of Kosovo lies smoldering from a Serb rampage that
has forced two out of every three ethnic Albanians to flee their
homes in the worst exodus in Europe since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee flows have threatened stability in neighboring
Montenegro and Macedonia _ each faces its own internal ethnic
tensions _ and overtaxed the meager resources of Albania, the
poorest nation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, President Slobodan
Milosevic is as intransigent as ever, giving scant hint that the
bombing campaign has brought him any closer to the peace agreement
NATO seeks, or that he might be budged by further bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, Congress returns Monday from a two week
recess amid growing calls for President Clinton to at least develop
a contingency plan to putting troops on the ground in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that there are limits to what can be
accomplished from the air,'' said Rep. Jim Turner, D-Texas, one of
11 members of Congress who visited NATO headquarters last week with
Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   What began March 24 as an air campaign designed to be a
sharp-edged diplomatic tool to coerce Milosevic to accept peace, in
other words, has suddenly begun to take on the peril and
uncertainty of war.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is looking for a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are changing their minds as to how serious this is
going to have to be,'' said Joe Collins, senior fellow for
political-military affairs at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a think tank in Washington. ``Clearly there
are a whole lot of people who never believed it was going to go
this far.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two weeks of bombing has taken its toll, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday, the strikes had demolished about 150 bridges,
headquarters buildings, barracks, ammo dumps and other fixed
targets across Yugoslavia, as well as scores of tanks, artillery
pieces and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated attacks on fuel storage and distribution centers had
destroyed half of the petroleum stocks in the country, NATO claims.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military casualties are estimated in the hundreds _ perhaps
much higher _ and the troops are largely hunkered down in Kosovo,
nursing dwindling supplies of precious fuel, food and ammunition
and hiding out from the NATO warplanes prowling overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This air campaign is being effective,'' NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea insisted Saturday in Brussels. ``We have inflicted a hell of a
lot of damage, quite frankly, on the Yugoslav armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, officials were beginning to speculate that Serb
forces in the field could be close to a catastrophic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuel's running out, ammo's running out, food isn't coming in.
My morale would be pretty low at this point,'' said U.S. Army Col.
Dick Bridges, a Pentagon spokesman. ``Speaking as a soldier, you're
defenseless, your country's not doing anything, your leaders aren't
doing anything and, just from a sheer human decency standpoint, I
don't think I'd want to go on in this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the air campaign lumbered into its third week, however,
military planners were also speaking openly of an operation that
could extend well into next month. No one could predict with any
certainty when or how it might end.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two weeks after Clark asked for 24 Apache helicopters,
which fly low and fast to take on troops and tanks with
laser-guided missiles, Maj. Gen. Charles Wald said on Saturday that
it would still be another ''seven to ten days'' before the first of
those helicopters is on the ground in Albania and ready for
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, said Wald, it isn't certain that the Apaches would
fight. That would require a decision from Clinton and an order from
Clark, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a month before all 24 of the Apaches are ready to
fight, said Wald, vice director of strategic plans and policy for
the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, raising the prospect that the NATO
air campaign could extend well into May.
</P>
<P>
   When alliance air attacks began March 24, there was reason for
policymakers in the United States and Europe to bet that a few days
of bombing might force Milosevic to accept NATO's terms: stop
ravaging Kosovo; withdraw troops and tanks; accept a NATO-led
peacekeeping force for the province; and guarantee the safe return
of Kosovo's refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, after all, Bosnian Serbs backed by Milosevic
collapsed after less than two weeks of NATO air strikes _ a victory
aided by heavy Serb losses on the ground against Croat and Muslim
forces.
</P>
<P>
   With that goal in mind, NATO began the fight for Kosovo with a
limited mission: send a message to Milosevic by attacking radar
systems, anti-aircraft missiles and airfields, but don't venture
into the heart of Belgrade and don't try to kill Serb troops as
they massed by the thousands in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, those troops dispersed throughout the province,
under orders from Milosevic to do as much shelling, torching and
terrorizing as was needed to force hordes of ethnical Albanians to
flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not getting the message,'' an exasperated Gen. Wesley
Clark, commander of the NATO campaign, told reporters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after the campaign began, Clark added 10 U.S.
warplanes to the mix, including five supersonic B-1 heavy bombers
capable of reducing an entire convoy of tanks to little more than
smoke and crumpled steel with its massive payload of armor-piercing
cluster bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, though, was that the Serb tanks and troops
rampaging across Kosovo were carrying out their mayhem beneath the
cloak of thick clouds and often near population centers, sharply
restricting the effectiveness of heavy bombers as well as
low-flying attack planes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most of the next week, American A-10 tank killers and
British Harrier attack craft were returning to their bases without
having dropped their bombs. Either they couldn't find their targets
or they couldn't be assured of hitting them without killing
innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly haven't hit a big enough percentage of his forces
yet,'' NATO air commodore David Wilby said Friday. ``This is not an
easy operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off slowly. The weather affected our operations,''
Wilby said. ``We're up against a wily enemy. He's beginning to dig
in. There are terrain, forests, deserted villages, which make
wonderful places for him to logger up against. It is quite
difficult to spot him. And, of course, once we spot him, then we've
got to bring our airplanes in to attack him quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, Clark asked to add the 50 strike planes and 25
support craft of the USS Roosevelt aircraft carrier, which joined
the NATO force last Tuesday. And on April 2, the Pentagon sent
Clark 13 additional F-117 stealth bombers, adding to a growing NATO
armada that by Saturday had reached some 600 warplanes and support
craft.
</P>
<P>
   The additions the Pentagon announced Saturday will bring the
NATO force to roughly 680 by early next week, and Defense
Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said he expects other NATO
allies will send additional warplanes in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon insisted the steady growth of the mission has been part of
a systematic plan that had, from its start, been mapped out as an
escalating campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It began as it was supposed to, said Bacon, with attacks on air
defense systems, then ramped up to take on command and control
centers, like headquarters buildings, before moving to key bridges
and highways used to supply Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the strikes focused increasingly on troops and tanks in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a bit confused,'' said Wald. ``The campaign is being
unfolded just exactly as Gen. Clark planned it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
