<HEADLINE>
MENIFEE WINS THE BLUE GRASS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ Menifee, the hometown horse named for a county
in Kentucky, thrust himself into the front ranks of candidates for
the Kentucky Derby Saturday when he ran down Cat Thief in the final
furlong and won the $750,000 Blue Grass Stakes by a length and a
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth victory in five starts for Menifee, and it
came three weeks after his only defeat, when he ran second in the
Tampa Bay Derby. And it came three weeks before the Kentucky Derby,
which will be run on May 1 at Churchill Downs in Louisville, about
75 miles west of this stately old center of thoroughbred racing
where they have been running the Blue Grass Stakes for the last 75
years.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his performance Saturday at Keeneland Race Course, a few
miles from where he was bred three years ago, the son of Harlan and
the mare Anne Campbell, and he gave one more moment of triumph to
the two men who nurtured him with great expectations: Jimmy Stone,
an oil and gas executive from New Orleans, and Arthur Hancock, the
son of the legendary Bull Hancock of Claiborne Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Hancock said, with feeling, ``He's a quick learner,
and he showed how quick.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Menifee's stock was soaring Saturday, that of several
of his rivals was not. Vicar, who won the Florida Derby and the
Fountain of Youth Stakes in his last two starts, finished third.
Kimberlite Pipe, winner of the Louisiana Derby, ran fourth. Lemon
Drop Kid, fifth. Wondertross, the 9-5 favorite, ran sixth. And
Prado's Landing _ who spent the winter in Dubai on the Persian Gulf
and flew to Kentucky to test the unusual training methods of his
owner, Sheik Mohammed al Maktoum _ finished dead last.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other 3-year-old horses were lying in ambush. On the
West Coast, the stablemates General Challenge and Prime Timber were
waiting after their one-two finish in the Santa Anita Derby. And a
new flash arose Saturday when the long shot Valhol won the Arkansas
Derby in the third start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, who rode Menifee in his last four races with all the
patience of a 45-year-old Hall of Fame jockey, steered his
3-year-old prodigy through traffic and turns, and then said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed that he could take it on the chin and keep running.
When I took him to the outside in the homestretch, he responded
with strength. He's a nice long-striding colt, and that should be
to his advantage in three weeks when he runs in the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who was not supposed to lose the Tampa Bay Derby, was
not exactly supposed to win the Blue Grass Stakes. He went off at
odds of 6-1, the fifth choice in a tightly matched field of eight
contenders for the Kentucky Derby. He won twice last summer, then
was sidelined for six months with a chip in his right knee. But
after that, he took the fast lane to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Both of his owners credited Day for choosing Menifee when he had
other choices in the pre-Derby confusion, notably Cat Thief and
Answer Lively, last year's juvenile champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat had a choice,'' Jimmy Stone said. ``But he picked Menifee,
and stuck with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Day said, ``Once the decision was made, I had great peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, who acknowledged that ``this is one of the best days of
my life,'' remembered with emotion: ``My grandfather used to bring
me to Keeneland when I was a little boy to watch the races when
there were two buildings here.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee prompted this tide of feeling when he nestled in fifth
place in the early running while Vicar and then Kimberlite Pipe set
the pace. Then, after three-quarters of a mile, Cat Thief took the
lead with Menifee sixth. They turned for home, and Vicar once more
nudged in front, with Menifee running fourth. Then Day made his
move to the outside, and Menifee outran Cat Thief and Vicar to the
wire.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the mile and an eighth in 1:48 3/5, finishing a length
and a quarter in front of Cat Thief, who had half a length over
Vicar. He also paid $17.40 for a $2 bet to win, and went home with
the first prize of $465,000.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, the trainer of Menifee, said: ``Unbelievable. I
am extremely excited about the way he broke, settled in and then
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a genuine long shot, the colt Valhol paid $62.80 for a
$2 bet in the Arkansas Derby, ourtrunning Certain by four lengths
with Torrid Sand third, Ecton Park fourth and Answer Lively fifth.
Valhol did not even run a race until February, when he finished
second at the Fair Grounds in New Orleans. One month later, he ran
fourth in the Louisiana Derby. And one month after that, he upset
the odds completely in the Arkansas Derby at 30-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
