<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES AWAIT TORRE'S RETURN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre was relaxing in a plush maroon chair behind
his desk at Yankee Stadium Saturday, just like always. There was a
pile of white lineup cards tempting him from a few inches away,
just like always. There was a calmness in his voice and a serenity
spread over his craggy face, just like always. Only it was not just
like always.
</P>
<P>
   The element missing from this typical of snapshots was Torre's
Yankee uniform, which remained in his closest. Torre is expected to
wear it during the presentation of the 1998 World Series rings
Sunday, and his slow lope onto the field should inflate the volume
at 161st Street into the decibel range of a Pearl Jam concert.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way it should be, rowdy and raucous. Torre will be
Yogi Berra Sunday. For guiding the Yankees to championships in two
of the last three seasons. For showing how to excel and actually
enjoy working under George Steinbrenner. For being another gritty
New Yorker. But, mostly, it should be boisterous to remind the
58-year-old Torre that he is not alone following prostate cancer
surgery three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans in New York are special people,'' Torre said. ``You
can walk through Manhattan, they just say, `Hi, Joe.' It's like
you're supposed to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is supposed to be exactly where he was Saturday, even
though he watched from Steinbrenner's box while Roger Clemens made
a scintillating Stadium debut with a 5-0 triumph over the Tigers.
Torre is supposed to sign autographs, advise players and chat with
Don Zimmer, his bench coach turned interim manager, as he did.
Saturday was more than a tease since Torre discussed a possible
timetable for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we get around May 1,'' Torre said, ``I think we'd
be getting close to a realistic time.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, before Torre had his prostate removed on March 18, he
did not even guarantee that he would return. While General Manager
Brian Cashman said there were no formal plans for Torre's return,
another club official theorized that Torre could return on May 7
against Seattle, which is the day after the Yankees finish a 10-day
trip. Dr. William Catalona, who performed Torre's surgery, stressed
that he should not return until at least 6 to 12 weeks after the
operation. It would be seven weeks by May 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way, I hope it works out that way, or
sooner,'' Zimmer said. ``You know what I mean? He knows his own
health. If it is May 1, he'll be ready to come back. He's too smart
to do something any earlier where he might have a setback.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer sounded eager about Torre's return, and he is. The
68-year-old Zimmer indicated that he would retire from baseball
after 51 years once Torre was able to work again unless the pain
from last month's arthroscopic surgery on his right knee subsided.
``I can't go through the whole season like it is,'' Zimmer said.
``I couldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre must remain patient, putting his recuperation ahead of
managing the Yankees. Zimmer, who has been aiding Torre's decisions
for the last three years and who has already scored a submission
hold over Steinbrenner, can continue, then rest, maybe strengthen
his knee and return. It would be silly for Torre to come back
prematurely, and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who has been walking every day, continued his
rehabilitation program by working out for the first time on Friday.
He pedaled an exercise bicycle and climbed the Stairmaster. He
wants to get his body to the point where he has some energy left
after a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor has pretty much turned me loose,'' Torre said. ``He
says whenever you think you're ready, you're the only one who knows
what your job involves.''
</P>
<P>
   This time is very precious, but it did not prevent Torre from
feeling strange when the Yankees hoisted the championship flag
without him on Friday. Even Andrea Rae, the manager's 3-year-old
daughter, could not understand why her father was watching
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting there and she's seeing Zim,'' Torre said. ``And
then they were talking about Yogi Berra and she was thinking in
terms of Yogi Bear. At Yogi Berra, her eyebrows went up. When they
went to a commercial, she said, `Where were you, Dad?' She couldn't
relate to me not being with the rest of the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will be back with the Yankees for another day Sunday,
collecting a ring that honors perhaps the best team ever. Zimmer
predicted that ``people will go crazy'' for Torre and jokingly
offered to help Torre put on the pinstripes. When Zimmer was told
that Torre was uncertain about wearing the uniform, he limped
toward the manager's office and said, ``I'm going to convince him
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect Torre in uniform Sunday and back for good by next month.
Just like always.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
