<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winkelsas latest quick-study call-up
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The newest member of the Braves is 25, was never
drafted, only mastered a slider and change-up in the past six
months and has heard his name pronounced just about every way
possible. Joe Winkelsas started last season in Class A, and stop
the Braves if you've heard this one again.
</P>
<P>
   He will join Kevin McGlinchy and Derrin Ebert as rookies making
their major-league debuts in the first week of this season. Like
McGlinchy, he came to his first spring camp as a nonroster invitee.
Winkelsas is the last step _ the Braves hope _ in the most
calamitous first week any bullpen of manager Bobby Cox's has ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a short period of time, yeah,'' Cox said. ``We're only in
our sixth ballgame and we've already made three moves.''
</P>
<P>
   This one is a statistical stretch: Winkelsas was hardly
untouchable over the spring. He allowed 16 hits and four walks in
seven appearances for a 8.38 ERA with a .356 batting average
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Winkelsas was scouted and signed in 1996 by John Stewart, the
Braves' northeast regional scouting supervisor, after the
right-hander had gone undrafted throughout his career at Elon
College. He had gotten by with an above-average fastball and
advanced to Class AA Greenville in the second half of last season,
but ranked well below Ebert, McGlinchy or even Luis Rivera among
reliever prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing 95 percent fastball and I had a natural sink,''
he said before Saturday's game. ``That's all I threw. So I went up
to AA (last season), but then I went to Maryland last year for fall
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where he began work with pitching coach Dave Miller, a
minor-league pitching instructor with Cleveland who helped Miller
develop his slider and changeup. The Braves liked enough of what
they saw to bring him to the major-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ridiculous,'' Winkelsas said. ``It took such a short
time. Some pitchers go half their careers and can't establish a
good change-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer plans
</P>
<P>
   With such inexperience, the Braves will be watching right-hander
Russ Springer's progress closely. Recovering from elbow and back
surgery, Springer will leave Monday for two or three extended
spring training appearances and then go on an injury rehab
assignment. He expects to be ready to join the Braves when they
return from a 15-day road trip at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long year,'' Springer said. ``All the guys we got right
now, including the young guys, are capable. I'm not going to come
in and save the day, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   But his experience alone makes Springer a commodity. He has
appeared in 222 games over his seven seasons in the majors. John
Rocker, Mike Cather and the three rookies went into Saturday's game
with a combined 119 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to know I'm going to be ready,'' said Springer, who
had bone chips removed from his elbow in October and a parts of a
herniated disc removed from his lower back in January. ``I need
some work down there. I've got to be ready to pitch in a normal
situation. I'm sure they're not going to throw me to the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson's presence forced at least one lineup alteration,
as Ryan Klesko was benched in favor of right-handed first baseman
Brian Hunter, who made his first start in his return stint with the
Braves. Klesko went 1-for-3 against Johnson last season. . . .
Gerald Williams, who hit .366 against left-handed pitching last
year, made his second start in a row in left field in place of Otis
Nixon. . . . With his steal of third base Friday, Keith Lockhart is
halfway to his career total in two seasons with the Braves (2).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
