<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal holds on ahead of Norman
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ With a recovery shot at the 18th hole that would
have made his mentor proud, Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal held
together a 1-over-par 73 Saturday at Augusta National to take a
one-shot lead into today's final round of the 63rd Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking his second Masters win, the 33-year-old Olazabal, a
former Seve Ballesteros pupil, fired his second shot at the 18th
from the left rough between two trees about 215 yards from the
hole, then two-putted for par, finishing at 7-under 209.
</P>
<P>
   His closest challenger is the week's biggest story _ Greg
Norman. The 44-year-old Australian stands just a stroke off the
lead after a turbulent 71 Saturday. It was three years ago that
Norman, leading by six shots after four holes, collapsed on Sunday
to lose to Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pate, who set a Masters record with seven consecutive
birdies on holes 7-13, shot a 7-under 65 and is tied for third,
with Sea Island's Davis Love III, two strokes back after an
up-and-down 70. Still in the picture, though forced to post
something low today, is Tiger Woods, who shot a 2-under 70 Saturday
and is at 2-under 214.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the way it looks, I'm right there,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for his bizarre 12th hole, Norman would be on top of
the board. After losing his ball in a bush behind the par-3 12th,
he collected himself to make a career Masters bogey after returning
to the tee box, sinking a 30-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony (Navarro, his caddie) kept saying walking up there, `This
is going to be a great bogey,' '' Norman said. ``I felt so
comfortable over that putt. It had eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   After a bogey at the 13th, Norman regrouped with a two-putt
birdie at the 15th and a closing birdie, after hitting to a few
feet, at the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Three strokes off the lead at 4 under are two U.S. Open
champions, Ernie Els (69) and Lee Janzen (73), plus Paraguay's
Carlos Franco (68) and Bob Estes (69).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
