<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pate's fire drags Westwood along
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ When Steve Pate made his seventh birdie at the
par-5 13th hole, playing partner Lee Westwood waved a towel at him
to cool him off. ``I figured he'd caught fire,'' Westwood said. And
hey, doesn't Pate play for Team Tabasco, the logo on his sleeve?
</P>
<P>
   Pate probably wished Westwood would have held off, because he
parred the 14th to end his streak. Westwood, meanwhile, shot a 68
that in comparison looked like a hack job. ``I wasn't holing
anything and he was holing everything,'' said Westwood, 25, a
rising British star.
</P>
<P>
   But he admitted Pate's momentum dragged him along _ to his
lowest round in three trips here. Pate finished with a 65.
</P>
<P>
   Long way from '97
</P>
<P>
   Many players said the course played easier than it has all week
because the breeze died down and slowed the greens.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many low rounds and such a dogfight among the
leaders on the back nine that a 3-wood, 7-iron eagle by Tiger Woods
on the downwind No. 13 went virtually unnoticed. Woods, who shot 70
and stands 2 under, said afterward the changes to Augusta National
have forced him to scale back the freewheeling that gave him the
1997 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then I was able to blow balls over the bunkers, but now
those lines have been taken away from me because of the rough,''
said Woods, one of the favorites coming into this week. Give him
the Groundhog Day award already for playing each round with Tim
Herron, one of only two players to have beaten Woods in the U.S.
Amateur. Herron shot 74 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces
</P>
<P>
   While Davis Love III of Sea Island flirted with the lead most of
the afternoon, his fellow Georgians waited in the clubhouse.
Stewart Cink of Smyrna shot 71 and at 1 under, regretted his
two-stroke penalty in the first round. ``That's a tough way to
learn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Mize of Columbus shot 72 to stand 2 over, as did Billy
Andrade of Atlanta (4-over). Playing in the first twosome of the
day, Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar shot 1-over 73 that left him ``a
little disappointed,'' especially considering three back-nine
bogeys. ``I think I tried to force some shots. ... Going for
everything is a mistake here.'' Kuchar trails Tom McKnight (73_220)
by one stroke in the race for low amateur. When asked how often he
thinks about the Masters, McKnight said, ``Roughly 18 holes a
round.'' ... Spain's Sergio Garcia shot 75 and South African Trevor
Immelman 78. ``The tournament is great, the course is unbelievable
and the crowds are good,'' Garcia said. ``Everything is OK except
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Just missed
</P>
<P>
   Pate's birdie tear missed matching the low third-round score of
63. That was set in 1986 by Nick Price, who was anything but steady
Saturday. Tied for fifth after two rounds, Price had a Jekyll-Hyde
round of even par-72. He doubled the third hole and shot 40 on the
front nine, but rebounded with an eagle at No. 13 and a birdie from
the sand at No. 16, ended up with a 32 on the back. He's tied for
9th.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pate, the following players had made six birdies in a
row: Johnny Miller (1975, third round starting at No. 2), Mark
Calcavecchia (1992, fourth round, starting at No. 13), David Toms
(1998, fourth round, starting at No. 12). ... The last players to
make seven birdies at Augusta were Toms and David Duval in the
final round of the 1998 Masters. Duval shot 67 that day and tied
for second. On Saturday, Duval birdied Amen Corner (Nos. 11-13)
Saturday en route to a 70. He stands 1-under. ``I'm still there,''
he said. ``I was close to putting up a 67 or 68. I really should
have, but didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot ..
</P>
<P>
   The pride of Paraguay, Masters rookie Carlos Franco, got back on
the leaderboard with a six-birdie 68. He's tied for fifth with
Ernie Els (69_212), whose four birdies came from less than 10 feet,
including a 9-iron to No. 9 that almost fell in the cup. ``If I'm
in the tournament, it starts there tomorrow,'' said Els, pointing
to the 10th tee. ``If I'm at 4 or 5 under, you have a chance. Look
at what Steve Pate did.'' Els best finish at the Masters: tied for
ninth in '94. ... Bob Estes shot a stealth 69 to tie Els and
Franco. He was so quiet, birdieing three of his last six holes,
that the scoreboards took a while to reflect his progress. ``I
don't have the resume of the rest of the guys. You have to earn
that respect,'' he said. He's never finished higher than 27th here.
... Known as a good putter, Brad Faxon shot a 68, his best round at
the Masters, and is 1 under. His best finish here is a tie for
ninth in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ... And who's not
</P>
<P>
   A shot off the lead going into the day, Scott McCarron hit in
the azaleas on the par-3 12th hole and triple bogeyed en route to
76. After rounds of 69-68, he was the only player with a shot at
four rounds in the 60s, so that Masters milestone is safe for
another year. ... Lee Janzen, who predicted he might have some
trouble in his Saturday round, bogeyed Nos. 14 and 16 for a 73 and
is tied for fifth at 4 under. He's never shot lower than 72 in the
third round at the Masters. ... Bernhard Langer cooled off after
his second-round 66, shooting a two-birdie, two-bogey 72 to stand 2
under. ... Justin Leonard doubled twice and shot 73; he's 1 under,
tied with Bill Glasson, who had six pars in his 73. ... Brandel
Chamblee slumped to a back-nine 39 for a 75.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
