<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDE11-CO     04-10 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eagles lost in 15's forest
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ For more than half a century, it was the most
benevolent, forgiving hole on the track. Its nickname,
``Firethorn,'' belied the 15th hole's status as the easiest hole at
Augusta National. Well, lookee now. Remove a few fairway mounds,
plant some pines, still tempt players to lay up or go for a green
now brown and fast, and you've got a new Masters hell hole.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask David Duval, who offered this advisory for today's
final round. ``If you have a chance, go out on that 15th fairway
and look at that green,'' said Duval, who came here a prohibitive
favorite, took a triple-bogey 8 at 15 on Friday and then
three-putted for par Saturday. ``It's not a pretty sight. Just
brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Ernie Els, who once viewed No. 15 as many players did: A
possible eagle hole, certainly a birdie possibility and no worse
than a par. ``They've got to think about that one again,'' said
Els, who's in contention at 4-under despite making three
consecutive pars at the 15th. ``They've really toughened up the tee
shot. There's no right side. We used to hit it down the right side
and go in with a 7 iron. I think guys like Tiger and David can
still go in, but us mortals....
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a really tough second shot,'' said Els. ``We used to
bargain on a four. Now, you make a five and you're kind of happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ask Davis Love III. Tactfully. ``It's not about just getting
it over the water any more,'' said Love, who was leading Saturday's
third round by two strokes at 7 under until he hit into the water
below the 15th hole and made double-bogey. ``No matter what club
you hit, it's over the green on 15.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this could come into play on the back nine today, and
help determine the winner of the 63rd Masters. As Els said, ``I
think 15 and 17 are the two key holes in the last stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   On 15, the problems are not just the water below but the
rock-hard green that isn't holding approaches, rather spilling them
off the back fringe. That's where Love's wedge, after he took a
drop, wound up. He was not alone. On the newly-toughened 15th,
players who've hit the green have found nearly as much treachery as
those who found the water. After Love's fourth shot hit the green
and rolled off, he chipped back up and on but two-putted for seven.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of two double-bogeys at the 15th Saturday, the
first time the hole has played below par this week. On Thursday, it
played a staggering average of 5.25 strokes. On Friday, that
improved slightly to 5.086. The field finally played the 15th below
par Saturday at an average of 4.786. Through three rounds, the hole
is playing at an average of 5.169 strokes, the 13th-hardest hole on
the course.
</P>
<P>
   All this is in sharp contrast to the hole's history. From
1942-98, the 500-yard 15th was the easiest hole on the course.
Average score per round: 4.786. The warning signs were there last
year, however, a cumulative 5.097 for the tournament. It was just
the third time No. 15 had played above par (also in 1987 and 1973).
</P>
<P>
   But much of that's changed, now that Augusta National
reconfigured the 15th. Twenty pines were added on the right side of
the fairway. Mounds that were there _ and helped sling-shot drives
down the fairway another 40-50 yards _ were removed. Mounds on the
right side of the green were also removed and six more pines
planted there. When Els played the new-look hole last October, he
didn't even recognize it. ``It's a forest on the right side.''
</P>
<P>
   And you can't see the eagles for the forest on this par-5. When
Andrew Magee holed out from 100 yards Saturday, it was just the
second eagle the 15th has yielded this week. The first came Friday
but didn't help Frank Lickliter make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   There have been four triple-bogey 8's _ most notably Duval's,
which left him feeling admittedly ``foolish'' _ and Hal Sutton's
nine on Friday. But it's the dearth of birdies that's been
damaging, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the green,'' said Duval. ``You have to hit a much more
accurate drive now. The green is very, very hard and very, very
fast.'' Which he discovered when his 25-foot eagle putt rolled
nearly 10 feet past and he missed coming back. Tiger Woods reached
in two, too, Saturday. Yet on a green he called ``shiny'' due to
too many grains, Woods struck a 25-foot up-hill putt twice as hard
as usual but still left it short.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Pate, having just parred No. 14 after a record seven
straight birdies, hit his second shot four feet from the hole,
``Which is way too far. There's no way that ball is going anywhere
but long.'' It did. He chipped on and two-putted for par at the
now-hellish 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
