<HEADER>
A3409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-10 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL HORDE IS ON THE HEELS OF OLAZABAL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga._ The leader board at the Masters is bunched as
tightly as rush-hour traffic in Manhattan, with 16 players within
five shots of the lead. Few Masters have entered the final day with
so many contenders and so many intriguing possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   From Greg Norman, a sentimental favorite, to Carlos Franco, who
has traveled from an impoverished childhood in Paraguay to the
plush fairways of Augusta National Golf Club, winning the Masters
would be a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only one player will prevail, and considering the caliber of
names at the top, the magnitude of the event and the difficulty of
the course, the winner will have to overcome one of the greatest
challenges of his career. But then, isn't that what a major is
supposed to be about?
</P>
<P>
   Ending a bizarre third round, and setting up an unusual amount
of drama, Jose Maria Olazabal finished at seven under par (209) and
led by one stroke over Greg Norman (210) and by two strokes over
Davis Love III and Steve Pate, who were tied for third place at
five under par. Pate, who shot a 65, roared into contention by
setting a Masters record of seven consecutive birdies, starting on
No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, Lee Janzen, Bob Estes and Franco were tied at four
under par. And many prominent players still believe they have a
chance. They include Steve Elkington, Nick Price and Colin
Montgomerie (all at three under par); Tiger Woods, Bernhard Langer,
Phil Mickelson and Lee Westwood (two under), and David Duval,
Justin Leonard, Jeff Sluman and the defending champion Mark O'Meara
(one under).
</P>
<P>
   There were many turning points Saturday, and once again some of
the most compelling moments involved Norman, who shot a resourceful
71, keeping his composure when trouble arose. Norman escaped
potential disaster at the par-3 12th hole when his errant tee shot
sailed over the green and into the bushes and could not be found.
After a five-minute search, he returned to the tee after a penalty
stroke, hit another shot that landed 22 feet left of the pin and
made a huge putt to salvage a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a putt that I saw all the way,'' Norman said. ``I never
doubted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not finding the ball may have been a break for Norman, who would
have faced a precarious shot from the bushes that would have made
making a bogey difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could have made bogey from the bushes, Norman said:
``I don't know. I made 4, and that's all I'm worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   But what will be going through Norman's mind Saturday night and
Sunday? The last time he reached Sunday in contention at the
Masters, in 1996, he began the final round with a six-stroke lead
over Nick Faldo, and most people expected him to cruise to his
first Masters victory. But his game fell apart during a final-round
78, and Faldo won by five strokes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lowest point of Norman's career, and despite winning
two British Open titles, he has longed for another chance at
Augusta. That opportunity is at hand, he has successfully returned
from last year's shoulder surgery and the gallery is clearly behind
him. It will be interesting to see how he handles another
emotionally charged final day, but he could sense people pulling
for him today as he returned to the 12th tee for his second tee
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every person in that gallery wanted me to hit it on
the green,'' Norman said. ``I could feel the emotion coming out of
them. That was the most I've ever felt on a golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   But to win, Norman will have to overtake Olazabal, who started
the day with a two-stroke lead at eight under par, yet somehow
managed to stay in front after Saturday's 73, his worst round of
the tournament. Olazabal saved par at No. 18 with a tremendous
approach out of the rough after pulling his tee shot, but over all
he was not as sharp Saturday as he was Thursday and Friday. Yet
after severe foot pain almost forced him to find a new career in
1996, the 1994 Masters champion was thrilled to be back in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I was one or two shots behind, I would be happy,''
Olazabal said. ``This is the first time I've been in this position
since my return. A one-shot lead is nothing. It's going to be a
hard day, but I'm very glad to be in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Pate, who began the day 10 strokes off the lead, then
started his streak of seven consecutive birdies on No. 7. After
breaking the previous mark of six consecutive birdies, set by
Johnny Miller (1975), Mark Calcavecchia (1992) and David Toms
(1998), Pate was confident, although he has never won a major.
</P>
<P>
   However, no matter what happens Sunday, much of the attention
will be focused on Norman, who will be in the final group with
Olazabal. Once again, his career and life will be altered by
another Sunday at Augusta. This time, he is hoping for a happier
ending, and he vowed not to let demons from the past re-enter his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I don't live in the past,'' Norman said.
``What's done is done. I don't reflect on negative situations. Some
people like to write about them and talk about them, but that's
their prerogative. I don't let that get in my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become a little more at peace and at ease with myself.
But don't get me wrong. Tomorrow, I'm going to play to win. That's
what I'm here for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
