<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-10 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DALY'S MAGIC TRICK 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It isn't quite deja vu, but Orlando Magic coach Chuck
Daly has noticed the similarities. A dozen years ago, his Detroit
Pistons went from being conference fodder to the conference finals,
thanks in part to two rookies: Dennis Rodman and John Salley.
</P>
<P>
   Daly played them and played them down the stretch, much to the
chagrin of some veterans. The rookies played with enthusiasm, and
neither needed the ball to be effective. It was a combination that
would help yield three straight trips to the NBA Finals and two
titles for the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to the Magic. Last year they didn't even make the
playoffs. Shortly after the season ended, the Magic brass met and
Daly made one request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had remembered what we did in Detroit, where we got really
lucky with that one draft (1986),'' Daly said. ``I said to (general
manager) John Gabriel, `We need to do the same thing here we did
there. We need to build a roster.' I needed to find people that I
could put into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He has found them in Michael Doleac and Matt Harpring. They play
every game. They play down the stretch. Harpring is even starting
with the injury to Bo Outlaw. They have played big roles in
Orlando's surprising rise back to the top of the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic had three first-round picks last June. They took
Doleac, a no-brainer because they wanted size, at No. 12. At No.
13, they took Keon Clark, then traded him to Denver. At No. 15, the
Magic snared Harpring, over whom Daly had salivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office at our practice complex looks out over the floor,''
Daly said, ``and when we brought this kid in for a workout, I saw
him for three minutes and said, `I want that kid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Daly recalled a conversation he had early in the 1986-87 season
with Billy Cunningham, then a television analyst. He said
Cunningham watched the Pistons and told Daly that the team, because
of the rookies, had moved up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand what he meant,'' Daly said. ``I just
didn't think two guys could be that important, especially guys who
didn't need the ball. But he was right. They were. And we did move
up the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   Doleac and Harpring are much different players from Rodman and
Salley. But they also bear testament to Daly's willingness to do
what has to be done, even if it seems unconventional or unorthodox.
The success of the rookies is even more remarkable given that Daly
basically has eliminated practices, another unusual decision.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, thanks in part to the rooks, the Magic really have
moved up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still don't know a lot about the league or other
players,'' Daly said. ``But they're great kids and they've made a
difference on our team. We got lucky. We were able to draft them
and I've been able to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also a little different off the floor as well. When the
team took a red-eye home following its Saturday night game in
Oakland March 13, Daly headed for Mass that Sunday morning. He he
saw the two rookies in the church _ still in their sweatsuits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kenny Anderson situation is going to be interesting to watch
over the summer. First, Anderson's remaining four years ($31
million) will, as of July 1, start to come out of Paul Gaston's
wallet. Should the Celtics be inclined to discuss alternatives,
don't be surprised if they do so with the Clippers. First, Los
Angeles desperately needs a point guard. Anderson is a name _
always a big thing for Donald Sterling _ and this time, under the
rules, he'd have to report if traded. The Clippers are well under
the cap and could afford him, especially if they re-signed one of
their own free agents and then traded him to Boston. While Pitino
is interested in Rodney Rogers, a better guy would be Lorenzen
Wright. He would help out on the front line and he's a talent, not
to mention a banger. Would the Clippers be dumb enough to do that?
Well, they're the Clippers. And they'd be getting something for an
asset. Plus, they have enough frontcourt players. The downside for
Boston would be finding a replacement for Anderson. Pitino might be
able to live with Dana Barros for the time being. You can bet the
house that Wayne Turner will be in Boston's camp unless someone
drafts him. He can do everything but shoot . . . The Celtics also
will have their $2 million ``middle class'' exception to offer to
free agents. But here's another twist: How many veterans around the
league are going to want to play Pitino Ball? The coach wants
veterans, needs veterans, but the word is out on the street, even
moreso after L'Affaire Anderson. ``Rick is going to need some
veterans on that team,'' observed Toronto's Charles Oakley,
mentioned as a potential Boston target but more likely to stay
where he is. ``He's got a young team and has to get some veterans.
You get veterans, you might change the style or the offense, you
never know. Get a big guy, more veterans, maybe you play more
man-to-man. Get some big guys inside and that makes a coach's job
easier. He's got a small team now. It's hard. You need big bodies
in the East. I don't care how many All-Stars you have or how much
you pay a guy. Money ain't the thing anymore. Everyone's got it.''
. . . The Celtics are on board, but not in the forefront, of next
month's Bill Russell ceremony at the FleetCenter. Normally, the
team is quick to embrace, promote, and market one of its many
legends, of which Russell is among the top. The idea started as a
way to raise funds for the National Mentoring Partnership, which is
similar to Big Brother/Big Sister. Russell sits on the
partnership's board and is active in the program. One of the ideas
apparently was to have the fund-raiser coincide with Russell's 65th
birthday, which was in February. Now it's the 30th anniversary of
his last title and retirement. There are a lot of big names who've
signed on, and the Celtics will be represented by Red Auerbach and
Pitino. But the event is being handled by Russell and his reps and
being promoted by a Boston public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of new names have popped into some draftniks' potential
lottery lists. One is Jumaine Jones of Georgia, a 6-foot-7-inch
skywalking sophomore who had some Bulldog fans thinking of
Dominique Wilkins. The other is 7-3 Alexander Radojevic, a 7-3,
235-pound juco lad who has signed with Ohio State. But there was a
lot of talk at the Portsmouth tournament that he might decide to
just turn pro. Radojevic played last season for Barton County
Community College in Kansas . . . Dave Cowens's name has surfaced
in the search to replace Jim Harrick at Rhode Island, along with
the names of college guys (Mike Deane, ex- of Marquette). But
here's another name that has surfaced: Kareem Abdul-Jabbar. The Big
Fella is eager to get into coaching . . . Daly was selected as one
of the all-time Top 10 coaches a couple years ago when the NBA
celebrated its 50th anniversary. But he and Jack Ramsay are the
only two contemporary coaches on the list never to have won a Coach
of the Year Award. Given the Magic's season, the Prince of
Pessimism has to be the front-runner, although, predictably, he's
loath even to discuss the matter. ``You know with this season, you
can go from first to eighth with a few losses in a week,'' he said.
Yeah, yeah, Chuck. But how would it feel? ``I'd be in shock,'' he
said. ``I don't concern myself with that stuff. The one other time
I was considered in '84, they gave it to Frank Layden. I'm just a
second banana, that's all.'' . . . The NBA has quietly welcomed
back referee Ron Olesiak, who settled his differences with the
Internal Revenue Service. The only remaining ref still not working
because of IRS problems is Blane Reichelt. He may fight the charges
in court . . . The Bulls are back in town  &UR; tonight &LR;  (wonder if
Antoine Walker will give Ron Harper the choke hold?) and you may
not even know or care. Chicago had a slew of free agents last
summer and only one re-signed, Bill Wennington. We asked him about
the difference traveling this year and in the past three. ``The
masses aren't there anymore,'' he said. ``You'd get to some places
and there'd be 500 people waiting for the bus. Now, it's more like
10 kids. It was surreal in the past three years and now it's back
to normal. For those of us who've been on other teams, and know
what it's really like, we go, `Oh yeah, that's what it's like.' I
remember when Jason Caffey was a rookie. He said to me, `Billy, is
it always like this?' I said, `Jason, it's never like this.' The
past three years is something that will never happen again for us.
It was just unbelievable.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It took a while, but the Spurs finally may have gotten their
very powerful act together. ``There's no real secret,'' says
coach/general manager Gregg Popovich. ``We've gotten better and so
has the schedule.'' The Spurs started out poorly and were 6-8 at
one point, two losses coming to the Lakers. But then they hit a
wondrous stretch littered with Denvers, Vancouvers, and Dallases
and went on a tear. They're through with that now, but showed
they're back with a big win at Houston Thursday night. Tim Duncan
is rounding into form, but David Robinson's numbers are down and
Popovich thinks he knows why. First, Robinson is in constant pain
(a la Patrick Ewing) with back and knee woes, and will be until he
retires. ``David's problem is that he has a ridiculous tolerance
for pain and he doesn't want to disappoint anyone in the world,''
said Popovich. ``He'll tell you, `I'm fine, I'm fine,' but you know
it is bothering him. He just presses on.'' Also, Robinson is
learning to play a different way. ``It's a transition in his
career,'' Popovich said. ``He's learning how to score in different
ways, other than just by sheer athleticism. He's got to play
smarter now. He can't do it by just being quicker or faster. His
game is going to change and he's going through it.'' Popovich is
pleased with the additions of Steve Kerr, Mario Elie, and Jerome
Kersey, saying they've added toughness and experience to the team.
``We played Utah tough last year in the playoffs, but we had no
perimeter game,'' he said. ``Now, we do.'' The Spurs will try to
re-sign Duncan this summer, but here's the pickle they're in. They
can't stay in the Alamodome, and the last chance to get a new arena
will come in a referendum either in November or January. What if
Duncan re-signs (he likes San Antonio, according to Popovich) and
the Spurs have to move? He might choose to wait until the summer of
2000, when he's a free agent, before re-signing. Or signing
elsewhere if the Spurs have to move. The referendum will be the
final say. If that doesn't pass, the Spurs are gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
