<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THEY COULD DO IT ALL OVER AGAIN...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of scouting being done right now in out-of-the-way
places like Portsmouth, Va., by NBA teams trying to figure out who
they should draft this summer. But for all the work and man hours
spent by every pro organization (and the Clippers), a lot of teams
still look silly after last year's choices.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at the top 10 players in the 1998 draft and see how
different it would turn out if teams could re-pick today.
</P>
<P>
   1. Clippers, Michael Olowokandi: Does anyone even care what they
do? Unfortunately, it's already clear the player of the '98 draft
is Toronto's Vince Carter, who could start at shooting guard or
small forward. New pick: Vince Carter
</P>
<P>
   2. Vancouver, Mike Bibby: Stu Jackson might want Olowokandi, but
Bibby's averaging 14 points and seven assists in 36 minutes. New
pick: Bibby
</P>
<P>
   3. Denver, Raef LaFrentz: Before he got hurt, LaFrentz was
outstanding. But the Nuggets can't pass on Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   New pick: Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   4. Toronto, Antawn Jamison: They're enjoying Carter today by way
of trade. If the Clippers had done their job, Toronto would have
had to find the second-best small forward.
</P>
<P>
   New pick: Paul Pierce
</P>
<P>
   5. Golden State, Vince Carter: What were the Warriors thinking
last June? Thanks, P.J. New pick: LaFrentz
</P>
<P>
   6. Dallas, Robert Traylor: What makes Don Nelson look dumber?
Picking Traylor or trading him for Dirk Nowitzki? And then they
still needed to obtain disappointing point guard Steve Nash. New
pick: Jason Williams
</P>
<P>
   7. Sacramento, Jason Williams: Hey, a team that did its
homework. If Nellie hadn't blown it, the Kings would have had to
improvise.
</P>
<P>
   They could go the best-player-available route, and everyone's
kicking themselves today for missing out on Georgia Tech's Matt
Harpring, who can guard small forwards or shooting guards and who
went to Orlando at 15. New pick: Matt Harpring
</P>
<P>
   8. Philadelphia, Larry Hughes: Eric Snow has been starting at
the point and the Sixers really need a forward. New pick: Michael
Doleac.
</P>
<P>
   9. Milwaukee, Dirk Nowitzki: Luckily, they dumped this German
import to Dallas. They need a backup point guard.
</P>
<P>
   New pick! Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   10. Boston, Paul Pierce: The Celtics got lucky, but Pierce
wouldn't last this long today. They still want a forward,
especially one who will politely listen to Rick Pitino's nonsense.
New pick: Jamison.
</P>
<P>
   __ Solid as Oak: Toronto's resurgence is directly related to the
addition of forward Charles Oakley. So the Raptors, who initially
offered the potential free agent a three-year deal worth $12
million, have upped the ante. Not its about $20 million over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was insulted by the first offer. ``What they offered me,
I think was embarrassing,'' Oakley said. ``If that's what they're
going to be offering me, I won't be staying. I would rather go
somewhere else for less. Hey, I'm having a good time. I don't want
the max.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Dee Brown believes the Raptors should re-sign Oakley at
any price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no more Oaks around,'' Brown said. ``There's (Dennis)
Rodman, but he's crazy. There's Jason Williams, but he's hurt. Who
else will dive for the loose ball, get a rebound, make a good pass,
give you tough defense, flagrant-foul a guy _ you can't teach
that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Slap the other cheek: Warriors forward Terry Cummings has
been a Pentecostal minister for more than 20 years but ranks third
in the league with eight technical fouls and also has been called
for two flagrant fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing more than $32,000 in salary for the technicals,
Cummings is not repentant, claiming the Warriors receive no respect
from referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going out of my way to get them,'' he said of the
technicals. ``I'm just trying to make a point. If I can get
technicals the way I'm getting them after all these years, somebody
may try to figure out what's wrong with Cummings or what's wrong
with the game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Peeler done? Former Lakers guard Anthony Peeler, who strained
his left calf March 15 against Utah, saw a specialist in Boston
this week and might not return to the Minnesota lineup this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fond farewell: Not every player is trashing the Sports Arena.
Phoenix's Danny Manning, a former Clipper, was asked what he'll
remember most about the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maintenance crew,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manning recalled long, lonely nights when he would travel to the
arena and stay there for hours as he worked to rehabilitate his
knee. He lifted weights and shot as the crew worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes until as late as 11 p.m.,'' Manning said. ``Hey, I
spent a lot of time with those guys. Sometimes, they'd leave the
lights on and the door unlocked for me.'' &QL; 
TOP 10 AND NO. 29 &QL; 
__ 1. Utah: What would record be if it played the Lakers more
often? &QL; 
__ 2. Portland: Now, Stoudamire's upset about lack of
fourth-quarter playing time. &QL; 
__ 3. San Antonio: Duncan averaged 24 points, 11 boards, three
blocks in 19-game span. &QL; 
__ 4. Orlando: Daly's moved Penny to shooting guard and revived
Darrell Armstrong's career. &QL; 
__ 5. Houston: Rockets wish Barkley would stop ripping other
teams. &QL; 
__ 6. Lakers: Rick Fox and Derek Harper need to find way to hold
team together. &QL; 
__ 7. Indiana: Yes, it's boring. But why waste a flashy team in
Indianapolis? &QL; 
__ 8. Miami: Riley should be NBA's second-winningest coach by end
of season. &QL; 
__ 9. Detroit: Grant Hill is the franchise, but Joe Dumars is
playing as if he's 25. &QL; 
__ 10. Atlanta: Starting to slump, but so is everybody else that
could occupy this spot. &QL; 
__ No. 29. Clippers: Management needs to make a few changes, like
firing themselves.!dlBy The Numbers!dl1,100!dlCareer games played
by New York's Herb Williams with Wednesday's 106-82 loss to the
Charlotte Hornets.!dl52!dlJersey number of Buck Williams, who will
have his number retired by the Nets today.!dl32!dlTimes this season
that Philadelphia's Allen Iverson has scored 10 or more points in a
quarter.!dl0!dlThe number of NBA teams which have used the same
starting five all season.!dlSign Of The Times!dlAt the start of the
season, the Bulls walled off the United Center lockers of both
Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, announcing plans to display them
at some point.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the lockers were opened, replaced by new
duplicates. The wood was clearly unworn in comparison to the
lockers aside them. The originals were gone, supposedly stored
somewhere secure.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Chicago would anyone try to safeguard Scottie Pippen's
locker stall.!dlRumor of the Week!dlFormer NBA players Garfield
Heard, Dennis Johnson and Maurice Cheeks have emerged as the top
candidates to replace recently fired Bernie Bickerstaff as head
coach of the Wizards.
</P>
</TEXT>
