<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3426 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-10 2169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS A TEAM WITH SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ That 3-0 hiccup Thursday night in Tampa aside, the
Bruins are finishing up the regular season with confidence. Before
their loss to the Lightning, they were 14-4-4, a run that left
Florida, Montreal, and the Rangers in the breeze and allowed Boston
some breathing room in the last week before the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Do you like what you see? You should.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the elements of success are obvious: The coaching of Pat
Burns, the netminding of Byron Dafoe, the metronomic dependability
of Ray Bourque, and a teamwide attention to defense that is
personified by the checking line of Rob DiMaio, Tim Taylor, and
P.J. Axelsson.
</P>
<P>
   Headed into Saturday's FleetCenter matinee against the Bolts,
the Bruins had lost only two of their last 12 games. They may not
be the most exciting entry in the Original 27 _ OK, so defense
isn't as sensational as, say, a Paul Kariya end-to-ender _ but
they're a reliable, respectable product headed into the postseason.
It's by no means a stretch to believe they could make it to the Cup
finals (insert the standard injury and bizarre officiating
disclaimers here).
</P>
<P>
   Two winning elements that haven't been accentuated enough in the
second half: the play of Kyle McLaren and the emergence of Joe
Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   McLaren, without question, is now the key to the blue line
corps. This is one case where the numbers do back up the theory.
When McLaren remained out in a contract squabble at the start of
the season, the Bruins went 6-6-3. When he banged up his shoulder
in Buffalo Jan. 15 and had to miss a month, they were a moribund
3-9-3. Headed into Saturday's action, the Bruins were 27-14-7
(.635) with McLaren in the lineup, 9-15-6 (.400) without him.
</P>
<P>
   Is McLaren a Norris Trophy candidate? Hardly. He doesn't have
the mobility, agility or the points to be considered in that group.
In fact, he often looks awkward back there; remember, he is still
only 21, probably a year or two away from being a finished
physiological product.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of his presence behind the Boston blue line is
indisputable. When he is one of the six in the backline rotation,
it's a far more formidable, complete, effective group. Their
strengths are different, but take either McLaren or Bourque out of
the defense, and the whole mosaic begins to fall apart rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's progress has been more ballyhooed, of course, but
it's worth underscoring again. With his every inch of progress, the
entire Boston offensive plan moves ahead in lockstep. If he keeps
getting better _ and he is savvy enough and skilled enough to make
that a virtual guarantee _ then the Bruins finally can solidify a
two-line attack.
</P>
<P>
   This much we have learned here in the hockey Hub in the '90s: A
one-line attack is a guaranteed first-round knockout in the
playoffs. A two-line attack doesn't make a trip to the finals a
fait accompli, but it is the pedigree needed to get there. Without
it, the postseason is only a matter of four, five, six, or seven
more games.
</P>
<P>
   The key elements are here. Depth is now the concern, an issue
that was evident after last season, too. They've got the coach
(with appropriate game plan), the goaltender, the defense, and the
ever-improving attack. What they lack, as we speak, are the four or
five depth players who can fill in and flourish when fatigue and
injury begin to chew away at the core players during an eight-week
playoff haul.
</P>
<P>
   Those role players did not show up from Providence. They didn't
arrive via trade or free agency. Can the Bruins win without them?
Yes. But it means everyone staying healthy, and everyone continuing
to play at _ or beyond _ expectation at the most difficult time of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calgary defenseman Steve Smith might make it back to the lineup
Monday night (vs. Vancouver) after suffering a frightening gash to
the neck last weekend when he upended Toronto forward Lladislav
Kohn. One of Kohn's skates opened up a 4-inch wound, nearly 2
inches deep, leaving Smith with nerve damage that doctors say could
take up to a year to heal. Locked up in a fight with Edmonton for
the final playoff spot in the West, the Flames have severely missed
Smith's steadying influence behind the blue line. The ugly incident
was reminiscent of the near-fatal gash that Clint Malarchuk
suffered while tending net for the Sabres at the start of the '90s
. . . The Penguins, in a freefall the last couple of weeks, should
have both Jaromir Jagr and Tom Barrasso back for Sunday's game in
Detroit. Jagr has been down only a week with a groin injury.
Barrasso, ex- of Acton-Boxboro HS, has been out since breaking a
small bone in his hand March 3. And it will warm the heart of every
Bruins fan to know that Ulf Samuelsson could be making his Red
Wings debut Sunday. Samuelsson fractured an ankle only days before
the Rangers dealt him to Hockeytown at the March 23 trade deadline
. . . The read here on the Eastern Conference: Any one of the eight
teams could make it to the Cup finals, and that especially includes
the local entry. Read No. 2: Whoever makes it to the final will
have about the same shot the Bruins had in '88 and '90, when they
managed to win only one of nine games vs. the mighty Oilers . . .
Showing a slight pulse after playing barely a shade over comatose
all season, the Blackhawks removed the ``interim'' tag from Lorne
Molleken Thursday and made him the head coach, with what is
believed to be a three-year deal worth some $400,000 per season.
Entering the weekend, the non-playoff-bound Hawks were 11-6-4 since
the 42-year-old Molleken took over for Dirk Graham, the ex-Hawk who
only last summer hired him as his assistant. OK, 11-6-4 doesn't
sound like much, but that pace over an 82-game season projects to
upwards of 100 points _ a level the Hawks have reached only three
times in the last 25 years . . . If not for his roommate, Keith
Jones, virtually dragging him out of the team hotel, Eric Lindros
might have not made it to the Nashville hospital where doctors
reinflated his collapsed lung last weekend. His followup surgery
Thursday in Philadelphia to remove a hardened blood clot below the
lung went smoothly, but no one realistically expects L'Enfant
Terrible to be back in the Flyer lineup before next fall. Doctors
say it will take at least a month for him to regenerate the great
amount of blood he lost _ about half his body's supply _ and he
thus far has refused transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appears increasingly obvious around Los Angeles that Larry
Robinson won't be back to coach the Kings, who will be out of the
playoffs for the third time in four years under his watch. Good
coach, Robinson, but the Kings have been in a personnel crisis ever
since he arrived _ in part the result of trades such as Dafoe and
Dmitri Khristich for Jozef Stumpel and Sandy Moger. Ouchmagoucha.
One of their few good swaps was getting Luc Robitaille back in
return for Kevin Stevens, but there also was the
multimillion-dollar Steve Duchesne faux pas. If Robinson walks and
the Kings overhaul the coach department, three good assistants
could be cut loose: Don Edwards, Rick Green, and Jay Leach . . . At
a time when the trend is to build sparkling practice facilities _
an industrywide attempt to coddle the players and, more important,
better market the product _ the Bruins continue to hide their
practices behind locked doors in Wilmington. The folks at the
Ristuccia Center run a clean, efficient operation, and most players
live only a short commute to the rink. It's a nice fit. But as the
'90s draw to a close, and ticket prices skyrocket, there are more
and more fans who never will be able to afford a seat in the
FleetCenter. If they can't at least go to a practice and experience
the sight and sounds of the game, and their only connection is the
televised product (a subject for another day), then eventually that
segment of the fan base will disappear. A new facility with a
couple of rinks, festooned with team merchandise and a box office
for Vault events would go a long way toward enhancing the team
profile . . . On the subject of ticket sales, you know times are
changing when 1,000 seats go unsold in Montreal and scalpers are
seen dumping them for half-price. It happened Wednesday when the
Hurricanes were in town . . . Ex-Canadien Vincent Damphousse has
reconnected with his scoring touch now that he's in San Jose. He
hit for the hat trick last Saturday against Vancouver, bringing
down a flurry of hats and, in true Silicon Valley fashion, a hail
of software disks. HearMe.com, a local on-line venture that allows
chatters to actually talk on-line, blanketed the house with the
free disks. In Detroit you get octopus. In Miami you get rats. And
in San Jose . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens, for giving up Damphousse, will get a fifth-round
pick this season and at least a second-rounder in the 2000 draft.
It could become a first-rounder if: Damphousse plays in 90 percent
of the Sharks' games this season, including the playoffs; he
averages at least a point per game; the Sharks make it to the
second round of the postseason. And if Damphousse signs in San Jose
as a free agent this summer, the Habs could end up with a first-
and second-round pick in 2000 . . . Ex-Bruin Joe Juneau came down
with the flu soon after his trade to Buffalo and entered weekend
play with only one goal since departing Washington. Don't look for
the Sabres to try to sign him as a free agent. He has the Canadiens
and Senators at the top of his wish list . . . Entering weekend
play, the Hurricanes were a grim 0-5-5 in their last 10 road games.
Listen carefully, and you almost can hear the Forever .500 fight
song, ``Brass Bonanza.'' New city. Same Whale . . . In case you
missed it, the Flames late last month picked up Robyn Regehr as
part of the compensation for sending Theo Fleury to the Avalanche.
Colorado, using the pick it acquired from Boston in the Landon
Wilson-Anders Myrvold exchange, made Regehr the 19th pick overall
in the '98 draft. The Flames could use the 6-foot-2-inch, 210-pound
Regehr now, but he must remain in junior (Kamloops) until his
club's season comes to an end . . . Still no new deal for Brian
Sutter in Calgary . . . Cup or no Cup, look for the Avalanche to be
sold this summer, before the opening of their new Pepsi Center.
Ascent Entertainment is expected to unload the Avalanche, Nuggets,
and new arena to former Memphis State guard Bill Laurie, whose net
worth is reported as just shy of $1 billion (he married Nancy
Walton, heir to the Wal-Mart fortune). Meanwhile, it's biz as usual
in Denver. The Avalanche last week signed Alex Tanguay, their top
pick (No. 12 overall) last June, to a three-year deal worth $2.925
million and assigned him to Hershey (AHL). Tanguay is a slick
passer and proficient scorer (he popped in five goals in training
camp before being returned to junior) and has a decent chance of
sticking next season _ depending how the change in ownership
influences the financial makeup of the roster . . . The Red Wings
since their deadline wheeling and dealing: eight straight wins and
a tie, outscoring the opposition, 31-12. It's a possibility that
the Wings will move Brendan Shanahan (hello, Hurricanes? Rangers?
Flyers? Devils?) over the summer, in part to recoup the two
first-round draft picks they sent to Chicago in the Chris Chelios
swap. Shanahan next season will make $4 million (the end of a
four-year, $15.2 million pact) before becoming a free agent July 1,
2000 . . . If you're wondering what happened to ex-Bruin Garry
Galley on the LA depth chart, he recently exited the lineup with an
abdominal strain, won't be back this last week of the season, and
may require offseason surgery . . . The Devils will honor Peter
Stastny before their game at Exit 16W against the Islanders Monday.
Stastny, the only Devil to be inducted into the Hockey Hall of
Fame, now lives in suburban St. Louis and is a special-assignment
scout for the Blues . . . The Minnesota Wild, ready to debut in
October 2000, are about to begin interviews for prospective GMs.
Some of the names believed to be on the punch list: Les Jackson,
Pierre Page, Herb Brooks, David McNab, Paul Holmgren, Ray Shero,
and Bobby Smith. The St. Paul-based club doesn't have its broadcast
plan in place yet, but no fewer than 150 resume tapes already have
found their way to Wild HQ. If only the league's ice surfaces were
as competitive as the broadcast booth . . . If you want to make it
inside the Vault for the NHL's June 26 amateur draft, admission is
free (note: This is not a cruel hoax! It's a freebie). The general
admission ducats can be picked up only at the FleetCenter box
office beginning May 7. Season ticket-holders will receive their
tickets via mail at the start of May. Before the trooping of the
teen-agers, Bourque will be honored on the 20th anniversary of his
draft day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
