<HEADLINE>
BROWNS SHOULD SIT ON COUCH IN NO. 1 SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tom Condon is used to what he's been hearing
the last few weeks about his No. 1 client, Kentucky quarterback Tim
Couch. But he's not used to hearing what's being said about
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The former Boston College and NFL offensive lineman who now runs
IMG's football department is used to hearing that the top-rated guy
in December has more holes in his resume than Tim Johnson by April.
He heard it a year ago as scouts tried to poke holes in Peyton
Manning before the Colts made Manning the draft's No. 1 pick. Now
he's hearing it about Couch, who was the consensus No. 1 pick when
the college football season ended but now is said by some (although
not many NFL personnel directors) to be in a dead heat with Oregon
quarterback Akili Smith and Heisman Trophy-winning running back
Ricky Williams for the draft's premier position.
</P>
<P>
   But what Condon is not used to, nor terribly happy about, are
attacks from his business rivals about how he supposedly stole
Couch from rival agent Steve Wichard by reducing his company's fee
to $50,000 (according to ESPN Magazine) or zero (according to the
Atlanta Constitution) while guaranteeing Couch $3 million in
endorsement income.
</P>
<P>
   According to two people who should know _ Condon and Couch _
IMG's management fee has remained a standard 3 percent, the same 3
percent it was for Manning, even though it was whispered that
Condon had lowballed the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Condon intends to make that point, with the assistance of Couch
and Manning, when he does an ESPN interview to rebut Wichard's
charges. According to Condon, Wichard has declined to be
interviewed for the ESPN piece, which apparently will be at odds
with what appeared in the company's biweekly sports magazine
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Such contradictions were not the intention of what is called
branding, a marketing tool in which a company like ESPN or Disney
produces more than one side of a business (in this case, TV and
print media) and then uses them to promote the other. The idea is
to promote each other's product, not knock it, but Condon contends
his side of this issue was never fairly told in ESPN Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN Magazine says I'm doing Couch's deal for $50,000,''
Condon said. ``At least that's better than the Atlanta
Constitution, which said we were doing it for zero. When they get
it up to 3 percent, they'll be correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting ESPN TV to come in and do the flip side of this
story because this fee stuff is unfair and it's a problem with your
other clients. They've asked Wichard to be interviewed and he told
them he wouldn't cooperate. We'll see how this ends up. We haven't
undercut our fees.''
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said for what some scouts have done to Couch
in recent months. If you believe his critics, he has gone from
being the most accurate and reliable passer available to a guy who
can't throw this and can't throw that.
</P>
<P>
   Smith supposedly is rising faster than flood waters and is in a
flat-footed tie with Couch and Williams, yet all of this has been
accomplished without a single college football game having been
played since January, which led Condon to laughingly comment,
``When we signed Tim, I thought he was a great player. Now I think
his arm got cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no different than what happened with Peyton last year.
All of a sudden Peyton was the thinking man but (Ryan) Leaf had the
arm. Now that's what Tim's going through.''
</P>
<P>
   That may come to an end Sunday when Couch finishes a private
workout for the Cleveland Browns in Lexington, Ky., that will be
run by head coach Chris Palmer and watched by personnel boss Dwight
Clark and club president Carmen Policy, who reportedly is a big
Couch supporter.
</P>
<P>
   When IMG ran a private workout for NFL scouts a few weeks back,
word leaked out that the Browns were upset that Condon had
orchestrated the entire event, having it run by former Patriots
offensive coordinator Larry Kennan. Condon ran a similarly
structured workout a year ago for Manning without a hitch and had
made clear to the top drafting teams that Couch would willingly
work out again for them privately, as he is doing Sunday for the
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through the teams and ask who they think will be
taken first _ and I talked with 18 of them this week about the
draft _ Tim went No. 1 to every one,'' Condon said. ``I expect
he'll be the guy. Akili Smith has a hell of an arm and he's a hell
of an athlete. He's deserving of a lot of consideration, as is
Ricky Williams and Tim Couch. But if I'm the new franchise with a
chance to put in place the linchpin for the next 10-15 years, you
have to believe Cleveland will select a quarterback and the facts
are Tim is the most proven and the best prepared for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Draft guru Gil Brandt doesn't disagree with that thinking,
although he tends to favor Smith's athleticism and arm strength
over Couch's. After spending two decades picking players for some
of the Dallas Cowboys' finest teams, Brandt knows well the value of
a runner like Williams, who may be the best back to come out in the
draft since Barry Sanders, but he also knows how far you go without
a top-flight quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he sees no way Cleveland can pass up one of the
top-rated ones, especially when you consider what will be left in
the college ranks after Couch, Smith, Donovan McNabb, and Daunte
Culpepper leave this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little question about Couch's arm strength but Billy
Kilmer had no arm and he took his team to the Super Bowl,'' Brandt
said. ``People are very high on Smith because he had some of the
best practices any quarterback has ever had before the East-West
game, and that's going back to Terry Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, why I would take a quarterback if I was Cleveland
is that in the next two drafts I don't see a quarterback coming out
you can count on. Someone may do it but I don't see it for a couple
of years. So if you don't get the guy now, in this draft, you may
not be in a position to get him in the future. You can say what you
want about running backs but ours is a quarterback-driven game. You
can't ever pass a top-rated quarterback up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at history. Look at last year. Last year (Andre)
Wadsworth and (Charles) Woodson were the top two rated players by
everybody, but who went first? Manning and Leaf. It's simple. Would
you rather own an acre of land in downtown Boston or 500 acres in
Maine?''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Condon believes in the end Cleveland will do
what the Colts did a year ago and revert to what was the consensus
when the college season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``In either situation (1 or 2) you make an awful lot of money,''
Condon said of the difference in drafting positions. ``So some of
this has to do with pride and legacy. For us, Cleveland would be
nice because our world headquarters is located there and it would
make it easier to market Tim but it doesn't really affect either
player financially very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't see a way Cleveland doesn't draft a quarterback
first really. Look at the last Super Bowl. John Elway was the
quarterback but each team had a running back taken in the sixth
round. If you look at the whole history of Carmen and Dwight in San
Francisco, they won with a lot of different running backs but only
two quarterbacks: Joe Montana and Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though Ricky Williams might be the best player coming
out, No. 1-drafted running backs haven't fared that well. And backs
like Earl Campbell, who Williams is compared to, don't normally
last at the top more than six years. Quarterbacks can play for 15.
So the real possibility I see is quarterbacks going 1-2-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon sees an even greater possibility that his client will go
No. 1, for the same reason Manning went ahead of Leaf a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leigh Steinberg (Smith's agent) has a guy with a real upside,
like he had last year with Leaf,'' Condon said. ``But he also has a
24-year-old kid who only played one year of (major) college ball
(as a full-time starter), who has a DWI, an assault charge (which
Smith does not dispute), and a father who's a pain in the ass with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Couch is 3 inches taller, 20 pounds heavier, comes from a
ball-control offense with many similarities to the one Chris Palmer
will run in Cleveland, is completely clean off the field, and is
great on the blackboard. He has all the tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sure bets in the world except that NFL personnel
people don't give a damn what an agent says about his player. Tim
understands that. But unless Cleveland thinks it can make Akili a
Hall of Famer in two or three years and can live with Ty Detmer in
the interim I don't see how they take anyone but Tim because you
don't have to hope for anything with him. He's got it all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seems there's a little tension between old friends Andy Reid and
Mike Holmgren. The Seahawks' new head coach, under whom Reid was
quarterbacks coach in Green Bay, questioned Reid's decision to name
untested free agent Doug Pederson the immediate Eagles starter
despite Pederson having never started an NFL game. ``You've got to
be careful of making promises like that because things happen and
you can let it wreck your team,'' Holmgren said. ``I'm not second
guessing that but you've got to be careful.'' When Reid learned
what his old mentor, who had also pursued Pederson, said of one of
his first decisions as the new Eagles coach, he claimed Holmgren
had made a similar promise to Pederson when trying to sign him.
``He told Doug he'd be the starter unless he threw every ball in
the dirt,'' Reid said . . . Some moves are hard to fathom. On
Thursday, the Packers obtained kick returner Jahine Arnold from the
Steelers for ``past considerations.'' Not long thereafter, they
withdrew their qualifying offer to return man Roell Preston, thus
making him a free agent. Arnold has been hurt the last two years (a
knee injury that kept him out all of 1997 and a broken collarbone
and finger injury that limited him last year) while Preston set
Packer records for kick-return yardage (1,497) and was selected to
the Pro Bowl last season. What did Arnold do to match that in 1998?
He returned three kickoffs for 78 yards and four punts for 19. I'd
never question the personnel decisions of Packer player guru Ron
Wolf, but go figure . . . I love Reggie White and a lot of what he
stands for, but his editorial in the Wall Street Journal last week
calling for women reporters to be barred from locker rooms went
around the bend and over the top. ``I can't see any legitimate
reason for forcing male athletes to walk around naked in front of
women who aren't their wives,'' White wrote. Me neither, but hasn't
anyone heard of a bathrobe and a towel in Green Bay? White also
wrote, ``I've seen a lot of female reporters and camerawomen ogling
guys in the locker room. There's not much a player can do about it,
which leads to a high level of frustration.'' First off, I think we
have a high-octane mix of ego and paranoia working here, but
wouldn't a simple robe end the frustration? As for the ogling of
men often 50-100 pounds overweight, I doubt it. If some of the guys
who play White's old position had a mirror and some common sense,
they'd cover themselves up voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Cardinals linebacker Jamir Miller to be coming to
New England unless Arizona can land a top linebacking prospect
early in the draft. First off, Miller is not a pass-rushing threat.
With the exception of one game last season, he never has been and
never will be. He is a fundamentally sound outside backer who is
strong against the run but not especially elusive or overpowering
when rushing the passer. He could be helpful in New England in that
run-stopper role he played in Arizona, but he wants too much money
and seems hell-bent on being what he isn't and the Patriots can't
make him. Last week he dumped agent Steve Baker in favor of
Steinberg, who has a good relationship with Cardinals management.
Steinberg represents Arizona quarterback Jake Plummer and last year
ironed out a big-money deal that was good for both his client and
the team. He now hopes to work out a short-term solution for Miller
in Arizona that would significantly increase his salary from the
$710,000 of a year ago to either a one-year deal for $1.5 million
or a two-year deal in the $4 million range. That is still possible
despite the recent signing of veteran free agent Rob Fredrickson to
a four-year, $7.9 million contract. That deal happened only after
Miller rejected Arizona's two-year, $6 million offer, but the sides
are still willing to talk and the disappointed Miller, who thought
he'd land a deal in the $6.5 million-a-year range when free agency
began, may be ready to listen to the sound of something other than
his own voice screaming, ``Show me the money.'' . . . The Steelers
can't seem to get a break. The same day they signed Wayne Gandy to
a four-year, $14 million deal to relieve their problems at left
tackle, they learned right tackle Justin Strzelczyk had to undergo
his second knee operation in less than a year after reinjuring a
ligament torn last October during a rehab workout. It is unlikely
he will play this season, so don't send the ostensibly retired Will
Wolford a going-away present yet. Steelers coach Bill Cowher had
tried to convince Wolford to stay one more year and just play on
passing downs but Wolford had a retirement party at his home in
Kentucky . . . Gandy had a funny explanation for why he finally
agreed to terms with the Steelers, a team with whom he had been
negotiating for some time. ``Their offer came up and I came down,''
the former St. Louis Ram said. ``I got tired of pleading and
begging with them and they got tired of pleading and begging with
me. So we signed a deal.'' Gandy started the last 64 games for the
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of fair play and equal time, here's what Leland
Hardy, one of Williams's agents, says of the draft possibilities:
``This is a high-stakes game of liar's poker right now. Teams all
talk about the players they don't really want but they all know
Ricky is the most prolific player in college football history. He
ran a 4.34 on Cleveland's clock and a 4.44 on Baltimore's at his
workout. He was 224 pounds (down 20 from two months ago) and
benched 225 22 times. There are no questions about Ricky Williams.
I thnk Ricky goes to Cleveland because they know his proven ability
to deliver. You don't pass on a once-in-a-lifetime back. Even if
you're leaning toward a quarterback for need, Ricky's ability so
far outshadows the rest they have to take him. The draft is all
about minimizing risk. What's the greater risk? An unproven
quarterback or a proven running back who was the greatest college
player in history?'' . . . Just for the record, here's one of the
things about Smith that concerns some teams. At Oregon, the coaches
reportedly had to use red and black checkers to help him understand
their offense. Red was the offense. Black was the defense. Early
confusion after arriving from junior college (and a three-year
stint in the Pittsburgh Pirates' minor league baseball system) kept
him on the bench and then sharing the position until early last
season, when he shined. Smith did well in postseason all-star games
and individual workouts this spring, but teams remember that just a
year ago he was suspended at Oregon for being involved in
fourth-degree assault, second-degree trespass, and harassment in
the wake of an incident outside a barroom. He was acquitted of the
assault charge but pleaded no contest to drunk driving and entered
an alcohol awareness program. When talent is as close as it is
between guys like Smith, Couch, and the other top-rated prospects,
such factors become magnified . . . This is how things can go as
the paranoia grows in the final days before the draft. Scouts are
worried about Williams's size 7 hands. They feel those small hands
have led him to fumble too often. Hey, you rush for 6,279 yards and
break 16 NCAA records, you might drop the ball a few times. Last
time I looked, he didn't drop the Heisman when they handed it to
him . . . On the other hand (pardon the pun), scouts are breathless
about Florida pass rusher Jevon Kearse, who has size 12 hands, ran
the 40 in 4.52 and 4.50 seconds at a recent workout, and had a
vertical leap of 40 1/2 inches. That's all well and good but he's
also a ``tweener'' without a real position unless he's playing
outside linebacker in a 3-4 defense. And that vertical leap won't
do him much good, by the way, since most tackles are taller than 40
1/2 inches. He won't be jumping over them to get to the quarterback
. . . When Eastern Michigan tackle L.J. Shelton is taken early in
the draft, don't be shocked if he looks familiar. His father is
former NBA star Lonnie Shelton, which probably explains some of the
unusual athletic ability he has packed into a 6-foot-5-inch frame
that is carrying more than 300 pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
