<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      04-10 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROMISES MORE WARPLANES FOR NATO CAMPAIGN AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States committed 82 more warplanes
Saturday to NATO's campaign against Yugoslavia, and the alliance
promised an aerial attack of ``increasing ferocity'' when better
weather returned over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four bombing waves were canceled in the 24 hours
ending Saturday morning because of cloud cover, said Col. Konrad
Freytag, a NATO spokesman. He said some missile attacks, less
dependent on weather, were launched from U.S. and British ships.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees reported the exodus of
mainly ethnic Albanians from the Serbian province of Kosovo had
topped a half-million persons.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana, Albania, international officials reported that more
than 4,000 new refugees from Kosovo crossed the Albanian border
Saturday and hundreds more were lined up on the Yugoslav side. The
troops of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for several days
have vacillated between opening border points and pushing ethnic
Albanians out, or closing crossings and urging people to return to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th day of NATO's airstrikes got under way as Serb
Christians prepared to celebrate Orthodox Easter today. Alliance
officials belittled Milosevic's claim of a cease-fire for the
holiest day of the Orthodox Christian calendar, pointing to
continued assaults on ethnic Albanian villages in Kosovo, populated
mostly by Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is the southern province of Serbia, one of the two pieces
of the remaining Yugoslavia. NATO has demanded that Milosevic
withdraw his forces from Kosovo and allow a cease-fire to be
policed by an international force.
</P>
<P>
   The additional U.S. planes brings the total committed by
Washington to approximately 480 _ out of the total of about 680
which NATO member nations have dedicated to the force.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said he expected ``other allies
will be announcing force enhancement soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon detailed the commitment as 24 more F-16 fighters armed
with HARM anti-radar missiles, four more tank-hunter A-10
Thunderbolts, six radar-jamming EA-6B Prowlers, 39 KC-135 and two
KC-10 refueling tanker aircraft and seven C130 transports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it will allow us to increase the intensity of the
air campaign over Kosovo and Yugoslavia,'' Bacon said, providing
``more deep strike capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Henderson, British armed forces minister, declared: ``When
the weather clears, the bombing will continue with increasing
ferocity.'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said allied planes
flew strikes Saturday ``in spite of weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Tanjug news agency carried a commentary Saturday
by the Yugoslav military that called NATO's strategy a ``fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance countered by pointing out that half of Yugoslavia's
most modern fighter planes had been destroyed in the air campaign
and that two of the three major army headquarters had been
decimated.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said half of the Yugoslav fuel stocks
have been destroyed, ``and it's increasingly difficult for the
Yugoslav army units to move the remaining fuel stocks around, to
get them into the units in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies' focus on more planes and more robust attacks came as
pressure mounted for NATO to at least begin to plan for the
deployment of allied ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a White House spokesman for the national security
council, said President Clinton continued to believe ``we can
achieve our objectives through the phased air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to persist until we prevail,'' he said. ``And
we're confident that day by day as we attack his military
infrastructure we can achieve our objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov told the Turkish daily
Hurriyet that he would not allow a land offensive into Kosovo to be
launched from his country, Reuters news service reported. NATO
already has 12,000 troops in Macedonia preparing to police what the
alliance hopes will be a cease-fire in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican weekly radio address, Rep. Heather Wilson,
R-N.M., called on Clinton to give Congress ``a complete picture of
the situation in the Balkans _ the effects of the bombing, the
military and nonmilitary options and the risks of each.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our airmen and sailors and soldiers have done their jobs well,
but it is unlikely that airpower can stop a door-to-door campaign
of repression,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns from a spring break this week, some
Republicans are expected to press for votes on resolutions that
would prohibit use of U.S. forces in a ground attack without
specific authorization of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his weekly radio address, did not mention the
Yugoslav fighting but talked about the administration's ``welfare
to work'' program. Clinton played golf Saturday afternoon at the
Army-Navy Club in suburban Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Shea insisted that the air assault has ``inflicted a hell of a
lot of damage, quite frankly, on the Yugoslav armed forces.'' He
said that Yugoslav army and special police forces were ``feeling
the pressure'' and ``are essentially static.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hiding themselves because obviously they now have to
contend with the serious risks of attacks from NATO,'' Shea said.
``They're off the main roads and seeking smaller roads now for
their operations. And of course, they are running out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good news that they're still there, but it is good
news that they're finding it increasingly difficult to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same Pentagon briefing at which the additional planes
were announced, Maj. General Charles Wald, vice-director of
strategic planning for the joint chiefs of staff, said it could be
as long as a month before 24 U.S. Apache attack helicopters could
be thrown fully into the NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters, which starred in the Persian Gulf War, allow
close-in strikes on ground troops and tanks and are largely
impervious to bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, Shea said it would
take an additional 124 flights into Tirana, capital of Albania, to
import the helicopters, accompanying multiple-launch rocket system
and the equipment and personnel to get the Apaches up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather has also delayed some of the equipment flights into
Tirana, where the airport is still being upgraded by U.S.
personnel. The airport is overwhelmed with flights of military
equipment and humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said ``NATO is in overdrive'' to provide food and supplies
for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the `ethnic cleansing' continues,'' Shea said,
detailing ``the distressing almost unbelievable pictures'' emerging
from camps in Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said another village was affected Friday. ``Again, the
usual story which is now becoming the daily routine of everybody
being stripped of their identify cards, their valuables, whatever,
being frog-marched to the border and then pushed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at least I imagine they're the lucky ones _ they're still
alive and can be cared for by the humanitarian relief
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton spoke by telephone with U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan, thanking him for his statement Friday
asking Milosevic to withdraw all Yugoslav forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said Clinton told Annan that the U.N. leader's statement
made clear ``there is a united front and that President Milosevic
must end his brutality and give the Kosovars the dignity and
security that they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that because Annan's statement ``was identical to the
one that you've heard from NATO countries once again shows that it
is not simply NATO that has formulated the objectives, but the
entire international community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
