<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-GIRL-1STLD     04-10 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-GIRL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING GIRL FOUND IN BOOKSTORE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update)   By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 14-year-old girl who was reported missing on
Thursday night was found Saturday afternoon at an East Village
bookstore, where she had apparently been reading for two days while
the police and more than 70 volunteers searched for her across
Manhattan, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said that the girl, Maureen Lynch, failed to return
home because of worries about her low grades.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen's parents, Mary and Robert Lynch, at first suspected
that their daughter's disappearance was related to her medical
condition, hydrocephalus, which causes a chronic buildup of fluid
in the brain and occasional fainting spells.
</P>
<P>
   Her orthodontist, Dr. Vincent LaBruna, told them that Maureen
appeared pale and light-headed during a Thursday afternoon
appointment, the last time she was seen before vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   When she did not come home at 7 p.m. that night, Mrs. Lynch
called the police and then began organizing a search party. Among
those who passed out more than 10,000 fliers Friday and Saturday
were classmates from the Convent of the Sacred Heart, a private
school on East 91st Street where Maureen is a ninth grader, and
residents from the Stuyvesant Town neighborhood where the family
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful for all the help we received,'' said Martha
Hayden, Maureen's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at 6:30 p.m., a customer at the Barnes &AMP; Noble on Astor
Place recognized Maureen from one of the fliers and called the
police. An officer arrived and took her to the 13th Precinct
station house, where she was reunited with her family.
</P>
<P>
   A sales clerk at the store said she noticed Maureen in the young
adult section over the past two days. Detectives said Maureen spent
both nights sleeping unnoticed in an out-of-the-way portion of the
lobby in the building where she lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hayden, who spoke to her granddaughter, said Maureen was
embarrassed. ``She had no idea there was such a fuss over her,''
she said. ``She feels really bad about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
