<HEADLINE>
WORM REPRISES ROLE IN LATE SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Somewhere out there is an imaginary line
drawn by Lakers management, and though it's unclear just where the
line is, suffice to say Dennis Rodman is perilously close to
crossing it.
</P>
<P>
   In a now-familiar scene, Rodman arrived 65 minutes late to
practice Saturday, a day after he refused to re-enter the fourth
quarter of the Lakers' victory over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds familiar, it should: exactly two weeks ago, Rodman
skipped a Saturday practice, a day after refusing to re-enter the
fourth quarter against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   That transgression led to meetings with management and coach,
who were assured Rodman would get his act together. It lasted two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you gonna write about this?'' Rodman asked a group of
reporters, upon entering the Forum. Then he walked toward the Forum
floor, threw his hand in the air and muttered something about being
``persecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending the rest of practice riding a stationary bike,
Rodman reappeared and told reporters, ``You've got a story today.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a story Kurt Rambis could do without. The Lakers' coach
said he did not speak with Rodman and had not resolved the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman apparently called ahead to say he had to pick up his son
and would be late, but Rambis said he hasn't determined whether the
absence is excused.
</P>
<P>
   Would the troubled forward start today's game against Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he shows up,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't talk to Dennis about anything. I had other things I
had to deal with today,'' Rambis said, then repeated his Rodman
philosophy: ``I'm not gonna freak out about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I wanted to happen,'' he said, ``but hey, it
happened.... I'm disappointed he didn't show up to practice on
time, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   It's generally believed that Lakers management warned Rodman two
weeks ago that any further problems could prompt his release.
Rambis wouldn't confirm if that's the case and said he doesn't feel
such action is warranted yet.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Lakers simply practiced without Rodman, then
brushed off any concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Kurt Rambis problem, it's not a Shaq O'Neal problem,''
O'Neal said. ``If I was in control, I ain't gonna say what I would
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant laughed at the predictable questions and said
Rodman's absence isn't a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much old habit. You just don't think about it too
much,'' he said. ``If it comes out (Sunday) that he doesn't know
the game plan, doesn't know the rotation, what we're doing then
that's different. I don't think it's gonna happen because he
prepares so much for the game. But if it does happen, then that's a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if, come playoff time, Rodman refuses to re-enter a
game in the fourth quarter?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, come playoff time, Dennis will be there,'' Bryant said.
``I'm not gonna even worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we were getting into when we signed Dennis,'' he
said. ``The method of thinking was his positives would outweigh the
negatives. So far, they have.''
</P>
<P>
   But certainly, Rodman is testing the coach's patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three kids,'' Rambis said, ``I have plenty of
patience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
