<HEADLINE>
UCLA SWEEPS ARIZONA IN SOFTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps it's strange that a team more than 30
games above .500 considers itself not playing well.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to UCLA softball, home of the nation's No. 1-ranked
team, where defensive letdowns and numerous come-from-behind
victories have people suggesting a lack of consistency.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, at least, the fears disappeared as the Bruins swept
No. 2 Arizona 6-2 and 3-2 on Saturday in a Pac-10 doubleheader at
Easton Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: the Bruins (38-1, 7-1) committed no errors and never
trailed in sweeping the Wildcats (33-7, 5-3) at home for the first
time in four years. Arizona tied the score 2-2 in each game, only
to see UCLA take the lead on Stacey Nuveman hits.
</P>
<P>
   Nuveman's bloop single to center in the sixth inning drove in
two runs in the first game, and her 19th home run of the season, a
solo shot to left in the bottom of the fifth, was the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a step in the right direction,'' Nuveman said, ``but
we haven't played our best yet. We haven't run on all cylinders, as
we like to say. Our potential we haven't shown.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, Arizona coach Mike Candrea said, he doesn't
want to see the Bruins when they're peaking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UCLA has numerous people it can rely on for offensive
punch. But on Saturday, first baseman Julie Marshall was 0 for 6
and shortstop Lyndsey Klein was 1 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Julie Adams fared better, going 3 for 7 with 2
RBI, although her two-run single followed Nuveman's in the first
game. Monroe High School graduate Lupe Brambila was 3 for 5 and
drove in the Bruins' first run of the day. Christie Ambrosi, who
had been slumping, went 3 for 5 with an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the most critical moments, only Nuveman stepped forward
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team does not rely on any one individual,'' UCLA coach
Sue Enquist said. ``You can take what Nuveman has done lately and
it just appears she has come through so many times. She's one of
the most prolific student-athletes to put on a uniform at UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuveman's heroics gave pitcher Courtney Dale (19-0) two
victories Saturday, which Dale said was a first in her UCLA career.
</P>
<P>
   Dale went the distance in the first game, scattering six hits
and giving up two earned runs, coming via Katie Swan's home run and
RBI groundout. In the second game, she relieved Amanda Freed in the
fifth inning and pitched 21/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   And the UCLA defense, which let down with three errors in a loss
last week at Washington, was flawless Saturday. It held leadoff
batter and Saugus High graduate Nicole Giordano hitless (0 for 8),
and it handed the Wildcats their third consecutive loss. Arizona,
the defending national runner-up, lost the second game of its
Wednesday doubleheader against Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not able to play seven innings right now,'' Candrea
said. ``It's been one inning that's come back to haunt us.It's been
a long time, I tell you, since we've had seven losses at this
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
