<SLUG> BC-GLF-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN LOST BALL, BUT FOUND HIS COMPOSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It was out there, somewhere betwixt the dogwoods
and the azaleas, amid billowing pillows of Golden Bell and Asiatic
Jasmine, in the clasped hands of Amen Corner, that Greg Norman was
supposed to have gone belly-up.
</P>
<P>
   Always has. And, some say, always will.
</P>
<P>
   Not so poetically, of course. In the past, when Norman has
choked away a Masters, there hasn't been much reason to scythe
through the sonnets and wade into the horticultural digest.
</P>
<P>
   But here we were in yesterday's third round, watching Norman,
Augusta National's eternal prisoner, waist deep in the flora and
fauna behind hole No. 12. A human metaphor, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Clawing at the jasmine and azaleas. Combing. Searching.
Thinking.
</P>
<P>
   And just what was Greg Norman thinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``Find the \Rblank\S ball! What do you think was going through
my mind?'' Norman replied.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, poetry.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, lost golf balls are quite ordinary. At Rockwood
or Z. Boaz. When you or I play.
</P>
<P>
   But as Norman said, ``I'd like to know how many balls have been
lost on the back of the 12th green in the third round of a major
championship like the Masters?''
</P>
<P>
   By rule, he had five minutes to find his tee shot on the par-3
hole. He had his caddie, Tony Navarro, along with playing partner
Lee Janzen and his caddie, all rummaging through the hallowed
shrubbery, while Rae's Creek gurgled nearby. And he also had
green-jacketed tournament officials, tapping their feet, jingling
pocket change, and probably reminding Norman that if he didn't
hurry up, CBS was going to cut to another Cadillac commercial.
</P>
<P>
   No pressure. It was only the third-round lead of this 63rd
Masters that was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give 500 bucks if anybody will go out and find that ball
on 12,'' Norman announced in the interview room.
</P>
<P>
   He never found it. But poignantly, Norman unearthed both his
composure and his golf game after his adventures through Amen
Corner.
</P>
<P>
   With the most often-rhapsodized, well-chronicled 18 holes in
golf left to play today, Norman can be found in a familiar
position:
</P>
<P>
   On the brink of the Masters leader board. Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Norman who has never won at Augusta National,
but has finished second _ often accompanied by a mushroom cloud _
thrice. This is the same Norman who has finished in second place
more than any golfer (27 times) in PGA Tour history.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it isn't the same Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the simmer of losing his ball yesterday _ which cost him
two strokes _ Norman stalked back to the tee box, plopped his
second tee shot 22 feet from the pin, and then rolled in his putt
for what could end up being one of most memorable bogeys in
tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   The ``old'' Norman also might not have recovered when he bogeyed
the very next hole, falling two strokes _ and seemingly reeling _
behind leader Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I feel much better about myself because of
what's happened in the last 12 months,'' Norman explained.
</P>
<P>
   He has had shoulder surgery and, more importantly, discovered
some much-needed mental chicken soup. During his months off from
tournament golf, he found himself spending quality time with
teenage daughter Morgan-Leigh and going to his son Gregory's
football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong,'' Norman said. ``Tomorrow I'm going out to
play and win because that's what I'm here for. But you realize
there are other things around.''
</P>
<P>
   So here we go again. Greg Norman, again, sits an arm's length
away from winning the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Don't say it. Don't even think it.
</P>
<P>
   Norman was the first golfer in PGA tour history to earn $10
million. He has won tournaments in 13 countries.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Augusta, where the dogwood blooms alongside the
camellias, where the rough isn't called rough but the ``second
cut,'' where the gallery is called ``patrons'' and the term
``bikini wax'' can get a TV guy fired, and where so many
Faulkner-come-latelies have crafted sonnets in ode to the great
toon-uh-mint, Norman has been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   You think people are going to be tuning in today to watch
Olazabal, the Spaniard with bad feet?
</P>
<P>
   No, here in Georgia, the day looms as another NASCAR
extravaganza. ``Crash'' Norman, racing headlong into Rae's Creek,
the Eisenhower Tree and Amen Corner. His wheels didn't come flying
off yesterday, but there's always today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that I don't live in the past,'' Norman said
yesterday. ``I've never been a believer in crying over spilled
milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that I'm here right now with a chance to
win tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   And we all know what that means. Here in Augusta. Gulp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
