<HEADLINE>
DON'T WALK, RUN FROM ARIZONA LIES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wherever you may be when this desperate dispatch reaches you,
please, please, STOP. Do not take one step closer to Arizona, not
until you've read this column.
</P>
<P>
   You've been lied to.
</P>
<P>
   You've been deceived.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but there's no time to mince words. When the
perpetrators of this mas sive conspiracy realize I'm attempting to
expose their plot, there's no telling what they'll do. If they're
capable of making outrageous falsehoods appear believable on a
national and international scale, they're capable of anything.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm begging you, pull over in Albu querque. Make a U-turn on
your way south from Saskatchewan. Switch it into reverse and head
back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is not what they say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, in the April issue of a supposedly legitimate
publication called Western Blue Chip Economic Forecast, Arizona was
listed as the top spot for job growth among all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   This follows reports that the Phoenix metropolitan area is among
the fastest-growing communities in the nation, with low
unemployment, great schools, afford able new housing and all the
amenities of a major city.
</P>
<P>
   DO NOT BELIEVE IT.
</P>
<P>
   Such accounts are as phony as the pho tographs you may have seen
of glorious sunsets, beautiful mountains, palm trees, swimming
pools, golf courses, hiking trails, shiny new buildings and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Lakes?
</P>
<P>
   As I write this, I haven't seen or tasted a drop of water in
weeks. &QL; 
UNDER THE FIREBALL
</P>
<P>
   It was all I could do to crawl here along the dry, scorched
desert to type out this report with fingers transformed into sticks
of beef jerky by the unrelenting fireball hovering about 30 feet
over our heads.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, you say. What about that fancy new retractable dome
ballpark in downtown Phoenix? I saw it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Trickery. Computer graphics.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually a sound stage in Burbank. And the so-called
ballplayers are rejects from soap operas. (If you've seen them
play, you'd know this.)
</P>
<P>
   For years I was an accomplice in this monumental frame-up. I
told friends back east about the beautiful weather, the lovely
neighborhoods, the unrestrained opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   I was a collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that same right-coast conspiracy wants you to abandon your
comfortable residences in the crowded East and Mid west _
presumably so they'll have have more room for their fancy estates.
</P>
<P>
   And you've done it. Hundreds of thou sands of you moved here.
</P>
<P>
   And you keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling up stakes and heading west, fooled by doctored images of
a lovely metropolis that, in fact, looks more like a piece of burnt
toast with pencils stuck in it. &QL; 
IT'S AN EVIL SCHEME
</P>
<P>
   It's this simple:
</P>
<P>
   If you move to Arizona, you'll die.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the cacti. You can't take a step anywhere
outdoors without getting stuck by some unholy spur.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, your foot first lands on the poison-filled
tail of the scorpions that cover the bare, brown earth like a
skittering blanket of beastly barbs.
</P>
<P>
   The overseers of this evil scheme will tell you I'm lying.
</P>
<P>
   They'll say I'm one of those Eastern transplants who drifted
here some years back, found the place full of beauty and
possibilities, and now want to keep it from becoming overcrowded by
those drawn to the same Southwestern paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it. These people will stop at nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They've even lied to you about the rat tlesnakes, making it seem
as if the slither ing monsters live in the desert under rocks and
prefer to keep to themselves. In fact, I'm surrounded by rattlers
as I type this, their chattering tails like hailstones on a tin
roof.
