<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICER-SLAIN-1STLD-W     04-10 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-SLAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST MADE IN KILLING OF NEW JERSEY POLICEMAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update, ID suspect)  By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 24-year-old New Jersey man was arrested and charged
Saturday in the fatal shooting of an Orange, N.J., police officer
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, identified by the police as Terrance Everett, was
arrested early Saturday at his home in East Orange after scores of
police officers spent 24 hours scouring the streets of Orange, a
2.2-square-mile city of 29,000 residents northwest of Newark, and
nearby communities.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with murder, criminal possession of a weapon and
robbery, said Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County
Prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery charges were for two separate incidents in which,
the police say, Everett used a gun to accost people on the street
just minutes before he was stopped by the officer he is accused of
killing, Joyce Anne Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   Everett was being held at the Essex County Jail Saturday night,
with bail set at $1 million, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Details about Everett were unavailable Saturday night. Weiss
said he could not provide information about Everett's occupation,
his address, or whether he had a criminal record. Everett has an
unlisted phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carnegie, 38, was shot in the head and abdomen at close
range after approaching Everett, who matched the description of the
robbery suspect, the authorities said. The victim's younger sister,
Gayle Carnegie, said the police called Saturday morning ``to say
they have the guy in custody and they would be getting back to us
with the details of the arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just so overjoyed to know that they caught the guy so
quickly,'' said Ms. Carnegie, a nurse's aide who lives in Newark.
``We know that the police do their job, and we know that they love
one of their own fellow police officers. They were out there all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the officers searching for their colleague's killer
worked through the night, canvassing the streets, backyards and
parking lots of the normally quiet town in patrol cars with their
sirens blaring. The police director, Richard Conti, was said to
have stayed in his office from Friday until about 7 a.m. Saturday;
his assistant left at 1 a.m., only to return later in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residents dropped bouquets at a makeshift memorial
near the site of the shooting, and friends and family members
lovingly recalled a woman who took seriously the role of the beat
cop as guardian of a community.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carnegie was the first member of the Orange Police
Department to die in the line of duty in 33 years, and the second
female New Jersey officer ever killed on the job. Her death sent
the 113-member police force into emotional turmoil, and members of
the City Council spent Saturday morning at police headquarters
consoling grief-stricken officers.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carnegie lived with her mother in North Plainfield,
where relatives gathered Saturday, sharing memories. She discovered
a love for law enforcement while working as a security guard at a
Sears department store, according to her mother, and continued to
work part-time as a guard at a clothing store when off-duty.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Carnegie said her family was comforted by Gov. Christie
Whitman's presence at the hospital where Joyce Carnegie was taken
Thursday evening, and by her recent signing of a bill that made
death or life in jail without parole the only penalties for anyone
convicted of killing a police officer acting in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral has been scheduled for 11 a.m. Thursday at St.
Matthew's Church on Oakwood Avenue in Orange, Ms. Carnegie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
