<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-FISHING-REEL     04-10 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FISHING-REEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: AN INVENTOR WHO HELPED NOVICES CAST LIKE PROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEN SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the fall of 1947, the fisherman R.D. Hull arrived at the
headquarters of Zero Hour Bomb Co. on Easton Street in Tulsa,
Okla., with a prototype of what would become America's most popular
fishing reel. It was made from the metal lid of a can of Folgers
Mountain Grown Drip Grind coffee, an 11-inch-long piece of wire, a
wooden sewing thread spool and braided nylon line.
</P>
<P>
   A West Texas watchmaker and inveterate tinkerer, Hull nailed his
contraption to a board and showed it to the general manager and
legal counsel of Zero Hour, which manufactured timed explosives
used in oil well drilling. He wanted to create a simple reel that
anyone could use without line snarls, and he got an idea for it
while watching a grocery store clerk pull string from a spool to
wrap a meat package.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reel types of the late 1940s had revolving
spools, and the models used for casting heavy lures and natural
baits had a notorious tendency to create line snarls, known as
backlashes. These occurred when the revolving spool turned faster
than the line departed the spool. It took great practice and
considerable patience to cast with a minimum amount of backlashing.
</P>
<P>
   Watching string come off a stationary spool made Hull realize
that backlashes could be avoided by using a fixed, rather than
revolving, spool. His timing was impeccable. Nylon was just
becoming established in the manufacture of monofilament fishing
line and would soon improve all aspects of angling. And, because
Zero Hour Bomb Co. was facing an expiring patent and a new postwar
technology landscape, it was ripe for new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   So ripe that in June 1949 the company produced 25 handmade
derivatives of Hull's can-cum-wire invention, called them
closed-faced reels, and never looked back. Within a few years Zero
Hour Bomb Co. had more of a business with fishing reels than time
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956 a friend of the company asked that a reel be sent to his
friend President Dwight D. Eisenhower, an avid angler. A reel was
sent to the White House, where security personnel saw the name of
the company on the package and promptly put the unopened box into a
tub of water and called a bomb squad to defuse it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, the company changed its name to Zebco. It got out
of the explosives business, and, mainly on the strength of Hull's
idea, went on to become one of the world's largest fishing tackle
manufacturers. In 50 years Zebco has sold an estimated 220 million
of these reels and is a major producer of other reels, rods, and
boating supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The closed-face reel devised by R.D. Hull would eventually
become known to anglers as a spincast or spincasting reel. It is
easily distinguished by its push-button line release, and by a
cone-shaped cover or hood that shrouds a stationary spool, a line
pickup device, and a line-winding mechanism. The covered spool
remains stationary when line is wound, or spun, around it, and when
it is unwound during casting.
</P>
<P>
   To draw attention to spincasting reels and to prove that they
were simple to use, even by someone who had never fished, Zebco's
early marketing was creative, to say the least. Its first sales
representative, George Goetz, wore boxing gloves while making
demonstrations. Another, Bill Carter of Texas, appeared at sport
shows with an identically dressed chimpanzee; he announced that the
reel was so simple that even a chimp could cast it, then handed the
reel to the chimp, which did.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Bill Carter cast a Zebco Model 11 spincasting reel
consecutively for 14 hours 14 minutes without a backlash. It was
calculated that he cast his five-eighths-ounce practice plug a
total distance of 70.9 miles in 3,453 backlash-free casts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the reel types that exist today, only the spincasting reel is
an entirely American invention, and it's still the easiest type of
reel to learn to use. A 5-year-old can learn to fish with
spincasting tackle in a short time but would have problems with any
other type of tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Durable and comparatively inexpensive, spincasting tackle is so
widely employed across North America that it ranks first in units
sold annually, with about half a dozen manufacturers producing it.
Nearly every spincasting reel comes spooled with line, which
eliminates the most basic rigging problem; no other reels are
supplied to consumers spooled by the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   But this equipment is virtually ignored by the most avid anglers
in the United States. A relatively low line capacity and
inefficient gears that curb cranking power limit the spincasting
reel to light- to medium-duty freshwater fishing applications.
</P>
<P>
   R.D. Hull worked for Zebco until his retirement in January 1977.
He designed 26 reels and held 35 United States and 30 Canadian
patents. He was inducted into the Sporting Goods Industry Hall of
Fame in 1975, and died in December 1977 at 64.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
