<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILMINGTON-REAL-NYT &LR;      04-10 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILMINGTON-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR WILMINGTON'S SHIPS TAVERN DISTRICT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Md.)  By MAUREEN MILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ When Jack B. Coonin started work as a jewelry
repairman in 1939, the southern end of North Market Street, this
city's main thoroughfare, was a vibrant Jewish community with
mouth-watering aromas wafting out of its bakeries and
delicatessens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little Europe,'' said Coonin, 77. ``I would walk up
Market Street on Fridays to collect the work from the jewelry shops
for the next week. It was shoulder-to-shoulder people. I had to
stop to talk to everybody _ they weren't customers, they were
friends. It was a neat community, it really was. The only screaming
you heard was from the mynah bird in the bakery.''
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, Coonin has had to keep the door locked
during the day at his cluttered jewelry and antique shop at 231
North Market Street, just north of the Amtrak passenger station.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the buildings around him are vacant, and only 10 people
live in the block. With hardly any pedestrian traffic, Coonin has
kept afloat with customers he has had for more than 30 years. His
more than a century-old building was badly in need of extensive
repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dying of old age,'' said Coonin. ``Pieces were falling
out from the ceiling and we've scraped a lot of water off the
floor. But I puttered along.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to an ambitious project being carried out by a
private, nonprofit development group, Coonin is preparing to
retire. His building is being bought as part of an estimated $70
million residential and retail restoration and redevelopment of a
six-block area a block north of the Christina River _ the city's
prime historic district.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say the plan by the Wilmington Renaissance Corp.
appears to be the first such single, major effort for residential
development in that area since Thomas Willling laid out plans for
the city in 1731. Willing developed a grid pattern of streets for
what was then called Willingtown, and sold lots. The first house,
dated 1732, was one block south of Coonin's shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the gateway to Wilmington,'' said Martin
Berger, who owns Berger Bros. office-furniture store across the
street from Coonin, as well as seven more buildings in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopers have named the area the Ships Tavern District
in honor of an 18th-century watering hole mentioned by George
Washington in his diaries. Washington, Thomas Jefferson, John Adams
and Aaron Burr all stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly the first redevelopment plan proposed for
downtown Wilmington, but the Ships Tavern project has been getting
a strong vote of confidence from residents, public officials and
private business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is right,'' said Mr. Coonin. ``I don't think it
will ever be depressed again.''
</P>
<P>
   The optimism can also be attributed to the fact that the project
is being spearheaded by the Renaissance Corp., which since 1993 has
had a string of small successes in revitalizing the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by the city's biggest employers _ such as E.I. du Pont
de Nemours &AMP; Co. and MBNA America Bank _ Renaissance is thought to
have the kind of muscle necessary for success. Board members
include representatives of Du Pont, as well as the city's major
banks. Mayor James H. Sills Jr. and City Council President James M.
Baker are also board members.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have the political and financial clout to pull it
off,'' said David J. Wilk, a real estate consultant.
</P>
<P>
   To oversee the project, Renaissance formed a separate
development arm headed by Joshua W. Martin III, chief executive of
Bell Atlantic Delaware. The development company reached an
agreement with the city to play a role in its center city urban
renewal plan. Under the contract, the group will have access to the
city's condemnation powers, a weapon against land speculators. The
city already controls 27 properties in or near the Ships Tavern
District.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment project, which comprises historic buildings
from Martin Luther King Boulevard to Fourth Street, will be done in
increments. The first phase of the development will focus on a row
of 18 buildings in the 200 block of North Market Street, chosen
because it features a strong inventory of buildings dating from the
19th century. This section, which could cost up to $20 million,
will be renovated as 80 apartments and 15 shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the buildings from the original Willingtown have
been lost, at least one structure with a brick Flemish-bond facade
could have been built as early as the late 18th century, said Eldon
du Pont Homsey, the architect on the project. The upper floors
retain such details as brownstone trim, decorative tiles and
cornices from the days when the area was a bustling commercial
district.
</P>
<P>
   Coonin's building once housed a jewelry maker. Coonin found that
out a few years ago when be bought a pocket watch from an old man
for the four ounces of gold it contained. When Coonin took the
watch apart he found an engraving noting that it was made by
``Charles F. Rudolph, 231 Market Street.'' The watch dates from
1875. ``I almost fell down,'' said Coonin, who now keeps the watch
tucked away in a safe.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say Jewish settlers were trading on the Delaware
River in nearby New Castle in the mid-17th century, and that one of
the earliest Jewish settlers in what is now Wilmington, in the
mid-18th century, was Abraham Judah, a merchant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1850, two brothers, Jacob and Daniel deSolis, began what grew
to be the city's first Jewish community when they opened a dry
goods store on Third Street.
</P>
<P>
   After 1880, the Jewish population increased with a wave of
immigrants from Russia, Austria and Poland. The Orthodox Adas
Kodesch congregation was formed several doors south of Mr. Coonin's
shop in 1889. By 1903, there were 800 Jewish immigrants in
Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Cohen, 76, a partner in the 57-year-old Cohen Bros.
furniture store, said that in the '30s the area was like the ``East
Side of New York on a small scale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people had just come from Europe in the early 1900s _
they'd only been in the country 20 or 30 years,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   But about 40 years ago the area began to lose its vitality. Many
merchants say the decline was hastened by an 11-month occupation of
the city by the Delaware National Guard following race riots in
April 1968. Cohen moved his store outside the city in the 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Coonin is cleaning out the shop he occupied for more than
30 years in anticipation of the start of construction. The initial
phase of the work will be done by Struever Bros., Eccles &AMP; Rouse of
Baltimore, a company that specializes in historic renovations.
Struever recently handled the $25 million conversion of the
American Can Co.building in Baltimore's Canton section into offices
and shops.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Renaissance Corp. does not intend to be a landowner,
it will hold options on properties, then turn them over to Struever
at the settlement table.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance will work with Struever to arrange financing
packages that could include bank loans made under the 1977 Federal
Community Reinvestment Act, requiring banks to make low-interest
loans in communities where they take deposits, as well as funds
from the sale of tax credits for renovation of historic buildings
under a federal program that gives investors credits for a certain
percentage of restoration work that the investors can use to offset
income taxes, said William C. Wyer, managing director of the
Renaissance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the plan also includes building a 1.8-mile trolley line
through the Ships Tavern District running from the new Riverfront
Arts Center on the Christina River to the Brandywine Creek to the
north as a way to tie the northern end of the city with the
development on the southern end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
