<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3677 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     04-10 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 18)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; UNDER GEMINI: A MEMOIR &LR;  By Isabel Bolton. Steerforth, $12. The
author, whose novels were highly praised in the 1940s and '50s,
describes growing up as an orphan in turn-of-the-century
Massachusetts with her identical twin sister, who died in a
swimming accident at the age of 14. In 1966, in The New York Times
Book Review, Diana Trilling called this slender book an
``extraordinarily poignant memoir of her quite extraordinary
childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRESTON FALLS &LR;  By David Gates. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. At
the center of this novel is a cynical, highly unlovable public
relations executive who takes a couple of months off to fix up his
family's getaway house in upstate New York. After a fight with his
wife lands him in jail, he hooks up with a lawyer who lures him
into cocaine trafficking. This scary tale of male vanity and the
dark underbelly of middle age was selected as one of the best books
of 1998 by the editors of The New York Times Book Review. ``You're
almost afraid to go back to the book once you've put it down,''
Michael Wood wrote last year. ``Anything could happen, and it's
likely to be horrible, irremediable.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE NATION, AFTER ALL. WHAT MIDDLE-CLASS AMERICANS REALLY THINK
ABOUT: GOD, COUNTRY, FAMILY, RACISM, WELFARE, IMMIGRATION,
HOMOSEXUALITY, WORK, THE RIGHT, THE LEFT, AND EACH OTHER &LR;  By Alan
Wolfe. Penguin, $13.95. Sifting through interviews with 200
middle-class folks of all stripes, a sociologist discovers far more
sympathy for civil rights, women's rights and religious diversity
than people often get credit for. This optimistic survey ``is a
fascinating and often stirring tour through an America that the
news media and would-be culture warriors seem not to know,'' Brent
Staples wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVILITY: MANNERS, MORALS, AND THE ETIQUETTE OF DEMOCRACY &LR;  By
Stephen L. Carter. Harper Perennial, $13. A law professor explores
the idea of civility (and incivility) from the evolution of
Euro-American etiquette to censorship in cyberspace, and urges a
more civil national discourse, especially where matters of faith
are concerned. ``His meditations on the tensions between democracy
and religion display ... eloquence and independence of mind,''
Michael Lind wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIRTHDAY LETTERS &LR;  By Ted Hughes. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $12.
The subject of these poems is Hughes' stormy relationship with
Sylvia Plath, and the result is an inevitably one-sided rebuke to
those who see him as the villain in Plath's 1963 suicide. Last year
the reviewer Katha Pollitt praised the ``emotional, direct,
regretful, entranced'' tone that ``pervades the book's strongest
poems, which are quiet and thoughtful and conversational.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has issued  &UR; TALES FROM OVID &LR;  ($14), in which
Hughes tackles the ironic, urbane Ovid of ancient Rome; somehow the
pairing clicks. ``The result is that rare thing _ an inspired act
of translation that stands as vigorous poetry in its own right,''
James Shapiro wrote in 1997. ``This book brilliantly succeeds at
bringing Ovid's passionate and disturbing stories to life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BE SWEET: A CONDITIONAL LOVE STORY &LR;  By Roy Blount Jr.
Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. The humorist's unflinching account of
his Georgia childhood has everything to do with his mother, Louise,
a difficult woman whose mystery haunts her son into adulthood.
```Be Sweet' is both literary and down-home, a thinking man's thigh
slapper'' and ``a serious heartbreaker,'' Josephine Humphreys wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LIFE OF INSECTS &LR;  By Victor Pelevin. Penguin, $11.95. The
human characters in this slippery Russian novel morph back and
forth into bugs _ chief among them are a trio of voracious
investors/mosquitoes and a sexy fly named Natasha. ``Political
allegory, antic fantasy, willful enigma: Victor Pelevin's latest
book ... is a little of all three,'' Michael Upchurch wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SHORT HISTORY OF BYZANTIUM &LR;  By John Julius Norwich. Vintage,
$17. This condensed version of the author's three-volume history
starts with the founding of Constantinople in 330 and its fall in
1453. ``Lord Norwich has sacrificed none of the virtues of the
longer work: lively narration and a taste for the eccentric
anecdote and revelatory detail,'' Michael Anderson wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM THE HOLY MOUNTAIN: A JOURNEY AMONG THE CHRISTIANS OF THE
MIDDLE EAST &LR;  By William Dalrymple. Owl/Holt, $16.95. This retraces
the path of two monks who traveled in the Byzantine Empire in the
late sixth and early seventh centuries. ``Dalrymple is the
professor whose obscure lectures you attend just so you can hear
him talk,'' Ted Conover wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ILLUSIONIST &LR;  By Dinitia Smith. Scribner, $12. This novel by
a reporter for The New York Times is about an androgynous man who
coasts into a rural New York town and the tragedy that results when
three lonely women are drawn into his web. The story's ``greatest
strength is the sensitivity with which Smith explores the
complexities of love,'' Edward Hower wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SKIN DEEP &LR;  By Diana Wagman. University of Mississippi, $15. A
former topless waitress enters a peculiar relationship with a young
doctor who pays her well to shroud herself completely in blue and
talk about beauty. In 1997 the reviewer Courtney Weaver called this
``a curious and disturbing'' first novel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
