<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990410.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEATING-AZR &LR;      04-10 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEATING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEATING: FINANCIER'S MYTH FINALLY SHATTERED  
 (ANALYSIS)
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In early 1989, just before Charles H Keating Jr. took American
Continental Corp. into bankruptcy, he ordered a series of illegal
raids on the corporate coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, who once towered over Arizona business and politics
like a colossus, admitted it publicly last week.
</P>
<P>
   In an agreement with federal prosecutors, he acknowledged
concocting phony loans to siphon $975,000 out of ACC, the
Phoenix-based corporation where he was CEO.
</P>
<P>
   With that plea bargain, Keating shattered his own myth, the
long-running legend of himself as a high-flying financial
visionary, bold entrepreneur and crusader against meddling
government regulators and other infidels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a knight on a white charger,'' Keating once declared.
</P>
<P>
   He also ended a major chapter in America's savings-and-loan
scandal, the saga of greed, deceit and insider dealing that
consumed billions of dollars through fraud and incompetence and
left broad political wounds that have yet to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Keating would not comment on the case this week. But his lawyer
said the 75-year-old man took the plea to avoid the risk of another
trial, which could have sent him back to prison. Recent family
tragedy may have weighed in his decision; the plea comes eight
weeks after the sudden death of a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Until last week, the 6-foot-5-inch Keating, a former champion
swimmer who built his first national reputation as a 1970s
pornography fighter, defiantly claimed that he was the innocent
victim of regulators' abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Keating derided regulators as ``scum.'' He saw them as petty,
rule-obsessed bureaucrats incapable of appreciating the
entrepreneurial genius he brought to the formerly staid savings and
loan industry.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and prickly as a saguaro, with a volcanic temper, Keating
heaped scorn on regulators who sought to restrain his use of
billions of dollars in federally insured deposits at Lincoln
Savings. The Southern California thrift, ACC's principal
subsidiary, was the centerpiece of his financial empire.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque on his desk proclaimed his combative creed: ``A man
can do no wrong if he always rides to the sound of the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 62 months that he owned Lincoln, Keating used other
people's money to bankroll his corporate Camelot on Camelback Road.
</P>
<P>
   He donated lavishly to Mother Teresa, bought a luxury Miami home
as an ``office'' and jetted off to gambling sprees in Monaco. He
commanded a three-jet corporate fleet that flew him around the
world and carried Sen. John McCain and other luminaries to his
luxurious retreat in the Bahamas. Its cost for four years: $31
million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Keating myth, he built a sleek, smooth-running
financial engine powered by his entrepreneurial genius, his
unerring instinct for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But after ACC's bankruptcy, Keating's critics branded him as a
savings and loan pirate in a Hermes tie, the archvillain of the
national S&AMP;L debacle, and predatory pusher of junk bonds to mostly
elderly investors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Keating was convicted in a California court of
defrauding bondholders. The verdict was overturned due to judicial
error, but prosecutors are seeking to have it restored.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 he was convicted in federal court on 73 felony counts.
He served 50 months in prison before that verdict was overturned
because of jury misconduct. He was heading toward a new trial until
last week's plea bargain _ in which he was sentenced to time served
_ settled his federal account.
</P>
<P>
   After his state conviction, Keating issued a a typically
thunderous declaration of innocence. He claimed he was made a
scapegoat for the S&AMP;L scandal by a ``vicious and vindictive group
of bureaucrats and sinister politicians hoping to cover their
perfidy and ignorance by pillorying Charlie Keating.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the core of his myth: Keating as martyr to the cause of
freeing Lincoln from bureaucratic bondage.
</P>
<P>
   Keating spent freely to advance his cause. After he took ACC
into bankruptcy and regulators seized Lincoln, he talked about his
shopping spree for political influence, noting that questions had
been raised about ``whether my financial support in any way
influenced several political figures to take up my cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say in the most forceful way I can: I certainly hope
so.''
</P>
<P>
   That blunt manifesto would echo throughout the Senate ethics
hearings on the men _ including then-Arizona Sen. Dennis DeConcini
and Sen. John McCain _ who would be dubbed the Keating Five for
intervening with federal regulators on Keating's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1987 meeting with the senators, regulators told of
Keating's recklessness: multimillion-dollar loans made without
basic checks of the borrower's ability to repay, wacky appraisals
of real estate, wholesale violation of regulatory guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Regulator Mike Patriarca said what it all meant for Keating's
self-professed visionaries: ``They're flying blind on all their
different loans and investments.''
</P>
<P>
   They were also flying high. In mid-1988, when American
Continental was nearing collapse and had little income except from
junk bond sales, two of Keating's planes took 21 members of the
Keating family on a three-week tour of Europe. There were luxury
hotel stays in Italy, Switzerland, Yugoslavia, Germany, France,
England and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Keating recorded the trip as a business expense. After all, he
reasoned, it included interviews with chefs for possible employment
at the Phoenician resort, his prize property that opened that fall.
He also studied the hotels' management techniques.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Keating threw the annual corporate Christmas party at
the Registry Resort in Scottsdale. The entertainment, featuring the
Peter Duchin Orchestra from New York, cost $27,143. ACC paid
$65,319 for food and drinks; $2,449 for Christmas trees; and $1,948
for Silly String.
</P>
<P>
   Such extravagance was part of Keating's illusion of prosperity,
which also included glowing annual reports that attracted thousands
of investors to ACC's bonds. The major accounting firms that put
their professional blessing on Keating's bottom line would later
pay $93 million to settle the investors' lawsuit. Keating's law
firms paid $55 million more.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Keating made a money-eating machine out of Lincoln,
which he had bought in 1984 for $52 million raised by junk bonds
issued by Michael Milken.
</P>
<P>
   Milken had been one of the first to recognize the opportunities
Congress provided in 1982 by curtailing federal regulation. Urged
on by the S&AMP;L lobby, Congress acted to revitalize an industry that
had always been limited to financing the American dream with home
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate result of deregulation was that many thrifts were
transformed from wallflowers of investment to high rollers that
played every game in the high-finance casino: high-risk real
estate, foreign currency futures, investments in restaurants and
hotels, and Milken's junk bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Former Fed Chairman Paul Volcker called it ``kamikaze banking.''
But backers of deregulation promised it would liberate the genius
of American entrepreneurship, getting regulators off the backs of
inspired men who knew how to make the economy hum.
</P>
<P>
   This brave new world was irresistible to developers like
Keating. They had spent their careers using their own money to fund
housing projects and shopping centers. Keating excelled at it,
building such developments as Dobson Ranch and the Islands in
Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   But building houses was boring compared with the thrill of
sitting at the controls of a savings and loan. S&AMP;L owners had
billions of dollars of deposits to fuel their speculative dreams,
backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The formula was foolproof: Profits went to the S&AMP;L owners; if
they failed, taxpayers would pick up the tab. It was a system that,
in the words of one congressman, ``privatized gain and socialized
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   And what losses! Regulators say Lincoln's failure cost taxpayers
$3.4 billion. This means that, on average, Keating lost about $1.8
million every day of the five-plus years he ran Lincoln. That's
$75,000 every hour, every day.
</P>
<P>
   Keating lived the regal life to which he felt he was entitled.
Luxury homes in Miami and the Bahamas, a fleet of luxury cars,
lavish salaries and bonuses for himself and his inner circle,
fistfuls of $50 bills handed to secretaries for shopping sprees,
handfuls of $100 bills tossed into the air at a pep rally for
swooning bond sellers shortly before bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 he took $3 million out of ACC for himself in salaries
and bonuses. At one point, six of the 10 highest-paid executives in
Arizona were on his payroll. He displayed his largesse on national
television, spontaneously telling a secretary he was raising her
salary to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highest-paid ACC executives was Keating's right-hand
woman, ACC President Judy Wischer. It was Wischer who inadvertently
gave the public a glimpse into the cult quality of American
Continental, where absolute, unquestioning loyalty to Keating was
an article of corporate faith.
</P>
<P>
   Wischer told of a ritual ACC passage up the corporate ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to bring someone, especially a woman, out of the
minor leagues when they have just been promoted, we let them fire
somebody,'' she said in a 1988 speech. ``Suddenly, they know
they're not playing by the same rules anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, testifying as the star witness in Keating's
federal trial, Wischer told how Keating concocted bogus land sales
to show a profit on his books.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of the third quarter in 1986, she said, he
pretended to make a $25 million sale of a portion of Continental
Ranch near Tucson to a Phoenix home builder, R.A. Homes.
</P>
<P>
   Keating drew R.A. Homes into the deal by promising that when he
found a legitimate buyer, he would pay the company the first $2.5
million in profits and split additional profits with it, Wischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Keating used that deal, plus another sham transaction on land in
La Paz County to avoid showing a quarterly loss. Instead he told
the world he had turned an $8 million profit.
</P>
<P>
   There were dozens of such bogus deals. But last week's plea deal
means he won't have to confront charges stemming from them. Nor
will a federal jury hear testimony from ACC bondholders seduced and
devastated by Keating's grand illusion.
</P>
<P>
   The bondholders have now recovered most of their money, through
lawsuits against Keating's accountants, lawyers and other
associates. Keating has been ordered to pay $3 billion for his
fraud. He hasn't paid a dime. He claims he is broke.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the bondholders, Keating's victims also include
the 10 insiders and business associates convicted of various
charges, the politicians, accountants, lawyers and appraisers whose
reputations were sullied, the American taxpayers who picked up the
tab and became more cynical about their government.
</P>
<P>
   But the plea deal is a way of signaling an end to the Keating
trauma. It not only relieves Keating from the dangers of a new
trial. It also spares prosecutors the burden of presenting a
complicated case with old evidence.
</P>
<P>
   With many of the criminal counts wiped out, Keating may cling to
the tattered remnants of his myth. He may proclaim that he wasn't
convicted for the land deals or bond sales that were the core of
the federal case. He may try to present his last raid on the
corporate treasury as an inconsequential footnote.
</P>
<P>
   But the history is in the books.
</P>
<P>
   Rep Jim Leach, R-Iowa, labeled Keating in 1989 ``a financiopath
of obscene proportions, the Rev. Jim Bakker of American commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge Stanley Sporkin said in 1990 that Keating had
conducted a sophisticated ``looting of Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ron Warnicke, the bankruptcy examiner who was one of
the first to report on Keating's fraud, drew a final lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arrogance in the handling of other people's money,'' he said,
``is a certain path to financial ruin.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
